WEBVTT

00:00:17.700 --> 00:00:20.440
Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson.

00:00:23.080 --> 00:00:28.220
To S.L.O., an American gentleman in accordance with whose classic taste the following narrative

00:00:28.220 --> 00:00:33.100
has been designed, it is now in return for numerous delightful hours and with the kindest

00:00:33.100 --> 00:00:36.900
wishes, dedicated by his affectionate friend, the author.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:40.760
To the hesitating purchaser.

00:00:41.980 --> 00:00:48.060
If sailor tales to sailor tunes, storm and adventure, heat and cold, if schooners, islands

00:00:48.060 --> 00:00:53.960
and maroons and buccaneers and buried gold, and all the old romance retold exactly in

00:00:53.960 --> 00:00:59.020
the ancient way, can please, as me they pleased of old, the wiser youngsters of today.

00:01:00.020 --> 00:01:06.000
So be it and fall on, if not, if studious youth no longer crave, his ancient appetites

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:12.360
forgot Kingston or Ballantine the brave, or Cooper of the wood and wave, so be it also,

00:01:12.360 --> 00:01:17.480
and may I and all my pirates share the grave where these and their creations lie.

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:21.040
Part One.

00:01:21.340 --> 00:01:23.540
The Old Buccaneer.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:24.800
Chapter One.

00:01:25.100 --> 00:01:27.280
The Old Sea Dog at the Admiral Binbow.

00:01:30.140 --> 00:01:33.980
Squire Trelawney, Dr. Livesey, and the rest of these gentlemen, having asked me to write

00:01:33.980 --> 00:01:38.240
down the whole particulars about Treasure Island, from the beginning to the end, keeping

00:01:38.240 --> 00:01:42.160
nothing back but the bearings of the island, and that only because there is still treasure

00:01:42.160 --> 00:01:42.940
not yet lifted.

00:01:43.620 --> 00:01:48.920
I take up my pen in the Year of Grace, 17 blank, and go back to the time when my father

00:01:48.920 --> 00:01:53.940
kept the Admiral Binbow in, and the brown old seaman with the saber-cut first took up

00:01:53.940 --> 00:01:55.280
his lodging under our roof.

00:01:56.500 --> 00:02:01.000
I remember him as if it were yesterday, as he came plodding to the inn door, his sea

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:06.960
chest following behind him in a handbarrow, a tall, strong, heavy, nut-brown man, his

00:02:06.960 --> 00:02:11.700
tarry pigtail falling over the shoulder of his soiled blue coat, his hands ragged and

00:02:11.700 --> 00:02:17.260
scarred with black broken nails, and the saber-cut across one cheek, a dirty, livid

00:02:17.260 --> 00:02:17.620
white.

00:02:18.820 --> 00:02:23.740
I remember him looking around the cove and whistling to himself as he did so, and then

00:02:23.740 --> 00:02:27.360
breaking out in that old sea song that he sang so often afterwards,

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:34.680
Fifteen men on the dead man's chest, yo ho ho and a bottle of rum, in the high old

00:02:34.680 --> 00:02:39.120
tottering voice that seemed to have been tuned and broken at the capstan bars.

00:02:40.180 --> 00:02:44.080
Then he rapped on the door with a bit of stick like a hand-spike that he carried,

00:02:44.540 --> 00:02:47.760
and when my father appeared, called roughly for a glass of rum.

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:54.320
This, when it was brought to him, he drank slowly, like a connoisseur, lingering on the

00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:57.740
taste and still looking about him at the cliffs and up at our signboard.

00:02:59.260 --> 00:03:03.980
This is a handy cove, says he at length, and a pleasant situated grog-shop.

00:03:04.540 --> 00:03:05.620
Much company, mate!

00:03:06.960 --> 00:03:10.300
My father told him no, very little company, the more was the pity.

00:03:11.480 --> 00:03:14.460
Well then, said he, this is the berth for me.

00:03:14.800 --> 00:03:17.540
Here you, matey! he cried to the man who trundled the barrow.

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:20.160
Bring up alongside and help up my chest.

00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:22.580
I'll stay here a bit, he continued.

00:03:23.140 --> 00:03:27.800
I'm a plain man, rum and bacon and eggs is what I want, and that head up there for to

00:03:27.800 --> 00:03:28.600
watch ships off.

00:03:29.180 --> 00:03:32.000
What you might call me, you might call me captain.

00:03:32.680 --> 00:03:34.220
Oh, I see what you're at, there!

00:03:34.220 --> 00:03:37.480
And he threw down three or four gold pieces on the threshold.

00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:42.060
You can tell me when I work through that, says he, looking as fierce as a commander.

00:03:43.780 --> 00:03:48.560
And indeed, bad as his clothes were and coarsely as he spoke, he had none of the

00:03:48.560 --> 00:03:52.940
appearance of a man who sailed before them, asked, but seemed like a mate or skipper,

00:03:53.160 --> 00:03:55.020
accustomed to be obeyed or to strike.

00:03:56.140 --> 00:04:00.100
The man who came with the barrow told us the mail had set him down the morning before at

00:04:00.100 --> 00:04:05.640
the Royal George, that he had inquired what inns there were along the coast, and hearing ours

00:04:05.640 --> 00:04:10.840
well spoken of, I suppose, and described as lonely, had chosen it from the others for

00:04:10.840 --> 00:04:11.900
his place of residence.

00:04:12.460 --> 00:04:14.960
And that was all we could learn of our guest.

00:04:17.060 --> 00:04:19.400
He was a very silent man by custom.

00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:24.000
All day he hung round the cove or upon the cliffs with a brass telescope.

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:29.660
All evening he sat in a corner of the parlour next the fire and drank rum and water very strong.

00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:35.820
Mostly he would not speak when spoken to, only look up sudden and fierce and blow through his

00:04:35.820 --> 00:04:41.400
nose like a foghorn, and we and the people who came about our house soon learned to let him be.

00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:47.480
Every day when he came back from his stroll he would ask if any seafaring men had gone by along

00:04:47.480 --> 00:04:48.020
the road.

00:04:49.060 --> 00:04:53.360
At first we thought it was the want of company of his own kind that made him ask this question,

00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:57.260
but at last we began to see that he was desirous to avoid them.

00:04:57.960 --> 00:05:03.140
When a seaman did put up at the Admiral Benbow, as now and then some did, making by the coast

00:05:03.140 --> 00:05:08.340
road for Bristol, he would look in at him through the curtain door before he entered the parlour,

00:05:08.620 --> 00:05:12.180
and he was always sure to be as silent as a mouse when any such was present.

00:05:14.100 --> 00:05:19.240
For me, at least, there was no secret about the matter, for I was, in a way, a sharer in his

00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:19.660
alarms.

00:05:20.780 --> 00:05:25.640
He had taken me aside one day and promised me a silver fourpenny on the first of every month

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:29.820
if I would only keep my weather-eye open for a seafaring man with one leg,

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:32.140
and let him know the moment he appeared.

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:37.100
Often enough, when the first of the month came round and I applied to him for my wage,

00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:40.520
he would only blow through his nose at me and stare me down.

00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:45.520
But before the week was out he was sure to think better of it, bring me my fourpenny piece,

00:05:46.060 --> 00:05:49.800
and repeat his orders to look out for the seafaring man with one leg.

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:54.620
How that personage haunted my dreams I need scarcely tell you.

00:05:55.180 --> 00:05:59.820
On stormy nights, when the wind shook the four corners of the house and the surf roared along

00:05:59.820 --> 00:06:05.040
the cove and up the cliffs, I would see him in a thousand forms and with a thousand diabolical

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:05.660
expressions.

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:09.700
Now the leg would be cut off at the knee, now at the hip.

00:06:10.400 --> 00:06:14.480
Now he was a monstrous kind of creature who never had but the one leg and that in the

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:15.400
middle of his body.

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:21.420
To see him leap and run and pursue me over hedge and ditch was the worst of nightmares.

00:06:22.020 --> 00:06:26.440
And altogether I paid pretty dear for my monthly fourpenny piece in the shape of these

00:06:26.440 --> 00:06:27.420
abominable fancies.

00:06:29.800 --> 00:06:34.820
But though I was so terrified by the idea of the seafaring man with one leg, I was far less

00:06:34.820 --> 00:06:37.700
afraid of the captain himself than anybody else who knew him.

00:06:38.880 --> 00:06:42.480
There were nights when he took a deal more rum and water than his head would carry,

00:06:42.500 --> 00:06:48.080
and then he would sometimes sit and sing his wicked old wild sea songs minding nobody.

00:06:48.860 --> 00:06:53.760
But sometimes he would call for glasses round and force all the trembling company to listen

00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:56.400
to his stories or bear a chorus to his singing.

00:06:57.660 --> 00:07:02.960
Often I have heard the house shaking with yo ho ho and a bottle of rum, all the neighbors

00:07:02.960 --> 00:07:07.960
joining in for dear life with the fear of death upon them and each singing louder than the other

00:07:07.960 --> 00:07:09.020
to avoid remark.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.500
For in these fits he was the most overriding companion ever known.

00:07:13.940 --> 00:07:17.000
He would slap his hand on the table for silence all round.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.020
He would fly up in a passion of anger at a question, or sometimes because none was put,

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:24.760
and so he judged the company was not following his story.

00:07:25.580 --> 00:07:30.240
Nor would he allow anyone to leave the inn till he had drunk himself sleepy and reeled off to bed.

00:07:32.180 --> 00:07:34.860
His stories were what frightened people worst of all.

00:07:35.240 --> 00:07:40.160
Dreadful stories they were about hanging and walking the plank and storms at sea and the

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:43.800
dry tortugas and wild deeds in places on the Spanish main.

00:07:44.980 --> 00:07:49.480
By his own account he must have lived his life among some of the wickedest men that God ever

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:54.000
allowed upon the sea, and the language in which he told these stories shocked our plain country

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.720
people almost as much as the crimes that he described.

00:07:58.660 --> 00:08:02.660
My father was always saying the inn would be ruined, for people would soon cease coming

00:08:02.660 --> 00:08:07.620
there to be tyrannized over and put down and sent shivering to their beds, but I really

00:08:07.620 --> 00:08:09.160
believe his presence did us good.

00:08:10.220 --> 00:08:13.780
People were frightened at the time, but on looking back they rather liked it.

00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:18.940
It was a fine excitement in a quiet country life, and there was even a party of the younger men who

00:08:18.940 --> 00:08:24.680
pretended to admire him, calling him a true sea dog and a real old salt and such like names,

00:08:24.860 --> 00:08:28.300
and saying there was the sort of man that made England terrible at sea.

00:08:30.220 --> 00:08:35.640
In one way indeed he bade fair to ruin us, for he kept on staying week after week and at last

00:08:35.640 --> 00:08:40.600
month after month, so that all the money had been long exhausted, and still my father never

00:08:40.600 --> 00:08:42.960
plucked up the heart to insist on having more.

00:08:44.180 --> 00:08:49.440
If ever he mentioned it, the captain blew through his nose so loudly that you might say he roared,

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:51.980
and stared my poor father out of the room.

00:08:53.240 --> 00:08:58.260
I have seen him wringing his hands after such a rebuff, and I am sure the annoyance and the

00:08:58.260 --> 00:09:02.000
terror he lived in must have greatly hastened his early and unhappy death.

00:09:03.820 --> 00:09:08.220
All the time he lived with us, the captain made no change whatever in his dress but to buy some

00:09:08.220 --> 00:09:09.400
stockings from a hawker.

00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:14.760
One of the cocks of his hat having fallen down, he let it hang from that day forth,

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:16.840
though it was a great annoyance when it blew.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:22.180
I remember the appearance of his coat, which he patched himself upstairs in his room,

00:09:22.300 --> 00:09:25.080
and which, before the end, was nothing but patches.

00:09:26.260 --> 00:09:30.560
He never wrote or received a letter, and he never spoke with any but the neighbors,

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:34.020
and with these, for the most part, only when drunk on rum.

00:09:34.980 --> 00:09:37.540
The great sea-chest none of us had ever seen open.

00:09:39.400 --> 00:09:42.460
He was only once crossed, and that was towards the end,

00:09:42.600 --> 00:09:46.040
when my poor father was far gone in the decline that took him off.

00:09:47.220 --> 00:09:51.940
Dr. Livesey came late one afternoon to see the patient, took a bit of dinner from my mother,

00:09:52.460 --> 00:09:56.900
and went into the parlor to smoke a pipe until his horse should come down from the hamlet,

00:09:57.160 --> 00:09:59.140
for we had no stabling at the old benbow.

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:04.680
I followed him in, and I remember observing the contrast the neat, bright doctor,

00:10:04.940 --> 00:10:08.680
with his powder as white as snow and his bright black eyes and pleasant manners,

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:13.500
made with a cultish country folk, and above all, with that filthy, heavy,

00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:19.200
leered scarecrow of a pirate of ours, sitting far gone in rum with his arms on the table.

00:10:20.440 --> 00:10:24.740
Suddenly he, the captain that is, began to pipe up his eternal song.

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:30.400
Fifteen men on the dead man's chest, yo ho ho and a bottle of rum,

00:10:30.980 --> 00:10:35.800
drink and the devil had done for the rest, yo ho ho and a bottle of rum.

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:43.360
At first I had supposed the dead man's chest to be that identical big box of his upstairs in the

00:10:43.360 --> 00:10:47.540
front room, and the thought had been mingled in my nightmares with that of the one-legged

00:10:47.540 --> 00:10:53.980
seafaring man. But by this time we had all long ceased to pay any particular notice to the song.

00:10:54.440 --> 00:11:00.400
It was new that night to nobody but Dr. Livesey, and on him I observed it did not produce an

00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:05.340
agreeable effect, for he looked up for a moment quite angrily before he went on with his talk to

00:11:05.340 --> 00:11:12.040
old tailor, the gardener, on a new cure for the rheumatics. In the meantime, the captain gradually

00:11:12.040 --> 00:11:16.580
brightened up at his own music, and at last flapped his hand upon the table before him,

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:24.660
in a way we all knew to mean silence. The voices stopped at once, all but Dr. Livesey's. He went on

00:11:24.660 --> 00:11:28.720
as before, speaking clear and kind and drawing briskly at his pipe between every word or two.

00:11:29.820 --> 00:11:34.800
The captain glared at him for a while, flapped his hand again, glared still harder,

00:11:34.800 --> 00:11:40.180
and at last broke out with a villainous low oath. Silence there between decks!

00:11:42.460 --> 00:11:47.380
Were you addressing me, sir? says the doctor, and when the ruffian had told him with another oath

00:11:47.380 --> 00:11:53.340
that this was so, I have only one thing to say to you, sir, replies the doctor, that if you keep on

00:11:53.340 --> 00:12:00.720
drinking rum, the world will soon be quit of a very dirty scoundrel. The old fellow's fury was awful.

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:06.680
He sprang to his feet, drew and opened a sailor's clasp knife, and balancing it open on the palm

00:12:06.680 --> 00:12:13.220
of his hand, threatened to pin the doctor to the wall. The doctor never so much as moved.

00:12:13.860 --> 00:12:17.900
He spoke to him as before, over his shoulder and in the same tone of voice,

00:12:18.240 --> 00:12:22.140
rather high so that all the room might hear, but perfectly calm and steady.

00:12:23.240 --> 00:12:28.120
If you do not put that knife this instant in your pocket, I promise upon my honor you shall hang

00:12:28.120 --> 00:12:34.580
at the next assesies. Then followed a battle of looks between them, but the captain soon knuckled

00:12:34.580 --> 00:12:38.840
under, put up his weapon, and resumed his seat, grumbling like a beaten dog.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:45.080
And now, sir, continued the doctor, since I now know there's such a fellow in my district,

00:12:45.380 --> 00:12:50.220
you may count I'll have an eye upon you day and night. I'm not a doctor only, I'm a magistrate,

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:54.340
and if I catch a breath of complaint against you, if it's only for a piece of incivility like

00:12:54.340 --> 00:12:59.380
tonight's, I'll take effectual means to have you hunted down and routed out of this. Let that suffice.

00:13:01.780 --> 00:13:05.260
Soon after, Dr. Livesey's horse came to the door, and he rode away,

00:13:05.700 --> 00:13:09.140
but the captain held his peace that evening, and for many evenings to come.

00:13:12.460 --> 00:13:15.620
Chapter 2. Black Dog Appears and Disappears

00:13:17.820 --> 00:13:21.920
It was not very long after this that there occurred the first of the mysterious events

00:13:21.920 --> 00:13:26.060
that rid us at last of the captain, though not, as you will see, of his affairs.

00:13:27.480 --> 00:13:31.440
It was a bitter cold winter, with long hard frosts and heavy gales,

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:35.700
and it was plain from the first that my poor father was little likely to see the spring.

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:40.420
He sank daily, and my mother and I had all the inn upon our hands,

00:13:40.540 --> 00:13:44.040
and were kept busy enough without paying much regard to our unpleasant guest.

00:13:46.040 --> 00:13:50.140
It was one January morning, very early, a pinching frosty morning,

00:13:50.140 --> 00:13:54.440
the cove all grey with hoar frost, the ripple lapping softly on the stones,

00:13:55.100 --> 00:13:58.660
the sun still low and only touching the hilltops and shining far to seaward.

00:13:59.800 --> 00:14:04.160
The captain had risen earlier than usual and set out down the beach, his cutlass swinging under

00:14:04.160 --> 00:14:10.220
the broad skirts of the old blue coat, his brass telescope under his arm, his hat tilted back upon

00:14:10.220 --> 00:14:16.880
his head. I remember his breath hanging like smoke in his wake as he strode off, and the last sound

00:14:16.880 --> 00:14:21.880
I heard of him as he turned the big rock was a loud snort of indignation, as though his mind

00:14:21.880 --> 00:14:28.660
was still running upon Dr. Livesey. Well, mother was upstairs with father, and I was laying the

00:14:28.660 --> 00:14:33.200
breakfast table against the captain's return, when the parlour door opened and a man stepped

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:39.980
in on whom I had never set my eyes before. He was a pale tallowy creature, wanting two fingers of

00:14:39.980 --> 00:14:46.160
the left hand, and though he wore a cutlass, he did not look much like a fighter. I had always

00:14:46.160 --> 00:14:52.540
my eye open for seafaring men with one leg or two, and I remember this one puzzled me. He was not

00:14:52.540 --> 00:14:58.700
sailorly, and yet he had a smack of the sea about him too. I asked him what was for his service,

00:14:58.800 --> 00:15:04.040
and he said he would take rum, but as I was going out of the room to fetch it, he sat down upon a

00:15:04.040 --> 00:15:09.480
table and motioned me to draw near. I paused where I was with my napkin in my hand.

00:15:10.620 --> 00:15:16.180
Come here, sonny, says he. Come nearer here. I took a step nearer.

00:15:16.920 --> 00:15:20.120
Is this here a table for my mate Bill? he asked with a kind of leer.

00:15:21.700 --> 00:15:25.700
I told him I did not know his mate Bill, and this was for a person who stayed in our house,

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:31.600
whom we called the captain. Well, said he, my mate Bill would be called the captain as like

00:15:31.600 --> 00:15:36.360
is not. He has a cut on one cheek, and a mighty pleasant way with him, particularly in drink,

00:15:36.360 --> 00:15:41.880
as my mate Bill. We'll put it, for argument like, that your captain has a cut on one cheek,

00:15:42.200 --> 00:15:46.220
and we'll put it, if you like, that that cheek's the right one. Ah, well, I told you.

00:15:46.560 --> 00:15:52.700
Now, is my mate Bill in this here house? I told him he was out walking. Which way,

00:15:52.820 --> 00:15:58.260
sonny, which way is he gone? And when I had pointed out the rock, and told him how the

00:15:58.260 --> 00:16:03.940
captain was likely to return, and how soon, and answered a few other questions. Ah, said he,

00:16:03.940 --> 00:16:10.300
this'll be as good as drink to my mate Bill. The expression of his face as he said these words

00:16:10.300 --> 00:16:14.820
was not at all pleasant, and I had my own reasons for thinking that the stranger was mistaken,

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:20.740
even supposing he meant what he said. But it was no affair of mine, I thought, and besides,

00:16:20.780 --> 00:16:25.800
it was difficult to know what to do. The stranger kept hanging about just inside the inn door,

00:16:26.180 --> 00:16:31.620
peering round the corner like a cat waiting for a mouse. Once I stepped out myself into the road,

00:16:31.620 --> 00:16:36.040
but he immediately called me back, and as I did not obey quick enough for his fancy,

00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:41.480
a most horrible change came over his tallowy face, and he ordered me in with an oath that made me

00:16:41.480 --> 00:16:47.740
jump. As soon as I was back again, he returned to his former manner, half fawning, half sneering,

00:16:48.200 --> 00:16:52.660
patted me on the shoulder, told me I was a good boy, and he had taken quite a fancy to me.

00:16:53.600 --> 00:16:58.900
I have a son of my own, said he, as like you as two blocks, and he's all the pride of my art.

00:16:58.900 --> 00:17:03.980
But the great thing for boys is discipline, Sonny, discipline. Now if you had sailed along

00:17:03.980 --> 00:17:09.040
with Bill, you wouldn't have stood there to be spoke to twice, not you. That was never Bill's

00:17:09.040 --> 00:17:14.660
way, nor the way of such as sailed with him. And here, sure enough, is my mate Bill, with a spyglass

00:17:14.660 --> 00:17:19.280
under his arm, bliss his old art, to be sure. You and me will just go back into the parlour,

00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:23.860
Sonny, and get behind the door, and we'll give Bill a little surprise. Bless his art, I say again.

00:17:25.720 --> 00:17:30.440
So saying, the stranger backed along with me into the parlour, and put me behind him in the corner,

00:17:30.640 --> 00:17:36.460
so that we were both hidden by the open door. I was very uneasy and alarmed, as you may fancy,

00:17:36.740 --> 00:17:40.920
and it rather added to my fears to observe that the stranger was certainly frightened himself.

00:17:42.040 --> 00:17:45.720
He cleared the hilt of his cutlass, and loosened the blade in its sheath,

00:17:46.160 --> 00:17:50.600
and all the time we were waiting there, he kept swallowing, as if he felt what we used to call

00:17:50.600 --> 00:17:57.200
a lump in the throat. At last in strode the captain, slammed the door behind him,

00:17:57.420 --> 00:18:02.200
without looking to the right or left, and marched straight across the room to where his breakfast

00:18:02.200 --> 00:18:09.240
awaited him. Bill, said the stranger in a voice that I thought he had tried to make bold and big.

00:18:11.200 --> 00:18:16.180
The captain spun round on his heel and fronted us. All the brown had gone out of his face,

00:18:16.180 --> 00:18:21.360
and even his nose was blue. He had the look of a man who sees a ghost, or the evil one,

00:18:21.440 --> 00:18:25.940
or something worse, if anything can be, and upon my word I felt sorry to see him,

00:18:26.220 --> 00:18:28.120
all in a moment turned so old and sick.

00:18:29.520 --> 00:18:34.260
Come, Bill, you know me. You know an old shipmate, Bill, surely, said the stranger.

00:18:35.840 --> 00:18:42.340
The captain made a sort of gasp. Black dog, said he. And who else, returned the other,

00:18:42.340 --> 00:18:47.600
getting more at his ease. Black dog as ever was. Come forth to see his old shipmate Billy

00:18:47.600 --> 00:18:53.320
at the Admiral Ben Bowen. Ah, Bill, Bill, we have seen a sight of times, us two,

00:18:53.340 --> 00:18:56.860
since I lost them two talons. Holding up his mutilated hand.

00:18:58.400 --> 00:19:04.580
Now look here, said the captain. You've run me down. Here I am. Well then, speak up. What is it?

00:19:06.200 --> 00:19:09.900
That's you, Bill, returned black dog. You're in the right of it, Billy.

00:19:10.360 --> 00:19:14.280
I'll have a glass of rum from this dear child here, as I've took such a liking to,

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:17.680
and we'll sit down, if you please, and talk square like old shipmates.

00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:23.700
When I returned with the rum, they were already seated on either side of the captain's breakfast

00:19:23.700 --> 00:19:29.340
table. Black dog next to the door, and sitting sideways, so as to have one eye on his old

00:19:29.340 --> 00:19:37.180
shipmate, and one, as I thought, on his retreat. He bade me go and leave the door wide open.

00:19:37.780 --> 00:19:43.520
None of y'all kiosks for me, sonny, he said, and I left them together and retired into the bar.

00:19:44.980 --> 00:19:49.560
For a long time, though I certainly did my best to listen, I could hear nothing but a low gabbling,

00:19:49.980 --> 00:19:53.860
but at last the voices began to grow higher, and I could pick up a word or two,

00:19:54.020 --> 00:20:01.140
mostly oaths from the captain. No, no, no, no, in an end of it, he cried once. And again,

00:20:01.140 --> 00:20:07.320
if it comes to swinging, swing all, say I. Then all of a sudden there was a tremendous explosion

00:20:07.320 --> 00:20:12.240
of oaths and other noises. The chair and table went over in a lump, a clash of steel followed,

00:20:12.640 --> 00:20:18.200
and then a cry of pain, and the next instant I saw a black dog in full flight, and the captain

00:20:18.200 --> 00:20:23.380
huntly pursuing, both with drawn cutlasses, and the former streaming blood from the left shoulder.

00:20:25.040 --> 00:20:30.180
Just at the door, the captain aimed at the fugitive, one last tremendous cut, which would

00:20:30.180 --> 00:20:34.920
certainly have split him to the chin had it not been intercepted by our big signboard of Admiral

00:20:34.920 --> 00:20:39.200
Benbow. You may see the notch on the lower side of the frame to this day.

00:20:41.140 --> 00:20:47.320
That blow was the last of the battle. Once out upon the road, Black Dog, in spite of his wound,

00:20:47.880 --> 00:20:52.640
showed a wonderful clean pair of heels and disappeared over the edge of the hill in half a minute.

00:20:54.700 --> 00:20:58.920
The captain, for his part, stood staring at the signboard like a bewildered man.

00:20:58.920 --> 00:21:04.500
Then he passed his hand over his eyes several times, and at last turned back into the house.

00:21:05.380 --> 00:21:11.740
Jim! says he. Rum! And as he spoke, he reeled a little, and caught himself with one hand

00:21:11.740 --> 00:21:20.940
against the wall. Are you hurt? cried I. Rum! he repeated. I must get away from here. Rum! Rum!

00:21:22.520 --> 00:21:27.800
I ran to fetch it, but I was quite unsteadied by all that had fallen out, and I broke one glass

00:21:27.800 --> 00:21:33.240
and fouled the tap, and while I was still getting in my own way, I heard a loud fall in the parlor,

00:21:33.440 --> 00:21:39.540
and running in, beheld the captain lying full length upon the floor. At the same instant,

00:21:39.700 --> 00:21:44.940
my mother, alarmed by the cries and fighting, came running downstairs to help me. Between us

00:21:44.940 --> 00:21:50.860
we raised his head. He was breathing very loud and hard, but his eyes were closed and his face

00:21:50.860 --> 00:21:56.060
a horrible color. Dear, dearie me! cried my mother. What a disgrace upon the house,

00:21:56.060 --> 00:22:02.540
and your poor father sick! In the meantime, we had no idea what to do to help the captain,

00:22:03.060 --> 00:22:06.700
nor any other thought but that he had got his death-hurt in the scuffle with the stranger.

00:22:08.020 --> 00:22:13.140
I got the rum, to be sure, and tried to put it down his throat, but his teeth were tightly shut,

00:22:13.260 --> 00:22:18.880
and his jaws as strong as iron. It was a happy relief for us when the door opened,

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:25.580
and Dr. Livesey came in on his visit to my father. Oh, doctor! we cried. What shall we do?

00:22:25.580 --> 00:22:32.300
Where is he wounded? Wounded? A fiddlesticks end, said the doctor. No more wounded than you or I.

00:22:32.500 --> 00:22:36.900
The man has had a stroke, as I warned him. Now, Mrs. Hawkins, just you run upstairs to your husband

00:22:36.900 --> 00:22:41.900
and tell him, if possible, nothing about it. For my part, I must do my best to save this fellow's

00:22:41.900 --> 00:22:49.460
trebly worthless life. Jim, you get me a basin. When I got back with the basin, the doctor had

00:22:49.460 --> 00:22:54.760
already ripped up the captain's sleeve and exposed his great sinewy arm. It was tattooed

00:22:54.760 --> 00:23:01.920
several places. Here's Luck, A Fair Wind, and Billy Bones' Fancy were very neatly and clearly

00:23:01.920 --> 00:23:07.220
executed on the forearm, and up near the shoulder there was a sketch of a gallows and a man hanging

00:23:07.220 --> 00:23:13.900
from it, done, as I thought, with great spirit. Prophetic, said the doctor, touching this picture

00:23:13.900 --> 00:23:22.140
with his finger. And now, Master Billy Bones, if that be your name, we'll have a look at the

00:23:22.140 --> 00:23:29.860
blood. No, sir, said I. Well, then, said he, you hold the basin, and with that he took his lancet

00:23:29.860 --> 00:23:36.920
and opened a vein. A great deal of blood was taken before the captain opened his eyes and looked

00:23:36.920 --> 00:23:43.540
mystically about him. First he recognized the doctor with an unmistakable frown. Then his glance

00:23:43.540 --> 00:23:49.840
fell upon me, and he looked relieved. But suddenly his colour changed, and he tried to raise himself,

00:23:49.840 --> 00:23:57.020
crying, Where is Black Dog? There is no Black Dog here, said the doctor, except what you have

00:23:57.020 --> 00:24:02.040
on your own back. You have been drinking rum. You have had a stroke, precisely as I told you,

00:24:02.040 --> 00:24:06.640
and I have just, very much against my own will, dragged you head-for-most out of the grave.

00:24:07.160 --> 00:24:14.140
Now, Mr. Bones, that's not my name, he interrupted. Much I care, returned the doctor. It's the name

00:24:14.140 --> 00:24:18.340
of a buccaneer of my acquaintance, and I call you by it for the sake of shortness, and what I have

00:24:18.340 --> 00:24:23.560
to say to you is this. One glass of rum won't kill you, but if you take one, you'll take another,

00:24:23.680 --> 00:24:29.200
and another, and I stick my wig, if you don't break off short, you'll die. Do you understand that? Die

00:24:29.200 --> 00:24:34.100
and go to your own place, like the man in the Bible. Come now, make an effort, I'll help you

00:24:34.100 --> 00:24:39.920
to your bed for once. Between us, with much trouble, we managed to hoist him upstairs,

00:24:40.260 --> 00:24:44.340
and laid him on his bed, where his head fell back on the pillow, as if he were almost fainting.

00:24:45.740 --> 00:24:51.300
Now, mind you, said the doctor, I clear my conscience, the name of rum for you is death.

00:24:52.420 --> 00:24:56.000
And with that, he went off to see my father, taking me with him by the arm.

00:24:57.760 --> 00:25:02.820
This is nothing, he said, as soon as he had closed the door. I have drawn blood enough to keep him

00:25:02.820 --> 00:25:07.940
quiet a while. He should lie for a week where he is. That is the best thing for him and you,

00:25:08.140 --> 00:25:10.480
but another stroke would settle him.

00:25:15.260 --> 00:25:19.340
Recorded October 10th, 2005, in Longmont, Colorado.

00:25:40.240 --> 00:25:41.120
III.

00:25:42.500 --> 00:25:48.500
THE BLACK SPOT About noon I stopped at the captain's door

00:25:48.500 --> 00:25:54.500
at some cooling drinks and medicines. He was lying very much as we had left him, only a little

00:25:54.500 --> 00:26:00.040
higher, and he seemed both weak and excited. "'Jim,' he said,

00:26:00.180 --> 00:26:05.480
"'you're the only one here that's worth anything, and you know I've always been good to you.

00:26:06.040 --> 00:26:11.420
Never a month but I've given you a silver fourpenny for yourself, and now you see, mate,

00:26:11.420 --> 00:26:19.440
I'm pretty low and deserted by all. And, Jim, you'll bring me one noggin of rum now, won't you, matey?'

00:26:20.380 --> 00:26:26.960
"'The doctor,' I began, but he broke in cursing the doctor in a feeble voice but heartily.

00:26:27.640 --> 00:26:32.700
"'Doctors is all swabs,' he said. "'And that doctor there, why,

00:26:33.260 --> 00:26:37.960
what do he know about seafarin men? I've been in places hot as pitch,

00:26:37.960 --> 00:26:44.620
and mates droppin round with yellowjack, and the blessed land a-heavin' like the sea with earthquakes.

00:26:45.900 --> 00:26:51.320
What did the doctor know of lands like that? And I lived on rum, I tell you.

00:26:52.400 --> 00:26:58.300
It's been meat and drink and man and wife to me, and if I'm not to have my rum now,

00:26:58.980 --> 00:27:05.160
I'm a poor old hulk on a lee shore, my blood'll be on you, Jim, and that doctor swab.'

00:27:06.120 --> 00:27:09.180
And he ran on again for a while with curses.

00:27:10.980 --> 00:27:17.460
"'Look, Jim, how my fingers fidges,' he continued in the pleading tone.

00:27:18.420 --> 00:27:24.260
"'I can't keep him still, not I. I haven't had a drop this blessed day.

00:27:24.800 --> 00:27:32.360
That doctor's a fool, I tell you. If I don't have a drain of rum, Jim, I'll have the horrors.

00:27:33.720 --> 00:27:40.780
"'I've seen some on him already. I've seen old Flint in the corner there behind you.

00:27:41.040 --> 00:27:48.560
His plain is print, I've seen him, and if I get the horrors, I'm a man that has lived rough,

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:54.020
and I'll raise cane. Your doctor himself said one glass wouldn't hurt me.

00:27:54.600 --> 00:27:59.040
I'll give you a golden guinea for a noggin, Jim.'

00:27:59.040 --> 00:28:02.880
He was growing more and more excited, and this alarmed me,

00:28:03.700 --> 00:28:10.920
for my father, who was very low that day and needed quiet. Besides, I was reassured by the

00:28:10.920 --> 00:28:16.500
doctor's words, now quoted to me, and rather offended by the offer of a bribe.

00:28:17.400 --> 00:28:24.820
"'I want none of your money,' said I, "'but what you owe my father. I'll get you one glass and no

00:28:24.820 --> 00:28:34.000
more.' When I brought it to him, he seized it greedily and drank it out. "'I, I,' said he,

00:28:34.400 --> 00:28:43.340
"'that's some better, sure enough.' And now, Meady, did that doctor say how long I was to lie here in

00:28:43.340 --> 00:28:53.100
this old berth? "'A week at least,' said I. "'Thunder!' he cried. "'A week? I can't do that.

00:28:53.660 --> 00:28:59.760
They'd have the black spot on me by then. The Lubbers is going about to get the wind of me

00:28:59.760 --> 00:29:06.040
this blessed moment. Lubbers as couldn't keep what they got, and want to nail what is in others.

00:29:06.960 --> 00:29:15.520
Is that seemingly behaviour now I want to know? But I am a saving soul. I never wasted good money

00:29:16.120 --> 00:29:23.640
nor lost it neither, and I'll trick them again. I'm not afraid on them. I'll shake out another

00:29:23.640 --> 00:29:29.820
reef, Meady, and dattle them again.' As he was thus speaking, he had risen from bed with great

00:29:29.820 --> 00:29:36.240
difficulty, holding to my shoulder with a grip that almost made me cry out, and moving his legs

00:29:36.240 --> 00:29:43.240
like so much dead weight. His words, spirited as they were in meaning, contrasted sadly with

00:29:43.240 --> 00:29:48.100
the weakness of the voice in which they were uttered. He paused when he had got into a sitting

00:29:48.100 --> 00:29:57.540
position on the edge. "'The doctor's done me,' he murmured. "'My ears is singing. Lay me back.'

00:29:58.520 --> 00:30:03.160
Before I could do much to help him, he had fallen back again to his former place,

00:30:03.600 --> 00:30:09.520
where he lay for a while silent. "'Jim,' he said at length,

00:30:10.060 --> 00:30:16.160
"'You saw that sea-faring man today.' "'Black dog?' I asked.

00:30:16.700 --> 00:30:25.580
"'Ah, black dog,' says he. "'He's a badden, but there's worse that put him on.

00:30:26.500 --> 00:30:33.100
Now, if I can't get away no how, and he tipped me the black spot, mind you,

00:30:33.720 --> 00:30:40.900
it's my old sea-chest thereafter. You get on a horse. You can, can't you?

00:30:41.520 --> 00:30:50.900
Well, then, you get on a horse, and go to—well, yes, I will—to that eternal doctor swab,

00:30:51.700 --> 00:30:59.880
and tell him to pipe all hands, magistrates and sitch, and he'll lay him aboard at the Admiral

00:30:59.880 --> 00:31:11.420
Benbow, all old Flint's crew, man and boy, all on him that's left. I was first mate, I was. Old

00:31:11.420 --> 00:31:18.360
Flint's first mate, and I'm the only one as knows the place. He gave it me at Savannah,

00:31:18.980 --> 00:31:28.520
when he lay a-dying, like as if I was to now, you see. But you won't peach unless they get the black

00:31:28.520 --> 00:31:38.730
spot on me, or unless you see that black dog again, or a seafairman with one leg. Jim, him above all.'

00:31:39.480 --> 00:31:47.140
"'But what is the black spot, Captain?' I asked. "'That's a summons mate. I'll tell you if they get

00:31:47.140 --> 00:31:54.590
that. But you keep your weather-eye open, Jim, and I'll share with you equals, upon my honour.'

00:31:55.810 --> 00:32:02.990
"'He wandered a little longer, his voice growing weaker. But soon after I had given him his medicine,

00:32:02.990 --> 00:32:09.870
which he took like a child, with the remark, If ever a seaman wanted drugs, it's me. He fell

00:32:09.870 --> 00:32:17.010
at last into a heavy, swoon-like sleep, in which I left him. What I should have done had all gone

00:32:17.010 --> 00:32:23.150
well, I do not know. Probably I should have told the whole story to the doctor, for I was in mortal

00:32:23.150 --> 00:32:28.210
fear lest the Captain should repent of his confessions and make an end of me. But as things

00:32:28.210 --> 00:32:34.990
fill out, my poor father died quite suddenly that evening, which put all other matters on one side.

00:32:36.490 --> 00:32:41.890
Our natural distress, the visits of the neighbours, the arranging of the funeral,

00:32:42.330 --> 00:32:47.470
and all the work of the inn to be carried on in the meanwhile, kept me so busy that I had

00:32:47.470 --> 00:32:51.090
scarcely time to think of the Captain, far less to be afraid of him.

00:32:53.150 --> 00:32:59.530
On the night before the funeral he was as drunk as ever, and it was shocking in that house of

00:32:59.530 --> 00:33:06.990
mourning to hear him singing away at his ugly old sea-song. But weak as he was, we were all in the

00:33:06.990 --> 00:33:13.070
fear of death for him, and the doctor was suddenly taken up with a case many miles away and was never

00:33:13.070 --> 00:33:19.890
near the house after my father's death. I have said the Captain was weak, and indeed he seemed

00:33:19.890 --> 00:33:26.610
rather to grow weaker than regain his strength. He clambered up and down stairs, and went from the

00:33:26.610 --> 00:33:31.630
parlour to the bar and back again, and sometimes put his nose out of doors to smell the sea,

00:33:32.130 --> 00:33:39.070
holding on to the walls as he went for support and breathing hard and fast like a man on a steep

00:33:39.070 --> 00:33:46.830
mountain. He never particularly addressed me, and it is my belief he had as good as forgotten his

00:33:46.830 --> 00:33:54.910
confidences. But his temper was more flighty and allowing for his bodily weakness more violent than

00:33:54.910 --> 00:34:02.370
ever. He had an alarming way now when he was drunk of drawing his cutlass and laying it bare before

00:34:02.370 --> 00:34:09.770
him on the table. But with all that, he minded people less and seemed shut up in his own thoughts

00:34:09.770 --> 00:34:19.650
and rather wandering. Once, for instance, to our extreme wonder, he piped up to a different air,

00:34:20.450 --> 00:34:27.530
kind of country love song that he must have learned in his youth before he had begun to follow the sea.

00:34:29.330 --> 00:34:36.870
So things passed until the day after the funeral, and about three o'clock of a bitter, foggy,

00:34:36.870 --> 00:34:43.570
frosty afternoon I was standing at the door for a moment, full of sad thoughts about my father,

00:34:44.330 --> 00:34:52.150
when I saw someone drawing slowly near along the road. He was plainly blind, for he tapped before

00:34:52.150 --> 00:35:00.610
him with a stick and wore a great green shade over his eyes and nose, and he was hunched as if with

00:35:00.610 --> 00:35:08.010
age or weakness, and wore a huge old tattered sea cloak with a hood that made him appear

00:35:08.010 --> 00:35:15.930
positively deformed. I never saw in my life a more dreadful looking figure. He stopped a little from

00:35:15.930 --> 00:35:21.630
the inn and, raising his voice in an odd sing song, addressed the air in front of him.

00:35:22.490 --> 00:35:29.330
Will any kind friend inform a poor blind man who has lost the precious sight of his eyes and the

00:35:29.330 --> 00:35:36.090
defense of his native country, England, and God bless King George, where or in what part

00:35:36.090 --> 00:35:42.110
of this country he may now be? You are at the Admiral Benbow, Blackhill Cove, my good man,

00:35:42.150 --> 00:35:52.590
said I. I hear a voice, said he, a young voice. Will you give me your hand, my kind young friend,

00:35:52.590 --> 00:36:00.990
and lead me in? I held out my hand, and the horrible soft-spoken eyeless creature gripped

00:36:00.990 --> 00:36:08.090
it in a moment like a vice. I was so startled that I struggled to withdraw, but the blind man

00:36:08.090 --> 00:36:15.970
pulled me close up to him with a single action of his arm. Now, boy, he said, take me in to the

00:36:15.970 --> 00:36:26.090
captain. Sir, said I. Upon my word, I dare not. Oh, he sneered, that's it. Take me in straight,

00:36:26.110 --> 00:36:34.410
or I'll break your arm. And he gave it as he spoke a wrench that made me cry out. Sir, said I. It is

00:36:34.410 --> 00:36:38.470
for yourself, I mean. The captain is not what he used to be. He sits with the drawn cutlass,

00:36:38.470 --> 00:36:46.950
another gentleman. Come now, march, interrupted he, and I never heard a voice so cruel and cold

00:36:46.950 --> 00:36:53.130
and ugly as that blind man's. Cowed me more than the pain, I began to obey him at once,

00:36:53.830 --> 00:36:58.630
walking straight in at the door and towards the parlour, where our sick old buccaneer was sitting,

00:36:58.810 --> 00:37:06.830
dazed with rum. The blind man clung close to me, holding me in one iron fist, and leaning almost

00:37:06.830 --> 00:37:13.690
more of his weight on me than I could carry. Lead me straight up to him, and when I'm in view,

00:37:13.790 --> 00:37:22.730
cry out. Here's a friend for you, Bill. If you don't, I'll do this. And with that he gave me a

00:37:22.730 --> 00:37:28.970
twitch that I thought would have made me faint. Between this and that I was so utterly terrified

00:37:28.970 --> 00:37:34.410
of the blind beggar that I forgot my terror of the captain, and as I opened the parlour door,

00:37:34.410 --> 00:37:37.590
cried out the words he had ordered in a trembling voice.

00:37:39.230 --> 00:37:45.850
The poor captain raised his eyes, and at one look the rum went out of him and left him staring

00:37:45.850 --> 00:37:52.030
sober. The expression of his face was not so much of terror as of mortal sickness.

00:37:53.750 --> 00:37:59.650
He made a movement to rise, but I do not believe he had enough force left in his body.

00:38:00.630 --> 00:38:09.390
Now, Bill, sit where you are, said the beggar. If I can't see, I can hear a finger steering.

00:38:10.670 --> 00:38:20.610
Business is business. Hold out your left hand. Boy, take his left hand by the wrist,

00:38:21.230 --> 00:38:27.850
and bring it near to my right. We both obeyed him to the letter, and I saw him pass something

00:38:27.850 --> 00:38:32.670
from the hollow of the hand that held his stick into the palm of the captain's,

00:38:32.670 --> 00:38:34.370
which closed upon it instantly.

00:38:35.850 --> 00:38:41.850
And now that's done, said the blind man, and at the words he suddenly left hold of me,

00:38:41.930 --> 00:38:46.870
and with incredible accuracy and nimbleness, skipped out of the parlour and into the road,

00:38:47.350 --> 00:38:55.770
where, as I still stood motionless, I could hear his stick go tap, tap, tapping into the distance.

00:38:56.410 --> 00:39:01.270
It was some time before either I or the captain seemed to gather our senses,

00:39:02.030 --> 00:39:07.550
but at length, and about at the same moment, I released his wrist, which I was still holding,

00:39:08.110 --> 00:39:11.130
and he drew in his hand and looked sharply into the palm.

00:39:13.470 --> 00:39:21.350
Ten o'clock, he cried. Six hours. We'll do them yet. And he sprang to his feet.

00:39:22.070 --> 00:39:29.250
Even as he did so, he reeled, put his hand to his throat, stood swaying for a moment,

00:39:29.850 --> 00:39:36.990
and then, with a peculiar sound, fell from his whole height face foremost to the floor.

00:39:38.090 --> 00:39:43.170
I ran to him at once, calling to my mother, but haste was all in vain.

00:39:44.510 --> 00:39:48.790
The captain had been struck dead by thundering apoplexy.

00:39:50.150 --> 00:39:56.290
It is a curious thing to understand, for I had certainly never liked the man,

00:39:56.850 --> 00:40:02.730
though of late I had begun to pity him, but as soon as I saw that he was dead,

00:40:03.290 --> 00:40:08.790
I burst into a flood of tears. It was the second death I had known,

00:40:09.350 --> 00:40:13.910
and the sorrow of the first was still fresh in my heart.

00:40:20.110 --> 00:40:22.910
Chapter 4 The Sea Chest

00:40:24.330 --> 00:40:27.990
I lost no time, of course, in telling my mother all that I knew,

00:40:28.590 --> 00:40:33.630
and perhaps should have told her long before, and we saw ourselves at once in a difficult

00:40:33.630 --> 00:40:40.290
and dangerous position. Some of the man's money, if he had any, was certainly due to us,

00:40:40.890 --> 00:40:46.190
but it was not likely that our captain's shipmates, above all the two specimens seen by me,

00:40:46.190 --> 00:40:52.350
Black Dog and the Blind Beggar, would be inclined to give up their booty in payment of the dead

00:40:52.350 --> 00:40:59.350
man's debts. The captain's order to mount at once and ride for Dr. Livesey would have left my mother

00:40:59.350 --> 00:41:06.350
alone and unprotected, which was not to be thought of. Indeed, it seemed impossible for either of us

00:41:06.350 --> 00:41:12.530
to remain much longer in the house. The fall of coals in the kitchen grate, the very ticking of

00:41:12.530 --> 00:41:19.030
the clock filled us with alarms. The neighbourhood, to our ears, seemed haunted by approaching

00:41:19.030 --> 00:41:25.090
footsteps, and what between the dead body of the captain on the parlour floor and the thought of

00:41:25.090 --> 00:41:31.850
that detestable Blind Beggar hovering near at hand and ready to return, there were moments when,

00:41:32.150 --> 00:41:39.510
as the saying goes, I jumped in my skin for terror. Something must speedily be resolved upon,

00:41:40.220 --> 00:41:46.230
and it occurred to us at last to go forth together and seek help in the neighbouring hamlet,

00:41:46.550 --> 00:41:52.990
no sooner said than done. Bareheaded as we were, we ran out at once in the gathering evening

00:41:52.990 --> 00:42:01.390
and the frosty fog. The hamlet lay not many hundred yards away, though out of view,

00:42:01.690 --> 00:42:07.310
on the other side of the next cove, and what greatly encouraged me, it was in an opposite

00:42:07.310 --> 00:42:12.170
direction from that whence the blind man had made his appearance and whither he had presumably

00:42:12.170 --> 00:42:19.690
returned. We were not many minutes on the road, though we sometimes stopped to lay hold of each

00:42:19.690 --> 00:42:26.850
other and hearken, but there was no unusual sound, nothing but the low wash of the ripple

00:42:26.850 --> 00:42:34.050
and the croaking of the inmates of the woods. It was already candlelight when we reached the hamlet,

00:42:34.670 --> 00:42:40.470
and I shall never forget how much I was cheered to see the yellow shine in doors and windows,

00:42:41.130 --> 00:42:46.330
but that, as it proved, was the best of the help we were likely to get in that quarter,

00:42:47.570 --> 00:42:54.690
for you would have thought men have been ashamed of themselves. No soul would consent to return

00:42:54.690 --> 00:43:01.850
with us to the Admiral Benbow. The more we told of our troubles, the more man, woman and child

00:43:01.850 --> 00:43:08.750
they clung to the shelter of their houses. The name of Captain Flint, though it was strange to me,

00:43:09.110 --> 00:43:13.910
was well enough known to some there and carried a great weight of terror.

00:43:15.310 --> 00:43:20.530
Some of the men who had been to field work on the far side of the Admiral Benbow remembered,

00:43:21.050 --> 00:43:26.530
besides, to have seen several strangers on the road, and taking them to be smugglers,

00:43:26.530 --> 00:43:34.430
to have bolted away, and one at least had seen a little lugger in what we called Kitt's Hole.

00:43:35.130 --> 00:43:41.250
For that matter, anyone who was a comrade of the captain's was enough to frighten them to death,

00:43:41.710 --> 00:43:47.550
and the short and the long of the matter was that while we could get several who were willing enough

00:43:47.550 --> 00:43:54.790
to ride to Dr. Livesey's, which lay in another direction, not one would help us to defend the inn.

00:43:56.530 --> 00:44:03.550
They say cowardice is infectious, but then argument is, on the other hand, a great emboldener,

00:44:04.050 --> 00:44:08.230
and so when each had said his say, my mother made them a speech.

00:44:09.130 --> 00:44:14.070
She would not, she declared, lose money that belonged to her fatherless boy.

00:44:15.090 --> 00:44:22.250
If none of the rest of you dare, she said, Jim and I dare. Back we will go, the way we came,

00:44:22.250 --> 00:44:28.830
and small thanks to you big hulking chicken-hearted men. We'll have that chest open

00:44:28.830 --> 00:44:36.110
if we die for it, and I'll thank you for that bag, Mrs. Crusley, to bring back our lawful money in.

00:44:37.330 --> 00:44:42.310
Of course I said I would go with my mother, and of course they all cried out at our foolhardiness,

00:44:43.050 --> 00:44:50.090
but even then not a man would go along with us. All they would do was to give me a loaded pistol

00:44:50.090 --> 00:44:55.770
lest we were attacked, and to promise to have our horses ready saddled in case we were pursued on

00:44:55.770 --> 00:45:01.410
our return, while one lad was to ride forward to the doctors in search of armed assistance.

00:45:02.790 --> 00:45:09.530
My heart was beating finally when we too set forth in the cold night upon this dangerous venture.

00:45:10.150 --> 00:45:15.690
A full moon was beginning to rise and peered readily through the upper edges of the fog,

00:45:15.690 --> 00:45:20.870
and this increased our haste, for it was plain, before we came forth again,

00:45:21.210 --> 00:45:26.710
that all would be as bright as day, and our departure exposed to the eyes of any watchers.

00:45:27.590 --> 00:45:34.370
We slipped along the hedges, noiseless and swift, nor did we see or hear anything to increase our

00:45:34.370 --> 00:45:40.410
terrors, till, to our relief, the door of the Admiral Benbow had closed behind us.

00:45:41.550 --> 00:45:47.810
I slipped the bolt at once, and we stood and panted for a moment in the dark, alone in the

00:45:47.810 --> 00:45:54.150
house with the dead captain's body. Then my mother got a candle in the bar, and holding each other's

00:45:54.150 --> 00:46:01.950
hands, we advanced into the parlour. He lay as we had left him, on his back, with his eyes open

00:46:01.950 --> 00:46:03.890
and one arm stretched out.

00:46:05.190 --> 00:46:08.450
"'Draw down the blind, Jim,' whispered my mother.

00:46:09.170 --> 00:46:10.930
"'They might come and watch outside.'

00:46:12.490 --> 00:46:15.070
"'And now,' said she, when I had done so,

00:46:15.070 --> 00:46:22.010
"'we have to get the key off that. And who's to touch it, I should like to know.'

00:46:22.830 --> 00:46:25.630
And she gave a kind of sob as she said the words.

00:46:26.650 --> 00:46:30.450
I went down on my knees at once. On the floor,

00:46:30.450 --> 00:46:37.670
close to his hand, there was a little round of paper, blackened on the one side. I could not

00:46:37.670 --> 00:46:44.690
doubt that this was the black spot, and taking it up, I found written on the other side,

00:46:44.890 --> 00:46:48.370
in a very good, clear hand, this short message.

00:46:49.690 --> 00:46:52.310
"'You have till ten to-night.'

00:46:53.790 --> 00:46:57.970
"'He had till ten, mother,' said I, and just as I said it,

00:46:58.560 --> 00:47:04.130
our old clock began striking. This sudden noise startled us shockingly,

00:47:05.070 --> 00:47:08.170
but the news was good, for it was only six.

00:47:10.030 --> 00:47:11.950
"'Now, Jim,' she said,

00:47:12.390 --> 00:47:13.380
"'that key.'

00:47:14.650 --> 00:47:22.370
I felt in his pockets, one after another, a few small coins, a thimble, and some thread and big

00:47:22.370 --> 00:47:29.430
needles, a piece of pigtail tobacco bitten away at the end. His gully with the crooked handle,

00:47:30.370 --> 00:47:36.650
pocket compass, and a tinder box were all that they contained, and I began to despair.

00:47:37.990 --> 00:47:40.890
"'Perhaps it's round his neck,' suggested my mother.

00:47:42.210 --> 00:47:47.810
Overcoming a strong repugnance, I tore open his shirt at the neck, and there, sure enough,

00:47:47.810 --> 00:47:54.150
hanging to a bit of tarry string, which I cut with his own gully, we found the key.

00:47:54.890 --> 00:47:59.070
At this triumph we were filled with hope, and hurried upstairs without delay

00:47:59.070 --> 00:48:04.610
to the little room where he had slept so long, and where his box had stood since the day of his

00:48:04.610 --> 00:48:12.710
arrival. It was like any other seaman's chest on the outside. The initial B burned on the top of it,

00:48:12.710 --> 00:48:18.150
with a hot iron, and the corner somewhat smashed and broken as by long, rough usage.

00:48:18.730 --> 00:48:23.330
"'Give me the key,' said my mother. And though the lock was very stiff,

00:48:23.850 --> 00:48:26.930
she had turned it and thrown back the lid in a twinkling.

00:48:28.290 --> 00:48:36.750
A strong smell of tobacco and tar rose from the interior, but nothing was to be seen on the top

00:48:36.750 --> 00:48:43.210
except a suit of very good clothes, carefully brushed and folded. They had never been worn,'

00:48:43.210 --> 00:48:51.810
my mother said. Under that the miscellany began. A quadrant, a tin canikin, several sticks of

00:48:51.810 --> 00:49:00.030
tobacco, two brace of very handsome pistols, a piece of bar silver, an old Spanish watch,

00:49:00.510 --> 00:49:06.330
and some other trinkets of little value and mostly of foreign make, a pair of compasses

00:49:06.330 --> 00:49:14.510
mounted with brass, and five or six curious West Indian shells. I have often wondered since

00:49:14.510 --> 00:49:20.890
why he should have carried about these shells with him in his wandering, guilty, and hunted life.

00:49:22.310 --> 00:49:27.710
In the meantime, we had found nothing of any value but the silver and the trinkets,

00:49:28.050 --> 00:49:33.450
and neither of these were in our way. Underneath there was an old boat cloak,

00:49:33.450 --> 00:49:42.000
whitened with sea salt on many a harbour bar. My mother pulled it up with impatience, and there

00:49:42.510 --> 00:49:51.710
lay before us the last things in the chest, a bundle tied up in oilcloth and looking like papers,

00:49:52.490 --> 00:49:58.770
and a canvas bag that gave forth at a touch the jingle of gold.

00:50:00.750 --> 00:50:06.090
I'll show these rogues that I'm an honest woman, said my mother. I'll have my dues,

00:50:06.410 --> 00:50:12.170
and not a firething over. Hold Mr. Crossley's bag. And she began to count over the amount

00:50:12.170 --> 00:50:16.790
of the captain's score from the sailor's bag into the one that I was holding.

00:50:18.190 --> 00:50:23.270
It was a long, difficult business, for the coins were of all countries and sizes,

00:50:23.910 --> 00:50:30.410
doubloons and louis d'ores and guineas and pieces of eight, and I know not what besides,

00:50:30.850 --> 00:50:37.410
all shaken together at random. The guineas, too, were about the scarcest, and it was with

00:50:37.410 --> 00:50:43.910
these only that my mother knew how to make her count. When we were about halfway through,

00:50:44.170 --> 00:50:51.650
I suddenly put my hand upon her arm, for I had heard in the silent frosty air a sound

00:50:51.650 --> 00:51:00.370
that brought my heart into my mouth, the tap, tap, tapping of the blind man's stick

00:51:00.370 --> 00:51:07.910
upon the frozen road. It drew nearer and nearer while we sat holding our breath.

00:51:08.670 --> 00:51:14.970
Then it struck sharp on the inn door, and then we could hear the handle being turned and the bolt

00:51:14.970 --> 00:51:23.130
rattling as the wretched being tried to enter, and then there was a long time of silence,

00:51:23.770 --> 00:51:33.130
both within and without. At last the tapping recommenced, and to our indescribable joy and

00:51:33.130 --> 00:51:38.730
gratitude died slowly away again until it ceased to be heard.

00:51:41.070 --> 00:51:47.330
"'Mother,' said I, "'take the hole and let's be going,' for I was sure the bolted door must

00:51:47.330 --> 00:51:52.190
have seemed suspicious and would bring the whole hornet's nest about our ears,

00:51:53.070 --> 00:51:59.290
though how thankful I was that I had bolted it. None could tell who had never met that terrible

00:51:59.290 --> 00:52:07.030
blind man. But my mother, frightened as she was, would not consent to take a fraction more than was

00:52:07.030 --> 00:52:14.110
due to her, and was obstinately unwilling to be content with less. It was not yet seven, she said,

00:52:14.450 --> 00:52:20.550
by a long way. She knew her rights and she would have them, and she was still arguing with me

00:52:20.550 --> 00:52:27.370
when a little low whistle sounded a good way off upon the hill. That was enough, and more than

00:52:27.370 --> 00:52:32.910
enough for both of us. "'I'll take what I have,' she said, jumping to her feet.

00:52:33.530 --> 00:52:38.070
"'And I'll take this to square the count,' said I, picking up the oil-skin packet.

00:52:39.110 --> 00:52:43.790
Next moment we were both groping downstairs, leaving the candle by the empty chest.

00:52:45.030 --> 00:52:51.790
And the next we had opened the door and were in full retreat. We had not started a moment too soon.

00:52:52.570 --> 00:52:59.910
The fog was rapidly dispersing. Already the moon shone quite clear on the high ground on either side,

00:52:59.910 --> 00:53:05.750
and it was only in the exact bottom of the dell and round the tavern door that a thin

00:53:05.750 --> 00:53:13.070
veil still hung unbroken to conceal the first steps of our escape. Far less than halfway to

00:53:13.070 --> 00:53:18.550
the hamlet, very little beyond the bottom of the hill, we must come forth into the moonlight.

00:53:19.350 --> 00:53:24.850
Nor was this all, for the sound of several footsteps running came already to our ears,

00:53:24.850 --> 00:53:27.930
and as we looked back in their direction a light,

00:53:27.930 --> 00:53:33.590
tossing to and fro and still rapidly advancing, showed that one of the newcomers carried a lantern.

00:53:34.990 --> 00:53:37.490
"'My dear,' said my mother suddenly,

00:53:38.050 --> 00:53:44.150
"'take the money and run on. I'm going to faint.' This was certainly the end for both of us,

00:53:44.150 --> 00:53:50.870
I thought. How I cursed the cowardice of the neighbours! How I blamed my poor mother for her

00:53:50.870 --> 00:53:58.390
honesty and her greed, for her past foolhardiness and present weakness! We were just at the little

00:53:58.390 --> 00:54:05.050
bridge by good fortune, and I helped her, tottering as she was, to the edge of the bank,

00:54:05.490 --> 00:54:12.910
where, sure enough, she gave a sigh and fell on my shoulder. I do not know how I found the strength

00:54:12.910 --> 00:54:19.750
to do it at all, and I'm afraid it was roughly done, but I managed to drag her down the bank

00:54:19.750 --> 00:54:26.190
and a little way under the arch. Farther I could not move her, for the bridge was too low to let

00:54:26.190 --> 00:54:33.150
me do more than crawl below it. So there we had to stay, my mother almost entirely exposed,

00:54:33.650 --> 00:54:37.790
and both of us within earshot of the inn."

00:55:06.410 --> 00:55:09.210
CHAPTER V.

00:55:09.210 --> 00:55:12.450
THE LAST OF THE BLIND MAN.

00:55:14.270 --> 00:55:22.870
My curiosity, in a sense, was stronger than my fear, for I could not remain where I was, but crept back to the bank again,

00:55:23.070 --> 00:55:28.970
whence, sheltering my head behind a bush of broom, I might command the road before our door.

00:55:29.630 --> 00:55:39.430
I was scarcely in position ere my enemies began to arrive, seven or eight of them, running hard, their feet beating out of time along the road,

00:55:39.830 --> 00:55:42.550
and the man with the lantern some paces in front.

00:55:44.230 --> 00:55:52.430
Three men ran together, hand in hand, and I made out, even through the mist, that the middleman of this trio was the blind beggar.

00:55:53.250 --> 00:55:56.190
The next moment his voice showed me that I was right.

00:55:57.170 --> 00:55:59.790
Down with the door! he cried.

00:56:01.130 --> 00:56:08.910
Ay, ay, sir, answered two or three, and a rush was made upon the Admiral Benbow, the lantern bearer following,

00:56:09.410 --> 00:56:17.050
and then I could see them pause, and hear speeches passed in a lower key, as if they were surprised to find the door open.

00:56:17.830 --> 00:56:21.950
But the pause was brief, for the blind man again issued his command.

00:56:22.570 --> 00:56:28.250
His voice sounded louder and higher, as if he were afire with eagerness and rage.

00:56:29.390 --> 00:56:34.230
In, in, in! he shouted, and cursed them for their delay.

00:56:35.950 --> 00:56:41.650
Four or five of them obeyed at once, two remaining on the road with the formidable beggar.

00:56:42.470 --> 00:56:48.510
There was a pause, then a cry of surprise, and then a voice shouting from the house.

00:56:50.250 --> 00:56:51.290
Bill's dead!

00:56:52.730 --> 00:56:55.870
But the blind man swore at them again for their delay.

00:56:57.010 --> 00:57:03.150
Search him, some of you shirking lubbers, and the rest of you aloft, and get the chest! he cried.

00:57:04.250 --> 00:57:09.810
I could hear their feet rattling up our old stairs, so that the house must have shook with it.

00:57:10.550 --> 00:57:14.090
Promptly afterwards, fresh sounds of astonishment arose.

00:57:14.470 --> 00:57:19.610
The window of the captain's room was thrown open with a slam and a jingle of broken glass.

00:57:20.250 --> 00:57:23.570
And a man leaned out into the moonlight, head and shoulders,

00:57:23.970 --> 00:57:26.690
and addressed the blind beggar on the road below him.

00:57:27.550 --> 00:57:28.970
Pugh! he cried.

00:57:29.350 --> 00:57:30.810
They've been before us.

00:57:31.310 --> 00:57:34.030
Someone's turned the chest out, alow and aloft.

00:57:35.530 --> 00:57:38.150
Is it there? roared Pugh.

00:57:38.690 --> 00:57:40.090
The money's there.

00:57:41.750 --> 00:57:43.450
The blind man cursed the money.

00:57:45.090 --> 00:57:47.870
Flint's fist, I mean! he cried.

00:57:49.450 --> 00:57:52.190
We don't see it here no how, returned the man.

00:57:53.630 --> 00:57:58.330
Here, you below there. Is it on Bill? cried the blind man again.

00:58:00.050 --> 00:58:05.350
At that, another fellow, probably he who had remained below to search the captain's body,

00:58:05.770 --> 00:58:06.910
came to the door of the inn.

00:58:08.210 --> 00:58:12.150
Bill's been overhauled already, said he. Nothing left.

00:58:13.750 --> 00:58:16.310
It's these people of the inn. It's that boy.

00:58:16.630 --> 00:58:20.510
I wish I had put his eyes out, cried the blind man Pugh.

00:58:21.230 --> 00:58:22.770
They were here no time ago.

00:58:22.930 --> 00:58:25.090
They had the door bolted when I tried it.

00:58:25.330 --> 00:58:27.050
Scatter, lads, and find them.

00:58:28.730 --> 00:58:33.370
Sure enough, they left their glim here, said the fellow from the window.

00:58:34.850 --> 00:58:36.330
Scatter and find them.

00:58:36.550 --> 00:58:37.690
Route the house out.

00:58:38.370 --> 00:58:41.870
reiterated Pugh, striking with his stick upon the road.

00:58:43.890 --> 00:58:47.630
Then there followed a great to-do through all our old inn,

00:58:47.950 --> 00:58:51.430
heavy feet pounding to and fro, furniture thrown over,

00:58:51.730 --> 00:58:55.550
doors kicked in, until the very rocks re-echoed,

00:58:55.750 --> 00:58:58.770
and the men came out again one after another on the road,

00:58:59.230 --> 00:59:01.770
and declared that we were no where to be found.

00:59:03.350 --> 00:59:07.850
And just then the same whistle that had alarmed my mother and myself

00:59:07.850 --> 00:59:12.270
over the dead captain's money was once more clearly audible through the night,

00:59:12.670 --> 00:59:14.510
but this time twice repeated.

00:59:16.110 --> 00:59:19.510
I had thought it to be the blind man's trumpet, so to speak,

00:59:20.070 --> 00:59:24.410
summoning his crew to the assault, but I now found that it was a signal

00:59:24.410 --> 00:59:28.610
from the hillside towards the hamlet, and, from its effect upon the

00:59:28.610 --> 00:59:31.830
Buccaneers, a signal to warn them of approaching danger.

00:59:33.650 --> 00:59:36.070
There's Dirk again, said one.

00:59:36.630 --> 00:59:38.870
Twice. We'll have to budge, mates.

00:59:40.410 --> 00:59:42.890
Budge, you skulk, cried Pugh.

00:59:43.090 --> 00:59:45.590
Dirk was a fool and a coward from the first.

00:59:45.970 --> 00:59:47.010
You wouldn't mind him.

00:59:47.330 --> 00:59:48.670
They must be close by.

00:59:48.810 --> 00:59:49.810
They can't be far.

00:59:50.150 --> 00:59:51.390
You have your hands on it.

00:59:51.630 --> 00:59:53.170
Scatter and look for them, dogs.

00:59:53.570 --> 00:59:56.090
Oh, shiver my soul, he cried.

00:59:56.730 --> 00:59:58.070
If I had eyes.

00:59:59.630 --> 01:00:04.330
This appeal seemed to produce some effect, for two of the fellows began

01:00:04.330 --> 01:00:08.670
to look here and there among the lumber, but half-heartedly, I thought,

01:00:09.030 --> 01:00:12.110
and with half an eye to their own danger all the time,

01:00:12.330 --> 01:00:14.850
while the rest stood irresolute on the road.

01:00:16.610 --> 01:00:20.470
You have your hands on thousands, you fools, and you hang a leg.

01:00:20.930 --> 01:00:24.450
You'd be as rich as kings if you could find it, and you know it's here,

01:00:24.450 --> 01:00:26.150
and you stand there skulking.

01:00:26.490 --> 01:00:30.590
There wasn't one of you dared face, Bill, and I did it, a blind man,

01:00:30.830 --> 01:00:32.830
and I'm to lose my chance for you.

01:00:33.290 --> 01:00:37.450
I'm to be a poor crawling beggar sponging for rum,

01:00:37.750 --> 01:00:39.750
when I might be rolling in a coach.

01:00:40.270 --> 01:00:43.750
If you had the pluck of a weevil in a biscuit, you would catch them still.

01:00:45.750 --> 01:00:46.650
Hang it, Pugh.

01:00:46.810 --> 01:00:49.550
We've got the doubloons, grumbled one.

01:00:50.770 --> 01:00:53.750
They might have hid the blessed thing, said another.

01:00:53.750 --> 01:00:57.170
Take the Georges, Pugh, and don't stand here squalling.

01:00:58.910 --> 01:01:00.790
Squalling was the word for it.

01:01:01.070 --> 01:01:05.270
Pugh's anger rose so high at these objections, till at last,

01:01:05.510 --> 01:01:10.410
his passion completely taking the upper hand, he struck at them right and left

01:01:10.410 --> 01:01:14.570
in his blindness, and his stick sounded heavily on more than one.

01:01:15.930 --> 01:01:20.510
These, in their turn, cursed back at the blind miscreant, threatened him in

01:01:20.510 --> 01:01:25.370
terms, and tried in vain to catch the stick and wrest it from his grasp.

01:01:26.850 --> 01:01:31.350
This quarrel was the saving of us, for while it was still raging,

01:01:31.710 --> 01:01:35.310
another sound came from the top of the hill on the side of the hamlet,

01:01:35.850 --> 01:01:37.810
the tramp of horses galloping.

01:01:38.910 --> 01:01:44.910
Almost at the same time a pistol shot, flash and report, came from the hedge side.

01:01:45.670 --> 01:01:51.390
And that was plainly the last signal of danger, for the buccaneers turned at once

01:01:51.390 --> 01:01:57.730
and ran, separating in every direction, one seaward along the cove, one slant

01:01:57.730 --> 01:02:03.810
across the hill, and so on, so that in half a minute not a sign of them remained but Pugh.

01:02:05.310 --> 01:02:11.630
Him they had deserted, whether in sheer panic or out of revenge for his ill words and blows,

01:02:11.630 --> 01:02:17.850
I know not, but there he remained behind, tapping up and down the road in a frenzy

01:02:17.850 --> 01:02:20.430
and groping and calling for his comrades.

01:02:21.470 --> 01:02:26.870
Finally he took the wrong turn, and ran a few steps past me, towards the hamlet, crying,

01:02:28.010 --> 01:02:35.730
Johnny, Black Dog, Dirk, and other names, you won't leave old Pugh, mates, not old Pugh.

01:02:37.010 --> 01:02:40.030
Just then the noise of horses topped the rise,

01:02:40.450 --> 01:02:46.310
and four or five riders came in sight in the moonlight and swept at full gallop down the slope.

01:02:47.690 --> 01:02:54.350
At this Pugh saw his error, turned with a scream, and ran straight for the ditch into which he

01:02:54.350 --> 01:03:01.630
rolled. But he was on his feet again in a second, and made another dash, now utterly bewildered,

01:03:02.030 --> 01:03:04.470
right under the nearest of the coming horses.

01:03:05.730 --> 01:03:12.230
The rider tried to save him, but in vain. Down went Pugh with a cry that rang high into the night,

01:03:12.810 --> 01:03:20.250
and the four hoofs trampled and spurned him and passed by. He fell on his side, then gently

01:03:20.250 --> 01:03:27.590
collapsed upon his face, and moved no more. I leaped to my feet and hailed the riders.

01:03:28.290 --> 01:03:33.790
They were pulling up at any rate, horrified at the accident, and I soon saw what they were.

01:03:34.690 --> 01:03:40.890
One, tailing out behind the rest, was a lad that had gone from the hamlet to Dr. Livesey's.

01:03:41.170 --> 01:03:44.770
The rest were revenue officers whom he had met by the way,

01:03:45.110 --> 01:03:48.450
and with whom he had had the intelligence to return at once.

01:03:50.330 --> 01:03:54.970
Some news of the lugger in Kitt's Hole had found its way to Supervisor Dance,

01:03:55.470 --> 01:04:01.690
and set him forth that night in our direction, and to that circumstance my mother and I owed

01:04:01.690 --> 01:04:11.130
our preservation from death. Pugh was dead, stone dead. As for my mother, when we had carried her up

01:04:11.130 --> 01:04:17.710
to the hamlet, a little cold water and salts and that soon brought her back again, and she was none

01:04:17.710 --> 01:04:22.590
the worse for her terror, though she still continued to deplore the balance of the money.

01:04:24.310 --> 01:04:29.630
In the meantime, the supervisor rode on, as fast as he could, to Kitt's Hole,

01:04:30.170 --> 01:04:36.690
but his men had to dismount and grope down the dingle, leading and sometimes supporting their

01:04:36.690 --> 01:04:43.410
horses, and in continual fear of ambushes. So it was no great matter for surprise that when they

01:04:43.410 --> 01:04:50.650
got down to the hole the lugger was already under way, though still close in. He hailed her.

01:04:51.750 --> 01:04:57.150
A voice replied, telling him to keep out of the moonlight or he would get some lead in him,

01:04:57.150 --> 01:05:01.210
and at the same time a bullet whistled close by his arm.

01:05:02.770 --> 01:05:05.930
Soon after the lugger doubled the point and disappeared.

01:05:07.650 --> 01:05:15.250
Mr. Dance stood there, as he said, like a fish out of water, and all he could do was to dispatch a

01:05:15.250 --> 01:05:24.410
man to be, to warn the cutter. And that, said he, is just about as good as nothing. They've got off

01:05:24.410 --> 01:05:34.090
clean, and there's an end. Only, he added, I'm glad I trod on Master Pew's corns, for by this time

01:05:34.090 --> 01:05:42.530
he had heard my story. I went back with him to the Admiral Benbow, and you cannot imagine a house in

01:05:42.530 --> 01:05:48.670
such a state of smash. The very clock had been thrown down by these fellows in their furious

01:05:48.670 --> 01:05:54.330
hunt after my mother and myself, and though nothing had actually been taken away except

01:05:54.330 --> 01:06:00.490
the captain's money-bag and a little silver from the till, I could see at once that we were ruined.

01:06:01.770 --> 01:06:03.990
Mr. Dance could make nothing of the scene.

01:06:05.370 --> 01:06:12.090
They got the money, you say? Well then, Hawkins, what in fortune were they after? More money,

01:06:12.090 --> 01:06:18.090
I suppose? No, sir, not money, I think, replied I.

01:06:18.670 --> 01:06:22.990
In fact, sir, I believe I have the thing in my breast-pocket,

01:06:23.330 --> 01:06:27.190
and, to tell you the truth, I should like to get it put in safety.

01:06:28.490 --> 01:06:33.270
To be sure, boy, quite right, said he. I'll take it, if you like.

01:06:34.670 --> 01:06:38.730
I thought, perhaps, Dr. Livesey, I began.

01:06:40.050 --> 01:06:46.490
Perfectly right, he interrupted, very cheerily. Perfectly right. A gentleman and a magistrate.

01:06:47.030 --> 01:06:51.870
And, now I come to think of it, I might as well ride round there myself,

01:06:52.150 --> 01:06:59.050
and report to him more squire. Master Pugh's dead, when all's done. Not that I regret it,

01:06:59.050 --> 01:07:04.170
but he's dead, you see, and people will make it out against an officer of His Majesty's revenue,

01:07:04.410 --> 01:07:10.570
if make it out they can. Now I'll tell you, Hawkins, if you like, I'll take you along.

01:07:11.850 --> 01:07:17.510
I thanked him heartily for the offer, and we walked back to the hamlet where the horses were.

01:07:18.430 --> 01:07:22.070
By the time I had told mother of my purpose, they were all in the saddle.

01:07:24.210 --> 01:07:29.570
Dogger, said Mr. Dance, you have a good horse. Take up this lad behind you.

01:07:30.830 --> 01:07:37.550
As soon as I was mounted, holding on to Dogger's belt, the supervisor gave the word, and the party

01:07:37.550 --> 01:07:41.910
struck out at a bouncing trot on the road to Dr. Livesey's house.

01:07:47.390 --> 01:07:50.430
CHAPTER VI THE CAPTAIN'S PAPERS

01:07:52.090 --> 01:07:59.150
We rode hard all the way till we drew up before Dr. Livesey's door. The house was all dark to the

01:07:59.150 --> 01:08:05.950
front. Mr. Dance told me to jump down and knock, and Dogger gave me a stirrup to descend by.

01:08:06.590 --> 01:08:09.250
The door was opened almost at once by the maid.

01:08:10.490 --> 01:08:13.310
Is Dr. Livesey in? I asked.

01:08:14.730 --> 01:08:18.490
No, she said. He had come home in the afternoon,

01:08:18.770 --> 01:08:22.950
but had gone up to the hall to dine and pass the evening with the squire.

01:08:24.390 --> 01:08:27.690
So there we go, boys, said Mr. Dance.

01:08:28.950 --> 01:08:32.170
This time, as the distance was short, I did not mount,

01:08:32.170 --> 01:08:39.630
but ran with Dogger's stirrup leather to the lodge gates, and up the long, leafless, moonlit avenue

01:08:39.630 --> 01:08:45.370
to where the white line of the hall buildings looked on either hand on great old gardens.

01:08:46.650 --> 01:08:53.250
Here Mr. Dance dismounted, and, taking me along with him, was admitted at a word into the house.

01:08:54.370 --> 01:09:00.130
The servant led us down a matted passage, and showed us at the end into a great library,

01:09:00.130 --> 01:09:06.970
all lined with bookcases and busts upon the top of them, where the squire and Dr. Livesey sat,

01:09:07.350 --> 01:09:10.370
pipe in hand, on either side of a bright fire.

01:09:11.770 --> 01:09:19.170
I had never seen the squire so near at hand. He was a tall man, over six feet high and broad in

01:09:19.170 --> 01:09:26.690
proportion, and he had a bluff, rough and ready face, all roughened and reddened and lined in his

01:09:26.690 --> 01:09:34.530
long travels. His eyebrows were very black and moved readily, and this gave him a look of some

01:09:34.530 --> 01:09:44.510
temper, not bad, you would say, but quick and high. Come in, Mr. Dance, says he, very stately

01:09:44.510 --> 01:09:51.970
and condescending. Good evening, Dance, says the doctor, with a nod. And good evening to you,

01:09:51.970 --> 01:09:59.510
friend Jim. What good wind brings you here? The supervisor stood up straight and stiff,

01:09:59.990 --> 01:10:05.550
and told his story like a lesson, and you should have seen how the two gentlemen leaned forward

01:10:05.550 --> 01:10:10.090
and looked at each other, and forgot to smoke in their surprise and interest.

01:10:11.570 --> 01:10:17.630
When they heard how my mother went back to the inn, Dr. Livesey fairly slapped his thigh,

01:10:17.630 --> 01:10:23.570
and the squire cried, Bravo! and broke his long pipe against the grate.

01:10:25.230 --> 01:10:31.350
Long before it was done, Mr. Trelawney, that, you will remember, was the squire's name,

01:10:31.950 --> 01:10:38.450
had got up from his seat and was striding about the room, and the doctor, as if to hear the better,

01:10:38.970 --> 01:10:44.490
had taken off his powdered wig and sat there looking very strange indeed with his own

01:10:44.490 --> 01:10:50.710
close-cropped black pall. At last Mr. Dance finished the story.

01:10:51.670 --> 01:11:00.530
Mr. Dance, said the squire, you are a very noble fellow, and as for riding down that black atrocious

01:11:00.530 --> 01:11:07.930
miscreant, I regard it as an act of virtue, sir, like stamping on a cockroach. This lad Hawkins

01:11:07.930 --> 01:11:14.710
is a trump, I perceive. Hawkins, will you ring that bell? Mr. Dance must have some ale.

01:11:15.930 --> 01:11:21.610
And so, Jim, said the doctor, you have the thing that they were after, have you?

01:11:22.830 --> 01:11:27.690
Here it is, sir, said I, and gave him the oil-skin packet.

01:11:29.290 --> 01:11:34.370
The doctor looked it all over, as if his fingers were itching to open it,

01:11:34.370 --> 01:11:39.350
but instead of doing that he put it quietly in the pocket of his coat.

01:11:41.350 --> 01:11:48.750
Squire, said he, when Dance has had his ale he must, of course, be off on his majesty's service,

01:11:49.390 --> 01:11:54.410
but I mean to keep Jim Hawkins here to sleep at my house, and, with your permission,

01:11:54.970 --> 01:11:58.650
I propose we should have up the cold pie and let him sup.

01:12:00.210 --> 01:12:06.470
As you will, Livesey, said the squire, Hawkins has earned better than cold pie.

01:12:08.430 --> 01:12:14.510
So a big pigeon pie was brought in and put on a side table, and I made a hearty supper,

01:12:14.710 --> 01:12:21.470
for I was as hungry as a hawk, while Mr. Dance was further complimented, and at last dismissed.

01:12:22.970 --> 01:12:30.970
And now, Squire, said the doctor, and now, Livesey, said the squire, in the same breath,

01:12:32.450 --> 01:12:39.510
one at a time, one at a time, laughed Dr. Livesey, you have heard of this flint, I suppose.

01:12:41.550 --> 01:12:48.130
Heard of him, cried the squire, heard of him, you say, he was the blood-thirstiest buccaneer that

01:12:48.130 --> 01:12:55.390
sailed. Blackbeard was a child to flint. The Spaniards were so prodigiously afraid of him

01:12:55.390 --> 01:13:02.370
that, I tell you, sir, I was sometimes proud he was an Englishman. I've seen his top sales with

01:13:02.370 --> 01:13:08.870
these eyes, off Trinidad, and the cowardly son of a rum-punchin' that I sailed with put back,

01:13:09.250 --> 01:13:11.830
put back, sir, into port of Spain.

01:13:13.230 --> 01:13:20.570
Well, I've heard of him myself in England, said the doctor, but the point is, had he money?

01:13:21.910 --> 01:13:28.910
Money, cried the squire, have you heard the story? What were these villains after but money?

01:13:29.470 --> 01:13:35.870
What do they care for but money? For what would they risk their rascal carcasses but money?

01:13:37.470 --> 01:13:44.670
That we shall soon know, replied the doctor, but you are so confoundedly hot-headed and

01:13:44.670 --> 01:13:52.530
exclamatory that I cannot get a word in. What I want to know is this. Supposing that I have here

01:13:52.530 --> 01:13:59.470
in my pocket some clue to where flint buried his treasure, will that treasure amount to much?

01:14:01.190 --> 01:14:08.850
Amount, sir, cried the squire, it will amount to this. If we have the clue you talk about,

01:14:09.290 --> 01:14:14.570
I fit out a ship in Bristol Dock, and take you and Hawkins here along,

01:14:15.030 --> 01:14:17.830
and I'll have that treasure if I search a year.

01:14:19.610 --> 01:14:26.530
Very well, said the doctor. Now then, if Jim is agreeable, we'll open the packet.

01:14:27.170 --> 01:14:35.350
And he laid it before him on the table. The bundle was sewn together, and the doctor had

01:14:35.350 --> 01:14:39.630
to get out his instrument case and cut the stitches with his medical scissors.

01:14:41.590 --> 01:14:46.350
It contained two things, a book and a sealed paper.

01:14:47.890 --> 01:14:51.990
First of all, we'll try the book, observed the doctor.

01:14:53.190 --> 01:14:59.290
The squire and I were both peering over his shoulder as he opened it, for Dr. Livesey had

01:14:59.290 --> 01:15:05.390
kindly motioned me to come round from the side table, where I had been eating, to enjoy the sport

01:15:05.390 --> 01:15:12.410
of the search. On the first page there were only some scraps of writing, such as a man with a pen

01:15:12.410 --> 01:15:20.870
in his hand might make for idleness or practice. One was the same as the tattoo mark, Billy Bones,

01:15:20.870 --> 01:15:31.490
his fancy. Then there was Mr. W. Bones, mate. No more rum. Off palm key he got it.

01:15:32.390 --> 01:15:39.870
And some other snatches, mostly single words and unintelligible. I could not help wondering

01:15:39.870 --> 01:15:49.250
who it was that had got it, and what it was that he got. A knife in his back, as like as not.

01:15:50.290 --> 01:15:54.870
Not much instruction there, said Dr. Livesey, as he passed on.

01:15:56.690 --> 01:16:03.590
The next ten or twelve pages were filled with a curious series of entries. There was a date

01:16:03.590 --> 01:16:09.350
at one end of the line, and at the other a sum of money, as in common account books,

01:16:09.810 --> 01:16:15.570
but instead of explanatory writing, only a varying number of crosses between the two.

01:16:17.150 --> 01:16:26.290
On the twelfth of June, 1745, for instance, a sum of seventy pounds had plainly become due to someone,

01:16:26.990 --> 01:16:35.030
and there was nothing but six crosses to explain the cause. In a few cases, to be sure, the name

01:16:35.030 --> 01:16:45.150
of a place would be added, as off Caracas, or a mere entry of latitude and longitude, as sixty-two

01:16:45.150 --> 01:16:55.590
seventeen twenty nineteen two forty. The record lasted over nearly twenty years,

01:16:56.010 --> 01:17:02.850
the amount of the separate entries growing larger as time went on, and at the end a grand total had

01:17:02.850 --> 01:17:10.890
been made out after five or six wrong additions, and these words appended. Bones. His pile.

01:17:12.390 --> 01:17:16.930
I can't make head or tail of this, said Dr. Livesey.

01:17:17.990 --> 01:17:24.970
The thing is as clear as noonday, cried the squire. This is the black-hearted hound's account book.

01:17:25.570 --> 01:17:32.410
These crosses stand for the names of ships or towns that they sank or plundered. The sums are

01:17:32.410 --> 01:17:38.110
the scoundrel's share, and where he feared an ambiguity, you see he added something clearer.

01:17:38.750 --> 01:17:45.090
Off Caracas, now. You see, here was some unhappy vessel boarded off that coast.

01:17:45.690 --> 01:17:50.010
God help the poor souls that manned her. Coral, long ago.

01:17:51.870 --> 01:17:58.910
Right, said the doctor. See what it is to be a traveller. Right. And the amounts increase,

01:17:58.970 --> 01:18:06.870
you see, as he rose in rank. There was little else in the volume, but a few bearings of places

01:18:06.870 --> 01:18:12.650
noted in the blank leaves towards the end, and a table for reducing French, English,

01:18:12.870 --> 01:18:21.090
and Spanish monies to a common value. Thrifty man, cried the doctor. He wasn't the one to be

01:18:21.090 --> 01:18:32.190
cheated. And now, said the squire, for the other. The paper had been sealed in several places with

01:18:32.190 --> 01:18:38.470
thimble by way of seal, the very thimble, perhaps, that I had found in the captain's pocket.

01:18:39.910 --> 01:18:45.810
The doctor opened the seals with great care, and there fell out the map of an island,

01:18:46.190 --> 01:18:54.010
with latitude and longitude, soundings, names of hills and bays and inlets, and every particular

01:18:54.010 --> 01:18:58.390
that would be needed to bring a ship to a safe anchorage upon its shores.

01:18:59.390 --> 01:19:07.470
It was about nine miles long and five across, shaped, you might say, like a fat dragon standing

01:19:07.470 --> 01:19:14.910
up, and had two fine landlocked harbours, and a hill in the centre part marked the Spyglass.

01:19:17.070 --> 01:19:23.070
There were several additions of a later date, but above all three crosses of red ink,

01:19:23.070 --> 01:19:29.770
two on the north part of the island, one in the south-west, and, beside this last,

01:19:30.030 --> 01:19:35.810
in the same red ink, and in a small, neat hand, very different from the captain's tottery

01:19:35.810 --> 01:19:46.610
characters, these words. Bulk of treasure here. Over on the back, the same hand had written this

01:19:46.610 --> 01:19:47.870
further information.

01:20:06.810 --> 01:20:13.290
The bar silver is in the north cache. You can find it by the trend of the east hummock,

01:20:13.290 --> 01:20:21.210
ten fathoms south of the black crag, with the face on it. The arms are easily found

01:20:21.210 --> 01:20:28.730
in the sandhill, N, point of north inlet cape, bearing E and a quarter N.

01:20:33.070 --> 01:20:41.390
That was all, but brief as it was, and, to me, incomprehensible, it filled the squire

01:20:41.390 --> 01:20:43.350
and Dr. Livesey with delight.

01:20:45.610 --> 01:20:50.110
Livesey, said the squire, you will give up this wretched practice at once.

01:20:50.730 --> 01:20:57.330
To-morrow I start for Bristol. In three weeks' time, three weeks, two weeks, ten days,

01:20:57.750 --> 01:21:04.490
we'll have the best ship, sir, and the choicest crew in England. Hawkins shall come as cabin boy.

01:21:05.310 --> 01:21:10.230
You'll make a famous cabin boy, Hawkins. You, Livesey, are ship's doctor.

01:21:10.870 --> 01:21:18.350
I am admiral. We'll take Redruth, Joyce, and Hunter. We'll have favourable winds,

01:21:18.810 --> 01:21:24.570
a quick passage, and not the least difficulty in finding the spot, and money to eat,

01:21:24.870 --> 01:21:28.650
to roll in, to play duck and drake with ever after.

01:21:31.090 --> 01:21:37.070
Trelawney, said the doctor, I'll go with you, and I'll go bail for it, so will Jim,

01:21:37.070 --> 01:21:41.950
and be a credit to the undertaking. There's only one man I'm afraid of.

01:21:43.070 --> 01:21:47.010
And who's that? cried the squire. Name the dog, sir.

01:21:48.630 --> 01:21:56.410
You, replied the doctor, for you cannot hold your tongue. We are not the only men who know

01:21:56.410 --> 01:22:03.070
of this paper. These fellows who attacked the inn to-night, bold, desperate blades, for sure,

01:22:03.070 --> 01:22:11.050
and the rest who stayed aboard that lugger, and more, I dare say, not far off, are one and all,

01:22:11.410 --> 01:22:17.850
through thick and thin, bound that they'll get that money. We must none of us go alone till we

01:22:17.850 --> 01:22:25.130
get to sea. Jim and I shall stick together in the meanwhile. You'll take Joyce and Hunter when you

01:22:25.130 --> 01:22:32.130
ride to Bristol, and from first to last not one of us must breathe a word of what we've found.

01:22:33.670 --> 01:22:41.550
Libsy, returned the squire, you are always in the right of it. I'll be as silent as the grave.

01:23:09.110 --> 01:23:11.930
literateloser.mitchellkdwyer.net

01:23:13.290 --> 01:23:18.230
Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson, chapters 7 and 8.

01:23:18.430 --> 01:23:19.770
Part 2, The Seacook.

01:23:20.850 --> 01:23:22.710
Chapter 7, I Go to Bristol.

01:23:24.450 --> 01:23:30.350
It was longer than the squire imagined ere we were ready for the sea, and none of our first plans,

01:23:30.350 --> 01:23:35.530
not even Dr. Livesey's of keeping me beside him, could be carried out as we intended.

01:23:36.470 --> 01:23:40.750
The doctor had to go to London for a physician to take charge of his practice.

01:23:41.790 --> 01:23:48.890
The squire was hard at work at Bristol, and I lived on at the hall under the charge of old Red Ruth,

01:23:49.130 --> 01:23:55.450
the gamekeeper, almost a prisoner, but full of sea dreams and the most charming anticipations

01:23:55.450 --> 01:23:57.890
of strange islands and adventures.

01:23:58.930 --> 01:24:04.930
I brooded by the hour together over the map, all the details which I well remembered.

01:24:05.690 --> 01:24:12.090
Sitting by the fire in the housekeeper's room, I approached that island in my fancy from every

01:24:12.090 --> 01:24:19.690
possible direction. I explored every acre of its surface. I climbed a thousand times to that tall

01:24:19.690 --> 01:24:25.830
they call the spyglass, and from the top enjoyed the most wonderful and changing prospects.

01:24:26.410 --> 01:24:32.230
Sometimes the isle was thick with savages with whom we fought, sometimes full of dangerous

01:24:32.230 --> 01:24:39.030
animals that hunted us, but in all my fancies nothing occurred to me so strange and tragic

01:24:39.030 --> 01:24:47.070
as our actual adventures. So the weeks passed on till one fine day there came a letter addressed

01:24:47.070 --> 01:24:53.670
to Dr. Livesey with this edition, to be opened in the case of his absence by Tom Red Ruth

01:24:53.670 --> 01:25:00.470
or Young Hawkins. Obeying this order we found, or rather I found, for the gamekeeper was a

01:25:00.470 --> 01:25:07.430
poor hand at reading anything but print, the following important news. Old Anchor Inn,

01:25:07.610 --> 01:25:14.550
Bristol, March 1, 17 something. Dear Livesey, as I do not know whether you are at the hall or

01:25:14.550 --> 01:25:23.190
in London, I send this in double to both places. The ship is bought and fitted. She lies at anchor

01:25:23.190 --> 01:25:30.270
ready for sea. You never imagined a sweeter schooner, a child might sail her. Two hundred

01:25:30.270 --> 01:25:38.250
tons, name Hispaniola. I got her through my old friend Blandly, who has proved himself throughout

01:25:38.250 --> 01:25:45.270
most surprising trump. The admirable fellow literally slaved in my interest and so I may say,

01:25:45.690 --> 01:25:51.970
did everyone in Bristol, as soon as they got wind of the port we sailed for, treasure I mean.

01:25:53.110 --> 01:25:58.310
Red Ruth, said I, interrupting the letter. Dr. Livesey will not like that. The squire has been

01:25:58.310 --> 01:26:05.530
talking after all. Well, who's a better write, growled the gamekeeper. A pretty rum go if squire

01:26:05.530 --> 01:26:12.310
ain't to talk for Dr. Livesey, I should think. At that I gave up all attempts at commentary and

01:26:12.310 --> 01:26:20.230
read straight on. Blandly himself found the Hispaniola and by the most admirable management

01:26:20.230 --> 01:26:26.910
got her for the merest trifle. There is a class of men in Bristol monstrously prejudiced against

01:26:26.910 --> 01:26:32.390
Blandly. They go the length of declaring that this honest creature would do anything for money,

01:26:32.390 --> 01:26:39.710
that the Hispaniola belonged to him, and that he sold it me absurdly high, the most transparent

01:26:39.710 --> 01:26:46.710
calumnies. None of them dare, however, to deny the merits of the ship. So far there was not a hitch.

01:26:47.150 --> 01:26:53.130
The work people, to be sure, riggers and what not, were most annoyingly slow, but time cured that.

01:26:53.570 --> 01:27:00.510
It was the crew that troubled me. I wished a round score of men, in case of natives,

01:27:00.510 --> 01:27:06.750
buccaneers or the odious French, and I had the worry of the deuce itself to find so much as half

01:27:06.750 --> 01:27:13.050
a dozen, till the most remarkable stroke of fortune brought me the very man that I required.

01:27:13.830 --> 01:27:20.290
I was standing on the dock when, by the merest accident, I fell in talk with him. I found he

01:27:20.290 --> 01:27:26.870
was an old sailor, kept a public house, knew all the seafaring men in Bristol, had lost his health

01:27:26.870 --> 01:27:34.230
and wanted a good berth as cook to get to sea again. He had hobbled down there that morning,

01:27:34.370 --> 01:27:40.390
he said, to get a smell of the salt. I was monstrously touched, so would you have been,

01:27:40.570 --> 01:27:47.730
and out of pure pity I engaged him on the spot to be the ship's cook. Long John Silver, he is called,

01:27:47.890 --> 01:27:54.430
and has lost a leg, but that I regarded as a recommendation, since he lost it in his country's

01:27:54.430 --> 01:28:03.350
under the immortal hawk. He has no pension, Livesey, imagine the abominable age we live in.

01:28:03.970 --> 01:28:09.630
Well, sir, I thought I had only found a cook, but it was a crew I had discovered. Between Silver

01:28:09.630 --> 01:28:16.490
and myself, we got together in a few days, a company of the toughest old salts imaginable.

01:28:17.070 --> 01:28:24.190
Not pretty to look at, but fellows by their faces of the most indomitable spirit. I declare,

01:28:24.190 --> 01:28:31.510
we could fight a frigate. Long John even got rid of two out of the six or seven I had already

01:28:31.510 --> 01:28:38.470
engaged. He showed me in a moment that they were just the sort of freshwater swabs we had to fear

01:28:38.470 --> 01:28:46.290
in an adventure of importance. I am in the most magnificent health and spirits, eating like a bull,

01:28:46.570 --> 01:28:52.850
sleeping like a tree, yet I shall not enjoy a moment till I hear my old tarpaulins tramping

01:28:52.850 --> 01:29:00.090
around the capstan. Seaward ho, hang the treasure, it's the glory of the sea that has turned my head,

01:29:00.230 --> 01:29:07.670
so now Livesey, come post. Do not lose an hour if you respect me. Let young Hawkins go at once to

01:29:07.670 --> 01:29:14.850
see his mother, with Red Ruth for a guard, and then both come full speed to Bristol. John Trelawney.

01:29:17.070 --> 01:29:23.290
Postscript. I did not tell you that Bland Lee, who by the way is to send a consort after us if we

01:29:23.290 --> 01:29:29.770
don't turn up by the end of August, had found an admirable fellow for sailing master, a stiff man

01:29:29.770 --> 01:29:36.270
which I regret, but in all other respects a treasurer. Long John Silver unearthed a very

01:29:36.270 --> 01:29:42.630
competent man for a mate, a man named Arrow. I have a boat swaying who pipes, Livesey, so things

01:29:42.630 --> 01:29:49.670
shall go man o' war fashion on board the good ship Hispaniola. I forgot to tell you that Silver

01:29:49.670 --> 01:29:56.210
is a man of substance. I know of my own knowledge that he has a banker's account which has never

01:29:56.210 --> 01:30:03.010
been overdrawn. He leaves his wife to manage the inn, and as she is a woman of colour, a pair of

01:30:03.010 --> 01:30:09.150
old bachelors like you and I may be excused for guessing that it is the wife, quite as much as

01:30:09.150 --> 01:30:19.110
the health that sends him back to roving. J.T. P.P.S. Hawkins may stay one night with his mother. J.T.

01:30:20.050 --> 01:30:25.830
You can fancy the excitement into which that letter put me. I was half beside myself with glee,

01:30:25.950 --> 01:30:32.730
and if ever I despised a man it was old Tom Redruth who could do nothing but grumble and lament.

01:30:33.290 --> 01:30:39.450
Any of the under gamekeepers would gladly have changed places with him, but such was not the

01:30:39.450 --> 01:30:46.390
Squire's pleasure, and the Squire's pleasure was like law among them all. Nobody but old Redruth

01:30:46.390 --> 01:30:54.670
would have dared so much as even to grumble. The next morning he and I set out on foot for the

01:30:54.670 --> 01:31:01.970
Admiral Benbow, and there I found my mother in good health and spirits. The captain who had so long

01:31:01.970 --> 01:31:07.930
been a cause of so much discomfort was gone where the wicked cease from troubling.

01:31:08.710 --> 01:31:13.830
The Squire had had everything repaired and the public rooms and the sign repainted,

01:31:14.290 --> 01:31:19.750
and had added some furniture, above all a beautiful armchair for mother in the bar.

01:31:20.630 --> 01:31:26.530
He had found her a boy as an apprentice also so that she should not want help while I was gone.

01:31:26.530 --> 01:31:33.970
It was on seeing that boy that I understood for the first time my situation. I had thought

01:31:33.970 --> 01:31:40.070
up to that moment of the adventures before me, not at all of the home that I was leaving,

01:31:40.330 --> 01:31:46.810
and now at sight of this clumsy stranger who was to stay here in my place beside my mother.

01:31:47.450 --> 01:31:53.510
I had my first attack of tears. I am afraid I led that boy a dog's life,

01:31:54.150 --> 01:31:59.590
for as he was new to the work I had a hundred opportunities of setting him right and putting

01:31:59.590 --> 01:32:06.470
him down, and I was not slow to profit by them. The night passed and the next day after dinner

01:32:06.470 --> 01:32:13.330
Redruth and I were afoot again and on the road. I said goodbye to mother and the cove where I had

01:32:13.330 --> 01:32:21.690
lived since I was born, and the dear old Admiral Benbow since he was repainted no longer quite so

01:32:21.690 --> 01:32:29.430
near. One of my last thoughts was of the captain who had so often strode along the beach with his

01:32:29.430 --> 01:32:37.130
cocked hat, his saber-cut cheek, and his old brass telescope. Next moment we had turned the corner

01:32:37.130 --> 01:32:44.950
and my home was out of sight. The mail picked us up about dusk at the Royal George on the Heath.

01:32:44.950 --> 01:32:52.010
I was wedged in between Redruth and a stout old gentleman, and in spite of the swift motion and

01:32:52.010 --> 01:32:58.650
the cold night air, I must have dozed a great deal from the very first, and then slept like a log

01:32:58.650 --> 01:33:07.070
uphill and down dale through stage after stage, for when I was awakened at last it was by a punch

01:33:07.070 --> 01:33:13.210
in the ribs, and I opened my eyes to find that we were standing still before a large building

01:33:13.210 --> 01:33:18.030
in a city street, and that the day had already broken a long time.

01:33:19.010 --> 01:33:26.490
Where are we, I asked. Bristol said Tom, get down. Mr Trelawney had taken up his residence at an inn

01:33:26.490 --> 01:33:33.290
far down the docks to superintend the work upon the schooner. Thither we had now to walk,

01:33:33.470 --> 01:33:39.710
and our way to my great delight lay along the quays and beside the great multitude of ships

01:33:39.710 --> 01:33:46.330
of all sizes and rigs and nations. In one, sailors were singing at their work. In another,

01:33:46.590 --> 01:33:52.430
there were men aloft high over my head hanging to threads that seemed no thicker than a spider's.

01:33:53.350 --> 01:34:00.870
Though I had lived by the shore all my life, I seemed never to have been near the sea till then.

01:34:01.790 --> 01:34:07.870
The smell of tar and salt was something new. I saw the most wonderful figureheads that had

01:34:07.870 --> 01:34:15.030
been far over the ocean. I saw besides many old sailors with rings in their ears and whiskers

01:34:15.030 --> 01:34:22.990
curled in ringlets and tarry pigtails and their swaggering clumsy sea walk. And if I had seen as

01:34:22.990 --> 01:34:30.190
many kings or archbishops, I could not have been more delighted. And I was going to see myself,

01:34:30.270 --> 01:34:37.290
to see in a schooner with a piping boatswain and pigtails singing seamen, to see bound for an

01:34:37.290 --> 01:34:43.150
unknown island and to seek for buried treasure. While I was still in this delightful dream,

01:34:43.390 --> 01:34:50.930
we came suddenly in front of a large inn and met Squire Trelawney, all dressed out like a sea officer

01:34:50.930 --> 01:34:58.390
in stout blue cloth, coming out of the door with a smile on his face and a capital imitation of a

01:34:58.390 --> 01:35:04.830
sailor's walk. Here you are, he cried, and the doctor came last night from London. Bravo!

01:35:04.830 --> 01:35:13.710
The ship's company complete. Oh, sir, cried I. When do we sail? Sail, says he. We sail tomorrow.

01:35:16.350 --> 01:35:19.630
Chapter 8 At the Sign of the Spyglass

01:35:20.270 --> 01:35:26.890
When I had done breakfasting, the squire gave me a note addressed to John Silver at the sign

01:35:26.890 --> 01:35:33.310
of the spyglass and told me I should easily find the place by following the line of the docks

01:35:33.310 --> 01:35:39.050
and keeping a bright lookout for a little tavern with a large brass telescope for sign.

01:35:40.170 --> 01:35:47.090
I set off, overjoyed at this opportunity to see some more of the ships and seamen, and picked my

01:35:47.090 --> 01:35:53.050
way among a great crowd of people and carts and bales, for the dock was now at its busiest

01:35:53.050 --> 01:36:00.030
until I found the tavern in question. It was a bright enough little place of entertainment.

01:36:00.490 --> 01:36:07.210
The sign was newly painted. The windows had neat red curtains. The floor was cleanly sanded.

01:36:07.490 --> 01:36:13.850
There was a street on each side and an open door on both, which made the large low room pretty

01:36:13.850 --> 01:36:21.290
clear to see in, in spite of clouds of tobacco smoke. The customers were mostly seafaring men,

01:36:21.290 --> 01:36:27.330
and they talked so loudly that I hung at the door, almost afraid to enter. As I was waiting,

01:36:27.330 --> 01:36:35.210
a man came out of a side room, and at a glance I was sure he must be Long John. His left leg was

01:36:35.210 --> 01:36:41.110
cut off close by the hip, and under the left shoulder he carried a crutch, which he managed

01:36:41.110 --> 01:36:47.950
with wonderful dexterity, hopping about upon it like a bird. He was very tall and strong,

01:36:48.210 --> 01:36:55.570
with a face as big as a ham, plain and pale, but intelligent and smiling. Indeed, he seemed in the

01:36:55.570 --> 01:37:02.270
most cheerful spirits, whistling as he moved about among the tables, with a merry word or a

01:37:02.270 --> 01:37:08.550
slap on the shoulder for the more favored of his guests. Now, to tell you the truth,

01:37:09.030 --> 01:37:14.990
from the very first mention of Long John in Squire Trelawney's letter, I had taken a fear

01:37:14.990 --> 01:37:21.790
in my mind that he might prove to be the very one-legged sailor whom I had watched for so long

01:37:21.790 --> 01:37:28.330
at the old Benbow, but one look at the man before me was enough. I had seen the captain and black

01:37:28.330 --> 01:37:34.230
dog and the blind man pew, and I thought I knew what a buccaneer was like, a very different creature,

01:37:34.330 --> 01:37:40.570
according to me, from this clean and pleasant tempered landlord. I plucked up courage at once,

01:37:40.710 --> 01:37:45.850
crossed the threshold, and walked right up to the man where he stood, propped on his crutch,

01:37:45.850 --> 01:37:53.010
talking to a customer. Mr. Silver, sir, I asked, holding out the note. Yes, my lad, said he.

01:37:53.190 --> 01:37:58.270
Such is my name, to be sure, and who may you be? And then, as he saw the squire's letter,

01:37:58.550 --> 01:38:05.850
he seemed to me to give something almost like a start. Oh, said he, quite loud and offering his

01:38:05.850 --> 01:38:13.670
hand, I see. You are our new cabin boy. Pleased I am to see you. And he took my hand in his large,

01:38:13.670 --> 01:38:21.570
firm grasp. Just then one of the customers at the far side rose suddenly and made for the door.

01:38:22.330 --> 01:38:28.070
It was close by him, and he was out in the street in a moment, but his hurry had attracted my notice,

01:38:28.330 --> 01:38:33.290
and I recognized him at glance. It was the tallow-faced man wanting two fingers,

01:38:33.630 --> 01:38:40.010
who had come first to the Admiral Benbow. Oh, I cried, stop him, it's black dog.

01:38:40.590 --> 01:38:45.810
I don't care, two coppers, who he is, cried Silver, but he hasn't paid his score. Harry,

01:38:45.930 --> 01:38:51.830
run and catch him. One of the others, who was nearest the door, leaped up and started in pursuit.

01:38:52.590 --> 01:38:57.630
If he were Admiral Hawk, he shall pay his score, cried Silver, and then, relinquishing my hand,

01:38:57.890 --> 01:39:05.810
who did you say he was? he asked. Black what? Dog, sir, said I. Has Mr. Trelawney not told you

01:39:05.810 --> 01:39:12.390
of the Buccaneers? He was one of them. So, cried Silver, in my house. Ben, run and help Harry.

01:39:12.790 --> 01:39:17.830
One of those swabs, was he? Was that you drinking with him, Morgan? Step up here.

01:39:18.350 --> 01:39:23.510
The man, whom he called Morgan, an old gray-haired, mahogany-faced sailor,

01:39:23.650 --> 01:39:27.170
came forward pretty sheepishly, rolling his quid.

01:39:27.890 --> 01:39:33.630
Now, Morgan, said Long John very sternly, you never clapped your eyes on that black,

01:39:33.630 --> 01:39:40.490
dog before, did you now? Not I, sir, said Morgan, with a salute. You didn't know his name, did you?

01:39:40.930 --> 01:39:47.610
No, sir. By the powers, Tom Morgan, it's as good for you, exclaimed the landlord. If you had been

01:39:47.610 --> 01:39:52.590
mixed up with the like of that, you would never have put another foot in my house. You may lay to

01:39:52.590 --> 01:39:59.870
that. And what was he saying to you? I don't rightly know, sir, answered Morgan. Do you call

01:39:59.870 --> 01:40:05.210
that a head on your shoulders or a blessed dead eye, cried Long John? Don't rightly know, don't you?

01:40:05.710 --> 01:40:11.470
Perhaps you don't happen to rightly know who you was speaking to, perhaps. Come now, what was he

01:40:11.470 --> 01:40:19.230
jawing? Voyages, captains, ships? Pipe up, what was it? We was a-talkin' of keel-hauling, answered

01:40:19.230 --> 01:40:25.010
Morgan. Keel-hauling, was you? And a mighty, suitable thing, too, and you may lay to that.

01:40:25.010 --> 01:40:31.510
Get back to your place for a lover, Tom. And then, as Morgan rolled back to his seat,

01:40:32.070 --> 01:40:36.830
Silver added to me in a confidential whisper that was very flattering as I thought.

01:40:37.490 --> 01:40:42.610
He's quite an honest man, Tom Morgan, only stupid. And now he ran on again, aloud.

01:40:43.010 --> 01:40:50.250
Let's see, Black Dog. No, I don't know the name, not I. Yet I kind of think I've, yes, I've seen

01:40:50.250 --> 01:40:55.770
the swab. He used to come here with a blind beggar, he used. That he did, you may be sure,

01:40:55.830 --> 01:41:02.970
said I. I knew that blind man, too. His name was Pew. It was, cried Silver, now quite excited, Pew.

01:41:03.790 --> 01:41:09.690
That were his name for certain. Ah, he looked a shark, he did. If we run down this Black Dog now,

01:41:09.770 --> 01:41:15.230
there'll be news for Cap and Trelawney. Ben's a good runner. Few seamen run better than Ben.

01:41:15.230 --> 01:41:21.410
He should run him down, hand over hand, by the powers. He talked a keel haul and did he? I'll

01:41:21.410 --> 01:41:27.510
keel haul him. All the time he was jerking out these phrases, he was stumping up and down the

01:41:27.510 --> 01:41:33.270
tavern on his crutch, slapping tables with his hand, and giving such a show of excitement as

01:41:33.270 --> 01:41:39.530
would have convinced an old Bailey judge or a Bow Street runner. My suspicions had been

01:41:40.230 --> 01:41:45.630
reawakened on finding Black Dog at the Spyglass, and I watched the cook narrowly.

01:41:46.190 --> 01:41:51.790
But he was too deep and too ready and too clever for me, and by the time the two men had come back

01:41:51.790 --> 01:41:57.450
out of breath and confessed that they had lost the track in a crowd and been scolded like thieves,

01:41:57.730 --> 01:42:04.470
I would have gone bail for the innocence of Long John Silver. See here now, Hawkins, said he.

01:42:04.470 --> 01:42:10.370
Here's a blessed hard thing on a man like me now, ain't it? There's Cap and Trelawney. What's he

01:42:10.370 --> 01:42:15.870
to think? Here I have this confounded son of a Dutchman sitting in my own house drinking of my

01:42:15.870 --> 01:42:22.510
own rum. Here you comes and tells me of it plain, and here I let him give us all the slip before my

01:42:22.510 --> 01:42:28.470
blessed dead lights. Now, Hawkins, you do me justice with the Cap'n. You're a lad you are,

01:42:28.470 --> 01:42:34.090
but you're as smart as paint. I see that when you first come in. Now, here it is. What could I do

01:42:34.090 --> 01:42:40.470
with this old timber I hobble on? When I was an AB master mariner, I'd have come up alongside of

01:42:40.470 --> 01:42:48.430
him hand over hand and broached him to in a brace of old shakes, I would, but now. And then all of

01:42:48.430 --> 01:42:54.430
a sudden he stopped and his jaw dropped as though he had remembered something. The score he burst

01:42:54.430 --> 01:43:01.630
out. Three goes a rum. Why shiver my timbers if I hadn't forgotten my score? And falling on a bench,

01:43:01.630 --> 01:43:08.070
he laughed until the tears ran down his cheeks. I could not help joining, and we laughed together

01:43:08.070 --> 01:43:16.470
peel after peel until the tavern rang again. Why, what a precious old sea calf I am, he said at last

01:43:16.470 --> 01:43:22.130
wiping his cheeks. You and me should get on well, Hawkins, for I'll take my Davey. I should be

01:43:22.130 --> 01:43:29.430
raided ship's boy. But come now, stand by to go about. This won't do. Duty is duty, mess mates.

01:43:29.430 --> 01:43:35.450
I'll put on my old cockerel hat and step along of you to Captain Trelawney and report this here

01:43:35.450 --> 01:43:41.590
affair. For mind you, it's serious, young Hawkins, and neither you nor me's come out of it with what

01:43:41.590 --> 01:43:47.810
I should make so bold as to call credit. Nor you neither, says you, not smart. None of the pair of

01:43:47.810 --> 01:43:53.990
us smart, but dash my buttons, that was a good one about my score. And he began to laugh again,

01:43:53.990 --> 01:44:00.110
and that so heartily, that though I did not see the joke as he did, I was again obliged to join

01:44:00.110 --> 01:44:06.390
him in his mirth. On our little walk along the quays, he made himself the most interesting

01:44:06.390 --> 01:44:11.770
companion, telling me about the different ships that we passed by, their rig, tonnage, and

01:44:11.770 --> 01:44:17.690
nationality, explaining the work that was going forward, how one was discharging, another taking

01:44:17.690 --> 01:44:23.850
in cargo, and a third making ready for sea, and every now and then telling me some little

01:44:23.850 --> 01:44:30.110
anecdote of ships or seamen, or repeating a nautical phrase till I had learned it perfectly,

01:44:30.690 --> 01:44:37.770
I began to see that here was one of the best of possible shipmates. When we got to the inn,

01:44:38.510 --> 01:44:45.090
the squire and Dr. Livesey were seated together, finishing a quart of ale with a toast in it,

01:44:45.090 --> 01:44:51.510
before they could go aboard the schooner on a visit of inspection. Long John told the story

01:44:51.510 --> 01:44:57.710
from first to last, with a great deal of spirit and the most perfect truth. That was how it were

01:44:57.710 --> 01:45:03.050
now, warranted Hawkins, he would say now and again, and I could always bear him entirely out.

01:45:03.770 --> 01:45:09.590
The two gentlemen regretted that Black Dog had got away, but we all agreed there was nothing to

01:45:09.590 --> 01:45:14.770
done, and after he had been complimented, Long John took up his crutch and departed.

01:45:16.230 --> 01:45:20.170
All hands aboard, by four this afternoon, shouted the squire after him.

01:45:20.650 --> 01:45:25.630
Aye, aye, sir, cried the cook in the passage. Well, squire, said Livesey, I don't put much

01:45:25.630 --> 01:45:31.390
faith in your discoveries as a general thing, but I will say this, John Silver suits me.

01:45:32.150 --> 01:45:36.590
The man's a perfect trump, declared the squire, and now, added the doctor,

01:45:36.590 --> 01:45:42.050
Jim may come on board with us, may he not? To be sure he may, says squire,

01:45:42.530 --> 01:45:48.570
take your hat, Hawkins, and we'll see the ship.

01:46:19.070 --> 01:46:20.550
CHAPTER IX.

01:46:21.490 --> 01:46:23.030
Powder and Arms.

01:46:27.190 --> 01:46:33.090
The Hispaniola lay some way out, and we went under the figureheads and round the

01:46:33.090 --> 01:46:39.970
stearns of many other ships, and their cables sometimes grated underneath our keel and

01:46:39.970 --> 01:46:48.590
sometimes swung above us. At last, however, we got alongside and were met and saluted as

01:46:48.590 --> 01:46:54.930
we stepped aboard by the mate, Mr. Arrow, a brown old sailor with earrings in his

01:46:54.930 --> 01:47:02.510
ears and a squint. He and the squire were very thick and friendly, but I soon

01:47:02.510 --> 01:47:07.090
observed that things were not the same between Mr. Trelawney and the captain.

01:47:09.570 --> 01:47:15.210
This last was a sharp-looking man who seemed angry with everything on board and

01:47:15.210 --> 01:47:22.030
soon to tell us why, for we had hardly got down into the cabin when a sailor followed us.

01:47:24.150 --> 01:47:28.670
Captain Smollett, sir, asking to speak with you, said he.

01:47:30.330 --> 01:47:35.210
I am always at the captain's orders. Show him in, said the squire.

01:47:39.590 --> 01:47:47.930
Well, Captain Smollett, what have you to say? All well, I hope? All ship-shape and seaworthy?

01:47:48.910 --> 01:47:56.330
Well, sir, said the captain. Better speak plain, I believe, even at the risk of offense.

01:47:57.590 --> 01:48:05.050
I don't like this cruise. I don't like the men, and I don't like my officer. That's

01:48:05.050 --> 01:48:14.230
sweet. Perhaps, sir, you don't like the ship, inquired the squire, very angry as I could see.

01:48:15.630 --> 01:48:22.770
I can't speak to that, sir, not having seen her tried, said the captain. She seems a clever

01:48:22.770 --> 01:48:32.770
craft. More I can't say. Possibly, sir, you may not like your employer either, says the squire.

01:48:33.670 --> 01:48:36.070
But here Dr. Livesey cut in.

01:48:37.870 --> 01:48:46.030
Stay a bit, said he. Stay a bit. No use of such questions as that but to produce ill feeling.

01:48:47.310 --> 01:48:53.570
The captain has said too much, or he has said too little, and I'm bound to say that I require

01:48:53.570 --> 01:49:01.790
an explanation of his words. You don't, you say, like this cruise. Now why?

01:49:03.930 --> 01:49:10.750
I was engaged, sir, on what we call sealed orders, to sail this ship for that gentleman

01:49:10.750 --> 01:49:19.110
where he should bid me, said the captain. So far so good. But now I find that every man before

01:49:19.110 --> 01:49:29.690
the mast knows more than I do. I don't call that fair now, do you? No, said Dr. Livesey. I don't.

01:49:31.570 --> 01:49:38.610
Next, said the captain. I learn we are going after treasure. Hear it from my own hands,

01:49:38.850 --> 01:49:46.290
mind you. Now treasure is ticklish work. I don't like treasure voyages on any account,

01:49:46.290 --> 01:49:52.810
and I don't like them above all when they are secret and when, begging your pardon,

01:49:52.990 --> 01:49:56.630
Mr. Trelawney, the secret has been told to the parrot.

01:49:59.250 --> 01:50:07.610
Silver's parrot? asked the squire. It's a way of speaking, said the captain. Blabbed, I mean.

01:50:08.590 --> 01:50:14.970
It's my belief neither of you gentlemen know what you are about, but I'll tell you my way of it.

01:50:14.970 --> 01:50:19.030
Life or death, and a close run.

01:50:20.770 --> 01:50:27.430
That is all clear, and I dare say true enough, replied Dr. Livesey.

01:50:27.970 --> 01:50:32.410
We take the risk, but we are not so ignorant as you believe us.

01:50:33.870 --> 01:50:38.850
Next, you say you don't like the crew. Are they not good seamen?

01:50:39.810 --> 01:50:47.210
I don't like them, sir, returned Captain Smollett, and I think I should have had the choosing of my

01:50:47.210 --> 01:50:57.110
own hands if you go to that. Perhaps you should, replied the doctor. My friend should perhaps have

01:50:57.110 --> 01:51:04.330
taken you along with him, but the slight, if there be one, was unintentional. And you don't

01:51:04.330 --> 01:51:07.830
like Mr. Arrow? I don't, sir.

01:51:08.450 --> 01:51:13.850
I believe he's a good seamen, but he's too free with the crew to be a good officer.

01:51:15.250 --> 01:51:20.930
A mate should keep himself to himself, shouldn't drink with the men before the mast.

01:51:22.610 --> 01:51:25.610
Do you mean he drinks? cried the squire.

01:51:26.910 --> 01:51:31.290
No, sir, replied the captain. Only that he's too familiar.

01:51:32.930 --> 01:51:41.610
Well, now, and the short and long of it, Captain? asked the doctor. Tell us what you want.

01:51:43.750 --> 01:51:47.930
Well, gentlemen, are you determined to go on this cruise?

01:51:49.570 --> 01:51:52.210
Like iron, answered the squire.

01:51:54.130 --> 01:51:56.210
Very good, said the captain.

01:51:57.170 --> 01:52:02.850
Then, as you've heard me very patiently, saying things that I could not prove,

01:52:03.830 --> 01:52:10.110
hear me a few words more. They are putting the powder and the arms in the forehold.

01:52:11.530 --> 01:52:15.690
Now you have a good place under the cabin. Why not put them there?

01:52:17.090 --> 01:52:18.050
First point.

01:52:20.310 --> 01:52:24.130
Then, you are bringing four of your own people with you,

01:52:24.350 --> 01:52:27.530
and they tell me some of them are to be birthed forward.

01:52:28.650 --> 01:52:31.790
Why not give them the births here beside the cabin?

01:52:33.310 --> 01:52:38.670
Second point. Any more? asked Mr. Turillani.

01:52:40.790 --> 01:52:46.410
One more, said the captain. There's been too much blabbing already.

01:52:48.050 --> 01:52:50.750
Far too much, agreed the doctor.

01:52:52.770 --> 01:53:00.950
I'll tell you what I've heard myself, continued Captain Smollett, that you have a map of an island,

01:53:02.390 --> 01:53:09.070
that there's crosses on the map to show where treasure is, and that the island lies.

01:53:10.810 --> 01:53:15.870
And then he named the latitude and longitude exactly.

01:53:18.050 --> 01:53:21.970
I never told that, cried the squire, to a soul.

01:53:23.470 --> 01:53:26.630
The hands know it, sir, returned the captain.

01:53:28.890 --> 01:53:33.150
Livesey, that must have been you or Hawkins, cried the squire.

01:53:35.110 --> 01:53:39.170
It doesn't much matter who it was, replied the doctor.

01:53:40.210 --> 01:53:46.710
And I could see that neither he nor the captain paid much regard to Mr. Turillani's protestations.

01:53:48.210 --> 01:53:52.580
Neither did I, to be sure. He was so loose a talker.

01:53:53.790 --> 01:54:00.690
Yet in this case I believe he was really right, and that nobody had told the situation of the island.

01:54:03.750 --> 01:54:10.290
Well, gentlemen, continued the captain, I don't know who has this map,

01:54:11.190 --> 01:54:16.850
but I make it a point. It shall be kept secret even from me and Mr. Arrow.

01:54:18.170 --> 01:54:20.930
Otherwise I would ask you to let me resign.

01:54:23.650 --> 01:54:25.850
I see, said the doctor.

01:54:27.650 --> 01:54:33.610
You wish us to keep this matter dark, and to make a garrison of the stern part of the ship,

01:54:34.550 --> 01:54:40.770
manned with my friend's own people, and provided with all the arms and powder on board.

01:54:42.270 --> 01:54:45.390
In other words, you fear a mutiny.

01:54:47.410 --> 01:54:57.670
Sir, said Captain Smollett, with no intention to take offence, I deny your right to put words into my mouth.

01:54:59.350 --> 01:55:06.850
No captain, sir, would be justified in going to sea at all if he had ground enough to say that.

01:55:09.010 --> 01:55:13.490
As for Mr. Arrow, I believe him thoroughly honest.

01:55:14.450 --> 01:55:19.250
Some of the men are the same. All may be for what I know.

01:55:21.430 --> 01:55:27.950
But I am responsible for the ship's safety, and the life of every man jack aboard of her.

01:55:29.590 --> 01:55:34.130
I see things going, as I think, not quite right.

01:55:35.450 --> 01:55:41.130
And I ask you to take certain precautions, or let me resign my berth.

01:55:42.750 --> 01:55:45.130
And that's all.

01:55:47.970 --> 01:55:51.430
Captain Smollett, began the doctor with a smile.

01:55:52.970 --> 01:55:56.550
Did ever you hear the fable of the mountain and the mouse?

01:55:58.470 --> 01:56:03.270
You'll excuse me, I dare say, but you remind me of that fable.

01:56:04.950 --> 01:56:10.210
When you came in here, I'll stake my wig. You meant more than this.

01:56:12.990 --> 01:56:16.390
Doctor, said the captain, you are smart.

01:56:17.730 --> 01:56:25.110
When I came in here, I meant to get discharged. I had no thought that Mr. Trelawney would hear a word.

01:56:27.190 --> 01:56:35.430
No more I would, cried the squire. Had Livesey not been here, I should have seen you to the deuce.

01:56:36.210 --> 01:56:45.050
As it is, I have heard you. I will do as you desire, but I think the worse of you.

01:56:47.270 --> 01:56:53.470
That's as you please, sir, said the captain. You'll find I do my duty.

01:56:55.870 --> 01:56:58.030
And with that he took his leave.

01:57:01.270 --> 01:57:10.970
Trelawney, said the doctor, contrary to all my notions, I believe you have managed to get two honest men on board with you.

01:57:12.170 --> 01:57:14.510
That man and John Silver.

01:57:16.790 --> 01:57:19.730
Silver if you like, cried the squire.

01:57:20.730 --> 01:57:30.860
But as for that intolerable humbug, I declare I think his conduct unmanly, unsalerly, and downright un-English.

01:57:33.370 --> 01:57:38.470
Well, says the doctor, we shall see.

01:57:41.490 --> 01:57:53.950
When we came on deck, the men had begun already to take out the arms and powder, yo-hoing at their work, while the captain and Mr. Arrow stood by superintending.

01:57:57.330 --> 01:57:59.910
The new arrangement was quite to my liking.

01:58:01.190 --> 01:58:09.410
The whole schooner had been overhauled, six berths had been made a stern out of what had been the after part of the main hold,

01:58:10.410 --> 01:58:17.770
and this set of cabins was only joined to the galley and forecastle by a sparred passage on the port side.

01:58:19.570 --> 01:58:30.780
It had been originally meant that the captain, Mr. Arrow, Hunter, Joyce, the doctor, and the squire were to occupy these six berths.

01:58:33.210 --> 01:58:40.730
Now Redruth and I were to get two of them, and Mr. Arrow and the captain were to sleep on deck in the companion,

01:58:41.490 --> 01:58:46.270
which had been enlarged on each side till you might have almost called it a roundhouse.

01:58:48.170 --> 01:58:57.770
Very low it was still, of course, but there was room to swing two hammocks, and even the mate seemed pleased with the arrangement.

01:59:00.670 --> 01:59:11.990
Even he, perhaps, had been doubtful as to the crew, but that is only guess, for as you shall hear, we had not long the benefit of his opinion.

01:59:15.430 --> 01:59:26.850
We were all hard at work, changing the powder and the berths, when the last man or two, and Long John along with them, came off in a shoreboat.

01:59:29.650 --> 01:59:35.590
The cook came up the side like a monkey for cleverness, and as soon as he saw what was doing,

01:59:36.310 --> 01:59:39.930
So ho, mates! says he. What's this?

01:59:41.650 --> 01:59:45.750
We're a changing of the powder, Jack, answers one.

01:59:46.970 --> 01:59:53.890
Why, by the powers! cried Long John. If we do, we'll miss the morning tide.

01:59:55.790 --> 02:00:03.930
My orders, said the captain shortly. You may go below, my man. Hands will want supper.

02:00:05.790 --> 02:00:14.350
Aye, aye, sir, answered the cook, and touching his forelock, he disappeared at once in the direction of his galley.

02:00:16.710 --> 02:00:19.690
That's a good man, captain, said the doctor.

02:00:21.590 --> 02:00:24.790
Very likely, sir, replied Captain Smollett.

02:00:26.150 --> 02:00:28.510
Easy with that, men, easy!

02:00:29.490 --> 02:00:39.970
He ran on to the fellows who were shifting the powder, and then suddenly observing me examining the swivel we carried amid ships, along Brass Nine.

02:00:41.050 --> 02:00:48.550
Hear you, ships boy! he cried. Out of that! Off with you to the cook, and get some work!

02:00:50.730 --> 02:00:59.930
And then, as I was hurrying off, I heard him say quite loudly to the doctor, I'll have no favourites on my ship.

02:01:01.930 --> 02:01:09.570
I assure you, I was quite of the squire's way of thinking, and hated the captain deeply.

02:01:17.750 --> 02:01:21.810
Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson

02:01:22.530 --> 02:01:26.570
Chapter 10 The Voyage

02:01:28.770 --> 02:01:43.030
All that night we were in a great bustle getting things stowed in their place, and boatfuls of the squire's friends, Mr. Blandly and the like, coming off to wish him a good voyage and a safe return.

02:01:45.130 --> 02:01:49.970
We never had a night at the Admiral Benbow when I had half the work.

02:01:51.430 --> 02:02:01.290
And I was dog-tired when, a little before dawn, the boatswain sounded his pipe, and the crew began to man the capstan bars.

02:02:03.390 --> 02:02:11.410
I might have been twice as weary, yet I would not have left the deck. All was so new and interesting to me.

02:02:11.410 --> 02:02:20.510
The brief commands, the shrill note of the whistle, the men bustling to their places in the glimmer of the ship's lanterns.

02:02:23.530 --> 02:02:28.670
Now, Barbecue, tip us a stave, cried one voice.

02:02:30.030 --> 02:02:32.150
The old one, cried another.

02:02:33.830 --> 02:02:44.390
Ay, ay, mates, said Long John, who was standing by with his crutch under his arm, and at once broke out in the air, and words I knew so well.

02:02:45.630 --> 02:02:48.590
Fifteen men on the dead man's chest.

02:02:49.770 --> 02:02:52.210
And the whole crew bore chorus.

02:02:53.430 --> 02:02:57.050
Yo ho ho, and a bottle a rum.

02:02:58.970 --> 02:03:03.470
And at the third ho, drove the bars before them with a will.

02:03:06.050 --> 02:03:16.170
Even at that exciting moment it carried me back to the old Admiral Benbow in a second, and I seemed to hear the voice of the captain piping in the chorus.

02:03:18.590 --> 02:03:24.770
But soon the anchor was short up. Soon it was hanging, dripping at the bows.

02:03:26.350 --> 02:03:32.670
Soon the sails began to draw, and the land and shipping to flit by on either side.

02:03:34.110 --> 02:03:41.630
And before I could lie down to snatch an hour of slumber, the Hispaniola had begun her voyage to the Isle of Treasure.

02:03:44.670 --> 02:03:49.010
I am not going to relate that voyage in detail.

02:03:50.230 --> 02:03:51.990
It was fairly prosperous.

02:03:53.590 --> 02:04:02.350
The ship proved to be a good ship, the crew were capable seamen, and the captain thoroughly understood his business.

02:04:04.050 --> 02:04:11.210
But before we came the length of Treasure Island, two or three things had happened which required to be known.

02:04:14.190 --> 02:04:19.830
Mr. Arrow, first of all, turned out even worse than the captain had feared.

02:04:21.750 --> 02:04:26.710
He had no command among the men, and people did what they pleased with him.

02:04:28.210 --> 02:04:40.110
But that was by no means the worst of it, for after a day or two at sea he began to appear on deck with hazy eye, red cheeks, stuttering tongue,

02:04:40.830 --> 02:04:43.110
and other marks of drunkenness.

02:04:45.450 --> 02:04:48.410
Time after time he was ordered below in disgrace.

02:04:50.970 --> 02:04:58.350
Sometimes he fell and cut himself, sometimes he lay all day long in his little bunk at one side of the companion,

02:05:00.170 --> 02:05:07.350
sometimes for a day or two he would be almost sober and attend to his work at least passably.

02:05:10.850 --> 02:05:14.910
In the meantime we could never make out where he got the drink.

02:05:16.290 --> 02:05:18.050
That was the ship's mystery.

02:05:19.550 --> 02:05:23.350
Watch him as we pleased, we could do nothing to solve it.

02:05:24.050 --> 02:05:29.310
And when we asked him to his face, he would only laugh if he were drunk,

02:05:29.990 --> 02:05:35.630
and if he were sober deny solemnly that he ever tasted anything but water.

02:05:38.210 --> 02:05:44.010
He was not only useless as an officer and a bad influence amongst the men,

02:05:44.710 --> 02:05:49.230
but it was plain that at this rate he must soon kill himself outright.

02:05:51.570 --> 02:06:04.730
So nobody was much surprised, nor very sorry, when one dark night with a head sea he disappeared entirely and was seen no more.

02:06:07.950 --> 02:06:10.210
Overboard, said the captain.

02:06:11.730 --> 02:06:16.010
Well, gentlemen, that saves the trouble of putting him in irons.

02:06:18.870 --> 02:06:25.650
But there we were, without a mate, and it was necessary, of course, to advance one of the men.

02:06:27.430 --> 02:06:32.190
The bosom, Job Anderson, was the likeliest man aboard,

02:06:32.910 --> 02:06:36.510
and though he kept his old title he served in a way as mate.

02:06:38.950 --> 02:06:43.810
Mr. Trelawney had followed the sea, and his knowledge made him very useful,

02:06:44.590 --> 02:06:47.570
for he often took a watch himself in easy weather.

02:06:48.770 --> 02:06:56.730
And the coxswain, Israel Hands, was a careful, wily, old, experienced seaman,

02:06:57.150 --> 02:07:00.010
who could be trusted at a pinch with almost anything.

02:07:03.590 --> 02:07:06.370
He was a great confidant of Long John Silver,

02:07:07.110 --> 02:07:11.750
and so the mention of his name leads me to speak of our ship's cook,

02:07:12.470 --> 02:07:14.790
Barbecue, as the men called him.

02:07:18.630 --> 02:07:22.390
Aboard ship he carried his crutch by a lanyard round his neck,

02:07:23.150 --> 02:07:25.630
to have both hands as free as possible.

02:07:27.130 --> 02:07:31.190
It was something to see him wedge the foot of the crutch against a bulkhead,

02:07:32.050 --> 02:07:35.710
and propped against it, yielding to every movement of the ship,

02:07:36.690 --> 02:07:39.590
still get on with his cooking like someone safe ashore.

02:07:41.770 --> 02:07:46.130
Still more strange was it to see him in the heaviest of weather cross the deck.

02:07:48.270 --> 02:07:52.890
He had a line or two rigged up to help him across the widest spaces,

02:07:53.930 --> 02:07:55.730
Long John's earrings they were called,

02:07:56.250 --> 02:07:59.110
and he would hand himself from one place to another,

02:07:59.850 --> 02:08:04.330
now using the crutch, now trailing it alongside by the lanyard,

02:08:04.790 --> 02:08:06.930
as quickly as another man could walk.

02:08:09.470 --> 02:08:14.710
Yet some of the men who had sailed with him before expressed their pity to see him so reduced.

02:08:17.910 --> 02:08:22.170
He's no common man, Barbecue, said the coxswain to me.

02:08:23.290 --> 02:08:25.570
He had good schooling in his young days,

02:08:26.030 --> 02:08:28.390
and can speak like a book when so minded,

02:08:29.030 --> 02:08:33.330
and brave, a lion's nothing alongside of Long John.

02:08:34.510 --> 02:08:38.890
I seen him grapple for and knock their heads together, him unarmed.

02:08:41.470 --> 02:08:45.210
All the crew respected, and even obeyed him.

02:08:46.410 --> 02:08:52.050
He had a way of talking to each, and doing everybody some particular service.

02:08:54.090 --> 02:08:56.370
To me he was unwiridly kind,

02:08:57.030 --> 02:09:01.470
and always glad to see me in the galley, which he kept as clean as a new pin,

02:09:02.630 --> 02:09:06.570
the dishes hanging up burnished, and his parrot in a cage in one corner.

02:09:08.530 --> 02:09:13.930
Come away, Hawkins, he would say, come and have a yarn with John.

02:09:14.920 --> 02:09:17.710
Nobody more welcome than yourself, my son.

02:09:19.150 --> 02:09:20.890
Sit you down and hear the news.

02:09:22.150 --> 02:09:23.390
Here's Captain Flint.

02:09:24.530 --> 02:09:28.000
I calls my parrot Captain Flint after the famous buccaneer.

02:09:29.350 --> 02:09:32.830
Here's Captain Flint predicting success to our voyage.

02:09:33.490 --> 02:09:34.470
Wasn't you, Captain?

02:09:35.990 --> 02:09:39.070
And the parrot would say with great rapidity,

02:09:39.070 --> 02:09:43.070
Pieces of eight, pieces of eight, pieces of eight,

02:09:43.410 --> 02:09:45.950
till you wondered that it was not out of breath,

02:09:46.810 --> 02:09:49.630
or till John threw his handkerchief over the cage.

02:09:52.670 --> 02:09:59.070
Now that bird, he would say, is maybe two hundred years old, Hawkins.

02:10:00.070 --> 02:10:06.510
They live forever mostly, and if anybody's seen more wickedness it must be the devil himself.

02:10:08.230 --> 02:10:12.410
She's sailed with England, the great Captain England, the pirate.

02:10:13.770 --> 02:10:21.910
She's been at Madagascar, and Malabar, and Suriname, and Providence, and Portobello.

02:10:23.830 --> 02:10:26.850
She was at the fishing up of the wrecked plate ships.

02:10:28.330 --> 02:10:31.850
It's there she learned pieces of eight, and little wonder,

02:10:32.730 --> 02:10:35.610
three hundred and fifty thousand of them Hawkins.

02:10:36.930 --> 02:10:41.270
She was at the boarding of the Viceroy of the Indies out of Goa she was,

02:10:41.370 --> 02:10:44.930
and to look at her you would think she was a baby.

02:10:46.690 --> 02:10:49.990
But you smelt powder, didn't you, Captain?

02:10:52.010 --> 02:10:55.230
Stand by to go about, the parrot would scream.

02:10:57.410 --> 02:11:01.210
Ah, she's a handsome craft she is, the cook would say,

02:11:02.250 --> 02:11:03.910
and give her sugar from his pocket.

02:11:03.910 --> 02:11:11.210
And then the bird would peck at the bars and swear straight on passing belief for wickedness.

02:11:13.070 --> 02:11:18.890
There, John would add, you can't touch pitch and not be mucked lad.

02:11:20.390 --> 02:11:24.830
Here's this poor old innocent bird of mine swearing blue fire,

02:11:25.570 --> 02:11:27.910
and none the wiser you may lay to that.

02:11:28.930 --> 02:11:32.370
She would swear the same in a manner of speaking before Chaplain.

02:11:34.410 --> 02:11:40.890
And John would touch his forelock with a solemn way he had that made me think he was the best of men.

02:11:44.070 --> 02:11:50.110
In the meantime, the squire and Captain Smollett were still on pretty distant terms with one another.

02:11:51.950 --> 02:11:54.270
The squire made no bones about the matter.

02:11:55.030 --> 02:11:56.590
He despised the captain.

02:11:58.970 --> 02:12:03.170
The captain on his part never spoke but when he was spoken to,

02:12:03.170 --> 02:12:07.970
and then sharp and short and dry, and not a word wasted.

02:12:10.090 --> 02:12:16.070
He owned, when driven into a corner, that he seemed to have been wrong about the crew,

02:12:17.350 --> 02:12:22.510
that some of them were as brisk as he wanted to see and all had behaved fairly well.

02:12:25.370 --> 02:12:29.510
As for the ship, he had taken a downright fancy to her.

02:12:30.430 --> 02:12:36.510
Shall I appoint nearer the wind than a man has a right to expect of his own married wife, sir?

02:12:38.030 --> 02:12:44.370
But, he would add, all I say is, we're not home again.

02:12:45.290 --> 02:12:47.510
And I don't like the crews.

02:12:49.570 --> 02:12:55.090
The squire had this, would turn away and march up and down the deck chin in air.

02:12:56.790 --> 02:13:02.070
A trifle more of that man, he would say, and I shall explode.

02:13:06.810 --> 02:13:12.310
We had some heavy weather, which only proved the qualities of the Hispaniola.

02:13:13.890 --> 02:13:20.450
Every man on board seemed well content, and they must have been hard to please if they had been otherwise.

02:13:20.450 --> 02:13:27.830
For it is my belief there never was a ship's company so spoiled since Noah put to sea.

02:13:30.030 --> 02:13:32.290
Double grog was going on the least excuse.

02:13:33.330 --> 02:13:38.930
There was duff on odd days as, for instance, if the squire heard it was any man's birthday.

02:13:40.430 --> 02:13:46.690
And always a barrel of apples standing broached in the waste for anyone to help himself that had a fancy.

02:13:49.450 --> 02:13:54.590
Never knew good come of it yet, the captain said to Dr. Livesey.

02:13:54.650 --> 02:13:59.010
Spoil folks for hands, make devils, that's my belief.

02:14:01.410 --> 02:14:05.570
But good did come of the apple barrel, as you shall hear.

02:14:06.930 --> 02:14:15.930
For if it had not been for that, we should have had no note of warning, and might all have perished by the hand of treachery.

02:14:18.490 --> 02:14:21.170
This was how it came about.

02:14:23.870 --> 02:14:27.570
We had run up the trades to get the wind of the island we were after.

02:14:28.730 --> 02:14:30.610
I am not allowed to be more plain.

02:14:31.770 --> 02:14:36.030
And now we were running down for it with a bright lookout day and night.

02:14:38.330 --> 02:14:43.690
It was about the last day of our outward voyage by the largest computation.

02:14:45.390 --> 02:14:52.850
Sometime that night, or at latest before noon of the morrow, we should sight the treasure island.

02:14:55.330 --> 02:15:01.570
We were heading south-southwest and had a steady breeze abeam and a quiet sea.

02:15:03.790 --> 02:15:09.690
The Hispaniola rolled steadily, dipping her bow-spirit now and then with a whiff of spray.

02:15:11.490 --> 02:15:13.950
All was drawing low and aloft.

02:15:15.150 --> 02:15:21.230
Everyone was in the bravest spirits, because we were now so near an end of the first part of our adventure.

02:15:24.670 --> 02:15:33.750
Now after sundown, when all my work was over and I was on my way to my birth, it occurred to me that I should like an apple.

02:15:35.650 --> 02:15:37.130
I ran on deck.

02:15:38.070 --> 02:15:41.230
The watch was all forward looking out for the island.

02:15:42.790 --> 02:15:47.910
The man at the helm was watching the luff of the sail and whistling away gently to himself.

02:15:49.450 --> 02:15:57.030
And that was the only sound excepting the swish of the sea against the bows and around the sides of the ship.

02:15:59.990 --> 02:16:05.630
In I got bodily to the apple-barrel and found there was scarce an apple left.

02:16:06.390 --> 02:16:13.170
But sitting down there in the dark, what with the sound of the waters and the rocking movement of the ship,

02:16:14.490 --> 02:16:22.970
I had either fallen asleep or was on the point of doing so when a heavy man sat down with rather a clash close by.

02:16:25.730 --> 02:16:34.170
The barrel shook as he leaned his shoulders against it, and I was just about to jump up when the man began to speak.

02:16:36.210 --> 02:16:38.710
It was Silver's voice.

02:16:40.350 --> 02:16:47.250
And before I had heard a dozen words, I would not have shown myself for all the world,

02:16:48.310 --> 02:16:54.770
but lay there, trembling and listening in the extreme of fear and curiosity.

02:16:56.230 --> 02:17:08.030
For from these dozen words I understood that the lives of all the honest men aboard depended upon me alone.

02:17:30.910 --> 02:17:33.990
XI. What I Heard in the Apple Barrel

02:17:34.890 --> 02:18:03.970
No, not I, said Silver. Flute was captain, I was quartermaster, along with my timber leg. The same broadside I lost my leg, O' Pew lost his deadlights. It was a master sergeant, him that amputated me, out of college and all, lattened by the bucket and what not, where he was hanged like a dog and sundried like the rest at Corso Castle. That was Robertsmen that was, and combed of changing names to their ships,

02:18:04.830 --> 02:18:28.350
royal fortune and so on. Now what a ship was christened, so let her stay, I says. So it was the Cassandra, as I brought us all safe home from Malabar after England took the Viceroy of the Indias. So it was with the old Walrus, Flint's old ship, as I've seen a muck with the red blood and fit to ink with the gold.

02:18:29.110 --> 02:18:38.530
Ah! cried another voice, that of the youngest hand on the board, and evidently full of admiration. He was the flower of the flock, was Flint.

02:18:39.470 --> 02:19:04.850
Davis was a man too, by all accounts, said Silver. I never sailed along a him, first with England, then with Flint, that's my story, and now here on my own account, in a manner of speaking. I laid by nine hundred safe from England, and two thousand after Flint. That ain't bad for a man before the mast, old safe in the bank. It ain't earning now, it's saving does it, you may lay to that.

02:19:05.570 --> 02:19:15.410
Where's all England's men now? I don't know, where's Flint? Why, most of them aboard here, and glad to get the duff, been begging before that some of them.

02:19:16.070 --> 02:19:38.070
Oh, Pew has had lost his sight, might have thought shame, spends twelve hundred pounds a year, like a lord in Parliament. Where is he now? Well, he's dead now and under hatches. But for two years before that, shiver me timbers, the man was starving. He begged and he stole and he cut throats and he starved at that by the powers.

02:19:39.010 --> 02:19:42.490
Well, it isn't much use after all, said the young seaman.

02:19:43.130 --> 02:19:58.110
Taint much use for fools, you may lay to that. That nor nothing, cried Silver. But now you look here, you're young, you are, you're smart as paint. I see that when I set my eyes on you, and I'll talk to you like a man.

02:19:58.110 --> 02:20:16.510
You may imagine how I felt when I heard this abominable old rogue addressing another in the very same words of flattery as he had used to myself. I think if I had been able that I would have killed him through the barrel. Meantime he ran on, little supposing he was overheard.

02:20:17.270 --> 02:20:31.070
Here it is about gentlemen of fortune. They live rough and they risk swinging. But they eat and drink like fighting cocks, and when the cruise is done, why, it's a hundreds of pounds instead of hundreds of farthings in their pockets.

02:20:31.600 --> 02:20:52.130
Now the most goes for rum and a good fling, and to the sea again in their shirts. But that's not the course I lay. I puts it all away. Some here, some there, and none too much anywheres by reason of suspicion. I'm fifty, mark you. Once back from this cruise I set up gentlemen in earnest.

02:20:52.890 --> 02:21:08.510
Time enough too, says you. Ah, but I've lived easy in the meantime. Never denied myself a nothing heart desires, and slept soft and ate dainty all my days but when at sea. And how did I begin? Before the mast like you.

02:21:09.220 --> 02:21:15.790
Well said the other. But all the other money's gone now, ain't it? You daren't show face in Bristol after this.

02:21:16.630 --> 02:21:20.670
Why, where might you suppose it was? asked Silver derisively.

02:21:21.590 --> 02:21:24.730
Had Bristol in banks and places? answered his companion.

02:21:25.470 --> 02:21:37.930
It were, said the cook. It were when we weighed anchor. But my old missus has it all by now, and the spy-glasses sold, lease and goodwill and rigging, and the old girl's off to meet me.

02:21:38.570 --> 02:21:43.550
I would tell you where, for I trust you. But it'd make jealousy among the mates.

02:21:44.490 --> 02:21:47.530
And you can trust your missus? asked the other.

02:21:48.410 --> 02:21:57.750
Gentlemen of fortune, returned the cook, usually trust little among themselves, and right they are you may lay to it. But I have a way with me I have.

02:21:57.750 --> 02:22:05.810
When a mate brings a slip on his cable, as one knows me I mean it, it won't be the same world with old John.

02:22:06.630 --> 02:22:18.310
There was some that was feared of Pugh, and some that was feared of Flint, but Flint his own self was feared of me, feared he was, and proud.

02:22:19.110 --> 02:22:26.310
There was a roughest crew afloat, was Flint. The devil himself would have been feared to go to sea with them.

02:22:26.530 --> 02:22:32.190
Well now, I tell you, I'm not a Boatsden man, and you've seen yourself how easy I keep company.

02:22:32.850 --> 02:22:38.710
But when I was quartermaster, lambs wasn't a word for Flint's old buccaneers.

02:22:39.770 --> 02:22:42.870
Ah, you may be sure of yourself in old John's ship.

02:22:43.450 --> 02:22:50.410
What I tell you now, replied the lad, I didn't half a quarter like this job till I had this talk with you, John.

02:22:51.130 --> 02:22:52.730
But there's my hand on it now.

02:22:53.210 --> 02:22:59.850
And a brave lad you were, and smart too, answered Silver, shaking hands so heartily that all the barrels shook.

02:23:00.290 --> 02:23:04.930
And a finer figurehead for a gentleman of fortune I've never clapped my eyes on.

02:23:05.790 --> 02:23:09.010
By this time I had begun to understand the meaning of their terms.

02:23:09.710 --> 02:23:15.390
By a gentleman of fortune they plainly meant neither more nor less than a common pirate.

02:23:15.990 --> 02:23:21.730
And the little scene that I had overheard was the last act in the corruption of one of the honest hands,

02:23:22.130 --> 02:23:24.090
perhaps of the last one left aboard.

02:23:24.610 --> 02:23:26.930
But on this point I was soon to be relieved.

02:23:27.450 --> 02:23:32.950
For Silver, giving a little whistle, a third man strolled up and sat down by the party.

02:23:33.710 --> 02:23:35.530
Dick Square, said Silver.

02:23:35.950 --> 02:23:41.470
Oh, I know Dick Square, returned the voice of the coxswain Israel Hands.

02:23:42.290 --> 02:23:43.610
He's no fool, he's Dick.

02:23:43.990 --> 02:23:45.650
And he turned his quid and spat.

02:23:46.450 --> 02:23:48.890
But look here, he went on.

02:23:49.290 --> 02:23:51.390
Here's what I want to know, Barbecue.

02:23:52.110 --> 02:23:56.850
How long are we going to stand off and on like a blessed bumboat?

02:23:57.550 --> 02:24:01.050
I've almost had enough of old Captain Smollett.

02:24:01.550 --> 02:24:03.630
He's hazed me long enough by thunder.

02:24:04.290 --> 02:24:09.130
I want to go into that cabin I do, I want their pickles and wine and that.

02:24:10.350 --> 02:24:11.650
Israel, said Silver.

02:24:12.490 --> 02:24:15.510
Your head ain't much account, or never was.

02:24:16.210 --> 02:24:19.970
But you are able to hear, I reckon, lest ways your ears is big enough.

02:24:20.770 --> 02:24:22.030
Now here's what I say.

02:24:22.510 --> 02:24:28.350
You'll berth forward and you'll live hard and you'll speak soft and you'll keep sober till I give the word.

02:24:28.870 --> 02:24:30.870
And you may lay to that my son.

02:24:31.990 --> 02:24:35.050
Well, I don't say no, do I?

02:24:35.310 --> 02:24:36.350
growled the coxswain.

02:24:37.290 --> 02:24:40.690
What I say is when, that's what I say.

02:24:41.250 --> 02:24:41.730
When?

02:24:42.030 --> 02:24:43.710
By the powers, cried Silver.

02:24:44.430 --> 02:24:47.170
Well now, if you want to know, I'll tell you when.

02:24:47.610 --> 02:24:50.210
The last moment I can manage and that's when.

02:24:50.710 --> 02:24:52.890
Here's a first great seaman, Captain Smollett.

02:24:53.330 --> 02:24:54.730
Sales the best ship for us.

02:24:55.210 --> 02:24:57.910
Here's the squire and the doctor with a map and such.

02:24:57.910 --> 02:25:00.210
I don't know where it is, do I?

02:25:00.530 --> 02:25:02.010
No more do you, says you.

02:25:02.630 --> 02:25:08.790
Well then, I mean the squire and doctor shall find the stuff and help us to get it aboard by the powers.

02:25:09.150 --> 02:25:10.130
Then we'll see.

02:25:10.610 --> 02:25:17.770
If I was sure of you all, sons of double Dutchmen, I'd have Captain Smollett navigate us half way back again before I struck.

02:25:18.290 --> 02:25:22.570
Why, we're all seaman aboard here, I should think, said the lad Dick.

02:25:23.870 --> 02:25:27.510
We're all forksle hands you mean, snapped Silver.

02:25:27.970 --> 02:25:31.110
We can steer a course, but who's to set one?

02:25:31.870 --> 02:25:34.670
That's what all of you gentlemen spit on, first and last.

02:25:34.910 --> 02:25:39.350
If I head my way, I'd have Captain Smollett work us back into the trades at least.

02:25:39.790 --> 02:25:45.230
Then we'd have no blessed miscalculations and a spoonful of water a day.

02:25:45.750 --> 02:25:47.230
But I know the sorts you are.

02:25:47.530 --> 02:25:52.210
I'll finish with them at the island, as soon as the blunts on board, and pity it is.

02:25:52.810 --> 02:25:54.850
But you're never happy till you're drunk.

02:25:55.310 --> 02:25:58.810
Split my sides, I've a sick heart to sail with the likes of you.

02:25:59.790 --> 02:26:01.990
Easy all, Long John, cried Israel.

02:26:02.290 --> 02:26:03.570
Who's a crossin' of you?

02:26:04.850 --> 02:26:08.510
Why, how many tall ships think you know have I seen laid aboard?

02:26:08.990 --> 02:26:13.590
And how many brisk lads dying in the sun at Execution Dock, cried Silver.

02:26:14.030 --> 02:26:16.790
And all for the same hurry and hurry and hurry.

02:26:17.050 --> 02:26:17.950
You hear me?

02:26:18.530 --> 02:26:20.710
I seen a thing or two at sea I have.

02:26:21.310 --> 02:26:25.430
If you would only lay your course in the pint into the windward,

02:26:25.770 --> 02:26:27.530
you would ride in carriages you would.

02:26:27.570 --> 02:26:29.350
But not you, I know you.

02:26:30.090 --> 02:26:33.130
You'll have your mouth full of brunt tomorrow and go hang.

02:26:33.670 --> 02:26:36.430
Everybody knows you was a kind of a chaplain, John.

02:26:36.930 --> 02:26:40.830
But there's others that could hand and steer as well as you, says Israel.

02:26:41.550 --> 02:26:43.450
They liked a bit of fun, they did.

02:26:43.930 --> 02:26:49.850
They wasn't so high and dry, know how, but took their fling like jolly companions every one.

02:26:50.810 --> 02:26:54.850
So, says Silver, well, and where are they now?

02:26:55.330 --> 02:26:57.730
Pew was that sort and he died a beggar man.

02:26:58.370 --> 02:27:00.850
Flint was and he died of rum at Savannah.

02:27:01.530 --> 02:27:03.690
And they was a sweet accrue, they was.

02:27:04.110 --> 02:27:05.230
Only where are they?

02:27:05.810 --> 02:27:10.110
But, asked Dick, when we do lay them a thwart, what are we to do with them anyhow?

02:27:10.850 --> 02:27:13.910
There's the man for me, cried the cook admiringly.

02:27:14.170 --> 02:27:15.590
That's what I call business.

02:27:16.330 --> 02:27:17.710
Well, what would you think?

02:27:17.710 --> 02:27:19.690
Put them ashore like maroons?

02:27:20.450 --> 02:27:24.250
That would have been England's way, or cut them down like that much park.

02:27:24.670 --> 02:27:26.970
That would have been Flint's or Billy Bone's.

02:27:27.730 --> 02:27:29.970
Billy was a man for that, said Israel.

02:27:30.490 --> 02:27:32.030
Dead men don't bite, says he.

02:27:32.370 --> 02:27:36.070
Well, he's dead now himself, and he knows long and short of it now.

02:27:36.250 --> 02:27:38.810
And if ever a rough hand come to port, it was Billy.

02:27:39.590 --> 02:27:42.070
Right you are, said Silver, rough and ready.

02:27:42.530 --> 02:27:44.470
But mark you here, I'm an easy man.

02:27:44.970 --> 02:27:46.710
I'm quite the gentleman, says you.

02:27:46.710 --> 02:27:48.350
But this time it's serious.

02:27:49.070 --> 02:27:50.110
Duty is duty, mates.

02:27:50.690 --> 02:27:52.590
I give my vote. Death.

02:27:53.350 --> 02:27:55.810
When I'm in Parliament and riding in me coach,

02:27:56.290 --> 02:27:58.690
I don't want none of these sea lawyers in the cabin

02:27:58.690 --> 02:28:02.170
a-coming home unlooked for like the devil at prayers.

02:28:03.110 --> 02:28:07.450
Wait, is what I say, to when the time comes, I let her rip.

02:28:08.250 --> 02:28:10.610
John, cried the cook, said, you're a man.

02:28:11.030 --> 02:28:13.690
You'll say so, Israel, when you see, said Silver.

02:28:14.450 --> 02:28:15.990
Only one thing I claim.

02:28:16.170 --> 02:28:17.630
I claim trellany.

02:28:18.250 --> 02:28:22.050
I'll wring his calf's head off his body with these hands, Dick,

02:28:22.430 --> 02:28:23.750
he added, breaking off.

02:28:24.050 --> 02:28:26.050
You just jump up like a sweet lad

02:28:26.050 --> 02:28:28.250
and get me an apple to wet me pipe like.

02:28:29.270 --> 02:28:31.530
You may fancy the terror I was in.

02:28:31.790 --> 02:28:35.230
I should have leaped out and run for it if I had found the strength,

02:28:35.650 --> 02:28:37.910
but my limbs and my heart misgave me.

02:28:38.170 --> 02:28:39.850
I heard Dick begin to rise.

02:28:40.250 --> 02:28:42.370
Then someone seemingly stopped him,

02:28:42.370 --> 02:28:44.330
and the voice of hands exclaimed,

02:28:44.530 --> 02:28:45.510
Oh, store that.

02:28:46.150 --> 02:28:48.590
Don't you get suckling of that bill, John.

02:28:48.930 --> 02:28:50.150
Let's have a go of the rum.

02:28:50.970 --> 02:28:53.530
Dick, said Silver, I trust you.

02:28:53.830 --> 02:28:55.710
I've a gauge on the pig, mind.

02:28:55.930 --> 02:28:56.730
There's the key.

02:28:57.470 --> 02:28:59.290
You fill a panikin and bring it up.

02:29:00.110 --> 02:29:01.290
Terrified I was.

02:29:01.790 --> 02:29:03.730
I could not help thinking to myself

02:29:03.730 --> 02:29:08.390
that this must have been how Mr. Arrow got the strong waters that destroyed him.

02:29:08.990 --> 02:29:10.470
Dick was gone but a little while,

02:29:10.470 --> 02:29:14.510
and during his absence Israel spoke straight on into the cook's ear.

02:29:14.950 --> 02:29:17.190
It was but a word or two that I could catch,

02:29:17.570 --> 02:29:19.550
and yet I gathered some important news,

02:29:20.070 --> 02:29:22.950
for besides other scraps that tended to the same purpose,

02:29:23.370 --> 02:29:24.930
this whole clause was audible.

02:29:25.790 --> 02:29:27.890
Not another man of the Magine.

02:29:28.410 --> 02:29:31.290
Hence there were still faithful men on board.

02:29:31.910 --> 02:29:33.050
When Dick returned,

02:29:33.270 --> 02:29:36.090
one after another of the trio took the panikin and drank,

02:29:36.550 --> 02:29:37.650
one to luck,

02:29:37.650 --> 02:29:38.710
another with,

02:29:39.030 --> 02:29:40.030
Here's to old Flint,

02:29:40.670 --> 02:29:43.150
and Silver himself sang in a kind of song,

02:29:43.630 --> 02:29:44.790
Here's to ourselves,

02:29:45.270 --> 02:29:46.370
and hold your luff,

02:29:46.570 --> 02:29:48.770
plenty of prizes and plenty of duff.

02:29:49.410 --> 02:29:52.530
Just then a sort of brightness fell upon me in the barrel,

02:29:52.570 --> 02:29:53.270
and looking up,

02:29:53.650 --> 02:29:55.090
I found the moon had risen,

02:29:55.370 --> 02:29:57.070
and was silvering the mizintop,

02:29:57.250 --> 02:29:59.530
and shining white on the luff of the forsel,

02:29:59.810 --> 02:30:01.630
and almost at the same time,

02:30:01.870 --> 02:30:03.430
the voice of the lookout shouted,

02:30:05.070 --> 02:30:06.190
Land Ho!

02:30:12.290 --> 02:30:13.410
Chapter 12

02:30:13.990 --> 02:30:15.330
Council of War

02:30:16.050 --> 02:30:19.270
There was a great rush of feet across the deck,

02:30:19.490 --> 02:30:22.510
I could hear people tumbling up from the cabin and the forsel,

02:30:22.970 --> 02:30:25.210
and slipping in an instant outside my barrel,

02:30:25.550 --> 02:30:27.250
I dived behind the forsel,

02:30:27.630 --> 02:30:29.090
and made double towards the stern,

02:30:29.270 --> 02:30:30.950
and came out upon the open deck,

02:30:30.950 --> 02:30:35.370
in time to join Hunter and Dr. Libzy in the rush for the weather bow.

02:30:36.370 --> 02:30:38.570
There all hands were already congregated,

02:30:38.950 --> 02:30:42.810
a belt of fog had lifted almost simultaneously with the appearance of the moon,

02:30:43.390 --> 02:30:44.910
away to the south-west of us,

02:30:45.170 --> 02:30:46.550
we saw two low hills,

02:30:46.870 --> 02:30:48.450
about a couple of miles apart,

02:30:49.010 --> 02:30:50.330
and rising behind one of them,

02:30:50.430 --> 02:30:51.690
a third and higher hill,

02:30:51.810 --> 02:30:53.890
whose peak was still buried in the fog,

02:30:54.410 --> 02:30:57.010
all three seemed sharp and conical in figure,

02:30:57.750 --> 02:31:00.010
so much I saw almost in a dream,

02:31:00.010 --> 02:31:03.910
for I had not yet recovered from my horrid fear of a minute or two before,

02:31:04.590 --> 02:31:08.290
and then I heard the voice of Captain Smollett issuing orders,

02:31:08.890 --> 02:31:11.710
the Hispaniola was laid a couple of points nearer the wind,

02:31:11.930 --> 02:31:15.730
and now sailed a course that would just clear the island on the east.

02:31:16.410 --> 02:31:18.570
And now men, said the captain,

02:31:18.790 --> 02:31:20.270
when all was sheated home,

02:31:20.830 --> 02:31:23.350
has any one of you ever seen that land ahead?

02:31:24.250 --> 02:31:26.190
I have, sir, said Silver,

02:31:26.630 --> 02:31:28.990
I've watered there with a trader I was cooking,

02:31:28.990 --> 02:31:32.170
the anchorage is on the south behind the ellet,

02:31:32.430 --> 02:31:34.630
I fancy, asked the captain.

02:31:35.170 --> 02:31:38.210
Yes, sir, Skelton Island, they calls it,

02:31:38.570 --> 02:31:40.670
it were a mean place for pirates once,

02:31:40.730 --> 02:31:42.070
and a hand we had on board,

02:31:42.210 --> 02:31:43.390
knowed all their names for it,

02:31:43.710 --> 02:31:46.730
that hill to the north they call the Foremast Hill,

02:31:47.090 --> 02:31:49.290
there are three hills in a row running southern,

02:31:49.750 --> 02:31:51.390
Four, Main and Misson, sir,

02:31:51.650 --> 02:31:54.150
but the main, that's the big one with the cloud on it,

02:31:54.370 --> 02:31:56.150
they usually calls it the Spyglass,

02:31:56.410 --> 02:31:58.110
by reason of a look out they kept,

02:31:58.110 --> 02:32:00.170
while they was in the anchorage cleaning,

02:32:00.570 --> 02:32:02.730
for it's there they clean the ships, sir,

02:32:02.910 --> 02:32:03.670
asking your pardon.

02:32:04.390 --> 02:32:06.790
I have a chart here, said Captain Smollett,

02:32:06.870 --> 02:32:08.270
and see if that's the place.

02:32:08.910 --> 02:32:11.690
Long John's eyes burned in his head as he took the chart,

02:32:12.030 --> 02:32:15.890
but by the fresh look of the paper I knew he was doomed to disappointment.

02:32:16.390 --> 02:32:19.510
This was not the map we found in Billy Bones' chest,

02:32:19.750 --> 02:32:22.370
but an accurate copy, complete in all things,

02:32:22.810 --> 02:32:24.270
names and heights and soundings,

02:32:24.270 --> 02:32:28.670
with the single exception of the red crosses and the written notes.

02:32:29.330 --> 02:32:31.650
Sharp as must have been his annoyance,

02:32:32.110 --> 02:32:34.330
Silver had the strength of mind to hide it.

02:32:34.730 --> 02:32:37.910
Yes, sir, said he, this is the spot to be sure,

02:32:38.370 --> 02:32:39.870
very prettily drawn out,

02:32:40.190 --> 02:32:41.570
who might have done that, I wonder,

02:32:42.030 --> 02:32:43.890
the pirates were too ignorant, I reckon.

02:32:44.530 --> 02:32:47.030
Aye, here it is, Captain Kidd's Anchorage,

02:32:47.530 --> 02:32:49.710
just the name my shipmate called it,

02:32:49.970 --> 02:32:52.010
there's strong current runs along the south,

02:32:52.010 --> 02:32:54.750
and they're away northward up the west coast.

02:32:55.210 --> 02:32:57.010
But you was, sir, says he,

02:32:57.270 --> 02:32:59.750
to hold your wind and keep the weather off the island.

02:33:00.370 --> 02:33:03.450
Lest ways, if such was your intention as to enter in Clareen,

02:33:03.730 --> 02:33:06.150
and there ain't no better place for that in these waters.

02:33:06.890 --> 02:33:09.170
Thank you, my man, said Captain Smollett.

02:33:09.770 --> 02:33:11.930
I'll ask you later on to give us help.

02:33:12.210 --> 02:33:13.310
You may go.

02:33:13.710 --> 02:33:18.090
I was surprised at the coolness with which John avowed his knowledge of the island,

02:33:18.090 --> 02:33:22.490
and I owned I was half frightened when I saw him drawing nearer to me.

02:33:22.990 --> 02:33:26.650
He did not know to be sure that I had overheard his counsel from the apple barrel,

02:33:27.210 --> 02:33:31.750
and yet I had by this time taken such a horror of his cruelty,

02:33:32.510 --> 02:33:36.330
duplicity and power that I could scarce conceal a shudder

02:33:36.330 --> 02:33:38.690
when he laid his hand upon my arm.

02:33:39.750 --> 02:33:44.270
Ah, says he, this here is a sweet spot, this island,

02:33:44.930 --> 02:33:47.290
a sweet spot for a lad to get ashore on.

02:33:47.770 --> 02:33:50.810
You'll bathe, and you'll climb trees, and you'll hunt goats, you will,

02:33:51.150 --> 02:33:54.070
and you'll get aloft on them hills like a goat yourself.

02:33:54.890 --> 02:33:56.270
Why, it makes you young again.

02:33:56.630 --> 02:33:59.250
I was going to forget my timber-leg I was.

02:33:59.650 --> 02:34:01.810
Isn't thing to be young and have ten toes?

02:34:01.970 --> 02:34:03.090
You may lay to that.

02:34:03.950 --> 02:34:07.310
When you want to go a bit of exploring, you just ask old John,

02:34:07.410 --> 02:34:09.510
and he'll put up a snack for you to take along.

02:34:10.350 --> 02:34:12.730
And clapping me in the friendliest way upon the shoulder,

02:34:12.890 --> 02:34:14.970
he hobbled off forward and went below.

02:34:15.570 --> 02:34:19.410
Captain Smollett, the squire, and Dr. Livesey were talking together

02:34:19.410 --> 02:34:22.950
on the quarter-deck, and anxious as I was to tell them my story,

02:34:23.090 --> 02:34:25.010
I durst not interrupt them openly.

02:34:25.430 --> 02:34:29.170
While I was still casting about in my thoughts to find some probable excuse,

02:34:29.690 --> 02:34:31.610
Dr. Livesey called me to his side.

02:34:31.890 --> 02:34:34.890
He had left his pipe below, and being a slave to tobacco

02:34:34.890 --> 02:34:36.650
had meant that I should fetch it.

02:34:36.850 --> 02:34:40.290
But as soon as I was near enough to speak and not to be overheard,

02:34:40.550 --> 02:34:41.690
I broke immediately.

02:34:42.330 --> 02:34:43.870
Doctor, let me speak.

02:34:44.390 --> 02:34:46.510
Get the captain and squire down to the cabin,

02:34:46.730 --> 02:34:48.870
and then make some pretense to send for me.

02:34:49.190 --> 02:34:50.750
I have terrible news.

02:34:51.710 --> 02:34:53.450
The doctor changed countenance a little,

02:34:53.750 --> 02:34:55.850
but next moment he was master of himself.

02:34:56.710 --> 02:34:58.650
Thank you, Jim, he said quite loudly.

02:34:58.730 --> 02:35:01.970
That was all I wanted to know, as if he had asked me a question.

02:35:02.690 --> 02:35:05.910
And with that he turned on his heel and rejoined the other two.

02:35:06.370 --> 02:35:09.390
They spoke together for a little, and though none of them started

02:35:09.390 --> 02:35:12.390
or raised his voice, or so much as whistled,

02:35:12.730 --> 02:35:16.290
it was plain enough that Dr. Livesey had communicated my request,

02:35:16.710 --> 02:35:20.530
for the next thing that I heard was the captain giving an order to Job Anderson,

02:35:20.970 --> 02:35:22.890
and all hands were piped on deck.

02:35:23.790 --> 02:35:28.250
My lads, said Captain Smollett, I have a word to say to you.

02:35:28.550 --> 02:35:31.890
This land that we have sighted is the place we have been sailing for.

02:35:32.310 --> 02:35:36.330
Mr. Trellony, being a very open-handed gentleman, as we all know,

02:35:36.670 --> 02:35:38.510
has just asked me a word or two,

02:35:38.510 --> 02:35:42.510
and as I was able to tell him that every man on board has done his duty,

02:35:42.950 --> 02:35:46.370
alow and aloft, as I never asked to see it done better,

02:35:46.770 --> 02:35:51.450
why he and I and the doctor are going below to the cabin to drink your health and luck,

02:35:51.810 --> 02:35:55.450
and you'll have grog served out for you to drink our health and luck.

02:35:55.790 --> 02:35:59.110
I'll tell you what I think of this. I think it handsome.

02:35:59.850 --> 02:36:04.570
And if you think as I do, you'll give a good sea cheer for the gentleman that does it.

02:36:05.290 --> 02:36:07.930
The cheer followed, that was a matter of course,

02:36:07.930 --> 02:36:11.310
but it rang out so full and hearty that I confess

02:36:11.310 --> 02:36:15.130
I could hardly believe these same men were plotting for our blood.

02:36:15.710 --> 02:36:19.150
One more cheer for Captain Smollett, cried Captain John,

02:36:19.450 --> 02:36:23.270
when the first had subsided, and this also was given with a will.

02:36:23.790 --> 02:36:26.190
On the top of that the three gentlemen went below,

02:36:26.210 --> 02:36:30.450
and not long after word was sent forward that Jim Hawkins was wanted in the cabin.

02:36:30.710 --> 02:36:33.190
I found them all three seated round the table,

02:36:33.430 --> 02:36:36.110
a bottle of Spanish wine and some raisins before them,

02:36:36.110 --> 02:36:39.610
and the doctor smoking away with his wig on his lap,

02:36:39.890 --> 02:36:42.690
and that I knew was a sign that he was agitated.

02:36:43.410 --> 02:36:45.870
The stern window was open, for it was a warm night,

02:36:46.050 --> 02:36:48.910
and you could see the moon shining behind on the ship's wake.

02:36:49.650 --> 02:36:54.490
Now Hawkins, said the squire, you have something to say? Speak up.

02:36:55.310 --> 02:36:58.490
I did as I was bid, and as short as I could make it,

02:36:58.710 --> 02:37:01.230
told the whole details of Silver's conversation.

02:37:01.910 --> 02:37:03.790
Nobody interrupted me till I was done,

02:37:03.790 --> 02:37:07.150
nor did any one of the three of them make so much as a movement,

02:37:07.530 --> 02:37:10.910
but they kept their eyes upon my face from first to last.

02:37:11.950 --> 02:37:14.850
Jim, said Dr. Livesey, take a seat.

02:37:15.290 --> 02:37:18.890
And they made me sit down a table beside them, poured me out a glass of wine,

02:37:19.090 --> 02:37:22.970
filled my hand with raisins, and all three, one after the other,

02:37:23.070 --> 02:37:27.010
and each with a bow, drank my good health and their service to me,

02:37:27.210 --> 02:37:28.670
for my luck and courage.

02:37:29.690 --> 02:37:33.390
Now Captain, said the squire, you were right and I was wrong.

02:37:33.390 --> 02:37:37.030
I own myself an ass, and I await your orders.

02:37:37.790 --> 02:37:40.910
No more an ass than I, sir, returned the captain.

02:37:41.750 --> 02:37:45.570
I never heard of a crew that meant a mutiny, but what showed signs before,

02:37:46.230 --> 02:37:50.710
for any man that had an eye in his head to see the mischief and to take steps according.

02:37:51.310 --> 02:37:54.030
But this crew, he added, beats me.

02:37:54.770 --> 02:38:00.270
Captain, said the doctor, with your permission, that's Silver, a very remarkable man.

02:38:00.950 --> 02:38:05.170
You look remarkably well from a yard-arm, sir, returned the captain.

02:38:05.790 --> 02:38:08.850
But this is talk. This don't lead to anything.

02:38:09.090 --> 02:38:14.890
I see three or four points, and with Mr. Trellony's permission I'll name them.

02:38:15.670 --> 02:38:20.730
You, sir, are the captain. It is for you to speak, said Mr. Trellony grandly.

02:38:21.370 --> 02:38:26.650
First point, began Mr. Smollett. We must go on, because we can't turn back.

02:38:26.650 --> 02:38:30.590
If I gave the word to go about, they would rise at once.

02:38:31.070 --> 02:38:36.150
Second point, we have time before us, at least until this treasure is found.

02:38:36.710 --> 02:38:39.630
Third point, there are faithful hands.

02:38:40.330 --> 02:38:43.370
Now, sir, it has got to come to blows sooner or later,

02:38:43.390 --> 02:38:47.430
and what I propose is to take time by the forelock, as the saying is,

02:38:47.770 --> 02:38:51.110
and come to blows some fine day when they least expect it.

02:38:51.470 --> 02:38:56.050
We can count, I take it, on your own home servants, Mr. Trellony?

02:38:56.050 --> 02:38:58.970
As upon myself, declared the squire.

02:38:59.730 --> 02:39:02.510
Three, reckoned the captain, ourselves make seven.

02:39:02.850 --> 02:39:05.930
Counting Hawkins here? Now, about the honest hands.

02:39:06.510 --> 02:39:09.310
Most likely Trellony's own men, said the doctor,

02:39:09.770 --> 02:39:12.310
those he had picked for himself before he lit on silver.

02:39:13.370 --> 02:39:16.070
Nay, replied the squire, hand was one of mine.

02:39:16.730 --> 02:39:19.930
I did think I could have trusted hands, added the captain.

02:39:20.790 --> 02:39:23.670
And to think that they're all Englishmen, broke out the squire.

02:39:23.670 --> 02:39:26.590
Sir, I could find it in my heart to blow the ship up.

02:39:27.470 --> 02:39:31.510
Well, gentlemen, said the captain, the best that I can say is not much.

02:39:32.230 --> 02:39:35.390
We must lay to, if you please, and keep a bright look out.

02:39:35.950 --> 02:39:39.710
It's trying on a man I know. It would be pleasanter to come to blows.

02:39:40.290 --> 02:39:42.450
But there's no help for it till we know our men.

02:39:43.010 --> 02:39:45.590
Lay to and whistle for a wind, that's my view.

02:39:46.590 --> 02:39:49.290
Jim here, said the doctor, can help us more than anyone.

02:39:49.610 --> 02:39:52.510
The men are not shy with him, and Jim is a noticing lad.

02:39:52.990 --> 02:39:56.190
Hawkins, I put prodigious faith in you, added the squire.

02:39:56.950 --> 02:40:00.750
I began to feel pretty desperate at this, for I felt altogether helpless.

02:40:01.230 --> 02:40:03.650
And yet, by an odd train of circumstances,

02:40:03.990 --> 02:40:06.410
it was indeed through me that safety came.

02:40:06.670 --> 02:40:08.490
In the meantime, talk as we pleased,

02:40:08.690 --> 02:40:12.210
there were only seven out of the twenty-six on whom we could rely,

02:40:12.470 --> 02:40:14.430
and out of these seven one was a boy,

02:40:14.810 --> 02:40:18.050
so that the grown men on our side were six to their nineteen.

02:40:39.290 --> 02:40:42.190
Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson

02:40:42.190 --> 02:40:46.090
Part 3. My Shore Adventure

02:40:46.090 --> 02:40:51.010
Chapter 13. How My Shore Adventure Began

02:40:52.870 --> 02:40:58.210
The appearance of the island when I came on deck next morning was altogether changed.

02:40:58.910 --> 02:41:09.110
Although the breeze had now utterly ceased, we had made a great deal of way during the night and were now lying becalmed about half a mile to the southeast of the low eastern coast.

02:41:09.910 --> 02:41:13.130
Grey colored woods covered a large part of the surface.

02:41:13.990 --> 02:41:24.930
This even tint was indeed broken up by streaks of yellow sand break in the lower lands and by many tall trees of the pine family out topping the others, some singly, some in clumps.

02:41:25.510 --> 02:41:28.250
But the general coloring was uniform and sad.

02:41:29.610 --> 02:41:33.610
The hills ran up clear above the vegetation in spires of naked rock.

02:41:34.490 --> 02:41:51.090
All were strangely shaped, and the spyglass, which was by three or four hundred feet the tallest on the island, was likewise the strangest in configuration, running up sheer from almost every side and then suddenly cut off at the top like a pedestal to put a statue on.

02:41:52.470 --> 02:41:55.750
The Hispaniola was rolling scuppers under in the ocean swell.

02:41:56.290 --> 02:42:06.210
The booms were tearing at the blocks, the rudder was banging to and fro, and the whole ship creaking, groaning, and jumping like a manufactory.

02:42:07.290 --> 02:42:24.630
I had to cling tight to the backstay, and the world turned giddily before my eyes, for though I was a good enough sailor when there was way on, this standing still and being rolled about like a bottle was a thing I never learned to stand without a qualm or so above all in the morning on an empty stomach.

02:42:26.130 --> 02:42:38.250
Perhaps it was this. Perhaps it was the look of the island, with its gray, melancholy woods, and wild stone spires, and the surf that we could both see and hear foaming and thundering on the steep beach.

02:42:38.250 --> 02:42:57.450
At least, although the sun shone bright and hot, and the shore birds were fishing and crying all around us, and you would have thought anyone would have been glad to get to land after being so long at sea, my heart sank, as the saying is, into my boots, and from the first look onward I hated the very thought of Treasure Island.

02:42:58.870 --> 02:43:13.290
We had a dreary morning's work before us, for there was no wind of any kind, and the boats had to be got out and manned, and the ship warped three or four miles round the corner of the island and up the narrow passage to the haven behind Skeleton Island.

02:43:14.270 --> 02:43:29.550
I volunteered for one of the boats, where I had, of course, no business. The heat was sweltering, and the men grumbled fiercely over their work. Anderson was in command of my boat, and instead of keeping the crew in order, he grumbled as loud as the worst.

02:43:30.730 --> 02:43:33.570
Well, he said with an oath, it's not forever.

02:43:35.290 --> 02:43:44.750
I thought this was a very bad sign, for up to that day the men had gone briskly and willingly about their business, but the very sight of the island had relaxed the cords of discipline.

02:43:45.870 --> 02:43:58.950
All the way in, Long John stood by the steersman and conned the ship. He knew the passage like the palm of his hand, and though the man in the chains got everywhere more water than was down in the chart, John never hesitated once.

02:44:00.030 --> 02:44:06.550
There's a strong scour with the ebb, he said, and this here passage has been dug out in a manner of speaking with a spade.

02:44:07.690 --> 02:44:18.610
We brought up just where the anchor was in the chart, about a third of a mile from each shore, the mainland on one side and Skeleton Island on the other. The bottom was clean sand.

02:44:19.610 --> 02:44:28.790
The plunge of our anchor sent up clouds of birds wheeling and crying over the woods, but in less than a minute they were down again, and all was once more silent.

02:44:30.150 --> 02:44:43.710
The place was entirely landlocked, buried in woods, the trees coming right down to High Watermark, the shores mostly flat, and the hilltops standing round at a distance in a sort of amphitheatre, one here, one there.

02:44:44.830 --> 02:44:54.450
Two little rivers, or rather two swamps, emptied out into this pond as you might call it, and the foliage round that part of the shore had a kind of poisonous brightness.

02:44:55.410 --> 02:45:08.630
From the ship we could see nothing of the house or stockade, for they were quite buried among trees, and if it had not been for the chart on the companion, we might have been the first that had ever anchored there since the island arose out of the seas.

02:45:10.090 --> 02:45:18.170
There was not a breath of air moving, nor a sound but that of the surf booming half a mile away along the beaches and against the rocks outside.

02:45:19.150 --> 02:45:25.550
A peculiar stagnant smell hung over the anchorage, a smell of sodden leaves and rotting tree trunks.

02:45:26.470 --> 02:45:30.790
I observed the doctor sniffing and sniffing, like someone tasting a bad egg.

02:45:32.030 --> 02:45:36.430
I don't know about treasure, he said, but I'll stick my wig, there's fever here.

02:45:38.410 --> 02:45:43.990
If the conduct of the men had been alarming in the boat, it became truly threatening when they had come aboard.

02:45:44.610 --> 02:45:47.690
They lay about the deck, growling together in talk.

02:45:48.510 --> 02:45:52.990
The slightest order was received with a black look and grudgingly and carelessly obeyed.

02:45:54.150 --> 02:45:59.510
Even the honest hands must have caught the infection, for there was not one man aboard to mend another.

02:46:00.450 --> 02:46:03.790
Mutiny, it was plain, hung over us like a thunder cloud.

02:46:05.170 --> 02:46:08.370
And it was not only we of the cabin party who perceived the danger.

02:46:09.210 --> 02:46:17.070
Long John was hard at work, going from group to group, spending himself in good advice, and as for example, no man could have shown a better.

02:46:17.970 --> 02:46:20.870
He fairly outstripped himself in willingness and civility.

02:46:21.250 --> 02:46:22.890
He was all smiles to everyone.

02:46:23.870 --> 02:46:29.230
If an order were given, John would be on his crutch in an instant with the cheeriest, I ice her, in the world.

02:46:29.630 --> 02:46:36.430
And when there was nothing else to do, he kept up, one song after another, as if to conceal the discontent of the rest.

02:46:38.030 --> 02:46:45.470
Of all the gloomy features of that gloomy afternoon, this obvious anxiety on the part of Long John appeared the worst.

02:46:46.750 --> 02:46:48.450
We held a council in the cabin.

02:46:50.690 --> 02:46:55.970
Sir, said the captain, if I risk another order, the whole ship will come about our ears by the run.

02:46:56.610 --> 02:47:00.030
You see, sir, here it is. I get a rough answer, do I not?

02:47:00.550 --> 02:47:03.450
Well, if I speak back, pikes will be going in two shakes.

02:47:03.450 --> 02:47:07.630
If I don't, silver will see there's something under that, and the game's up.

02:47:08.170 --> 02:47:10.310
Now we've only one man to rely on.

02:47:11.370 --> 02:47:13.590
And who is that? asked the squire.

02:47:14.050 --> 02:47:18.630
Silver, sir, returned the captain. He's as anxious as you and I to smother things up.

02:47:19.310 --> 02:47:25.130
This is a tiff. He'd soon talk him out of it if he had the chance, and what I propose to do is to give him the chance.

02:47:25.690 --> 02:47:30.330
Let's allow the men an afternoon ashore. If they all go, why, we'll fight the ship.

02:47:30.330 --> 02:47:34.690
If they none of them go, well, then we hold the cabin and God defend the right.

02:47:35.170 --> 02:47:41.290
If some go, you mark my word, sir, silver will bring them aboard again as mild as lambs.

02:47:41.810 --> 02:47:46.650
It was so decided. Loaded pistols were served out to all the shoremen.

02:47:47.370 --> 02:47:54.750
Hunter, Joyce, and Dredruth were taken into our confidence and received the news with less surprise and a better spirit than we had looked for.

02:47:55.150 --> 02:47:57.890
And then the captain went on deck and addressed the crew.

02:47:59.450 --> 02:48:04.170
My lads, said he, we've had a hot day and are all tired and out of sorts.

02:48:04.670 --> 02:48:07.710
A turn ashore will hurt nobody. The boats are still in the water.

02:48:08.070 --> 02:48:11.850
You can take the gigs and as many as please may go ashore for the afternoon.

02:48:12.410 --> 02:48:14.930
I'll fire a gun half an hour before sundown.

02:48:16.790 --> 02:48:21.790
I believe the silly fellows must have thought they would break their shins over treasure as soon as they were landed,

02:48:21.790 --> 02:48:31.450
for they all came out of their sulks in a moment and gave a cheer that started the echo in a faraway hill and sent the birds once more flying and squalling around the anchorage.

02:48:32.850 --> 02:48:34.850
The captain was too bright to be in the way.

02:48:35.430 --> 02:48:38.830
He whipped out of sight in a moment, leaving Silver to arrange the party.

02:48:39.230 --> 02:48:41.430
And I fancy it was as well he did so.

02:48:42.190 --> 02:48:47.030
Had he been on deck, he could no longer so much as have pretended not to understand the situation.

02:48:47.330 --> 02:48:49.250
It was as plain as day.

02:48:49.250 --> 02:48:53.270
Silver was the captain and a mighty rebellious crew he had of it.

02:48:53.910 --> 02:49:00.110
The honest hands, and I was soon to see it proved that there were such on board, must have been very stupid fellows.

02:49:00.870 --> 02:49:08.850
Or rather, I suppose the truth was this, that all hands were disaffected by the example of the ringleaders, only some more, some less,

02:49:09.170 --> 02:49:13.970
and a few, being good fellows in the main, could neither be led nor driven any further.

02:49:14.530 --> 02:49:20.770
It is one thing to be idle and skulk, and quite another to take a ship and murder a number of innocent men.

02:49:22.150 --> 02:49:24.410
At last, however, the party was made up.

02:49:24.810 --> 02:49:30.310
Six fellows were to stay on board, and the remaining thirteen, including Silver, began to embark.

02:49:32.050 --> 02:49:37.730
Then it was that there came into my head the first of the mad notions that contributed so much to save our lives.

02:49:38.510 --> 02:49:43.390
If six men were left by Silver, it was plain our party could not take and fight the ship,

02:49:43.750 --> 02:49:49.290
and since only six were left, it was equally plain that the cabin party had no present need of my assistance.

02:49:50.150 --> 02:49:52.470
It occurred to me at once to go ashore.

02:49:53.230 --> 02:50:00.230
In a jiffy I had slipped over the side and curled up in the four sheets of the nearest boat, and almost at the same moment she shoved off.

02:50:01.590 --> 02:50:04.350
No one took notice of me, only the bow oar saying,

02:50:04.350 --> 02:50:06.770
As that you, Jim, keep your head down.

02:50:07.610 --> 02:50:15.430
But Silver, from the other boat, looked sharply over and called out to know if that were me, and from that moment I began to regret what I had done.

02:50:16.590 --> 02:50:23.530
The crews raced for the beach, but the boat I was in, having some start and being at once the lighter and the better manned,

02:50:23.730 --> 02:50:27.810
shot far ahead of her consort, and the bow had struck among the shoreside trees,

02:50:27.810 --> 02:50:35.050
and I had caught a branch and swung myself out and plunged into the nearest thicket, while Silver and the rest were still a hundred yards behind.

02:50:36.430 --> 02:50:38.430
Jim, Jim! I heard him shouting.

02:50:39.350 --> 02:50:41.330
But you may suppose I paid no heed.

02:50:42.030 --> 02:50:47.410
Jumping, ducking, and breaking through, I ran straight before my nose till I could run no longer.

02:51:10.910 --> 02:51:12.310
XIV.

02:51:13.130 --> 02:51:14.370
THE FIRST BLOW.

02:51:16.590 --> 02:51:26.610
I was so pleased at having given the slip too long, John, that I began to enjoy myself and look around me with some interest on the strange land that I was in.

02:51:27.450 --> 02:51:48.770
I had crossed a marshy tract full of willows, bulrushes, and odd outlandish swampy trees, and I had now come out upon the skirts of an open piece of undulating sandy country, about a mile long, dotted with a few pines and a great number of contorted trees, not unlike the oak in growth, but pale in the foliage like willows.

02:51:49.430 --> 02:51:56.390
On the far side of the open stood one of the hills, with two quaint craggy peaks shining vividly in the sun.

02:51:57.470 --> 02:52:01.210
I now felt, for the first time, the joy of exploration.

02:52:01.990 --> 02:52:03.650
The isle was uninhabited.

02:52:04.070 --> 02:52:10.130
My shipmates I had left behind, and nothing lived in front of me but dumb brutes and fowls.

02:52:10.970 --> 02:52:13.210
I turned hither and thither among the trees.

02:52:14.130 --> 02:52:17.090
Here and there were flowering plants, unknown to me.

02:52:17.710 --> 02:52:25.470
Here and there I saw snakes, and one raised his head from a ledge of rock and hissed at me with a noise not unlike the spinning of a top.

02:52:26.390 --> 02:52:31.110
Little did I suppose that he was a deadly enemy and that the noise was the famous rattle.

02:52:32.270 --> 02:52:39.670
Then I came to a long thicket of these oak-like trees, live or evergreen oaks, I heard afterwards they should be called,

02:52:40.030 --> 02:52:47.290
which grew low along the sand like brambles, the boughs curiously twisted, the foliage compact like thatch.

02:52:48.470 --> 02:52:54.310
The thicket stretched down from the top of one of the sandy knolls, spreading and growing taller as it went,

02:52:54.310 --> 02:53:01.950
until it reached the margin of the broad reedy fen through which the nearest of the little rivers soaked its way into the anchorage.

02:53:02.970 --> 02:53:09.430
The marsh was steaming in the strong sun, and the outline of the spyglass trembled through the haze.

02:53:10.790 --> 02:53:14.710
All at once there began to go a sort of bustle among the bulrushes.

02:53:15.130 --> 02:53:18.510
A wild duck flew up with a quack, another followed,

02:53:18.510 --> 02:53:25.210
and soon over the whole surface of the marsh a great cloud of birds hung screaming and circling in the air.

02:53:26.330 --> 02:53:31.550
I judged at once that some of my shipmates must be drawing near along the borders of the fen.

02:53:32.470 --> 02:53:37.610
Nor was I deceived, for soon I heard the very distant and low tones of a human voice,

02:53:38.130 --> 02:53:43.050
which, as I continued to give ear, grew steadily louder and nearer.

02:53:43.890 --> 02:53:51.710
This put me in a great fear, and I crawled under cover of the nearest live oak and squatted there, harkening as silent as a mouse.

02:53:54.150 --> 02:53:59.030
Another voice answered, and then the first voice, which I now recognized to be Silvers,

02:53:59.610 --> 02:54:06.410
once more took up the story and ran on for a long while in a stream, only now and again interrupted by the other.

02:54:07.130 --> 02:54:14.010
By the sound they must have been talking earnestly and almost fiercely, but no distinct word came to my hearing.

02:54:15.490 --> 02:54:22.290
At last the speakers seemed to have paused and perhaps to have sat down, for not only did they cease to draw any nearer,

02:54:22.630 --> 02:54:27.770
but the birds themselves began to grow more quiet and to settle again to their places in the swamp.

02:54:29.050 --> 02:54:32.150
And now I began to feel that I was neglecting my business,

02:54:32.150 --> 02:54:36.690
that since I had been so foolhardy as to come ashore with these desperadoes,

02:54:36.830 --> 02:54:39.410
the least I could do was to overhear them at their councils,

02:54:39.930 --> 02:54:46.750
and that my plain and obvious duty was to draw as close as I could manage under the favorable ambush of the crouching trees.

02:54:48.390 --> 02:54:51.230
I could tell the direction of the speakers pretty exactly,

02:54:51.690 --> 02:54:53.310
not only by the sound of their voices,

02:54:53.750 --> 02:55:00.190
but by the behavior of the few birds that still hung in alarm above the heads of the intruders.

02:55:00.710 --> 02:55:05.390
Crawling on all fours, I made steadily but slowly towards them,

02:55:05.750 --> 02:55:09.730
till at last, raising my head to an aperture among the leaves,

02:55:10.150 --> 02:55:14.150
I could see clear down into a little green dell beside the marsh,

02:55:14.710 --> 02:55:16.610
and closely set about with trees,

02:55:17.150 --> 02:55:22.430
where Long John Silver and another of the crew stood face to face in conversation.

02:55:24.370 --> 02:55:26.370
The sun beat full upon them.

02:55:27.350 --> 02:55:30.130
Silver had thrown his hat beside him on the ground,

02:55:30.610 --> 02:55:33.030
and his great, smooth, blonde face,

02:55:33.370 --> 02:55:34.710
all shining with heat,

02:55:35.210 --> 02:55:38.030
was lifted to the other man's in a kind of appeal.

02:55:39.290 --> 02:55:40.690
Mate, he was saying,

02:55:41.150 --> 02:55:43.370
it's because I think's gold dust of you,

02:55:43.590 --> 02:55:45.430
gold dust and you may lay to that.

02:55:45.910 --> 02:55:47.710
If I hadn't took to you like pitch,

02:55:47.970 --> 02:55:49.890
do you think I'd have been here a warning of you?

02:55:50.510 --> 02:55:52.790
All's up, you can't make nor mend.

02:55:53.270 --> 02:55:54.950
It's to save your neck that I'm speaking,

02:55:54.950 --> 02:55:57.250
and if one of the Wildons knew it,

02:55:57.350 --> 02:55:58.490
where'd I be, Tom?

02:55:58.690 --> 02:56:00.550
Now tell me, where'd I be?

02:56:02.530 --> 02:56:04.130
Silver, said the other man,

02:56:04.530 --> 02:56:07.070
and I observed he was not only red in the face,

02:56:07.390 --> 02:56:09.090
but spoke as hoarse as a crow,

02:56:09.470 --> 02:56:11.930
and his voice shook, too, like a taut rope.

02:56:12.590 --> 02:56:13.850
Silver, says he,

02:56:14.650 --> 02:56:17.510
you're old and you're honest, or has the name for it,

02:56:17.630 --> 02:56:20.470
and you've money, too, which lots of poor sailors hasn't,

02:56:20.670 --> 02:56:22.350
and you're brave, or I'm mistook,

02:56:22.350 --> 02:56:25.230
and will you tell me you'll let yourself be led away

02:56:25.230 --> 02:56:26.950
with that kind of a mess of swabs?

02:56:27.270 --> 02:56:28.090
Not you.

02:56:28.510 --> 02:56:31.150
As sure as God sees me, I'd sooner lose my hand,

02:56:31.410 --> 02:56:32.850
if I turn again my duty.

02:56:33.870 --> 02:56:35.570
And then, all of a sudden,

02:56:36.050 --> 02:56:37.730
he was interrupted by a noise.

02:56:38.650 --> 02:56:41.030
I had found one of the honest hands.

02:56:41.630 --> 02:56:44.050
Well, here, at that same moment,

02:56:44.430 --> 02:56:45.530
came news of another.

02:56:46.550 --> 02:56:48.390
Far away, out in the marsh,

02:56:48.710 --> 02:56:50.410
there arose, all of a sudden,

02:56:50.410 --> 02:56:53.090
a sound like the cry of anger,

02:56:53.550 --> 02:56:55.210
then another on the back of it,

02:56:55.330 --> 02:56:57.230
and then one horrid,

02:56:57.510 --> 02:56:58.750
long-drawn scream.

02:57:00.030 --> 02:57:01.570
The rocks of the spyglass

02:57:01.570 --> 02:57:03.630
re-echoed it a score of times.

02:57:04.350 --> 02:57:05.830
The whole troop of marsh birds

02:57:05.830 --> 02:57:07.910
rose again, darkening heaven,

02:57:08.250 --> 02:57:09.690
with a simultaneous whir,

02:57:10.370 --> 02:57:11.990
and long after that death yell

02:57:11.990 --> 02:57:13.650
was still ringing in my brain,

02:57:14.270 --> 02:57:16.250
silence had re-established its empire,

02:57:16.630 --> 02:57:18.230
and only the rustle of the

02:57:18.230 --> 02:57:20.110
redescending birds and the boom

02:57:20.110 --> 02:57:22.110
of the distant surges disturbed

02:57:22.110 --> 02:57:24.090
the languor of the afternoon.

02:57:26.010 --> 02:57:27.650
Tom had leaped at the sound,

02:57:27.810 --> 02:57:29.030
like a horse at the spur,

02:57:29.490 --> 02:57:31.470
but Silver had not winked an eye.

02:57:32.350 --> 02:57:33.570
He stood where he was,

02:57:33.850 --> 02:57:35.230
resting lightly on his crutch,

02:57:35.650 --> 02:57:37.330
watching his companion like a snake

02:57:37.330 --> 02:57:38.310
about to spring.

02:57:39.810 --> 02:57:41.490
John! said the sailor,

02:57:41.610 --> 02:57:42.670
stretching out his hand.

02:57:43.550 --> 02:57:44.950
Hands off! cried Silver,

02:57:45.390 --> 02:57:47.790
leaping back a yard, as it seemed to me,

02:57:47.790 --> 02:57:49.530
with the speed and security

02:57:49.530 --> 02:57:51.590
of a trained gymnast.

02:57:52.550 --> 02:57:54.130
Hands off if you like, John Silver,

02:57:54.330 --> 02:57:54.970
said the other.

02:57:55.470 --> 02:57:57.010
It's a black conscience that can make you

02:57:57.010 --> 02:57:58.970
feared of me, but in heaven's name

02:57:58.970 --> 02:58:00.150
tell me, what was that?

02:58:01.650 --> 02:58:03.170
That! returned Silver,

02:58:03.450 --> 02:58:05.690
smiling away, but wearier than ever,

02:58:06.090 --> 02:58:07.910
his eye a mere pinpoint in his

02:58:07.910 --> 02:58:09.530
big face, but gleaming

02:58:09.530 --> 02:58:10.890
like a crumb of glass.

02:58:11.630 --> 02:58:13.930
That! Oh, I reckon that'll be

02:58:13.930 --> 02:58:14.230
Alan!

02:58:15.670 --> 02:58:18.090
And at this point Tom flashed out

02:58:18.090 --> 02:58:18.790
like a hero.

02:58:19.730 --> 02:58:20.890
Alan! he cried.

02:58:21.590 --> 02:58:23.610
Then rest his soul for a true seaman.

02:58:24.010 --> 02:58:25.410
And as for you, John Silver,

02:58:25.710 --> 02:58:27.130
long you've been a mate of mine,

02:58:27.190 --> 02:58:28.630
but you're mate of mine no more.

02:58:29.030 --> 02:58:31.530
If I die like a dog, I'll die in my duty.

02:58:32.050 --> 02:58:33.430
You've killed Alan, have you?

02:58:33.890 --> 02:58:35.210
Kill me too if you can,

02:58:35.350 --> 02:58:36.370
but I defy you.

02:58:37.450 --> 02:58:39.590
And with that, this brave fellow

02:58:39.590 --> 02:58:41.790
turned his back directly on the cook

02:58:41.790 --> 02:58:43.790
and set off walking for the beach.

02:58:43.790 --> 02:58:46.850
But he was not destined to go far.

02:58:47.750 --> 02:58:48.630
With a cry,

02:58:48.970 --> 02:58:50.890
John seized the branch of a tree,

02:58:51.390 --> 02:58:53.070
whipped the crutch out of his armpit,

02:58:53.190 --> 02:58:54.730
and sent that uncouth missile

02:58:54.730 --> 02:58:56.050
hurtling through the air.

02:58:56.970 --> 02:58:58.270
It struck poor Tom,

02:58:58.430 --> 02:59:00.910
point foremost, and with stunning violence,

02:59:01.350 --> 02:59:02.570
right between the shoulders

02:59:02.570 --> 02:59:03.910
in the middle of his back.

02:59:04.830 --> 02:59:05.970
His hands flew up,

02:59:06.270 --> 02:59:08.470
he gave a sort of gasp, and fell.

02:59:10.530 --> 02:59:12.370
Whether he were injured much or little,

02:59:12.370 --> 02:59:13.830
none could ever tell.

02:59:14.830 --> 02:59:16.810
Like enough, to judge from the sound,

02:59:17.090 --> 02:59:18.810
his back was broken on the spot.

02:59:19.530 --> 02:59:20.650
But he had no time

02:59:20.650 --> 02:59:21.890
given him to recover.

02:59:23.130 --> 02:59:24.850
Silver, agile as a monkey,

02:59:25.010 --> 02:59:26.830
even without leg or crutch,

02:59:27.290 --> 02:59:28.230
was on the top of him

02:59:28.230 --> 02:59:30.170
next moment, and had twice

02:59:30.170 --> 02:59:31.990
buried his knife up to the hilt

02:59:31.990 --> 02:59:33.450
in that defenseless body.

02:59:34.530 --> 02:59:35.870
From my place of ambush,

02:59:36.230 --> 02:59:37.530
I could hear him pant aloud

02:59:37.530 --> 02:59:38.890
as he struck the blows.

02:59:40.530 --> 02:59:43.130
I do not know what it rightly is

02:59:43.130 --> 02:59:45.030
to faint, but I do know

02:59:45.030 --> 02:59:46.430
that for the next little while

02:59:46.430 --> 02:59:48.310
the whole world swam away

02:59:48.310 --> 02:59:50.250
from before me in a whirling mist.

02:59:51.050 --> 02:59:52.370
Silver and the birds

02:59:52.370 --> 02:59:54.590
and the tall spyglass hilltop

02:59:54.590 --> 02:59:56.350
going round and round

02:59:56.350 --> 02:59:58.470
and topsy-turvy before my eyes,

02:59:58.870 --> 03:00:00.190
and all manner of bells

03:00:00.190 --> 03:00:01.830
ringing and distant voices

03:00:01.830 --> 03:00:03.390
shouting in my ear.

03:00:04.950 --> 03:00:06.790
When I came again to myself,

03:00:07.190 --> 03:00:08.870
the monster had pulled himself together

03:00:08.870 --> 03:00:10.910
his crutch under his arm,

03:00:11.210 --> 03:00:12.670
his hat upon his head.

03:00:14.010 --> 03:00:15.030
Just before him,

03:00:15.210 --> 03:00:17.250
Tom lay motionless upon the sward,

03:00:18.010 --> 03:00:18.690
but the murderer

03:00:18.690 --> 03:00:20.090
minded him not a whit,

03:00:20.770 --> 03:00:22.330
cleansing his blood-stained knife

03:00:22.330 --> 03:00:24.530
the while upon a wisp of grass.

03:00:25.990 --> 03:00:27.670
Everything else was unchanged,

03:00:28.210 --> 03:00:29.550
the sun still shining

03:00:29.550 --> 03:00:31.190
mercilessly on the steaming

03:00:31.190 --> 03:00:32.970
marsh and the tall pinnacle

03:00:32.970 --> 03:00:34.830
of the mountain, and I could

03:00:34.830 --> 03:00:36.430
scarce persuade myself that murder

03:00:36.430 --> 03:00:38.890
had been actually done and a human life

03:00:38.890 --> 03:00:40.490
cruelly cut short a moment

03:00:40.490 --> 03:00:42.190
since before my eyes.

03:00:44.130 --> 03:00:44.730
But now

03:00:44.730 --> 03:00:46.570
John put his hand into his pocket,

03:00:47.130 --> 03:00:48.630
brought out a whistle, and

03:00:48.630 --> 03:00:50.430
blew upon it several modulated

03:00:50.430 --> 03:00:52.690
blasts that rang far across the heated

03:00:52.690 --> 03:00:53.150
air.

03:00:54.450 --> 03:00:56.430
I could not tell, of course, the meaning

03:00:56.430 --> 03:00:58.370
of the signal, but it instantly

03:00:58.370 --> 03:00:59.510
awoke my fears.

03:01:00.330 --> 03:01:01.550
More men would be coming.

03:01:02.130 --> 03:01:03.290
I might be discovered.

03:01:03.290 --> 03:01:05.750
They had already slain two

03:01:05.750 --> 03:01:07.470
of the honest people. After

03:01:07.470 --> 03:01:09.590
Tom and Alan might not I come

03:01:09.590 --> 03:01:10.190
next?

03:01:11.910 --> 03:01:13.570
Instantly I began to extricate

03:01:13.570 --> 03:01:15.550
myself and crawl back again

03:01:15.550 --> 03:01:17.450
with what speed and silence I could

03:01:17.450 --> 03:01:19.510
manage to the more open portion

03:01:19.510 --> 03:01:20.090
of the wood.

03:01:21.250 --> 03:01:23.510
As I did so, I could hear hails

03:01:23.510 --> 03:01:25.670
coming and going between the old buccaneer

03:01:25.670 --> 03:01:27.610
and his comrades, and this

03:01:27.610 --> 03:01:29.530
sound of danger lent me wings.

03:01:30.710 --> 03:01:31.570
As soon as I

03:01:31.570 --> 03:01:33.450
was clear of the thicket, I ran

03:01:33.450 --> 03:01:35.650
as I never ran before, scarce

03:01:35.650 --> 03:01:37.310
minding the direction of my flight,

03:01:37.710 --> 03:01:39.970
so long as it led me from the murderers.

03:01:40.390 --> 03:01:41.570
And as I ran,

03:01:41.810 --> 03:01:43.950
fear grew and grew upon me

03:01:43.950 --> 03:01:45.650
until it turned into a kind

03:01:45.650 --> 03:01:46.450
of frenzy.

03:01:48.470 --> 03:01:49.550
Indeed, could

03:01:49.550 --> 03:01:51.450
anyone be more entirely lost

03:01:51.450 --> 03:01:53.530
than I? When the

03:01:53.530 --> 03:01:55.530
gun fired, how should I dare

03:01:55.530 --> 03:01:57.590
to go down to the boats among those

03:01:57.590 --> 03:01:59.490
fiends still smoking from their

03:01:59.490 --> 03:02:01.850
prime? Would not the first

03:02:01.850 --> 03:02:03.610
of them who saw me wring my neck

03:02:03.610 --> 03:02:04.550
like a snipes?

03:02:05.410 --> 03:02:07.670
Would not my absence itself be an evidence

03:02:07.670 --> 03:02:09.630
to them of my alarm, and therefore

03:02:09.630 --> 03:02:10.730
of my fatal knowledge?

03:02:11.730 --> 03:02:13.350
It was all over, I thought.

03:02:14.210 --> 03:02:15.670
Goodbye to the Hispaniola,

03:02:16.070 --> 03:02:17.810
goodbye to the squire, the doctor,

03:02:17.810 --> 03:02:19.550
and the captain. There was

03:02:19.550 --> 03:02:21.770
nothing left for me but death by starvation

03:02:21.770 --> 03:02:23.490
or death by the hands of the

03:02:23.490 --> 03:02:24.170
mutineers.

03:02:25.890 --> 03:02:27.670
All this while, as I say,

03:02:27.670 --> 03:02:29.710
I was still running, and

03:02:29.710 --> 03:02:31.710
without taking any notice, I had drawn

03:02:31.710 --> 03:02:33.730
near to the foot of the little hill with

03:02:33.730 --> 03:02:35.730
the two peaks, and had got into

03:02:35.730 --> 03:02:37.610
a part of the island where the live

03:02:37.610 --> 03:02:39.750
oaks grew more widely apart, and

03:02:39.750 --> 03:02:41.730
seemed more like forest trees in their

03:02:41.730 --> 03:02:42.910
bearing and dimensions.

03:02:44.110 --> 03:02:45.910
Mingled with these were a few scattered

03:02:45.910 --> 03:02:47.750
pines, some fifty,

03:02:48.110 --> 03:02:50.090
some nearer seventy, feet high.

03:02:50.910 --> 03:02:51.810
The air, too,

03:02:52.030 --> 03:02:53.670
smelt more freshly than down beside

03:02:53.670 --> 03:02:54.190
the marsh.

03:02:54.990 --> 03:02:57.230
And here a fresh alarm

03:02:57.230 --> 03:02:59.150
brought me to a standstill with

03:02:59.150 --> 03:03:00.190
a thumping heart.

03:03:03.210 --> 03:03:04.190
14

03:03:05.510 --> 03:03:07.490
Recorded November 16th,

03:03:07.550 --> 03:03:09.310
2005, in Longmont,

03:03:09.570 --> 03:03:09.830
Colorado.

03:03:34.130 --> 03:03:34.690
15.

03:03:35.950 --> 03:03:37.330
The Man of the Island

03:03:38.430 --> 03:03:47.130
From the side of the hill, which was here steep and stony, a spout of gravel was dislodged and fell rattling and bounding through the trees.

03:03:49.210 --> 03:03:55.910
My eyes turned instinctively in that direction, and I saw a figure leap with great rapidity behind the trunk of a pine.

03:03:57.390 --> 03:04:02.390
What it was, whether bear or man or monkey, I could in no wise tell.

03:04:03.050 --> 03:04:12.410
It seemed dark and shaggy, more I knew not, but the terror of this new apparition brought me to a stand.

03:04:14.690 --> 03:04:23.730
I was now, it seemed, cut off upon both sides, behind me the murderers, before me this lurking nondescript.

03:04:26.290 --> 03:04:30.810
And immediately I began to prefer the dangers that I knew to those I knew not.

03:04:32.390 --> 03:04:45.410
Silver himself appeared less terrible in contrast with this creature of the woods, and I turned on my heel, and looking sharply behind me over my shoulder began to retrace my steps in the direction of the boats.

03:04:47.330 --> 03:04:52.970
Instantly the figure reappeared, and making a wide circuit began to head me off.

03:04:54.690 --> 03:05:04.450
I was tired at any rate, but had I been as fresh as when I rose, I could see it was in vain for me to contend in speed with such an adversary.

03:05:06.050 --> 03:05:15.850
From trunk to trunk the creature flitted like a deer, running manlike on two legs, but unlike any man that I had ever seen, stooping almost double as it ran.

03:05:17.310 --> 03:05:21.070
Yet a man it was, I could no longer be in doubt about that.

03:05:23.730 --> 03:05:26.770
I began to recall what I had heard of cannibals.

03:05:28.030 --> 03:05:39.150
I was within an ace of calling for help, but the mere fact that he was a man, however wild, had somehow reassured me, and my fear of silver began to revive in proportion.

03:05:40.110 --> 03:05:45.430
I stood still, therefore, and cast about for some method of escape.

03:05:46.770 --> 03:05:52.430
And as I was so thinking, the recollection of my pistol flashed into my mind.

03:05:55.230 --> 03:06:08.770
As soon as I remembered I was not defenseless, courage glowed again in my heart, and I set my face resolutely for this man of the island, and walked briskly towards him.

03:06:11.210 --> 03:06:22.250
He was concealed by this time behind another tree trunk, but he must have been watching me closely, for as soon as I began to move in his direction, he reappeared and took a step to meet me.

03:06:22.970 --> 03:06:34.370
Then he hesitated, drew back, came forward again, and at last, to my wonder and confusion, he threw himself on his knees and held out his clasped hands in supplication.

03:06:36.470 --> 03:06:38.030
At that I once more stopped.

03:06:39.130 --> 03:06:40.450
Who are you, I asked?

03:06:42.910 --> 03:06:47.810
Ben Gunn, he answered, and his voice sounded hoarse and awkward like a rusty lock.

03:06:48.050 --> 03:06:54.730
I'm poor Ben Gunn, I am, and I haven't spoken with a Christian these three years.

03:06:57.270 --> 03:07:02.950
I could now see that he was a white man like myself, and that his features were even pleasing.

03:07:03.530 --> 03:07:07.190
His skin, wherever it was exposed, was burnt by the sun.

03:07:07.890 --> 03:07:13.250
Even his lips were black, and his fair eyes looked quite startling in so dark a face.

03:07:14.310 --> 03:07:18.870
Of all the beggar men that I had seen or fancied, he was the chief for raggedness.

03:07:19.610 --> 03:07:36.970
He was clothed with tatters of old ship's canvas and old sea cloth, and this extraordinary patchwork was all held together by a system of the most various and incongruous fastenings, brass buttons, bits of stick, and loops of tarrygaskin.

03:07:39.070 --> 03:07:45.230
About his waist he wore an old brass buckled leather belt, which was one thing solid in his whole accoutrement.

03:07:47.850 --> 03:07:50.390
Three years, I cried, were you shipwrecked?

03:07:51.990 --> 03:07:55.430
Nay, mate, said he, marooned.

03:07:57.050 --> 03:08:11.110
I had heard the word, and I knew it stood for a horrible kind of punishment common enough among the buccaneers, in which the offender is put ashore with a little powder and shot, and left behind on some desolate and distant island.

03:08:13.030 --> 03:08:19.550
Marooned three years a-gone, he continued, and lived on goats since then, and berries, and oysters.

03:08:20.950 --> 03:08:24.170
Wherever a man is, says I, a man can do for himself.

03:08:25.350 --> 03:08:28.750
But, mate, my heart is sore for Christian diet.

03:08:29.750 --> 03:08:32.570
You mightn't happen to have a piece of cheese about you now.

03:08:33.290 --> 03:08:43.610
No, well, many's the long night I've dreamed of cheese, toasted mostly, and woke up again, and here I were.

03:08:46.030 --> 03:08:50.930
If ever I can get aboard again, said I, you shall have cheese by the stone.

03:08:52.530 --> 03:09:03.830
All this time he had been feeling the stuff of my jacket, smoothing my hands, looking at my boots, and generally in the intervals of his speech, showing a childish pleasure in the presence of a fellow creature.

03:09:04.870 --> 03:09:08.390
But at my last words he perked up into a kind of startled sliness.

03:09:10.490 --> 03:09:17.530
If ever you can get aboard again, says you, he repeated, why now, who's to hinder you?

03:09:19.010 --> 03:09:21.610
Not you, I know, was my reply.

03:09:22.850 --> 03:09:24.630
And right you was, he cried.

03:09:25.970 --> 03:09:28.030
Now you, what do you call yourself, mate?

03:09:30.670 --> 03:09:31.850
Jim, I told him.

03:09:33.270 --> 03:09:36.990
Jim, Jim, says he, quite pleased apparently.

03:09:38.010 --> 03:09:43.010
Well now, Jim, I've lived that rough as you'd be ashamed to hear of.

03:09:43.010 --> 03:09:48.990
Now, for instance, you wouldn't think I had a pious mother to look at me, he asked.

03:09:50.410 --> 03:09:52.950
Why, no, not in particular, I answered.

03:09:53.530 --> 03:10:07.110
Ah, well, said he, but I had remarkable pious, and I was a civil pious boy, and could rattle off my cataclysm that fast as you couldn't tell one word from another.

03:10:08.450 --> 03:10:16.190
And here's what it come to, Jim, and it begun with Chuck Farthen on the blessed gravestones.

03:10:17.990 --> 03:10:21.230
That's what it begun with, but it went further than that.

03:10:23.130 --> 03:10:29.670
And so my mother told me, and predicted the whole thing she did, the pious woman.

03:10:30.490 --> 03:10:32.930
But it were providence that put me here.

03:10:32.930 --> 03:10:38.410
I've sought it all out in this here lonely island, and I'm back on piety.

03:10:39.210 --> 03:10:46.690
You don't catch me tasting rum so much, but just a thimbleful for luck, of course, the first chance I have.

03:10:47.630 --> 03:10:52.590
I'm bound I'll be good, and I see the way too.

03:10:52.870 --> 03:10:59.910
And Jim, looking all round him and lowering his voice to a whisper, I'm rich.

03:11:01.150 --> 03:11:10.080
I now felt sure that the poor fellow had gone crazy in his solitude, and I suppose I must have shown the feeling on my face, for he repeated the statement hotly.

03:11:10.930 --> 03:11:20.130
Rich, rich, I says, and I'll tell you what, I'll make a man of you, Jim. Ah, Jim, you'll bless your stars, you will.

03:11:20.750 --> 03:11:22.850
He was the first that found me.

03:11:24.510 --> 03:11:34.610
And at this there came suddenly a lowering shadow over his face, and he tightened his grasp upon my hand and raised a forefinger threateningly before my eyes.

03:11:35.610 --> 03:11:41.730
Now, Jim, you tell me true. That ain't Flint's ship, he asked.

03:11:44.390 --> 03:11:46.730
At this I had a happy inspiration.

03:11:47.870 --> 03:11:52.390
I began to believe that I had found an ally, and I answered him at once.

03:11:52.850 --> 03:11:58.290
It's not Flint's ship, and Flint is dead, but I'll tell you true as you ask me.

03:11:58.550 --> 03:12:03.170
There are some of Flint's hands aboard. Worse luck for the rest of us.

03:12:04.470 --> 03:12:10.830
Not a man with one leg, he gasped.

03:12:11.210 --> 03:12:18.050
Silver, I asked. Ah, silver, says he. That were his name.

03:12:20.350 --> 03:12:23.350
He's the cook and the ringleader, too.

03:12:24.790 --> 03:12:29.130
He was still holding me by the wrist, and at that he gave it quite a ring.

03:12:32.310 --> 03:12:40.270
If you was sent by Long John, says he, I'm as good as pork, and I know it.

03:12:40.970 --> 03:12:42.950
But where was you, do you suppose?

03:12:44.710 --> 03:12:53.250
I had made my mind up in a moment, and by way of answer told him the whole story of our voyage and the predicament in which we found ourselves.

03:12:54.010 --> 03:12:58.690
He heard me with the keenest interest, and when I had done, he patted me on the head.

03:13:00.070 --> 03:13:06.230
You're a good lad, Jim, said he, and you're all in a clove hitch, ain't you?

03:13:06.830 --> 03:13:12.350
Well, you just put your trust in Ben Gunn. Ben Gunn's the man to do it.

03:13:12.350 --> 03:13:21.370
Would you think it likely now that your squire would prove a liberal-minded one in case of help, him being in a clove hitch, as you remark?

03:13:23.190 --> 03:13:26.170
I told him the squire was the most liberal of men.

03:13:26.810 --> 03:13:36.310
Aye, but you see, returned Ben Gunn, I didn't mean giving me a gate to keep and a suit of livery clothes and such.

03:13:36.310 --> 03:13:49.550
That's not my mark, Jim. What I mean is, would he be likely to come down to the tune of, say, one thousand pounds out of money that's as good as a man's own already?

03:13:51.690 --> 03:13:54.110
I'm sure he would, said I.

03:13:55.950 --> 03:13:57.990
As it was, all hands were to share.

03:13:58.590 --> 03:14:02.850
And passage home, he added with a look of great shrewdness.

03:14:03.610 --> 03:14:12.090
Why, I cried, the squire's a gentleman, and besides, if we got rid of the others, we should want you to help work the vessel home.

03:14:13.990 --> 03:14:19.330
Ah, said he, so you would, and he seemed very much relieved.

03:14:20.810 --> 03:14:26.210
Now I'll tell you what, he went on. So much I'll tell you no more.

03:14:27.050 --> 03:14:33.350
I were in Flint's ship when he buried the treasure, he and six along, six strong seamen.

03:14:34.470 --> 03:14:39.530
They was ashore nigh a week, and us standing off in the old walrus.

03:14:40.470 --> 03:14:49.110
One fine day up went the signal, and here come Flint by himself in a little boat, and his head done up in a blue scarf.

03:14:49.330 --> 03:14:54.910
The sun was getting up, and mortal white he looked about the cut water.

03:14:56.190 --> 03:15:01.350
But there he was, you mind, and not the six all dead, dead and buried.

03:15:01.710 --> 03:15:06.870
How he done it, not a ban, a board, us could make out.

03:15:07.430 --> 03:15:13.090
It was a battle, murder, and sudden death, least ways, him against six.

03:15:13.830 --> 03:15:18.510
Billy Bones was the mate, Long John, he was the quartermaster.

03:15:19.330 --> 03:15:27.790
And they asked him where the treasure was. Ah, says he, you can go ashore if you like and stay, he says.

03:15:28.190 --> 03:15:30.830
But as for the ship, she'll beat up for more.

03:15:33.770 --> 03:15:37.350
By thunder, that's what he said.

03:15:39.950 --> 03:15:45.530
Well, I was in another ship three years back, and we sighted this island.

03:15:45.530 --> 03:15:49.970
Boys, said I, here's Flint's treasure, let's land and find it.

03:15:50.450 --> 03:15:56.670
But the captain was displeased at that, but my mess-mates were all of a mind and landed.

03:15:57.210 --> 03:16:01.890
Twelve days they looked for it, and every day they had worse word of me.

03:16:02.690 --> 03:16:05.430
Until one fine morning all hands went aboard.

03:16:06.750 --> 03:16:13.730
As for you, Benjamin Gunn, says they, here's a musket, they says, and a spade and a pickaxe.

03:16:13.730 --> 03:16:18.650
You can stay here and find Flint's money for yourself, they says.

03:16:20.190 --> 03:16:28.290
Well, Jim, three years have I been here, and not a bite a Christian diet from that day to this.

03:16:28.930 --> 03:16:35.050
But now you look here, look at me. Do I look like a man before the mast?

03:16:35.470 --> 03:16:38.770
No, says you, no I weren't neither, I says.

03:16:40.810 --> 03:16:43.090
And with that he winked and pinched me hard.

03:16:43.730 --> 03:16:48.130
Just you mention them words to your squire, Jim, he went on.

03:16:48.890 --> 03:16:51.230
Nor he weren't neither, that's the words.

03:16:51.730 --> 03:16:56.430
Three years he were the man of this island, light and dark, fair and rain.

03:16:57.010 --> 03:17:04.290
And sometimes he would maybe think upon a prayer, says you, and sometimes he would maybe think of his old mother.

03:17:05.310 --> 03:17:07.710
So be as she's alive, you'll say.

03:17:08.570 --> 03:17:15.910
But the most part of Gunn's time, this is what you'll say, the most part of his time was took up with another matter.

03:17:16.990 --> 03:17:19.450
And then you'll give him a nip like I do.

03:17:21.010 --> 03:17:24.050
And he pinched me again in the most confidential manner.

03:17:25.030 --> 03:17:30.810
Then, he continued, then you'll laugh when you'll say this, Gunn is a good man, you'll say.

03:17:30.810 --> 03:17:41.990
And he puts a precious sight more confidence, precious sight, mind that, in a gentleman born than in these gentlemen, a fortune having been one himself.

03:17:43.930 --> 03:17:49.890
Well, I said, I don't understand one word that you've been saying, but that's neither here nor there.

03:17:50.470 --> 03:17:51.850
For how am I to get on board?

03:17:52.630 --> 03:17:56.890
Ah, said he, that's the hitch for sure.

03:17:56.890 --> 03:18:01.330
Well, there's my boat that I made with my two hands.

03:18:01.970 --> 03:18:03.650
I keep her under the white rock.

03:18:03.770 --> 03:18:07.630
If the worst come to the worst, we might try that after dark.

03:18:08.490 --> 03:18:10.750
Hi, he broke out.

03:18:10.850 --> 03:18:11.530
What's that?

03:18:13.150 --> 03:18:20.930
For just then, although the sun had still an hour or two to run, all the echoes of the island awoke and bellowed to the thunder of a cannon.

03:18:22.390 --> 03:18:24.870
They've begun to fight, I cried, follow me.

03:18:24.870 --> 03:18:28.190
And I began to run towards the anchorage.

03:18:29.070 --> 03:18:35.970
My terrors all forgotten, while close at my side, the marooned man and his goat skins trotted easily and lightly.

03:18:37.370 --> 03:18:39.110
Left, left, says he.

03:18:40.750 --> 03:18:42.470
Keep to your left hand, mate, Jim.

03:18:43.690 --> 03:18:44.970
Under the trees with you.

03:18:45.850 --> 03:18:47.590
There's where I killed my first goat.

03:18:47.990 --> 03:18:53.830
They don't come down here now, they're all mastheaded on them mountings for fear of Benjamin Gunn.

03:18:53.830 --> 03:18:57.330
Ah, and there's the setamary.

03:18:57.850 --> 03:18:59.370
Cemetery, he must have meant.

03:18:59.870 --> 03:19:01.050
You see them mounds.

03:19:01.690 --> 03:19:04.930
I come here and pray now and then.

03:19:05.350 --> 03:19:09.170
When I thought maybe a Sunday would be about due.

03:19:10.010 --> 03:19:13.330
It weren't quite a chapel, but it seemed more solemn-like.

03:19:14.150 --> 03:19:16.990
And then, says you, Ben Gunn was short-handed.

03:19:17.350 --> 03:19:21.410
No chapling, no so much as a Bible and a flag, you says.

03:19:22.490 --> 03:19:26.450
So he kept talking as I ran, neither expecting nor receiving an answer.

03:19:27.390 --> 03:19:32.850
The cannon shot was followed, after a considerable interval by a volley of small arms.

03:19:33.470 --> 03:19:34.410
Another pause.

03:19:35.290 --> 03:19:43.170
And then, not a quarter of a mile in front of me, I beheld the Union Jack flutter in the air above a wood.

03:20:00.330 --> 03:20:05.030
Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson Part 4

03:20:05.030 --> 03:20:09.070
Chapter 16 The Stockade

03:20:10.990 --> 03:20:14.190
The narrative is continued by the Doctor.

03:20:15.490 --> 03:20:17.210
How the ship was abandoned.

03:20:20.690 --> 03:20:22.710
It was about half past one,

03:20:23.430 --> 03:20:25.550
three bells in the sea phrase,

03:20:26.370 --> 03:20:29.090
that the two boats went ashore from the Hispaniola.

03:20:30.070 --> 03:20:33.870
The captain, the squire, and I were taking matters over in the cabin.

03:20:34.470 --> 03:20:35.890
Had there been a breath of wind,

03:20:35.890 --> 03:20:40.290
we should have fallen on the six mutineers who were left aboard with us.

03:20:40.550 --> 03:20:42.770
Slipped our cable and away to sea.

03:20:43.910 --> 03:20:45.050
But the wind was wanting,

03:20:46.010 --> 03:20:47.830
and to complete our helplessness,

03:20:48.350 --> 03:20:52.030
down came Hunter with the news that Jim Hawkins had slipped into a boat

03:20:52.030 --> 03:20:54.210
and was gone ashore with the rest.

03:20:55.990 --> 03:20:58.730
It never occurred to us to doubt Jim Hawkins,

03:20:58.830 --> 03:21:00.690
but we were alarmed for his safety.

03:21:01.510 --> 03:21:03.270
With the men and the temper they were in,

03:21:03.270 --> 03:21:07.210
it seemed an even chance if we should see the lad again.

03:21:07.750 --> 03:21:08.790
We ran on deck.

03:21:10.410 --> 03:21:12.510
The pitch was bubbling in the seams.

03:21:13.550 --> 03:21:16.410
The nasty stench of the place turned me sick.

03:21:17.230 --> 03:21:20.350
If ever a man smelt fever and dysentery,

03:21:20.810 --> 03:21:23.070
it was in that abominable anchorage.

03:21:23.890 --> 03:21:28.010
The six scoundrels were sitting grumbling under a sail in the forecastle.

03:21:28.010 --> 03:21:30.950
A shore we could see the gigs made fast,

03:21:31.430 --> 03:21:33.070
and a man sitting in each,

03:21:33.710 --> 03:21:35.670
hard by where the river runs in.

03:21:36.410 --> 03:21:38.070
One of them was whistling,

03:21:38.470 --> 03:21:39.430
Lily Bolero.

03:21:42.950 --> 03:21:44.110
Waiting was a strain,

03:21:44.750 --> 03:21:47.250
and it was decided that Hunter and I should go ashore

03:21:47.650 --> 03:21:50.090
with the jolly boat in quest of information.

03:21:51.730 --> 03:21:53.510
The gigs had leaned to their right,

03:21:53.730 --> 03:21:55.690
but Hunter and I pulled straight in,

03:21:55.690 --> 03:21:58.370
in the direction of the stockade upon the chart.

03:21:59.310 --> 03:22:01.230
The two who were left guarding their boats

03:22:01.230 --> 03:22:03.850
seemed in a bustle at our appearance.

03:22:05.350 --> 03:22:07.890
Lily Bolero stopped off,

03:22:08.010 --> 03:22:11.010
and I could see the pair discussing what they ought to do.

03:22:12.630 --> 03:22:14.190
Had they gone and told Silver,

03:22:14.450 --> 03:22:15.850
all might have turned out differently.

03:22:16.410 --> 03:22:18.570
But they had their orders, I suppose,

03:22:18.590 --> 03:22:20.770
and decided to sit quietly where they were

03:22:20.770 --> 03:22:22.910
and hark back again to Lily Bolero.

03:22:25.730 --> 03:22:28.310
There was a slight bend in the coast,

03:22:28.390 --> 03:22:30.990
and I steered so as to put it between us.

03:22:31.810 --> 03:22:32.970
Even before we landed,

03:22:33.030 --> 03:22:34.690
we had thus lost sight of the gigs.

03:22:35.910 --> 03:22:38.410
I jumped out and came as near running as I durst,

03:22:38.450 --> 03:22:41.730
with a big silk handkerchief under my hat for coolness sake,

03:22:42.090 --> 03:22:44.750
and abrasive pistols ready primed for safety.

03:22:46.490 --> 03:22:49.870
I had not gone a hundred yards when I reached the stockade.

03:22:52.310 --> 03:22:54.010
This was how it was.

03:22:54.510 --> 03:22:58.250
A spring of clear water rose almost at the top of a knoll.

03:22:58.910 --> 03:23:01.490
Well, on the knoll, and enclosing the spring,

03:23:01.550 --> 03:23:03.490
they had clapped a stout log-house

03:23:03.490 --> 03:23:06.450
fit to hold two score of people in a pinch

03:23:06.450 --> 03:23:08.850
and loop-hold for musketry on either side.

03:23:09.810 --> 03:23:12.630
All around this they had cleared a wide space,

03:23:13.190 --> 03:23:16.890
and then the thing was completed by a paling six feet high,

03:23:17.230 --> 03:23:18.290
without door or opening,

03:23:18.290 --> 03:23:21.050
too strong to pull down without time and labour,

03:23:21.750 --> 03:23:24.150
and too open to shelter the besiegers.

03:23:27.690 --> 03:23:31.410
The people in the log-house had them in every way.

03:23:32.210 --> 03:23:35.950
They stood quiet in shelter and shot the others like partridges.

03:23:37.870 --> 03:23:40.170
All they wanted was a good watch and food.

03:23:41.590 --> 03:23:43.190
For short of a complete surprise,

03:23:43.270 --> 03:23:45.110
they might have held the place against a regiment.

03:23:46.970 --> 03:23:49.550
What particularly took my fancy was the spring,

03:23:50.410 --> 03:23:52.130
for though we had a good enough place of it

03:23:52.130 --> 03:23:53.750
in the cabin of the Hispaniola,

03:23:53.990 --> 03:23:55.690
with plenty of arms and ammunition,

03:23:56.410 --> 03:23:58.910
and things to eat, and excellent wines,

03:23:59.510 --> 03:24:01.070
there had been one thing overlooked.

03:24:01.770 --> 03:24:02.870
We had no water.

03:24:05.090 --> 03:24:08.530
I was thinking this over when there came ringing over the island,

03:24:08.970 --> 03:24:11.010
the cry of a man at the point of death.

03:24:12.430 --> 03:24:14.510
I was not new to violent death.

03:24:15.310 --> 03:24:17.710
I have served His Royal Highness the Duke of Cumberland

03:24:17.710 --> 03:24:20.210
and got a wound myself at Fontenroy.

03:24:21.690 --> 03:24:24.470
But I know my pulse went dot and carry one.

03:24:26.430 --> 03:24:28.590
Jim Hawkins is gone, was my first thought.

03:24:30.710 --> 03:24:32.650
It is something to have been an old soldier,

03:24:32.830 --> 03:24:34.610
but more still to have been a doctor.

03:24:35.470 --> 03:24:37.810
There is no time to dilly-dally in our work,

03:24:37.810 --> 03:24:40.270
and so now I made up my mind instantly,

03:24:41.030 --> 03:24:43.170
and with no time lost returned to shore

03:24:43.170 --> 03:24:45.250
and jumped on board the jolly boat.

03:24:47.790 --> 03:24:50.150
By good fortune Hunter pulled a good oar.

03:24:50.570 --> 03:24:53.550
We made the water fly and the boat was soon alongside,

03:24:54.250 --> 03:24:56.050
and I aboard the schooner.

03:24:58.730 --> 03:25:01.090
I found them all shaken as was natural.

03:25:01.790 --> 03:25:04.390
The squire was sitting down as white as a sheet,

03:25:04.390 --> 03:25:07.950
thinking of the harm he had led us to, the good soul.

03:25:09.010 --> 03:25:11.730
And one of the six forecastle hands was a little better.

03:25:16.310 --> 03:25:18.950
There's a man, says Captain Smollett,

03:25:19.250 --> 03:25:21.450
nodding towards him, new to his work.

03:25:22.190 --> 03:25:25.550
He came nigh-hand, fainting doctor, when he heard the cry.

03:25:26.230 --> 03:25:28.930
Another touch of the rudder and that man would join us.

03:25:30.310 --> 03:25:32.190
I told my plan to the captain,

03:25:32.190 --> 03:25:34.590
and between us we settled on the details

03:25:34.590 --> 03:25:35.550
of its accomplishment.

03:25:36.730 --> 03:25:39.370
We put old Redruth in the gallery

03:25:39.370 --> 03:25:41.150
between the cabin and the forecastle

03:25:41.150 --> 03:25:42.950
with three or four loaded muskets

03:25:42.950 --> 03:25:44.470
and a mattress for protection.

03:25:45.730 --> 03:25:48.070
Hunter brought the boat round under the stern port,

03:25:48.650 --> 03:25:50.630
and Joyce and I set to work loading her

03:25:50.630 --> 03:25:53.750
with powder tins, muskets, bags of biscuits,

03:25:54.150 --> 03:25:56.750
kegs of pork, a cask of cognac,

03:25:57.370 --> 03:25:59.510
and my invaluable medicine chest.

03:26:00.610 --> 03:26:04.030
In the meantime, the squire and the captain stayed on deck,

03:26:04.610 --> 03:26:06.610
and the latter hailed the coxswain,

03:26:07.490 --> 03:26:09.030
who was the principal man aboard.

03:26:10.290 --> 03:26:11.690
Mr. Hands, he said,

03:26:13.630 --> 03:26:16.370
here are two of us with a brace of pistols each.

03:26:16.750 --> 03:26:19.910
If any one of you six make a signal of any description,

03:26:19.970 --> 03:26:21.070
that man's dead.

03:26:22.710 --> 03:26:24.310
They were a good deal taken aback,

03:26:24.310 --> 03:26:25.870
and after a little consultation,

03:26:26.030 --> 03:26:28.470
one and all tumbled down the four companion,

03:26:28.470 --> 03:26:30.590
thinking no doubt to take us on the rear.

03:26:31.410 --> 03:26:32.830
But when they saw Redruth

03:26:32.830 --> 03:26:35.790
waiting for them in the sparred galley,

03:26:36.330 --> 03:26:38.050
they went about ship at once,

03:26:38.550 --> 03:26:40.170
and head popped out again on deck.

03:26:41.290 --> 03:26:43.310
Down, dog, cries the captain,

03:26:44.350 --> 03:26:46.090
and the head popped back again,

03:26:46.090 --> 03:26:47.670
and we heard no more

03:26:47.670 --> 03:26:50.470
for the time of these six very faint-hearted seamen.

03:26:54.170 --> 03:26:57.250
By this time, tumbling things in as they came,

03:26:57.970 --> 03:27:01.250
we had the jolly boat loaded as much as we dared.

03:27:02.190 --> 03:27:05.850
Joyce and I got out through the stern port,

03:27:07.050 --> 03:27:10.650
and we made for shore again as fast as oars could take us.

03:27:12.590 --> 03:27:15.890
This second trip fairly aroused the watchers along shore.

03:27:17.450 --> 03:27:19.230
Lily Bolero was dropped again,

03:27:19.530 --> 03:27:22.310
and just before we lost sight of them behind the little point,

03:27:22.610 --> 03:27:24.850
one of them whipped ashore and disappeared.

03:27:27.810 --> 03:27:31.110
I had half a mind to change my plan and destroy their boats,

03:27:31.350 --> 03:27:35.110
but I feared that Silver and the others might be close at hand,

03:27:35.610 --> 03:27:38.810
and all might very well be lost by trying for too much.

03:27:40.890 --> 03:27:43.890
We had soon touched land in the same place as before,

03:27:44.810 --> 03:27:46.750
and set to provision the blockhouse.

03:27:48.490 --> 03:27:50.070
All three made the first journey,

03:27:50.310 --> 03:27:53.950
heavily laden, and tossed our stores over the palisade.

03:27:55.130 --> 03:27:57.430
Then, leaving Joyce to guard them,

03:27:57.770 --> 03:28:00.150
one man to be sure, but with half a dozen muskets,

03:28:02.170 --> 03:28:05.790
Hunter and I returned to the jolly boat and loaded ourselves once more.

03:28:06.590 --> 03:28:08.990
So we proceeded, without pausing to take breath,

03:28:09.310 --> 03:28:11.130
till the whole cargo was bestowed,

03:28:11.410 --> 03:28:14.590
and the two servants took up their position in the blockhouse,

03:28:14.610 --> 03:28:18.210
and I, with all my power, sculled back to the Hispinola.

03:28:21.330 --> 03:28:23.750
That we should have risked a second boatload

03:28:23.750 --> 03:28:25.970
seems more daring than it really was.

03:28:26.750 --> 03:28:28.570
They had the advantage of numbers, of course,

03:28:28.570 --> 03:28:30.270
but we had the advantage of arms.

03:28:31.470 --> 03:28:33.490
Not one of the men ashore had a musket,

03:28:34.010 --> 03:28:37.230
and before they could get within range for pistol shooting,

03:28:37.890 --> 03:28:41.310
we flattered ourselves we should be able to give a good account,

03:28:42.390 --> 03:28:43.770
of a half a dozen at least.

03:28:45.670 --> 03:28:48.190
The squire was waiting for me at the square,

03:28:48.190 --> 03:28:51.170
and in the stern window all his faintness gone from him.

03:28:51.830 --> 03:28:53.750
He caught the painter and made it fast,

03:28:53.830 --> 03:28:57.130
and we fell to loading the boat for our very lives.

03:28:58.450 --> 03:29:01.110
Pork, powder and biscuit was the cargo,

03:29:01.530 --> 03:29:04.950
with only a musket and a cutlass apiece for the squire and me,

03:29:05.730 --> 03:29:07.210
and Redruth and the captain.

03:29:08.350 --> 03:29:10.690
The rest of the arms and powder we dropped overboard

03:29:10.690 --> 03:29:12.750
in two fathoms and a half of water,

03:29:13.210 --> 03:29:16.910
so that we could see the bright steel shining far below us in the sun

03:29:16.910 --> 03:29:18.670
on the clean sandy bottom.

03:29:20.450 --> 03:29:22.630
By this time the tide was beginning to ebb,

03:29:22.750 --> 03:29:24.950
and the ship was swinging round to her anchor.

03:29:26.070 --> 03:29:27.910
Voices were heard faintly hollowing

03:29:28.910 --> 03:29:31.130
in the direction of the two gigs,

03:29:32.090 --> 03:29:34.410
and though this reassured us for Joyce and Hunter,

03:29:35.870 --> 03:29:37.310
who were well to the eastward,

03:29:37.630 --> 03:29:39.450
it warned our party to be off.

03:29:41.930 --> 03:29:44.550
Redruth retreated from his place in the gallery,

03:29:45.570 --> 03:29:47.110
and dropped into the boat,

03:29:47.810 --> 03:29:49.730
which we then brought round to the ship's counter

03:29:49.730 --> 03:29:51.730
to be handier for Captain Smollett.

03:29:52.930 --> 03:29:55.030
Now, men, said he, do you hear me?

03:29:55.690 --> 03:29:58.030
There was no answer from the forecastle.

03:29:59.770 --> 03:30:01.490
It's to you, Abraham Gray.

03:30:01.750 --> 03:30:03.130
It's to you I am speaking.

03:30:05.370 --> 03:30:06.510
Still no reply.

03:30:07.830 --> 03:30:10.630
Gray, resumed Mr. Smollett a little louder,

03:30:11.130 --> 03:30:12.470
I'm leaving this ship,

03:30:12.470 --> 03:30:15.170
and I order you to follow your captain.

03:30:16.390 --> 03:30:18.130
I know you are a good man at bottom,

03:30:18.490 --> 03:30:22.170
and I dare say not one of the lot of you is as bad as he makes out.

03:30:23.230 --> 03:30:25.170
I have my watch here in my hand.

03:30:26.330 --> 03:30:28.750
I give you thirty seconds to join me in.

03:30:30.170 --> 03:30:31.250
There was a pause.

03:30:32.270 --> 03:30:34.590
Come, my fine fellow, continued the captain.

03:30:35.190 --> 03:30:36.970
Don't have so long in stays.

03:30:37.070 --> 03:30:40.430
I'm risking my life in the lives of these good gentlemen every second.

03:30:41.130 --> 03:30:42.510
There was a sudden scuffle,

03:30:43.370 --> 03:30:44.330
a sound of blows,

03:30:44.430 --> 03:30:47.790
and out burst Abraham Gray with a knife cut on the side of his cheek,

03:30:48.330 --> 03:30:50.790
and came running to the captain like a dog to the whistle.

03:30:51.930 --> 03:30:54.630
I'm with you, sir, said he,

03:30:55.090 --> 03:30:58.570
and the next moment he and the captain had dropped a board of us,

03:30:58.690 --> 03:31:00.330
and we shoved off and given way.

03:31:01.550 --> 03:31:03.550
We were clear out of the ship,

03:31:03.610 --> 03:31:06.610
but not yet ashore in our stockade.

03:31:33.750 --> 03:31:35.150
This

03:31:38.050 --> 03:31:45.070
fifth trip was quite different from any of the others. In the first place,

03:31:45.690 --> 03:31:52.950
the little Galapot of a boat that we were in was gravely overloaded. Five grown men,

03:31:53.310 --> 03:31:59.990
and three of them, Trelawney, Redrith, and the captain, over six feet high,

03:31:59.990 --> 03:32:08.530
was already more than she was meant to carry. Add to that the powder, pork, and bread bags.

03:32:10.610 --> 03:32:18.050
The gunwale was lipping astern. Several times we shipped a little water, and my breeches and

03:32:18.050 --> 03:32:23.410
the tails of my coat were all soaking wet before we had gone a hundred yards.

03:32:25.630 --> 03:32:33.650
The captain made us trim the boat, and we got her to lie a little more evenly. All the same,

03:32:33.950 --> 03:32:42.170
we were afraid to breathe. In the second place, the ebb was now making a strong,

03:32:42.730 --> 03:32:49.950
rippling current running westward through the basin, and then southward and seaword

03:32:49.950 --> 03:32:57.210
down the straits by which we had entered in the morning. Even the ripples were a danger

03:32:57.210 --> 03:33:03.510
to our overloaded craft, but the worst of it was that we were swept out of our true course,

03:33:04.190 --> 03:33:12.990
and away from our proper landing place behind the point. If we let the current have its way,

03:33:12.990 --> 03:33:17.430
we should come ashore beside the gigs, where the

03:33:18.870 --> 03:33:24.930
I cannot keep her head for the stockade, sir, said I to the captain.

03:33:26.390 --> 03:33:32.350
I was steering while he and Redrith, two fresh men, were at the oars.

03:33:33.650 --> 03:33:38.310
The tide keeps washing her down. Could you pull a little stronger?

03:33:39.850 --> 03:33:46.970
Not without swamping the boat, said he. You must bear up, sir. If you please,

03:33:47.550 --> 03:33:55.230
bear up until you see you're gaining. I tried and found by experiment that the

03:33:55.230 --> 03:34:02.810
tide kept sweeping us westward until I had laid her head due east, or just about right angles,

03:34:02.810 --> 03:34:09.750
to the way we ought to go. We'll never get ashore at this rate, said I.

03:34:12.390 --> 03:34:18.530
If it's the only course that we can lie, sir, we must even lie it, returned the captain.

03:34:19.950 --> 03:34:29.210
We must keep upstream. You see, sir, he went on. If once we drop to the leeward of the landing

03:34:29.210 --> 03:34:36.530
place, it's hard to say where we should get ashore, besides the chance of being boarded

03:34:36.530 --> 03:34:46.170
by the gigs, whereas the way we go, the current must slacken, and then we can dodge back along

03:34:46.170 --> 03:34:55.750
the shore. The currents less already, sir, said the man gray, who is sitting in the four sheets.

03:34:56.590 --> 03:34:58.410
You can ease her off a bit.

03:35:01.070 --> 03:35:05.470
Thank you, my man, said I, quite as if nothing had happened,

03:35:06.290 --> 03:35:11.730
for we had all quietly made up our minds to treat him like one of ourselves.

03:35:15.010 --> 03:35:20.090
Suddenly the captain spoke up again, and I thought his voice was a little changed.

03:35:21.010 --> 03:35:22.690
The gun, said he.

03:35:24.170 --> 03:35:30.910
I have thought of that, said I, for I made sure he was thinking of a bombardment of the fort.

03:35:32.510 --> 03:35:39.570
They could never get the gun ashore, and if they did, they could never haul it through the woods.

03:35:41.990 --> 03:35:44.370
Look astern, doctor, replied the captain.

03:35:46.190 --> 03:35:54.630
We had entirely forgotten the Long Nine, and there, to our horror, were the five rogues busy

03:35:54.630 --> 03:36:03.050
about her, getting off her jacket, as they called the stout, tarpaulin cover under which she sailed.

03:36:05.130 --> 03:36:13.230
Not only that, but it flashed into my mind at the same moment that the round shot and the powder

03:36:13.230 --> 03:36:20.290
for the gun had been left behind, and a stroke with an axe could put it all

03:36:20.290 --> 03:36:30.170
into the possession of the evil ones aboard. Israel was Flint's gunner, said Gray hoarsely.

03:36:33.930 --> 03:36:39.470
At any risk, we put the boat's head direct for the landing place.

03:36:40.790 --> 03:36:48.030
By this time, we had got so far out of the run of the current that we kept steerage way even

03:36:48.030 --> 03:36:53.930
at our necessarily gentle rate of rowing, and I could keep her steady for the goal.

03:36:55.630 --> 03:37:02.410
But the worst of it was that with the course I now held, we turned our broadside,

03:37:02.890 --> 03:37:08.830
instead of our stern, to the Hispaniola, and offered a target like a barn door.

03:37:13.050 --> 03:37:22.850
I could hear as well as see that brandy-faced rascal, Israel, hands plumping down a round shot

03:37:22.850 --> 03:37:34.210
on the deck. Who's the best shot? asked the captain. Mr. Trollnalli, out and away, said I.

03:37:37.350 --> 03:37:42.610
Mr. Trollnalli, will you please pick me off one of these men, sir?

03:37:43.290 --> 03:37:46.190
Hands, if possible, said the captain.

03:37:48.150 --> 03:37:53.150
Trollnalli was as cool as steel. He looked to the priming of his gun.

03:37:54.470 --> 03:38:00.750
Now, cried the captain. Easy with that gun, sir, or you'll swamp the boat.

03:38:01.950 --> 03:38:05.630
All hands stand by to trim her when he aims.

03:38:08.690 --> 03:38:15.870
The squire raised his gun, the rowing ceased, and we leaned over to the other side

03:38:15.870 --> 03:38:23.890
to keep the balance, and all was so nicely contrived that we did not ship a drop.

03:38:25.870 --> 03:38:35.150
They had the gun by this time, slewed round upon the swivel, and hands, who was at the muzzle

03:38:35.150 --> 03:38:53.870
with the rammer, was in consequence the most exposed. However, we had no luck, for just as

03:38:56.950 --> 03:39:05.290
The cry he gave was echoed not only by his companions on board, but by a great number

03:39:05.290 --> 03:39:12.610
of voices from the shore. And looking in that direction, I saw the other pirates

03:39:13.470 --> 03:39:19.610
trooping out from among the trees and tumbling into their places in the boats.

03:39:22.010 --> 03:39:24.850
Here comes the gig, sir, said I.

03:39:26.950 --> 03:39:32.850
Give way, then, cried the captain. We mustn't mind if we swamp her now.

03:39:33.450 --> 03:39:35.910
If we can't get ashore, rolls up.

03:39:38.270 --> 03:39:41.870
Only one of the gigs is being manned, sir, I added.

03:39:43.010 --> 03:39:47.890
The crew of the other most likely going round by shore to cut us off.

03:39:51.070 --> 03:39:54.990
They'll have a hot run, sir, returned the captain.

03:39:56.490 --> 03:40:02.250
Jack ashore, you know. It's not them, my mind. It's the round shot.

03:40:03.950 --> 03:40:13.870
Carpet bowls, my lady's maid couldn't miss. Tell us, squire, when you see the match and we'll hold water.

03:40:16.370 --> 03:40:25.170
In the meanwhile, we had been making headway at a good pace, for a boat so overloaded and we had

03:40:25.170 --> 03:40:33.430
shipped but little water in the process. We were now close in, thirty or forty strokes,

03:40:33.830 --> 03:40:40.850
and we should beach her, for the ebb had already disclosed a narrow belt of sand below the

03:40:40.850 --> 03:40:49.190
clustering trees. The gig was no longer to be feared. The little point had already concealed

03:40:49.190 --> 03:40:58.130
it from our eyes. The ebb tide, which had so cruelly delayed us, was now making reparations

03:40:58.130 --> 03:41:04.470
and delaying our sailets. The one source of danger was the gun.

03:41:06.430 --> 03:41:12.870
If I durst, said the captain, I'd stop and pick off another man.

03:41:14.650 --> 03:41:19.010
But it was plain that they meant nothing should delay their shot.

03:41:20.390 --> 03:41:24.170
They had never so much as looked at their fallen comrade,

03:41:24.990 --> 03:41:29.930
though he was not dead and I could see him trying to crawl away.

03:41:31.570 --> 03:41:33.490
Ready, cried the squire.

03:41:34.590 --> 03:41:37.990
Hold, cried the captain, quick as an echo.

03:41:41.090 --> 03:41:47.490
And he and Redrith backed with a great heave that sent her stern bodily underwater.

03:41:48.910 --> 03:41:55.370
The report fell in at the same instant of time. This was the first that Jim heard,

03:41:55.930 --> 03:41:59.730
the sound of the squire's shot not having reached him.

03:42:01.250 --> 03:42:09.630
Where the ball passed, not one of us precisely knew, but I fancy it must have been over our heads,

03:42:10.110 --> 03:42:13.750
and that the wind of it may have contributed to our disaster.

03:42:15.970 --> 03:42:23.970
At any rate, the boat sank by the stern, quite gently, in three feet of water,

03:42:24.530 --> 03:42:30.050
leaving the captain and myself facing each other on our feet.

03:42:31.570 --> 03:42:36.710
The other three took complete headers and came up again, drenched and bubbling.

03:42:39.210 --> 03:42:46.850
So far there was no great harm, no lives were lost, and we could wade ashore in safety.

03:42:48.530 --> 03:42:51.350
But there were all our stores at the bottom,

03:42:51.990 --> 03:42:58.790
and to make things worse, only two guns out of the five remained in a state for service.

03:43:00.590 --> 03:43:05.370
Mine I had snatched from my knees and held over my head by a sort of instinct.

03:43:07.130 --> 03:43:11.850
As for the captain, he had carried his over his shoulder by a bandolier,

03:43:12.610 --> 03:43:19.910
and like a wise man, lock uppermost. The other three had gone down with the boat.

03:43:22.090 --> 03:43:28.750
To add to our concern, we heard voices already drawing near us in the woods along shore.

03:43:29.910 --> 03:43:36.670
We had not only the danger of being cut off from the stockade in our half-crippled state,

03:43:37.930 --> 03:43:44.690
but the fear before us whether if Hunter and Joyce were attacked by half a dozen,

03:43:45.770 --> 03:43:49.850
they would have the sense and conduct to stand firm.

03:43:51.490 --> 03:44:02.510
Hunter was steady, that we knew. Joyce was a doubtful case, a pleasant, polite man for a valet,

03:44:03.510 --> 03:44:08.350
and to brush one's clothes but not entirely fitted for man of war.

03:44:10.750 --> 03:44:18.070
With all this in our minds, we waded ashore as fast as we could, leaving behind us

03:44:18.070 --> 03:44:24.730
the poor jolly boat and a good half of all our powder and provisions.

03:44:47.790 --> 03:44:50.590
CHAPTER XVIII.

03:44:50.590 --> 03:44:56.170
Narrative continued by the Doctor. End of the first day's fighting.

03:44:59.270 --> 03:45:06.010
We made our best speed across the strip of wood that now divided us from the stockade,

03:45:07.370 --> 03:45:12.050
and at every step we took the voices of the buccaneers rang nearer.

03:45:14.070 --> 03:45:19.970
Soon we could hear their footfalls as they ran and the cracking of the branches

03:45:19.970 --> 03:45:23.090
as they breasted across a bit of thicket.

03:45:28.450 --> 03:45:34.730
I began to see we should have a brush for it in earnest and looked to my priming.

03:45:36.530 --> 03:45:44.370
Captain, said I, Trenolny is the dead shot. Give him your gun. His own is useless.

03:45:45.970 --> 03:45:53.630
They exchanged guns and Trenolny, silent and cool as he had been since the beginning of the bustle,

03:45:54.830 --> 03:45:59.130
hung a moment on his heel to see that all was fit for service.

03:46:00.650 --> 03:46:07.650
At the same time, observing Grey to be unarmed, I handed him my cutlass.

03:46:08.390 --> 03:46:12.750
It did all our hearts good to see him spit in his hand,

03:46:13.970 --> 03:46:18.150
knit his brows and make the blade sing through the air.

03:46:19.430 --> 03:46:24.990
It was plain from every line of his body that our new hand was worth his salt.

03:46:29.150 --> 03:46:35.770
Forty paces farther, we came to the edge of the wood and saw the stockade in front of us.

03:46:36.730 --> 03:46:43.710
We struck the enclosure about the middle of the south side and almost at the same time,

03:46:44.230 --> 03:46:52.850
seven mutineers, Job Anderson, the Botswain at their head, appeared in full cry at the southwestern corner.

03:46:54.970 --> 03:47:02.110
They paused as if taken aback and before they recovered, not only the Squire and I,

03:47:02.110 --> 03:47:06.390
but Hunter and Joyce from the blockhouse had time to fire.

03:47:07.910 --> 03:47:15.250
The four shots came in rather a scattering volley, but they did the business. One of the

03:47:15.250 --> 03:47:22.270
enemy actually fell and the rest, without hesitation, turned and plunged into the trees.

03:47:24.970 --> 03:47:31.330
After reloading, we walked down the outside of the palisade to see to the fallen enemy.

03:47:32.110 --> 03:47:35.550
He was stone dead, shot through the heart.

03:47:38.730 --> 03:47:46.710
We began to rejoice over our good success when just at that moment a pistol cracked in the bush.

03:47:47.850 --> 03:47:55.990
A ball whistled close past my ear and poor Tom Rudrith stumbled and fell his length on the ground.

03:47:57.270 --> 03:48:05.910
Both the Squire and I returned the shot, but as we had nothing to aim at, it is probable we only

03:48:05.910 --> 03:48:11.730
wasted powder. Then we reloaded and turned our attention to poor Tom.

03:48:14.630 --> 03:48:20.670
The Captain and Gray were already examining him and I saw with half an eye that all was over.

03:48:23.490 --> 03:48:30.530
I believe the readiness of our return volley had scattered the mutineers once more,

03:48:31.390 --> 03:48:38.690
for we were suffered without further molestation to get the poor old gamekeeper hoisted over the

03:48:38.690 --> 03:48:44.390
stockade and carried, groaning and bleeding, into the log house.

03:48:46.410 --> 03:48:56.070
Poor old fellow. He had not uttered one word of surprise, complaint, fear, or even acquiescence

03:48:56.070 --> 03:49:04.190
from the very beginning of our troubles till now. When we had laid him down in the log house to die,

03:49:05.590 --> 03:49:12.830
he had lain like a Trojan behind his mattress in the gallery. He had followed every order silently,

03:49:13.710 --> 03:49:19.250
doggedly, and well. He was the oldest of our party by a score of years,

03:49:20.210 --> 03:49:27.770
and now sullen, old, serviceable servant. It was he that was to die.

03:49:30.250 --> 03:49:37.070
The Squire dropped down beside him on his knees and kissed his hand, crying like a child.

03:49:41.090 --> 03:49:49.890
Be I going, Doctor? he asked. Tom, my man, said I. You're going home.

03:49:52.450 --> 03:49:56.970
I wish I had a lick at them with the gun first, he replied.

03:49:59.270 --> 03:50:04.250
Tom, said the Squire, say you forgive me, won't you?

03:50:05.210 --> 03:50:10.790
Would that be respectful, like, from me to you, Squire, was the answer.

03:50:12.390 --> 03:50:15.450
Howsoever, so be it. Amen.

03:50:18.330 --> 03:50:24.190
After a little while of silence, he said he thought somebody might read a prayer.

03:50:25.430 --> 03:50:29.630
It is the custom, sir, he added apologetically.

03:50:30.870 --> 03:50:35.550
And not long after, without another word, he passed away.

03:50:38.030 --> 03:50:44.970
In the meantime, the captain, whom I had observed to be wonderfully swollen about the chest and

03:50:44.970 --> 03:50:55.770
pockets, had turned out a great many various stores. The British Colors, a Bible, a coil of

03:50:55.770 --> 03:51:02.850
Scottish rope, pen, ink, the log book, and pounds of tobacco.

03:51:04.990 --> 03:51:11.050
He had found a longish fir tree lying felled and trimmed in the enclosure,

03:51:12.290 --> 03:51:17.170
and with the help of Hunter, he had set it up at the corner of the log house,

03:51:17.870 --> 03:51:20.010
where the trunks crossed and made an angle.

03:51:21.710 --> 03:51:29.530
Then, climbing on the roof, he had with his own hand bent and run up the Colors.

03:51:32.030 --> 03:51:40.210
This seems mightily to relieve him. He re-entered the log house and set about counting up the stores

03:51:40.210 --> 03:51:47.510
as if nothing else existed. But he had an eye on Tom's passage for all that.

03:51:48.470 --> 03:51:57.290
And as soon as all was over, he came forward with another flag and reverently spread it on the body.

03:51:59.550 --> 03:52:05.190
Don't you take on, sir, he said, shaking the squire's hand.

03:52:06.650 --> 03:52:14.430
All's well with him. No fear for a hand that's been shot down in his duty to captain and owner.

03:52:15.370 --> 03:52:22.010
It mayn't be good divinity, but it's a fact. Then he pulled me aside.

03:52:25.270 --> 03:52:32.070
Dr. Livesey, he said, in how many weeks do you and Squire expect the consort?

03:52:34.650 --> 03:52:42.250
I told him it was a question not of weeks, but of months, that if we were not back by the end of

03:52:42.250 --> 03:52:51.510
August, Blanley was to send to find us. But neither sooner nor later. You can calculate

03:52:51.510 --> 03:53:01.010
for yourself, I said. Why, yes, returned the captain, scratching his head. And making a

03:53:01.010 --> 03:53:08.310
large allowance, sir, for all the gifts of Providence, I should say we were pretty close-hauled.

03:53:11.170 --> 03:53:13.990
How do you mean? I asked.

03:53:15.790 --> 03:53:18.410
It's a pity, sir. We lost that second load.

03:53:19.330 --> 03:53:25.370
That's what I mean, replied the captain. As for powder and shot will do.

03:53:26.470 --> 03:53:33.350
The rations are short. Very short. So short, Dr. Livesey.

03:53:33.510 --> 03:53:36.750
There were perhaps as well without that extra mouth.

03:53:38.410 --> 03:53:41.690
And he pointed to the dead body under the flag.

03:53:46.070 --> 03:53:53.390
Just then, with a roar and a whistle, a round shot passed high above the roof

03:53:53.390 --> 03:53:57.550
of the log house and plumped far beyond us in the wood.

03:53:59.310 --> 03:54:06.810
Oh ho, said the captain, blaze away. You've little enough powder already, my lads.

03:54:09.510 --> 03:54:15.570
At the second trial, the aim was better. And the ball descended inside the stockade,

03:54:17.190 --> 03:54:20.770
scattering a cloud of sand, but doing no further damage.

03:54:22.330 --> 03:54:28.630
Captain, said the squire, the house is quite invisible from the ship.

03:54:29.850 --> 03:54:35.570
It must be the flag they are aiming at. Would it not be wiser to take it in?

03:54:36.410 --> 03:54:41.730
Strike my colors, cried the captain. No, sir, not I.

03:54:42.790 --> 03:54:47.650
And as soon as he had said the words, I think we all agreed with him.

03:54:48.390 --> 03:54:53.050
For was not only a piece of stout, seemingly good feeling,

03:54:54.470 --> 03:55:01.310
it was good policy besides and showed our enemies that we despised their cannonade.

03:55:04.350 --> 03:55:08.930
All through the evening, they kept thundering away.

03:55:09.790 --> 03:55:16.590
Ball after ball flew over or fell short, or kicked up the sand in the enclosure.

03:55:18.690 --> 03:55:25.210
But they had to fire so high that the shot fell dead and buried itself in the soft sand.

03:55:26.830 --> 03:55:33.850
We had no ricochet to fear. And though one popped in through the roof of the log house,

03:55:33.950 --> 03:55:39.410
and out again through the floor, we soon got used to that sort of horseplay,

03:55:40.050 --> 03:55:42.050
and minded it no more than cricket.

03:55:44.930 --> 03:55:49.110
There is one good thing about all of this, observed the captain.

03:55:50.930 --> 03:55:56.750
The wood in front of us is likely clear. The ebb has made a good while.

03:55:57.990 --> 03:56:02.950
Our stores should be uncovered. Volunteers to go and bring in pork?

03:56:05.810 --> 03:56:11.750
Gray and Hunter were the first to come forward. While armed, they stole out of the stockade,

03:56:12.630 --> 03:56:19.090
but approved a useless mission. The mutineers were bolder than we fancied.

03:56:19.830 --> 03:56:22.670
Or they put more trust in Israel's gunnery.

03:56:25.170 --> 03:56:28.990
For four or five of them were busy carrying off our stores

03:56:28.990 --> 03:56:33.570
and waiting out with them to one of the gigs that lay close by.

03:56:35.590 --> 03:56:39.010
Pulling an oar sewed to hold her steady against the current.

03:56:41.190 --> 03:56:48.830
Silver was in the stern, sheets in command. And every man of them was now provided with a musket.

03:56:49.110 --> 03:56:52.010
From some secret magazine of their own.

03:56:55.310 --> 03:57:00.330
The captain sat down to his log, and here is the beginning of the entry.

03:57:03.810 --> 03:57:10.210
Alexander Smollett, master. David Livesey, ship's doctor.

03:57:12.290 --> 03:57:18.650
Abraham Gray, carpenter's mate. John Trinolny, owner.

03:57:21.350 --> 03:57:30.850
John Hunter and Richard Joyce, owner-servants, landsmen. Being all that is left faithful of the

03:57:30.850 --> 03:57:39.530
ship's company, with stores for ten days at short rations, came ashore this day and flew British

03:57:39.530 --> 03:57:48.690
colors on the log house in Treasure Island. Thomas Redruth, owner-servant, landsman.

03:57:49.410 --> 03:57:55.070
Shot by the mutineers. James Hawkins, cabin boy.

03:57:57.550 --> 03:58:02.090
And at the same time, I was wondering over poor Jim Hawkins's fate.

03:58:04.310 --> 03:58:05.730
A hail on the land side.

03:58:08.490 --> 03:58:12.310
Somebody's hailing us, said Hunter, who was on guard.

03:58:13.750 --> 03:58:21.570
Doctor! Squire! Captain! Hello, Hunter! Is that you? came the cries.

03:58:23.710 --> 03:58:34.150
And I ran to the door in time to see Jim Hawkins, safe and sound, come climbing over the stockade.

03:58:57.030 --> 03:58:59.830
CHAPTER XIX

03:58:59.830 --> 03:59:04.310
Narrative resumed by Jim Hawkins, the garrison in the stockade.

03:59:05.890 --> 03:59:11.970
As soon as Ben Gunn saw the colours, he came to a halt, stopped me by the arm, and sat down.

03:59:12.690 --> 03:59:15.870
Now, said he, there's your friends, sure enough.

03:59:16.890 --> 03:59:19.790
Far more likely it's the mutineers, I answered.

03:59:20.770 --> 03:59:26.530
That, he cried, why, in a place like this, where nobody puts in but gentlemen a fortune,

03:59:26.530 --> 03:59:30.970
silver would fly the jolly roger, you don't make no doubt of that.

03:59:31.330 --> 03:59:32.590
No, that's your friends.

03:59:33.110 --> 03:59:37.110
There's been blows too, and I reckon your friends has had the best of it,

03:59:37.350 --> 03:59:42.510
and here they are, ashore in the old stockade, as was made years and years ago by Flint.

03:59:43.430 --> 03:59:50.030
Ah, he was the man to have a headpiece was Flint, barring rum, his match were never seen.

03:59:50.510 --> 03:59:53.850
He were afraid of none, not he, only silver.

03:59:54.490 --> 03:59:56.090
Silver was that genteel.

03:59:57.290 --> 04:00:00.370
Well, said I, that may be so, and so be it,

04:00:00.710 --> 04:00:03.670
all the more reason that I should hurry on and join my friends.

04:00:04.610 --> 04:00:11.910
Nay, mate, returned Ben, not you, you're a good boy, or I'm a stook, but you're only a boy all told.

04:00:12.710 --> 04:00:18.870
Now, Ben Gunn is fly, rum wouldn't bring me there where you're going, not rum wouldn't,

04:00:18.910 --> 04:00:22.490
till I see your born gentleman, and gets on his word of honour,

04:00:22.490 --> 04:00:27.050
and you won't forget my words, a precious sight, that's what you'll say,

04:00:27.550 --> 04:00:30.670
a precious sight, more confidence, and then nips him,

04:00:31.530 --> 04:00:35.330
and he pinched me the third time with the same air of cleverness,

04:00:35.950 --> 04:00:41.730
and when Ben Gunn is wanted, you know where to find him, Jim, just where you found him today,

04:00:42.450 --> 04:00:46.750
and him that comes is to have a white thing in his hand, and he's to come alone.

04:00:47.310 --> 04:00:52.250
Oh, and you'll say this, Ben Gunn, says you, has reasons of his own.

04:00:53.170 --> 04:00:58.130
Well, said I, I believe I understand, you have something to propose,

04:00:58.270 --> 04:01:03.970
and you wish to see the squire or the doctor, and you're to be found where I found you, is that all?

04:01:05.030 --> 04:01:11.570
And when, says you, he added, why, from about noon observation to about six bells.

04:01:12.970 --> 04:01:15.330
Good, said I, and now may I go?

04:01:15.790 --> 04:01:22.330
You won't forget, he inquired anxiously, precious sight and reasons of his own, says you,

04:01:22.490 --> 04:01:27.450
reasons of his own, that's the mainstay, as between man and man.

04:01:27.970 --> 04:01:32.410
Well then, still holding me, I reckon you can go, Jim.

04:01:33.170 --> 04:01:38.770
And Jim, if you was to see silver, you wouldn't go for to sell Ben Gunn?

04:01:39.730 --> 04:01:41.810
Wild horses wouldn't draw it from you?

04:01:42.450 --> 04:01:46.470
No, says you, and if them pirates came ashore, Jim,

04:01:46.810 --> 04:01:49.290
what would you say but there'd be widows in the morning?

04:01:49.890 --> 04:01:55.890
Here he was interrupted by a loud report, and a cannonball came tearing through the trees,

04:01:56.210 --> 04:02:00.590
and pitched into the sand, not a hundred yards from where we two were talking.

04:02:01.190 --> 04:02:05.430
The next moment each of us had taken to his heels in a different direction.

04:02:06.330 --> 04:02:10.010
For a good hour to come, frequent reports shook the island,

04:02:10.350 --> 04:02:12.410
and the balls kept crashing through the woods.

04:02:13.070 --> 04:02:16.750
I moved from hiding place to hiding place, always pursued,

04:02:16.750 --> 04:02:20.690
or so it seemed to me, by these terrifying missiles.

04:02:21.450 --> 04:02:25.750
But towards the end of the bombardment, though I still durst not venture in the

04:02:25.750 --> 04:02:31.450
direction of the stockade, where the balls fell off nest, I had begun, in a manner,

04:02:31.870 --> 04:02:35.810
to pluck up my heart again, and after a long detour to the east,

04:02:36.170 --> 04:02:38.510
crept along among the shoreside trees.

04:02:39.590 --> 04:02:44.570
The sun had just set, the sea breeze was rustling and tumbling in the woods,

04:02:44.570 --> 04:02:47.590
and ruffling the grey surface of the anchorage.

04:02:47.990 --> 04:02:52.350
The tide, too, was far out, and great tracks of sand lay uncovered.

04:02:52.870 --> 04:02:57.070
The air, after the heat of the day, chilled me through my jacket.

04:02:57.810 --> 04:03:00.530
The Hispaniola still lay where she had anchored.

04:03:01.170 --> 04:03:07.670
But sure enough, there was the Jolly Roger, the black flag of piracy flying from her peak.

04:03:08.210 --> 04:03:11.290
Even as I looked, there came another red flash,

04:03:11.290 --> 04:03:14.310
and another report that sent the echoes clattering,

04:03:14.830 --> 04:03:17.270
and one more round shot whistled through the air.

04:03:17.610 --> 04:03:19.430
It was the last of the cannonade.

04:03:20.370 --> 04:03:24.090
I lay for some time watching the bustle which succeeded the attack.

04:03:24.670 --> 04:03:28.370
Men were demolishing something with axes on the beach near the stockade,

04:03:28.790 --> 04:03:31.290
the poor Jolly Boat I afterwards discovered.

04:03:32.390 --> 04:03:37.210
Away, near the mouth of the river, a great fire was glowing among the trees,

04:03:37.210 --> 04:03:41.870
and between that point and the ship, one of the gigs kept coming and going.

04:03:42.250 --> 04:03:46.890
The men, whom I had seen so gloomy, shouting at the oars like children.

04:03:47.510 --> 04:03:50.630
But there was a sound in their voices which suggested rum.

04:03:51.710 --> 04:03:54.990
At length I thought I might return towards the stockade.

04:03:55.430 --> 04:04:00.090
I was pretty far down on the low sandy spit that encloses the anchorage to the east,

04:04:00.450 --> 04:04:05.470
and is joined at half water to Skeleton Island, and now, as I rose to my feet,

04:04:05.470 --> 04:04:10.810
I saw, some distance further down the spit and rising from among the low bushes,

04:04:11.290 --> 04:04:15.850
an isolated rock, pretty high and peculiarly white in colour.

04:04:16.590 --> 04:04:20.510
It occurred to me that this might be the white rock of which Ben Gunn had spoken,

04:04:20.930 --> 04:04:26.050
and that some day or other a boat might be wanted, and I should know where to look for one.

04:04:27.330 --> 04:04:30.890
Then I skirted amongst the woods until I had regained the rear,

04:04:30.890 --> 04:04:36.190
or shoreward side of the stockade, and was soon warmly welcomed by the faithful party.

04:04:37.290 --> 04:04:40.570
I had soon told my story and begun to look about me.

04:04:41.070 --> 04:04:46.410
The log house was made of unsquared trunks of pine, roof, walls and a floor.

04:04:47.150 --> 04:04:52.890
The latter stood in several places, as much as a foot or a foot and a half above the surface of the

04:04:52.890 --> 04:04:59.070
sand. There was a porch at the door, and under this porch a little spring welled up into an

04:04:59.070 --> 04:05:05.430
artificial basin of a rather odd kind, no other than a great ship's kettle of iron with the bottom

04:05:05.430 --> 04:05:12.110
knocked out and sunk to her bearings, as the captain said, among the sand. Little had been

04:05:12.110 --> 04:05:17.850
left besides the framework of the house, but in one corner there was a stone slab laid down by way

04:05:17.850 --> 04:05:25.390
of a hearth and an old rusty iron basket to contain the fire. The slopes on the knoll and all the

04:05:25.390 --> 04:05:30.490
side of the stockade had been cleared of timber to build the house, and we could see by the

04:05:30.490 --> 04:05:36.170
stumps what a fine and lofty grove had been destroyed. Most of the soil had been washed away

04:05:36.170 --> 04:05:42.150
or buried in drift after removal of the trees. Only where the streamlet ran down from the kettle,

04:05:42.590 --> 04:05:48.090
a thick bed of moss and some ferns and some little creeping bushes were still green among the sand.

04:05:48.990 --> 04:05:55.370
Very close to the stockade, too close for defence, they said, the wood still flourished high and dense,

04:05:55.390 --> 04:06:01.690
all of fur on the land side, but towards the sea with a large admixture of live oaks.

04:06:02.710 --> 04:06:08.770
The cold evening breeze, of which I have spoken, whistled through every chink of the rude building

04:06:08.770 --> 04:06:15.150
and sprinkled the floor with a continual rain of fine sand. There was sand in our eyes,

04:06:15.570 --> 04:06:21.710
sand in our teeth, sand in our suppers, sand dancing in the spring at the bottom of the kettle

04:06:21.710 --> 04:06:27.710
for all the world-like porridge beginning to boil. Our chimney was a square hole in the roof,

04:06:28.150 --> 04:06:33.250
it was but a little part of the smoke that found its way out, the rest eddied about the house and

04:06:33.250 --> 04:06:40.290
kept us coughing and piping in the eye. Add to this that Grey, the new man, had his face tied up

04:06:40.290 --> 04:06:46.130
in a bandage for a cut that he had got in breaking away from the mutineers, and that poor old Tom

04:06:46.130 --> 04:06:52.110
Redruth, still unburied, lay along the wall stiff and stark under the Union Jack.

04:06:54.670 --> 04:06:59.110
If we had been allowed to sit idle, we should have all fallen into the blues,

04:06:59.530 --> 04:07:04.930
but Captain Smollett was never the man for that. All hands were called up before him,

04:07:05.190 --> 04:07:12.390
and he divided us into watches, the Doctor and Grey and I for one, the Squire, Hunter and Joyce

04:07:12.390 --> 04:07:18.630
upon the other. Tired though we all were, two were sent out for firewood, two more were set

04:07:18.630 --> 04:07:24.330
to dig a grave for Redruth, the Doctor was named Cook, I was put sentry at the door,

04:07:24.610 --> 04:07:30.010
and the Captain himself went from one to another, keeping up our spirits and lending a hand wherever

04:07:30.010 --> 04:07:36.450
it was wanted. From time to time the Doctor came to the door for a little air, and to rest his eyes,

04:07:36.450 --> 04:07:41.690
which were almost smoked out of his head, and whenever he did so he had a word for me.

04:07:42.810 --> 04:07:49.830
That man Smollett, he said once, is a better man than I am, and when I say that it means a deal,

04:07:50.390 --> 04:07:57.470
Jim. Another time he came and was silent for a while, then he put his head on one side and

04:07:57.470 --> 04:08:07.210
looked at me. Is this Ben Gunn a man? he asked. I do not know, sir, said I. I am not very sure

04:08:07.210 --> 04:08:14.850
whether he's sane. If there's any doubt about that matter he is, returned the Doctor. A man who has

04:08:14.850 --> 04:08:20.170
been three years biting his nails on a desert island, Jim, can't expect to appear as sane as

04:08:20.170 --> 04:08:26.790
you or me. It doesn't lie in human nature. Was it cheese you said he had a fancy for?

04:08:27.770 --> 04:08:35.970
Yes, sir, cheese, I answered. Well, Jim, says he, just see the good stuff that comes out of being

04:08:35.970 --> 04:08:43.110
dainty in your food. You've seen my snuff box, haven't you? And you never saw me take snuff,

04:08:43.710 --> 04:08:49.930
the reason being that in my snuff box I carry a piece of Parmesan cheese, a cheese made in Italy,

04:08:49.930 --> 04:08:59.150
very nutritious. Well, that's for Ben Gunn. Before supper was eaten, we buried old Tom in the sand

04:08:59.150 --> 04:09:05.690
and stood round him for a while bareheaded in the breeze. A good deal of firewood had been got in,

04:09:05.910 --> 04:09:11.230
but not enough for the captain's fancy, and he shook his head over it and told us we must get

04:09:11.230 --> 04:09:18.310
back to this tomorrow rather livelier. Then, when we had eaten our pork and each had a good stiff

04:09:18.310 --> 04:09:23.670
glass of brandy grog, the three chiefs got together in a corner to discuss our prospects.

04:09:25.110 --> 04:09:31.370
It appears they were at their wits end what to do, the stores being so low that we must

04:09:31.370 --> 04:09:37.350
have been starved into surrender long before help came. But our best hope, it was decided,

04:09:37.870 --> 04:09:44.530
was to kill off the buccaneers until they either hold down their flag or ran away with the Hispaniola.

04:09:45.250 --> 04:09:52.230
From 19, they were already reduced to 15, two others were wounded, and at least one,

04:09:52.510 --> 04:09:59.090
the man beside the gun, severely wounded if he were not dead. Every time we had a crack at them,

04:09:59.270 --> 04:10:05.150
we were to take it, saving our own lives with the extremist care. And besides that,

04:10:05.150 --> 04:10:13.770
we had two able allies, Rum and the climate. As for the first, though we were about half a mile away,

04:10:13.770 --> 04:10:20.190
we could hear them roaring and singing late into the night. And as for the second, the doctor staked

04:10:20.190 --> 04:10:26.170
his wig that, can't where they were in the marsh, and unprovided with remedies, the half of them would

04:10:26.170 --> 04:10:34.170
be on their backs before a week. So, he added, if we are not all shot first, they'll be glad to be

04:10:34.170 --> 04:10:39.410
packing in the schooner. It's always a ship and they can get to buccaneering again, I suppose.

04:10:40.830 --> 04:10:48.010
First ship that I ever lost, said Captain Smollett. I was dead tired, as you may fancy,

04:10:48.410 --> 04:10:54.350
and when I got to sleep, which was not after a great deal of tossing, I slept like a log of wood.

04:10:55.450 --> 04:11:00.710
The rest had long been up and had already breakfasted and increased the pile of firewood

04:11:00.710 --> 04:11:05.890
by about half as much again when I was wakened by a bustle and the sound of voices.

04:11:06.710 --> 04:11:13.270
Flag of truce, I heard someone say, and then immediately after with a cry of surprise,

04:11:14.090 --> 04:11:21.710
silver himself! And at that, up I jumped, and rubbing my eyes, ran to a loophole in the wall.

04:11:44.870 --> 04:11:47.670
CHAPTER XX.

04:11:47.670 --> 04:11:49.390
Silver's Embassy

04:11:51.530 --> 04:12:03.390
Sure enough, there were two men just outside the stockade, one of them waving a white cloth, the other no less a person than Silver himself, standing placidly by.

04:12:04.050 --> 04:12:12.550
It was still quite early, and the coldest morning that I think I was ever abroad in, a chill that pierced into the marrow.

04:12:13.310 --> 04:12:18.930
The sky was bright and cloudless overhead, and the tops of the trees shone rosily in the sun.

04:12:19.830 --> 04:12:29.810
But where Silver stood with his lieutenant, all was in shadow, and they waded knee-deep into a low, white vapor that had crawled during the night out of the morass.

04:12:29.810 --> 04:12:39.050
The chill and the vapor taken together told a poor tale of the island. It was plainly a damp, feverish, unhealthy spot.

04:12:40.150 --> 04:12:44.650
Keep indoors, men, said the captain. Ten to one, this is a trick.

04:12:45.750 --> 04:12:51.030
Then he hailed the buccaneer. Who goes? Stand, or we fire.

04:12:52.090 --> 04:12:54.810
Flag of truce, cried Silver.

04:12:55.830 --> 04:13:02.410
The captain was in the porch, keeping himself carefully out of the way of a treacherous shot, should any be intended.

04:13:03.050 --> 04:13:05.150
He turned and spoke to us.

04:13:05.710 --> 04:13:07.190
Doctors watch on the lookout.

04:13:07.870 --> 04:13:10.510
Doctor livesay, take the north side, if you please.

04:13:11.010 --> 04:13:13.310
Gym, the east, grey, west.

04:13:13.890 --> 04:13:16.710
The watch below, all hands to load muskets.

04:13:17.310 --> 04:13:19.130
Lively men, and careful.

04:13:19.850 --> 04:13:22.490
And then he turned again to the mutineers.

04:13:23.330 --> 04:13:25.710
And what do you want with your flag of truce?

04:13:26.030 --> 04:13:26.870
He cried.

04:13:27.890 --> 04:13:30.230
This time it was the other man who replied.

04:13:31.510 --> 04:13:34.830
Captain Silver, sir, to come on board and make terms.

04:13:35.350 --> 04:13:36.070
He shouted.

04:13:37.290 --> 04:13:39.590
Captain Silver? Don't know him.

04:13:40.030 --> 04:13:40.830
Who's he?

04:13:41.130 --> 04:13:44.510
Cried the captain, and we could hear him adding to himself.

04:13:45.290 --> 04:13:46.390
Captain, is it?

04:13:46.390 --> 04:13:48.990
My heart, and here's promotion.

04:13:50.270 --> 04:13:52.030
Long John answered for himself.

04:13:52.910 --> 04:13:59.930
Me, sir, these poor lads have chosen me captain, after your desertion, sir.

04:14:00.550 --> 04:14:04.250
Laying a particular emphasis upon the word desertion.

04:14:05.290 --> 04:14:10.190
We're willing to submit, if we can come to terms, and no bones about it.

04:14:10.190 --> 04:14:13.130
All I ask is your word, Captain Smollett,

04:14:13.670 --> 04:14:16.590
to let me safe and sound out of this here stockade,

04:14:16.990 --> 04:14:20.070
and one minute to get our shot before a gun is fired.

04:14:21.190 --> 04:14:27.250
My man, said Captain Smollett, I have not the slightest desire to talk to you.

04:14:27.590 --> 04:14:30.850
If you wish to talk to me, you can come, that's all.

04:14:31.430 --> 04:14:35.970
If there's any treachery, it'll be on your side, and the Lord help you.

04:14:37.090 --> 04:14:40.670
That's enough, Captain, shouted Long John cheerily.

04:14:41.490 --> 04:14:42.790
A word's from you's enough.

04:14:43.290 --> 04:14:46.250
I know a gentleman, and you may lay to that.

04:14:47.010 --> 04:14:51.870
We could see the man who carried the flag of truce, attempting to hold Silver back.

04:14:52.550 --> 04:14:56.690
Nor was that wonderful, seeing how cavalier had been the captain's answer.

04:14:57.490 --> 04:15:03.630
But Silver laughed at him aloud, and slapped him on the back as if the idea of alarm had been absurd.

04:15:03.630 --> 04:15:09.270
Then he advanced to the stockade, threw over his crutch, got a leg up,

04:15:09.630 --> 04:15:15.630
and with great vigor and skill succeeded in surmounting the fence and dropping safely to the other side.

04:15:16.650 --> 04:15:24.170
I will confess that I was far too much taken up with what was going on to be of the slightest use this century.

04:15:24.890 --> 04:15:29.850
Indeed, I had already deserted my eastern loophole and crept up behind the captain,

04:15:29.850 --> 04:15:36.490
who had now seated himself on the threshold with his elbows on his knees, his head in his hands,

04:15:36.770 --> 04:15:41.910
and his eyes fixed on the water as it bubbled out of the old iron kettle in the sand.

04:15:42.590 --> 04:15:45.390
He was whistling, Come, lasses and lads.

04:15:46.590 --> 04:15:49.570
Silver had terrible hard work getting up the knoll,

04:15:49.870 --> 04:15:54.610
while with the steepness of the incline, the thick tree stumps, and the soft sand,

04:15:55.050 --> 04:15:58.190
he and his crutch were as helpless as a ship in stays.

04:15:58.190 --> 04:16:03.650
But he stuck to it like a man in silence, and at last arrived before the captain,

04:16:04.170 --> 04:16:06.270
whom he saluted in the handsomest style.

04:16:07.270 --> 04:16:12.170
He was tricked down his best, an immense blue coat, thick with brass buttons,

04:16:12.610 --> 04:16:18.170
hung as low as to his knees, and a fine-laced hat was set upon the back of his head.

04:16:19.310 --> 04:16:24.950
Here you are, my man, said the captain, raising his head. You had better sit down.

04:16:26.030 --> 04:16:29.990
You ain't a-goin' to let me inside, captain, complained Long John.

04:16:30.730 --> 04:16:34.850
It's a main cold mornin', to be sure, to sit outside upon the sand.

04:16:35.930 --> 04:16:40.690
Why, Silver, said the captain, if you had pleased to be an honest man,

04:16:40.970 --> 04:16:44.130
you might have been sitting in your galley. It's your own doing.

04:16:44.650 --> 04:16:48.050
You're either my ship's cook, and then you were treated handsome,

04:16:48.530 --> 04:16:53.550
or Captain Silver, a common mutineer and pirate, and then you can go hang.

04:16:54.790 --> 04:17:00.490
Well, well, captain, returned the sea cook, sitting down as he was bidden on the sand.

04:17:01.570 --> 04:17:03.970
You'll have to give me a hand up again, that's all.

04:17:04.190 --> 04:17:06.430
A sweet, pretty place you have of it here.

04:17:06.970 --> 04:17:10.010
Ah, there's Jim. Top of the morning to you, Jim.

04:17:10.510 --> 04:17:11.970
Doctor, here's my service.

04:17:13.110 --> 04:17:17.950
Why, there you are all together like a happy family, in a manner of speaking.

04:17:17.950 --> 04:17:23.890
If you have anything to say, my man, better say it, said the captain.

04:17:25.010 --> 04:17:27.790
Right you were, Captain Smollett, replied Silver.

04:17:28.830 --> 04:17:30.390
Duty's duty, to be sure.

04:17:30.970 --> 04:17:35.030
Well, now, you look here. That was a good lay of yours last night.

04:17:35.610 --> 04:17:41.410
I don't deny it was a good lay. Some of you pretty handy with a hand in spike.

04:17:42.050 --> 04:17:45.450
And I'll not deny neither, but what some of my people was shook.

04:17:45.450 --> 04:17:51.550
Maybe all was shook. Maybe I was shook myself. Maybe that's why I'm here for terms.

04:17:52.510 --> 04:17:56.270
But you mark me, captain. It won't do twice by thunder.

04:17:57.150 --> 04:18:00.750
We'll have to do sentry go and ease off for a point or so on the rum.

04:18:01.650 --> 04:18:04.530
Maybe you think we were all a sheet in the wind's eye.

04:18:04.970 --> 04:18:06.790
But I tell you, I was sober.

04:18:07.270 --> 04:18:12.790
I was only dog-tired, and if I'd awoken a second sooner, I'd have caught you with the act I would.

04:18:13.370 --> 04:18:16.250
He wasn't dead when I got round to him, not he.

04:18:17.530 --> 04:18:21.650
Well, said Captain Smollett, as cool as can be.

04:18:22.630 --> 04:18:27.770
All that Silver said was a riddle to him, but you would never have guessed it from his tone.

04:18:28.550 --> 04:18:35.190
As for me, I began to have an inkling. Ben Gunn's last words came back to my mind.

04:18:35.890 --> 04:18:41.670
I began to suppose that he had paid the Buccaneers a visit while they had all laid drunk together round their fire,

04:18:41.670 --> 04:18:46.650
and I reckoned up with Glee that we had only fourteen enemies to deal with.

04:18:47.730 --> 04:18:50.050
Well, here it is, said Silver.

04:18:51.170 --> 04:18:54.510
We want that treasure, and we'll have it. That's our point.

04:18:55.270 --> 04:18:58.830
You would just as soon save your lives, I reckon, and that's yours.

04:18:59.910 --> 04:19:01.410
You have a chart, haven't you?

04:19:02.230 --> 04:19:04.610
That's as may be, replied the captain.

04:19:05.830 --> 04:19:09.610
Ah, well, you have, I know that, returned Long John.

04:19:09.610 --> 04:19:16.510
You needn't be so husky with a man. There ain't a particle of service in that, and you may lay to it.

04:19:17.010 --> 04:19:19.530
What I mean is, we want your chart.

04:19:20.270 --> 04:19:23.050
Now, I never meant you no harm myself.

04:19:24.170 --> 04:19:27.410
That won't do with me, my man, interrupted the captain.

04:19:28.250 --> 04:19:34.070
We know exactly what you mean to do, and we don't care for now, you see. You can't do it.

04:19:34.910 --> 04:19:38.570
And the captain looked at him calmly and proceeded to fill a pipe.

04:19:39.330 --> 04:19:40.710
If Abbey Grey...

04:19:41.630 --> 04:19:42.690
Silver broke out.

04:19:43.830 --> 04:19:46.530
Avast there! cried Mr. Mullet.

04:19:46.890 --> 04:19:55.550
Grey told me nothing, and so I asked him nothing, and what's more, I would see you and him and this whole island blown clean out of the water into blazes first.

04:19:55.950 --> 04:19:58.450
So there's my mind for you, my man, on that.

04:19:59.470 --> 04:20:02.690
This little whiff of temper seemed to cool Silver down.

04:20:03.350 --> 04:20:06.750
He had been growing nettled before, but now he pulled himself together.

04:20:07.830 --> 04:20:10.290
Like enough, said he.

04:20:10.890 --> 04:20:17.210
I would set no limits to what gentlemen might consider shipshape, or might not, as the case were.

04:20:17.910 --> 04:20:23.190
And seeing as how you're about to take a pipe, captain, I'll make so free as to do likewise.

04:20:24.490 --> 04:20:36.050
And he filled a pipe and lighted it, and the two men sat silently smoking for quite a while, now looking each other in the face, now stopping their tobacco, now leaning forward to spit.

04:20:36.050 --> 04:20:39.110
It was as good as the play to see them.

04:20:40.610 --> 04:20:44.450
Now, resumed Silver, here it is.

04:20:45.090 --> 04:20:52.090
You give us the chart to get the treasure by, and dropping shooting poor seamen and stoving of their heads in while asleep.

04:20:52.730 --> 04:20:55.510
You do that, and we'll offer you a choice.

04:20:56.030 --> 04:21:05.430
Either you come along aboard with us once the treasure is shipped, and then I'll give you my affidavit upon my word of honour to clap you somewhere safe ashore.

04:21:05.430 --> 04:21:14.610
Or if that ain't to your fancy, some of my hands being rough and having old scores on account of hazing, then you can stay here you can.

04:21:15.030 --> 04:21:24.290
We'll divide stores with you, man for man, and I'll give my affidavit, as before, to speak the first ship I sight and send him here to pick you up.

04:21:25.090 --> 04:21:32.390
Now you'll own that stalking, handsomer you couldn't look to get now you, and, I hope, raising his voice.

04:21:32.390 --> 04:21:41.090
That all the hands in this here blockhouse will overhaul my words, for what is spoke to one is spoke to all.

04:21:42.150 --> 04:21:48.610
Captain Smollett rose from his seat and knocked out the ashes of his pipe in the palm of his left hand.

04:21:49.850 --> 04:21:51.750
Is that all? he asked.

04:21:52.870 --> 04:21:56.790
Every last word by thunder, answered John.

04:21:57.450 --> 04:22:01.450
Refuse that, and you've seen the last of me but musket balls.

04:22:02.930 --> 04:22:05.190
Very good, said the captain.

04:22:05.810 --> 04:22:07.130
Now you'll hear me.

04:22:07.550 --> 04:22:14.470
If you'll come up one by one unarmed, I'll engage to clap you all in irons and take you home to a fair trial in England.

04:22:15.130 --> 04:22:23.050
If you won't, my name is Alexander Smollett, I've phoned my sovereign's colours, and I'll see you all to Davy Jones.

04:22:23.630 --> 04:22:29.650
You can't find the treasure, you can't sail the ship, there's not a man among you fit to sail the ship.

04:22:29.650 --> 04:22:34.010
You can't fight us, Grey there, got away from five of you.

04:22:34.590 --> 04:22:39.970
Your ship's in irons, Master Silver, you're on a lee shore, and so you'll find.

04:22:40.710 --> 04:22:45.910
I stand here and I tell you so, and they're the last good words you'll ever get from me,

04:22:46.110 --> 04:22:50.850
for in the name of heaven I'll put a bullet in your back when I next meet you.

04:22:51.590 --> 04:22:56.890
Tramp, my lad, bundle out of this, please, hand over hand and double quick.

04:22:59.470 --> 04:23:04.170
Silver's face was a picture, his eyes started in his head with wrath.

04:23:04.810 --> 04:23:06.670
He shook the fire out of his pipe.

04:23:07.690 --> 04:23:10.130
Give me a hand up, he cried.

04:23:11.110 --> 04:23:13.530
Not I, returned the captain.

04:23:14.290 --> 04:23:17.230
Who'll give me a hand up, he roared.

04:23:17.770 --> 04:23:19.690
Not a man amongst us moved.

04:23:19.690 --> 04:23:25.770
Growling the foulest imprecations, he crawled along the sand till he got hold of the porch,

04:23:26.250 --> 04:23:29.030
and could hoist himself again upon his crutch.

04:23:29.730 --> 04:23:31.430
Then he spat into the spring.

04:23:32.430 --> 04:23:34.370
There, he cried.

04:23:34.990 --> 04:23:36.310
That's what I think here.

04:23:36.750 --> 04:23:42.190
Before an hour's out, I'll stove in your old block house like a rum punchin'.

04:23:42.190 --> 04:23:44.050
Laugh by thunder, laugh.

04:23:44.690 --> 04:23:48.210
Before an hour's out, you'll laugh upon the other side.

04:23:48.210 --> 04:23:51.230
Them that'll die'll be the lucky ones.

04:23:52.430 --> 04:23:58.380
And with a dreadful oath, he stumbled off, ploughed down the sand, and was helped across the stockade

04:23:58.730 --> 04:24:03.050
after four or five failures by the man with the flag of truce,

04:24:03.550 --> 04:24:07.250
and disappeared in an instant afterwards among the trees.

04:24:24.650 --> 04:24:25.610
CHAPTER XXI.

04:24:25.870 --> 04:24:27.250
THE ATTACK.

04:24:27.670 --> 04:24:32.330
As soon as Silver disappeared, the Captain, who had been closely watching him, turned

04:24:32.330 --> 04:24:37.430
towards the interior of the house, and found not a man of us at his post but grey, and

04:24:37.430 --> 04:24:39.450
it was the first time we'd ever seen him angry.

04:24:40.790 --> 04:24:42.590
Quarters! he roared.

04:24:42.850 --> 04:24:48.990
And then, as we all slunk back to our places, Grey, he said, I'll put your name in the log.

04:24:49.370 --> 04:24:51.210
You've stood by your duty like a seaman.

04:24:51.810 --> 04:24:54.310
Mr. Trelawney, I'm surprised at you, sir.

04:24:54.670 --> 04:24:56.770
Doctor, I thought you had worn the King's coat.

04:24:56.870 --> 04:25:00.670
If that was how you served at Fontanoi, sir, you'd have been better in your birth.

04:25:01.810 --> 04:25:02.790
The doctors watched.

04:25:02.950 --> 04:25:04.290
We're all back at their loopholes.

04:25:04.290 --> 04:25:08.870
The rest were busy loading the spare muskets, and everyone with a red face, you may be certain,

04:25:09.110 --> 04:25:11.010
and a flea in his ears, the saying is.

04:25:12.210 --> 04:25:14.570
The Captain looked on for a while in silence.

04:25:14.930 --> 04:25:15.750
Then he spoke.

04:25:17.010 --> 04:25:20.610
My lads, he said, I've given Silver broadside.

04:25:21.270 --> 04:25:27.170
I pitched it in red hot on purpose, and before the hour's out, as he said, we shall be boarded.

04:25:27.770 --> 04:25:32.370
We're outnumbered, I needn't tell you that, but we fight in shelter, and a minute ago

04:25:32.370 --> 04:25:34.110
I should have said we fought with discipline.

04:25:34.890 --> 04:25:37.990
I've no manner of doubt that we can drub them, if you choose.

04:25:39.230 --> 04:25:42.690
Then he went the rounds and saw, as he said, that all was clear.

04:25:43.630 --> 04:25:48.430
On the two short sides of the house, east and west, there were only two loopholes.

04:25:48.910 --> 04:25:53.670
On the south side, where the porch was, two again, and on the north side, five.

04:25:54.370 --> 04:25:57.270
There was a round score of muskets for the seven of us.

04:25:57.550 --> 04:26:01.390
The firewood had been built into four piles, tables, you might say.

04:26:01.390 --> 04:26:06.610
One about the middle of each side, and on each of these tables some ammunition and four

04:26:06.610 --> 04:26:09.110
loaded muskets were laid ready to the hand of the defenders.

04:26:10.070 --> 04:26:12.210
In the middle, the cutlasses lay ranged.

04:26:13.790 --> 04:26:15.830
Toss out the fire, said the Captain.

04:26:16.330 --> 04:26:19.010
The chill is past, and we mustn't have smoke in our eyes.

04:26:20.410 --> 04:26:25.030
The iron firebasket was carried bodily out by Mr. Trelawney, and the embers smothered

04:26:25.030 --> 04:26:25.890
among the sand.

04:26:27.370 --> 04:26:28.790
Hawkins hasn't had his breakfast.

04:26:28.970 --> 04:26:29.810
Hawkins, help yourself.

04:26:29.970 --> 04:26:32.970
Back to your post to eat it, continued Captain Smollett.

04:26:33.270 --> 04:26:34.130
Lively now, my lad.

04:26:34.570 --> 04:26:35.830
You'll want it before you've done.

04:26:36.510 --> 04:26:38.770
Hunter, serve out a round of brandy to all hands.

04:26:39.510 --> 04:26:43.970
And while this was going on, the Captain completed, in his own mind, the plan of defense.

04:26:45.050 --> 04:26:47.590
Doctor, you will take the door, he resumed.

04:26:48.090 --> 04:26:49.250
See and don't expose yourself.

04:26:49.350 --> 04:26:51.110
Keep within, and fire through the porch.

04:26:51.930 --> 04:26:53.330
Hunter, take the east side, there.

04:26:53.950 --> 04:26:56.230
Joyce, you stand by the west, my man.

04:26:56.850 --> 04:26:58.810
Mr. Trelawney, you're the best shot.

04:26:58.970 --> 04:27:01.910
You and Gray will take this long north side with the five loopholes.

04:27:02.370 --> 04:27:03.790
It's there the danger is.

04:27:04.070 --> 04:27:08.190
If they can get up to it and fire in upon us through our own ports, things would begin

04:27:08.190 --> 04:27:08.950
to look dirty.

04:27:10.050 --> 04:27:12.410
Hawkins, neither you nor I are much account of the shooting.

04:27:12.790 --> 04:27:14.690
We'll stand by to load and bear a hand.

04:27:15.510 --> 04:27:17.630
As the Captain had said, the chill was past.

04:27:18.130 --> 04:27:22.130
As soon as the sun had climbed above our girdle of trees, it fell with all its force upon

04:27:22.130 --> 04:27:24.830
the clearing and drank up the vapors at a draft.

04:27:25.870 --> 04:27:29.490
Soon the sand was baking and the resin melting in the logs of the blockhouse.

04:27:29.970 --> 04:27:34.170
Jackets and coats were flung aside, shirts thrown open at the neck and rolled up to the

04:27:34.170 --> 04:27:39.010
shoulders, and we stood there, each at his post, in a fever of heat and anxiety.

04:27:40.250 --> 04:27:41.710
An hour passed away.

04:27:42.490 --> 04:27:44.050
Hang them, said the Captain.

04:27:44.470 --> 04:27:46.490
This is as dull as the doldrums.

04:27:46.750 --> 04:27:47.850
Gray whistled for a wind.

04:27:48.330 --> 04:27:51.630
And just at that moment came the first news of the attack.

04:27:52.790 --> 04:27:56.810
If you please, sir, said Joyce, if I see anyone, am I to fire?

04:27:57.550 --> 04:27:59.870
I told you so, cried the Captain.

04:28:01.030 --> 04:28:04.550
Thank you, sir, returned Joyce with the same quiet civility.

04:28:05.810 --> 04:28:10.290
Nothing followed for a time, but the remark had set us all on the alert, straining ears

04:28:10.290 --> 04:28:14.930
and eyes, the musketeers with their pieces balanced in their hands, the Captain out in

04:28:14.930 --> 04:28:18.910
the middle of the blockhouse, with his mouth very tight and a frown on his face.

04:28:19.810 --> 04:28:24.090
So some seconds passed, till suddenly Joyce whipped up his musket and fired.

04:28:24.830 --> 04:28:28.770
The report had scarcely died away, ere it was repeated and repeated from without in

04:28:28.770 --> 04:28:34.110
a scattering volley, shot behind shot like a string of geese from every side of the enclosure.

04:28:35.010 --> 04:28:39.110
Several bullets struck the log house, but not one entered, and as the smoke cleared

04:28:39.110 --> 04:28:43.830
away and vanished, the stockade and the woods around it looked as quiet and empty as before.

04:28:44.470 --> 04:28:49.310
Not a bow waved, not the gleam of a musket barrel betrayed the presence of our foes.

04:28:50.630 --> 04:28:51.630
Did you hit your man?

04:28:52.270 --> 04:28:52.970
Asked the Captain.

04:28:54.030 --> 04:28:56.830
No, sir, replied Joyce, I believe not, sir.

04:28:57.750 --> 04:29:00.910
Next best thing to tell the truth, muttered Captain Smollett.

04:29:01.330 --> 04:29:02.170
Load his gun, Hawkins.

04:29:02.990 --> 04:29:05.090
How many should say there were on your side, Doctor?

04:29:06.150 --> 04:29:08.810
I know precisely, said Doctor Livesey.

04:29:09.310 --> 04:29:10.970
Three shots were fired on this side.

04:29:10.970 --> 04:29:14.870
I saw the three flashes, two close together, one farther to the west.

04:29:16.010 --> 04:29:17.650
Three, repeated the Captain.

04:29:18.010 --> 04:29:19.790
And how many on yours, Mr. Trelawney?

04:29:20.710 --> 04:29:22.390
But this was not so easily answered.

04:29:22.990 --> 04:29:25.910
There had come many from the north, seven by the Squire's computation,

04:29:26.070 --> 04:29:27.410
eight or nine according to Gray.

04:29:27.950 --> 04:29:30.530
From the east and west, only a single shot had been fired.

04:29:31.230 --> 04:29:34.910
It was plain therefore that the attack would be developed from the north, and

04:29:34.910 --> 04:29:38.390
that on the other three sides we were only to be annoyed by a show of hostilities.

04:29:38.390 --> 04:29:41.550
But Captain Smollett made no change in his arrangements.

04:29:42.030 --> 04:29:44.870
If the mutineers succeeded in crossing the stockade, he argued,

04:29:45.070 --> 04:29:47.650
they would take possession of any unprotected loophole and

04:29:47.650 --> 04:29:49.650
shoot us down like rats in our own stronghold.

04:29:50.770 --> 04:29:54.210
Suddenly, with a loud huzzah, a little cloud of pirates

04:29:54.210 --> 04:29:58.290
leaped from the woods on the north side and ran straight on the stockade.

04:29:58.790 --> 04:30:02.530
At the same moment, the fire was once more opened from the woods, and

04:30:02.530 --> 04:30:06.550
a rifle ball sang through the doorway and knocked the doctor's musket into bits.

04:30:07.610 --> 04:30:10.270
The boarders swarmed over the fence like monkeys.

04:30:10.710 --> 04:30:13.010
Squire and Gray fired again and yet again.

04:30:13.490 --> 04:30:17.670
Three men fell, one forwards into the enclosure, two back on the outside.

04:30:18.350 --> 04:30:21.530
But of these, one was evidently more frightened than hurt, for

04:30:21.530 --> 04:30:25.330
he was on his feet again in a crack and instantly disappeared among the trees.

04:30:26.670 --> 04:30:30.310
Two had bit the dust, one had fled, four had made good their footing inside our

04:30:30.310 --> 04:30:32.690
defenses, while from the shelter of the woods,

04:30:32.690 --> 04:30:36.390
seven or eight men, each evidently supplied with several muskets,

04:30:36.630 --> 04:30:39.130
kept up a hot though useless fire on the log house.

04:30:40.070 --> 04:30:42.810
The four who had boarded made straight before them for the building,

04:30:42.990 --> 04:30:47.250
shouting as they ran, and the men among the trees shouted back to encourage them.

04:30:47.650 --> 04:30:50.950
Several shots were fired, but such was the hurry of the marksmen

04:30:50.950 --> 04:30:53.090
that not one appears to have taken effect.

04:30:53.630 --> 04:30:57.330
In a moment, the four pirates had swarmed up the mound and were upon us.

04:30:58.770 --> 04:31:02.090
The head of Job Anderson, the boatswain, appeared at the middle loophole.

04:31:02.730 --> 04:31:07.750
Adam, all hands, all hands, he roared in a voice of thunder.

04:31:08.670 --> 04:31:12.230
At the same moment, another pirate grasped Hunter's musket by the muzzle,

04:31:12.650 --> 04:31:15.270
wrenched it from his hands, plucked it through the loophole, and

04:31:15.270 --> 04:31:18.890
with one stunning blow, laid the poor fellow senseless on the floor.

04:31:19.910 --> 04:31:23.270
Meanwhile, a third, running unharmed all around the house,

04:31:23.710 --> 04:31:26.870
appeared suddenly in the doorway and fell with his cutlass on the doctor.

04:31:27.710 --> 04:31:29.390
Our position was utterly reversed.

04:31:30.050 --> 04:31:33.490
A moment since we were firing under cover at an exposed enemy,

04:31:33.870 --> 04:31:36.610
now it was we who lay uncovered and could not return a blow.

04:31:37.750 --> 04:31:41.350
The log house was full of smoke, to which we owed our comparative safety.

04:31:42.090 --> 04:31:45.670
Cries and confusion, the flashes and reports of pistol shots, and

04:31:45.670 --> 04:31:47.590
one loud groan rang in my ears.

04:31:48.110 --> 04:31:52.010
Out, lads, out and fight them in the open, cutlasses, cried the captain.

04:31:52.810 --> 04:31:56.370
I snatched a cutlass from the pile, and someone at the same time snatching

04:31:56.370 --> 04:31:59.330
another gave me a cut across the knuckles, which I hardly felt.

04:31:59.950 --> 04:32:01.910
I dashed out of the door into the clear sunlight.

04:32:02.430 --> 04:32:04.770
Someone was close behind, I knew not whom.

04:32:05.390 --> 04:32:08.510
Right in front, the doctor was pursuing his assailant down the hill,

04:32:08.810 --> 04:32:11.670
just as my eyes fell upon him, beat down his guard, and

04:32:11.670 --> 04:32:14.690
sent him sprawling on his back with a great slash across his face.

04:32:15.670 --> 04:32:19.410
Round the house, lads, round the house, cried the captain, and

04:32:19.410 --> 04:32:22.610
even in the hurly burly, I perceived a change in his voice.

04:32:23.710 --> 04:32:27.450
Mechanically I obeyed, turned eastwards, and with my cutlass raised,

04:32:27.990 --> 04:32:29.390
ran around the corner of the house.

04:32:30.010 --> 04:32:32.210
Next moment, I was face to face with Anderson.

04:32:32.750 --> 04:32:35.250
He roared aloud, and his hanger went up above his head,

04:32:35.450 --> 04:32:36.330
flashing in the sunlight.

04:32:37.150 --> 04:32:40.650
I had not time to be afraid, but as the blow still hung impending,

04:32:41.010 --> 04:32:42.790
leaped in a trice upon one side, and

04:32:42.790 --> 04:32:45.970
missing my foot in the soft sand, rolled headlong down the slope.

04:32:47.150 --> 04:32:48.890
When I had first sallied from the door,

04:32:49.050 --> 04:32:52.250
the other mutineers had been already swarming up the palisade to make

04:32:52.250 --> 04:32:53.010
an end of us.

04:32:53.590 --> 04:32:56.490
One man, in a red knight cap, with the cutlass in his mouth,

04:32:56.850 --> 04:32:59.310
had even gotten upon the top and thrown a leg across.

04:32:59.810 --> 04:33:01.490
Well, so short had been the interval,

04:33:01.730 --> 04:33:04.750
that when I found my feet again, all was in the same posture.

04:33:05.170 --> 04:33:07.530
The fellow with the red knight cap still halfway over,

04:33:07.650 --> 04:33:10.810
another still just showing his head above the top of the stockade.

04:33:11.550 --> 04:33:14.470
And yet, in this breath of time, the fight was over, and

04:33:14.470 --> 04:33:15.670
the victory was ours.

04:33:16.530 --> 04:33:20.130
Grey, following close behind me, had cut down the big boatswain,

04:33:20.130 --> 04:33:22.350
and Airy had time to recover from his last blow.

04:33:23.030 --> 04:33:26.570
Another had been shot at a loophole in the very act of firing into the house,

04:33:26.770 --> 04:33:30.050
and now lay in agony, the pistol still smoking in his hand.

04:33:30.750 --> 04:33:33.710
A third, as I had seen, the doctor had disposed of at a blow.

04:33:34.310 --> 04:33:38.090
Of the four who had scaled the palisade, only one remained unaccounted for, and

04:33:38.090 --> 04:33:40.090
he, having left his cutlass on the field,

04:33:40.370 --> 04:33:43.250
was now clambering out again with the fear of death upon him.

04:33:44.270 --> 04:33:48.830
Fire, fire from the house, cried the doctor, and you lads, back into cover.

04:33:49.710 --> 04:33:52.890
But his words were unheeded, no shot was fired, and

04:33:52.890 --> 04:33:56.450
the last boarder made good his escape and disappeared with the rest into the wood.

04:33:57.630 --> 04:34:01.090
In three seconds, nothing remained of the attacking party but the five who had

04:34:01.090 --> 04:34:04.770
fallen, four on the inside, and one on the outside of the palisade.

04:34:06.350 --> 04:34:09.450
The doctor and Grey and I ran full speed for shelter.

04:34:10.110 --> 04:34:13.370
The survivors would soon be back where they'd left their muskets, and

04:34:13.370 --> 04:34:15.590
at any moment the fire might recommence.

04:34:17.390 --> 04:34:20.470
The house was by this time somewhat cleared of smoke, and

04:34:20.470 --> 04:34:22.910
we saw at a glance the price we'd paid for victory.

04:34:23.430 --> 04:34:25.330
Hunter lay beside his loophole stunned.

04:34:26.010 --> 04:34:28.990
Joyce, by his, shot through the head, never to move again.

04:34:29.470 --> 04:34:32.170
While in the center, the squire was supporting the captain,

04:34:32.470 --> 04:34:33.630
one as pale as the other.

04:34:34.530 --> 04:34:36.910
The captain's wounded, said Mr. Trelawney.

04:34:37.810 --> 04:34:38.470
Have they run?

04:34:38.770 --> 04:34:39.790
Asked Mr. Smollett.

04:34:41.130 --> 04:34:43.670
All that could, you may be bound, returned the doctor.

04:34:43.670 --> 04:34:46.150
But there's five of them, we'll never run again.

04:34:47.750 --> 04:34:49.070
Five, cried the captain.

04:34:49.170 --> 04:34:49.830
Come, that's better.

04:34:49.930 --> 04:34:51.890
Five against three leaves us four to nine.

04:34:52.610 --> 04:34:54.350
That's better odds than we had it starting.

04:34:55.030 --> 04:34:59.350
We were seven to 19 then, we thought we were, and that's as bad to bear.

04:35:00.350 --> 04:35:02.910
The mutineers were soon only eight in number, for

04:35:02.910 --> 04:35:07.230
the man shot by Mr. Trelawney on board the schooner died the same evening of his wound.

04:35:07.730 --> 04:35:11.310
But this was, of course, not known till after by the faithful party.

04:35:31.150 --> 04:35:32.150
CHAPTER XXII.

04:35:32.330 --> 04:35:34.230
HOW MY SEA ADVENTURE BEGAN.

04:35:35.510 --> 04:35:39.630
There was no return of the mutineers, not so much as another shot out of the woods.

04:35:40.190 --> 04:35:43.530
They had got their rations for that day, as the captain put it,

04:35:43.590 --> 04:35:48.010
and we had the place to ourselves and a quiet time to overhaul the wounded and get dinner.

04:35:48.870 --> 04:35:51.350
Squire and I cooked outside in spite of the danger,

04:35:51.670 --> 04:35:54.150
and even outside we could hardly tell where we were at

04:35:54.150 --> 04:35:57.570
for the horror of the loud groans that reached us from the doctor's patients.

04:35:59.030 --> 04:36:02.670
Out of the eight men who had fallen in the action, only three still breathed,

04:36:03.410 --> 04:36:07.890
that one of the pirates who'd been shot at the loophole, Hunter and Captain Smollett,

04:36:07.890 --> 04:36:10.570
and of these the first two were as good as dead.

04:36:10.910 --> 04:36:13.550
The mutineer, indeed, died under the doctor's knife,

04:36:13.950 --> 04:36:17.850
and Hunter, do what we could, never recovered consciousness in this world.

04:36:18.530 --> 04:36:23.110
He lingered all day, breathing loudly like the old buccaneer at home in his epileptic fit,

04:36:23.910 --> 04:36:28.030
but the bones of his chest had been crushed by the blow and his skull fractured and falling,

04:36:28.450 --> 04:36:32.690
and sometime in the following night, without sign or sound, he went to his maker.

04:36:33.470 --> 04:36:37.210
As for the captain, his wounds were grievous indeed, but not dangerous.

04:36:37.210 --> 04:36:39.410
No organ was fatally injured.

04:36:40.210 --> 04:36:43.010
Anderson's ball, for it was Job that shot him first,

04:36:43.490 --> 04:36:46.590
had broken his shoulder blade and touched the lung, not badly.

04:36:47.190 --> 04:36:50.130
The second had only torn and displaced some muscles in the calf.

04:36:50.570 --> 04:36:54.810
He was sure to recover, the doctor said, but in the meantime, and for weeks to come,

04:36:55.250 --> 04:36:59.310
he must not walk or move his arm near so much as speak when he could help it.

04:36:59.590 --> 04:37:02.370
My own accidental cut across the knuckles was a flea bite.

04:37:02.950 --> 04:37:06.970
Dr. Lavesy patched it up with plaster and pulled my ears for me into the bargain.

04:37:07.710 --> 04:37:12.090
After dinner, the squire and the doctor sat by the captain's side a while in consultation,

04:37:12.630 --> 04:37:16.430
and when they talked to their hearts content, it being then a little past noon,

04:37:16.990 --> 04:37:21.670
the doctor took up his hat and pistols, girt on a cutlass, put the chart in his pocket,

04:37:22.090 --> 04:37:25.750
and with a musket over his shoulder, crossed the palisade on the north side

04:37:25.750 --> 04:37:27.530
and set off briskly through the trees.

04:37:29.330 --> 04:37:31.930
Grey and I were sitting together at the far end of the blockhouse,

04:37:31.930 --> 04:37:34.210
to be out of earshot of our officers consulting,

04:37:34.210 --> 04:37:38.530
and Grey took his pipe out of his mouth and fairly forgot to put it back in again,

04:37:38.790 --> 04:37:40.790
so thunderstruck was he at this occurrence.

04:37:41.970 --> 04:37:46.530
Why, in the name of Davy Jones, he said, is Dr. Lavesy mad?

04:37:48.030 --> 04:37:51.990
Why, no, says I, he's about the last of this crew for that, I take it.

04:37:52.630 --> 04:37:58.810
Willship me, said Grey, mad he may not be, but if he is not, you mark my words, I am.

04:37:59.310 --> 04:38:03.270
I take it, I replied, that the doctor has his idea, and if I'm right,

04:38:03.270 --> 04:38:04.970
he's going now to see Ben Gunn.

04:38:06.390 --> 04:38:10.970
I was right, as appeared later, but in the meantime, the house being stifling hot

04:38:10.970 --> 04:38:14.570
and the little patch of sand inside the palisade ablaze with midday sun,

04:38:15.230 --> 04:38:19.270
I began to get another thought into my head, which was not by any means so right.

04:38:19.850 --> 04:38:24.190
What I began to do was to envy the doctor walking in the cool shadow of the woods

04:38:24.190 --> 04:38:27.130
with the birds about him and the pleasant smell of the pines,

04:38:27.130 --> 04:38:30.130
while I sat grilling with my clothes stuck to the hot resin

04:38:30.130 --> 04:38:33.990
and so much blood about me and so many poor dead bodies lying all around,

04:38:34.070 --> 04:38:37.190
that I took a disgust of the place that was almost as strong as fear.

04:38:38.110 --> 04:38:41.690
All the time I was washing out the blockhouse and then washing up the things for dinner,

04:38:42.170 --> 04:38:46.570
this disgust and envy kept growing stronger and stronger, till at last,

04:38:46.890 --> 04:38:49.450
being near a bread bag and no one then observing me,

04:38:49.770 --> 04:38:54.450
I took the first step toward my escapade and filled both pockets of my coat with biscuit.

04:38:55.490 --> 04:38:59.830
I was a fool, if you like, and I certainly was going to do a foolish, over-bold act.

04:39:00.130 --> 04:39:03.290
But I was determined to do it, with all the precautions in my power.

04:39:03.870 --> 04:39:05.790
These biscuits, should anything befall me,

04:39:06.130 --> 04:39:09.430
would keep me at least from starving till far on in the next day.

04:39:09.970 --> 04:39:12.550
The next thing I laid hold of was a brace of pistols,

04:39:12.630 --> 04:39:17.270
and as I already had a powder horn and bullets, I felt myself well supplied with arms.

04:39:18.270 --> 04:39:22.310
As for the scheme I had in my head, it was not a bad one in itself.

04:39:22.810 --> 04:39:27.710
I was to go down the sandy spit that divides the anchorage on the east from the open sea,

04:39:27.710 --> 04:39:30.430
find the white rock I'd observed last evening,

04:39:30.790 --> 04:39:34.410
and ascertain whether it was there or not that Ben Gunn had hidden his boat,

04:39:34.770 --> 04:39:37.030
a thing quite worth doing, as I still believe.

04:39:37.890 --> 04:39:40.730
But as I was certain I should not be allowed to leave the enclosure,

04:39:41.130 --> 04:39:44.830
my only plan was to take French leave and slip out when nobody was watching,

04:39:45.210 --> 04:39:48.610
and that was so bad a way of doing it as made the thing itself wrong.

04:39:49.050 --> 04:39:51.950
But I was only a boy, and I had made my mind up.

04:39:52.790 --> 04:39:56.990
Well, as things at last fell out, I found an admirable opportunity.

04:39:56.990 --> 04:40:00.550
The squire and Grey were busy helping the captain with his bandages.

04:40:00.850 --> 04:40:01.830
The coast was clear.

04:40:02.270 --> 04:40:05.490
I made a bolt forward over the stockade and into the thickest of the trees,

04:40:05.930 --> 04:40:09.450
and before my absence was observed, I was out of cry of my companions.

04:40:10.550 --> 04:40:13.530
This was my second folly, far worse than the first,

04:40:13.870 --> 04:40:16.450
as I left but two sound men to guard the house.

04:40:17.030 --> 04:40:20.390
But like the first, it was a help towards saving all of us.

04:40:21.270 --> 04:40:23.950
I took my way straight for the east coast of the island,

04:40:23.950 --> 04:40:26.550
for I was determined to go down to the seaside of the spit

04:40:26.550 --> 04:40:29.250
to avoid all chance of observation from the anchorage.

04:40:29.830 --> 04:40:32.950
It was already late in the afternoon, though still warm and sunny.

04:40:33.530 --> 04:40:37.470
As I continued to thread the tall woods, I could hear from far before me

04:40:37.470 --> 04:40:39.650
not only the continuous thunder of the surf,

04:40:40.050 --> 04:40:42.870
but a certain tossing of foliage and grinding of boughs

04:40:42.870 --> 04:40:45.830
which showed me the sea breeze had set in higher than usual.

04:40:46.850 --> 04:40:50.550
Soon cool draughts of air began to reach me, and a few steps farther,

04:40:50.890 --> 04:40:53.250
I came forth into the open borders of the grove

04:40:53.250 --> 04:40:56.150
and saw the sea lying blue and sunny to the horizon,

04:40:56.510 --> 04:40:59.190
and the surf tumbling and tossing its foam along the beach.

04:41:00.950 --> 04:41:03.270
I have never seen the sea quiet around Treasure Island.

04:41:03.770 --> 04:41:06.750
The sun might blaze overhead, the air be without a breath,

04:41:06.970 --> 04:41:10.230
the surface smooth and blue, but still these great rollers

04:41:10.230 --> 04:41:12.810
would be running along all the external coasts,

04:41:12.930 --> 04:41:14.830
thundering and thundering by day and night,

04:41:14.910 --> 04:41:17.290
and I scarce believed there is one spot in the island

04:41:17.290 --> 04:41:19.430
where a man would be out of earshot of their noise.

04:41:20.390 --> 04:41:22.750
I walked along beside the surf with great enjoyment,

04:41:22.750 --> 04:41:25.570
till, thinking I was now got far enough to the south,

04:41:26.030 --> 04:41:27.770
I took the cover of some thick bushes

04:41:27.770 --> 04:41:30.050
and crept warily up to the ridge of the spit.

04:41:31.430 --> 04:41:34.310
Behind me was the sea, in front the anchorage.

04:41:34.850 --> 04:41:37.810
The sea breeze, as though it had the sooner blown itself out

04:41:37.810 --> 04:41:40.190
by its unusual violence, was already in an end.

04:41:40.790 --> 04:41:43.290
It had been succeeded by light, variable airs

04:41:43.290 --> 04:41:46.530
from the south and southeast, carrying great banks of fog,

04:41:46.930 --> 04:41:49.470
and the anchorage, under the lee of Skeleton Island,

04:41:49.850 --> 04:41:52.030
lay still and leaden as when we first entered it.

04:41:52.030 --> 04:41:54.510
The Hispaniola, in that unbroken mirror,

04:41:54.950 --> 04:41:57.570
was exactly portrayed from the truck to the waterline,

04:41:57.770 --> 04:41:59.690
the Jolly Roger hanging from her peak.

04:42:00.430 --> 04:42:03.290
Alongside lay one of the gigs, silver in the stern sheets,

04:42:03.450 --> 04:42:05.030
him I could always recognize,

04:42:05.490 --> 04:42:08.030
while a couple of men were leaning over the stern bulwarks,

04:42:08.650 --> 04:42:11.750
one of them with a red cap, the very rogue I'd seen some hours

04:42:11.750 --> 04:42:13.890
before stride legs upon the palisade.

04:42:14.630 --> 04:42:16.250
Apparently they were talking and laughing,

04:42:16.430 --> 04:42:18.250
though at that distance, upwards of a mile,

04:42:18.490 --> 04:42:20.650
I could of course hear no word of what was said.

04:42:20.650 --> 04:42:24.330
All at once there began the most horrid, unearthly screaming,

04:42:24.450 --> 04:42:25.950
which at first startled me badly,

04:42:26.430 --> 04:42:28.990
though I had soon remembered the voice of Captain Flint,

04:42:29.170 --> 04:42:31.970
and even thought I could make out the bird by her bright plumage,

04:42:32.130 --> 04:42:34.230
as she sat perched upon her master's wrist.

04:42:35.430 --> 04:42:38.330
Soon after, the jolly boat shoved off and pulled for shore,

04:42:38.630 --> 04:42:40.550
and the man with the red cap and his comrade

04:42:40.550 --> 04:42:42.190
went below by the cabin companion.

04:42:43.510 --> 04:42:46.670
Just about the same time, the sun had gone down behind the spyglass,

04:42:46.890 --> 04:42:48.750
and as the fog was collecting rapidly,

04:42:48.750 --> 04:42:50.490
it began to grow dark and earnest.

04:42:50.990 --> 04:42:53.870
I saw I must lose no time if I were to find the boat that evening.

04:42:54.610 --> 04:42:56.950
The white rock, visible enough above the brush,

04:42:57.370 --> 04:42:59.930
was still some eighth of a mile further down the spit,

04:43:00.170 --> 04:43:02.310
and it took me a goodish while to get up with it

04:43:02.310 --> 04:43:04.390
crawling often on all fours among the scrub.

04:43:05.210 --> 04:43:07.930
Night had almost come when I laid my hand on its rough sides.

04:43:08.550 --> 04:43:12.150
Right below it, there was an exceedingly small hollow of green turf,

04:43:12.330 --> 04:43:15.010
hidden by banks and a thick underwood about knee deep,

04:43:15.470 --> 04:43:16.830
that grew there very plentifully,

04:43:16.830 --> 04:43:19.410
and in the center of the dell, sure enough,

04:43:19.790 --> 04:43:21.170
a little tent of goatskins,

04:43:21.510 --> 04:43:23.830
like what the gypsies carry about with them in England.

04:43:24.470 --> 04:43:27.090
I dropped into the hollow, lifted the side of the tent,

04:43:27.470 --> 04:43:31.730
and there was Ben Gunn's boat, homemade if ever anything was homemade,

04:43:32.370 --> 04:43:34.870
a rude lopsided framework of tough wood,

04:43:35.390 --> 04:43:38.970
and stretched upon that a covering of goatskin with the hair inside.

04:43:39.730 --> 04:43:42.310
The thing was extremely small, even for me,

04:43:42.510 --> 04:43:45.870
and I can hardly imagine that it could have floated with a full-sized man.

04:43:45.870 --> 04:43:48.830
There was one port set as low as possible,

04:43:49.090 --> 04:43:52.430
a kind of stretcher in the bows, and a double paddle for propulsion.

04:43:53.150 --> 04:43:56.730
I had not then seen a coracle, such as the ancient Britons made,

04:43:57.030 --> 04:43:58.390
but I have seen one since,

04:43:58.570 --> 04:44:01.350
and I can give you no fairer idea of Ben Gunn's boat

04:44:01.350 --> 04:44:05.350
than by saying it was like the first and worst coracle ever made by man.

04:44:05.790 --> 04:44:08.570
But the great advantage of the coracle certainly possessed,

04:44:08.950 --> 04:44:10.950
for it was exceedingly light and portable.

04:44:12.010 --> 04:44:13.710
Well, now that I had found the boat,

04:44:13.710 --> 04:44:16.350
you would have thought I'd had enough of truantry for once.

04:44:16.930 --> 04:44:19.590
But in the meantime, I had taken another notion,

04:44:19.790 --> 04:44:23.290
and become so obstinately fond of it, that I would have carried it out,

04:44:23.350 --> 04:44:25.650
I believe, in the teeth of Captain Smollett himself.

04:44:26.350 --> 04:44:30.990
This was to slip out under cover of night, cut the Hispaniola adrift,

04:44:31.230 --> 04:44:33.030
and let her go ashore where she fancied.

04:44:33.350 --> 04:44:35.550
I had quite made up my mind that the mutineers,

04:44:35.610 --> 04:44:38.790
after their repulse of the morning, had nothing nearer their hearts

04:44:38.790 --> 04:44:40.650
than to up anchor and away to sea.

04:44:41.110 --> 04:44:43.850
This, I thought, it would be a fine thing to prevent.

04:44:44.390 --> 04:44:46.950
And now that I had seen how they left their watchmen

04:44:46.950 --> 04:44:50.410
unprovided with a boat, I thought it might be done with a little risk.

04:44:51.810 --> 04:44:54.990
Down I sat to wait for darkness, and made a hearty meal of biscuit.

04:44:55.670 --> 04:44:58.210
It was a night out of ten thousand for my purpose.

04:44:58.570 --> 04:45:00.570
The fog had now buried all heaven.

04:45:00.970 --> 04:45:03.430
As the last rays of daylight dwindled and disappeared,

04:45:04.450 --> 04:45:06.790
absolute blackness settled down on Treasure Island.

04:45:07.430 --> 04:45:09.770
And when at last I shouldered the coracle,

04:45:09.850 --> 04:45:13.130
and groped my way stumblingly out of the hollow where I had supped,

04:45:13.390 --> 04:45:16.250
there were but two points visible on the whole anchorage.

04:45:17.090 --> 04:45:18.950
One was the great fire on shore,

04:45:19.310 --> 04:45:22.150
by which the defeated pirates lay carousing in the swamp.

04:45:22.890 --> 04:45:25.390
The other, a mere blur of light upon the darkness,

04:45:25.950 --> 04:45:27.850
indicated the position of the anchored ship.

04:45:28.110 --> 04:45:30.150
She had swung round to the ebb.

04:45:30.250 --> 04:45:31.490
Her bow was now toward me.

04:45:31.490 --> 04:45:33.610
The only lights on board were in the cabin,

04:45:33.610 --> 04:45:36.570
and what I saw was merely a reflection on the fog

04:45:36.570 --> 04:45:39.270
of the strong rays that flowed from the stern window.

04:45:40.010 --> 04:45:41.690
The ebb had already run some time,

04:45:41.850 --> 04:45:44.490
and I had to wade through a long belt of swampy sand,

04:45:44.930 --> 04:45:46.690
where I sank several times above the ankle

04:45:46.690 --> 04:45:48.810
before I came to the edge of the retreating water.

04:45:49.310 --> 04:45:52.250
And wading a little way in, with some strength and dexterity,

04:45:52.570 --> 04:45:55.170
set my coracle keel downwards on the surface.

04:46:00.690 --> 04:46:02.710
November 5, 2005

04:46:32.150 --> 04:46:33.550
XXIII.

04:46:33.550 --> 04:46:37.250
The Ebb Tide Runs.

04:46:37.830 --> 04:46:43.150
The coracle, as I had ample reason to know before I was done with her, was a very safe

04:46:43.150 --> 04:46:48.470
boat for a person of my height and weight, both buoyant and clever in a sea-way.

04:46:49.070 --> 04:46:53.330
But she was the most cross-grained, lop-sided craft to manage.

04:46:54.450 --> 04:47:00.070
Do as you please, she always made more leeway than anything else, and turning round and

04:47:00.070 --> 04:47:03.010
the maneuver she was best at.

04:47:03.950 --> 04:47:09.910
Even Ben Gunn himself has admitted that she was queer to handle till you knew her way.

04:47:10.890 --> 04:47:12.910
Certainly, I did not know her way.

04:47:13.110 --> 04:47:16.490
She turned in every direction but the one I was bound to go.

04:47:17.170 --> 04:47:22.830
The most part of the time we were broadside on, and I am very sure I never should have

04:47:22.830 --> 04:47:24.710
made the ship at all but for the tide.

04:47:25.290 --> 04:47:28.010
By good fortune, paddle as I please.

04:47:28.450 --> 04:47:35.690
The tide was still sweeping me down, and there lay the Hispaniola right in the fairway, hardly

04:47:35.690 --> 04:47:36.770
to be missed.

04:47:37.470 --> 04:47:42.230
First, she loomed before me like a blot of something yet blacker than darkness.

04:47:42.730 --> 04:47:48.630
Then her spars and hull began to take shape, and the next moment, as it seemed, for the

04:47:48.630 --> 04:47:53.810
further I went the brisker grew the current of the ebb, I was alongside of her hauser

04:47:53.810 --> 04:47:55.250
and had laid hold.

04:47:56.730 --> 04:48:01.910
The hauser was as taut as a bowstring, and the current so strong she pulled upon her

04:48:01.910 --> 04:48:02.230
anchor.

04:48:03.090 --> 04:48:08.950
All round the hull in the blackness the rippling current bubbled and chattered like a little

04:48:08.950 --> 04:48:09.970
mountain stream.

04:48:10.990 --> 04:48:15.410
One cut with my seagully and the Hispaniola would go humming down the tide.

04:48:16.330 --> 04:48:22.410
So far so good, but it next occurred to my recollection that a taut hauser suddenly cut

04:48:22.410 --> 04:48:25.310
his a thing as dangerous as a kicking horse.

04:48:25.950 --> 04:48:31.610
Ten to one, if I were so foolhardy as to cut the Hispaniola from her anchor, I and the

04:48:31.610 --> 04:48:33.990
coracle would be knocked clean out of the water.

04:48:34.710 --> 04:48:41.010
This brought me to a full stop, and if fortune had not again particularly favored me, I should

04:48:41.010 --> 04:48:42.730
have had to abandon my design.

04:48:43.530 --> 04:48:48.510
But the light airs which had begun blowing from the south east and south had hauled round

04:48:48.510 --> 04:48:50.610
after nightfall into the south west.

04:48:51.370 --> 04:48:57.310
Just while I was meditating a puff came, caught the Hispaniola and forced her up into the

04:48:57.310 --> 04:49:04.250
current, and to my great joy I felt the hauser slacken in my grasp, and the hand by which

04:49:04.250 --> 04:49:07.450
I held it dip for a second under water.

04:49:08.470 --> 04:49:14.850
With that I made my mind up, took out my gully, opened it with my teeth, and cut one strand

04:49:14.850 --> 04:49:18.210
after another till the vessel swung only by two.

04:49:18.950 --> 04:49:24.430
Then I lay quiet, waiting to sever these last when the strain should be once more lightened

04:49:24.430 --> 04:49:25.750
by a breath of wind.

04:49:26.690 --> 04:49:34.230
All this time I hooded the sound of loud voices from the cavern, but to say truth, my mind

04:49:34.230 --> 04:49:38.730
had been so entirely taken up with other thoughts that I had scarcely given ear.

04:49:39.630 --> 04:49:43.910
Now, however, when I had nothing else to do I began to pay more heed.

04:49:44.510 --> 04:49:50.270
One I recognized for the coxswain's Israel hands that had been flint's gunner in former

04:49:50.270 --> 04:49:54.630
days, the other was of course my friend of the red nightcap.

04:49:55.290 --> 04:50:00.270
Both men were plainly the worse for drink, and they were still drinking, for even while

04:50:00.270 --> 04:50:05.390
I was listening one of them with a drunken cry opened the stern window and threw out

04:50:05.390 --> 04:50:07.910
something which I defined to be an empty bottle.

04:50:08.350 --> 04:50:13.290
But they were not only tipsy, it was plain that they were furiously angry.

04:50:14.250 --> 04:50:19.010
Oaths flew like hailstones, and every now and then there came forth such an explosion,

04:50:19.370 --> 04:50:22.290
as I thought was sure to end in blows.

04:50:22.790 --> 04:50:27.730
But each time the quarrel passed off and the voices grumbled lower for a while until the

04:50:27.730 --> 04:50:31.910
next crisis came, and in its turn passed away without result.

04:50:32.610 --> 04:50:38.390
On shore I could see the glow of the great campfire burning warmly through the shore-side

04:50:38.390 --> 04:50:39.090
trees.

04:50:40.190 --> 04:50:46.310
Someone was singing a dull old droning sailor's song with a droop and a quaver at the end

04:50:46.310 --> 04:50:51.950
of every verse, and seemingly no end to it at all but the patience of the singer.

04:50:52.810 --> 04:51:01.890
I heard it on the voyages more than once and remembered these words, but one man of her

04:51:01.890 --> 04:51:08.090
And I thought it was a ditty rather too dolefully appropriate for a company that had met such

04:51:08.090 --> 04:51:09.890
cruel losses in the morning.

04:51:10.490 --> 04:51:17.130
But indeed from what I saw all these buccaneers were as callous as the seas they sailed on.

04:51:18.190 --> 04:51:23.330
At last the breeze came, the schooner sidled and drew nearest in the dark.

04:51:23.830 --> 04:51:29.890
I felt the hauser slacken once more and with a good tough effort cut the last fibres through.

04:51:30.510 --> 04:51:37.090
The breeze had but little action on the coracle, and I was almost instantly swept against the

04:51:37.090 --> 04:51:38.450
bows of the Hispaniola.

04:51:38.910 --> 04:51:45.090
At the same time the schooner began to turn upon her heel, spinning slowly end for end

04:51:45.090 --> 04:51:46.270
across the current.

04:51:47.310 --> 04:51:53.070
I wrought like a fiend, for I expected every moment to be swamped, and since I found I

04:51:53.070 --> 04:51:57.570
could not push the coracle directly off I now shoved straight astern.

04:51:57.570 --> 04:52:03.870
At length I was clear of my dangerous neighbour, and just as I gave the last impulsion my hands

04:52:03.870 --> 04:52:08.970
came across a light cord that was trailing overboard across the stern bulwarks.

04:52:09.610 --> 04:52:11.330
Instantly I grasped it.

04:52:11.670 --> 04:52:14.350
Why I should have done so I can hardly say.

04:52:15.230 --> 04:52:20.730
It was at first mere instinct, but once I had it in my hands and found it fast curiosity

04:52:20.730 --> 04:52:25.590
began to get the upper hand and I determined I should have one look through the cabin window.

04:52:26.450 --> 04:52:32.390
I pulled in hand over hand on the cord and when I judged myself near enough rose at infinite

04:52:32.390 --> 04:52:38.090
risk to about half my height and thus commanded the roof and a slice of the interior of the

04:52:38.090 --> 04:52:38.430
cabin.

04:52:39.550 --> 04:52:44.590
By this time the schooner and her little consort were gliding pretty swiftly through the water.

04:52:44.930 --> 04:52:48.190
Indeed we had already fetched up level with the campfire.

04:52:49.010 --> 04:52:55.270
The ship was talking, as sailors say loudly, treading the innumerable ripples with an incessant

04:52:55.270 --> 04:53:00.710
weltering splash, and until I got my eye above the windowsill I could not comprehend why

04:53:00.710 --> 04:53:02.430
the watchman had taken no alarm.

04:53:03.390 --> 04:53:08.090
One glance, however, was sufficient, and it was only one glance that I durst take from

04:53:08.090 --> 04:53:09.550
that unsteady skiff.

04:53:09.910 --> 04:53:16.210
It showed me hands and his companions locked together in deadly wrestle, each with a hand

04:53:16.210 --> 04:53:17.330
upon the other's throat.

04:53:18.210 --> 04:53:22.570
I dropped upon the thwart again, none too soon, for I was near overboard.

04:53:22.570 --> 04:53:27.830
I could see nothing for the moment but these two furious and crimson faces swaying together

04:53:27.830 --> 04:53:32.890
under the smoky lamp, and I shut my eyes to let them grow once more familiar with the

04:53:32.890 --> 04:53:33.330
darkness.

04:53:34.330 --> 04:53:38.630
The endless ballad had come to an end at last, and the whole diminished company about the

04:53:38.630 --> 04:53:42.090
campfire had broken into the chorus I had heard so often.

04:53:42.950 --> 04:53:49.610
Fifteen men on a dead man's chest, yo ho ho and a bottle of rum, drink in the devil

04:53:49.610 --> 04:53:54.170
had done for the rest, yo ho ho and a bottle of rum.

04:53:55.170 --> 04:53:59.590
I was just thinking how busy drink and the devil were at that very moment in the cabin

04:53:59.590 --> 04:54:03.850
of the Hispaniola when I was surprised by a sudden lurch of the coracle.

04:54:04.650 --> 04:54:08.610
At the same moment she yawed sharply and seemed to change her course.

04:54:09.190 --> 04:54:11.810
The speed in the meantime had strangely increased.

04:54:12.930 --> 04:54:18.350
I opened my eyes at once, all around me were little ripples, combing over with a sharp

04:54:18.350 --> 04:54:21.450
bristling sound and slight phosphorescence.

04:54:21.970 --> 04:54:28.010
The Hispaniola herself, a few yards in whose wake I was still being whirled along, seemed

04:54:28.010 --> 04:54:33.130
to stagger in her course, and I saw her spars toss a little against the blackness of the

04:54:33.130 --> 04:54:33.390
night.

04:54:34.190 --> 04:54:38.770
Nay, as I looked longer I made sure she was also wheeling to the southward.

04:54:39.510 --> 04:54:43.130
I glanced over my shoulder and my heart jumped against my ribs.

04:54:43.630 --> 04:54:47.130
There right behind me was the glow of the campfire.

04:54:47.470 --> 04:54:52.730
The current had turned at right angles, sweeping round along with it the tall schooner and

04:54:52.730 --> 04:54:54.350
the little dancing coracle.

04:54:54.930 --> 04:55:00.230
Ever quickening, ever bubbling higher, ever muttering louder it went spinning through

04:55:00.230 --> 04:55:01.990
the narrows for the open sea.

04:55:02.930 --> 04:55:08.330
Suddenly the schooner in front of me gave a violent yaw, turning perhaps through twenty

04:55:08.330 --> 04:55:13.430
degrees and almost at the same moment one shout followed another from on board.

04:55:13.910 --> 04:55:19.830
I could hear feet pounding on the companion ladder and I knew that the two drunkards had

04:55:19.830 --> 04:55:25.210
last been interrupted in their quarrel and awakened to a sense of their disaster.

04:55:25.650 --> 04:55:30.570
I lay down flat in the bottom of that wretched skiff and devoutly recommended my spirit to

04:55:30.570 --> 04:55:31.070
its maker.

04:55:31.570 --> 04:55:37.030
At the end of the straights I made sure we must fall off into some bar of raging breakers

04:55:37.030 --> 04:55:43.410
where all my troubles would be ended speedily, and though I could perhaps bear to die I could

04:55:43.410 --> 04:55:46.370
not bear to look upon my fate as it approached.

04:55:47.410 --> 04:55:53.130
So I must have lain for hours, continually beaten to a fro upon the billows, now and

04:55:53.130 --> 04:55:59.070
again wetted with flying sprays, and never ceasing to expect a death at the next plunge.

04:56:00.150 --> 04:56:06.870
Gradually weariness grew upon me, a numbness, an occasional stupor fell upon my mind even

04:56:06.870 --> 04:56:13.730
in the midst of my terrors, until sleep at last supervened, and in my sea-tossed coracle

04:56:13.730 --> 04:56:18.890
I lay and dreamed of Holm and the old Admiral Benbow.

04:56:22.730 --> 04:56:24.350
Chapter twenty-four

04:56:24.350 --> 04:56:26.370
The Cruise of the Coracle

04:56:27.770 --> 04:56:32.590
It was broad day when I awoke and found myself tossing at the south-west end of Treasure

04:56:33.230 --> 04:56:39.190
The sun was up, but was still hid from me behind the great bulk of the spy-glass, which

04:56:39.190 --> 04:56:43.410
on this side descended almost to the sea in formidable cliffs.

04:56:45.090 --> 04:56:50.910
Hall-bowl and head and mizzen-mast hill were at my elbow, the hill bare and dark, the head,

04:56:51.410 --> 04:56:57.270
bound with cliffs forty or fifty feet high and fringed with great masses of fallen rock.

04:56:57.810 --> 04:57:03.070
I was scarce a quarter of a mile to seaward, and it was my first thought to paddle in and

04:57:03.070 --> 04:57:03.350
land.

04:57:04.010 --> 04:57:05.890
The notion was soon given over.

04:57:06.370 --> 04:57:12.690
Among the fallen rocks the breakers spouted and bellowed, loud reverberations, heavy sprays

04:57:12.690 --> 04:57:16.250
flying and falling succeeded one another from second to second.

04:57:16.950 --> 04:57:23.330
And I saw myself, if I ventured nearer, dashed to death upon the rough shore, or, spending

04:57:23.330 --> 04:57:27.310
my strength in vain, to scale the beetling crags.

04:57:28.190 --> 04:57:32.910
Nor was that all, for crawling together on the flat tables of rock, or letting themselves

04:57:32.910 --> 04:57:41.670
drop into the sea with loud reports, I beheld huge, slimy monsters, soft snails, as it were,

04:57:41.690 --> 04:57:47.330
of incredible bigness, two or three score of them together, making the rocks to echo

04:57:47.330 --> 04:57:48.590
with their barkings.

04:57:49.370 --> 04:57:54.410
I have understood since that they were sea lions and entirely harmless, but the look

04:57:54.410 --> 04:57:59.830
of them added to the difficulty of the shore and the high running of the surf was more

04:57:59.830 --> 04:58:02.350
than enough to disgust me of that landing place.

04:58:03.370 --> 04:58:07.310
I felt willing rather to starve at sea than to confront such perils.

04:58:08.370 --> 04:58:11.930
In the meantime I had a better chance, as I supposed, before me.

04:58:12.830 --> 04:58:18.350
North of Hall Bowlin Head the land runs in a long way, leaving at low tide a long stretch

04:58:18.350 --> 04:58:19.230
of yellow sand.

04:58:19.670 --> 04:58:24.370
To the north of that again there comes another cape, cape of the woods as it was marked

04:58:24.370 --> 04:58:29.670
upon the chart, buried in tall green pines which descended to the margin of the sea.

04:58:30.710 --> 04:58:35.070
I remembered what Silver had said about the current that sets northward along the whole

04:58:35.070 --> 04:58:39.410
west coast of Treasure Island, and seeing from my position that I was already under

04:58:39.410 --> 04:58:44.770
its influence, I preferred to leave Hall Bowlin Head behind me and reserve my strength for

04:58:44.770 --> 04:58:48.470
an attempt to land upon the kindlier looking cape of the woods.

04:58:49.410 --> 04:58:55.070
There was a great smooth swell upon the sea, the wind blowing steadily and gently from

04:58:55.070 --> 04:58:55.610
the south.

04:58:55.950 --> 04:59:02.250
There was no contrarity between that and the current, and the billows rose and fell unbroken.

04:59:03.230 --> 04:59:06.190
Had it been otherwise I must long ago have perished.

04:59:06.430 --> 04:59:12.770
But as it was, it was surprising how easily and securely my little and light boat could

04:59:13.370 --> 04:59:18.930
Often, as I still lay at the bottom and kept no more than an eye above the gunwale, I would

04:59:18.930 --> 04:59:22.170
see a big blue summit heaving close above me.

04:59:22.690 --> 04:59:27.670
Yet the coracle would but bounce a little, dance as if on springs and subside on the

04:59:27.670 --> 04:59:30.470
other side into the trough as lightly as a bird.

04:59:31.930 --> 04:59:36.870
I began after a little to grow very bold and sat up to try my skill at paddling.

04:59:37.470 --> 04:59:42.990
But even a small change in the disposition of the weight would produce violent changes

04:59:42.990 --> 04:59:48.610
in the behavior of a coracle, and I had hardly moved before the boat, giving up at once her

04:59:48.610 --> 04:59:53.830
gentle dancing movement ran straight down a slope of water so steep that it made me

04:59:53.830 --> 04:59:59.210
giddy and struck her nose with a spout of spray deep into the side of the next wave.

05:00:00.750 --> 05:00:06.850
I was drenched and terrified, and fell instantly back into my old position whereupon the coracle

05:00:06.850 --> 05:00:11.670
seemed to find her head again and led me as softly as before among the billows.

05:00:12.090 --> 05:00:16.710
It was plain she was not to be interfered with, and at that rate, since I could no way

05:00:16.710 --> 05:00:20.770
influence her course, what hope had I left of reaching land?

05:00:21.730 --> 05:00:25.550
I began to be horribly frightened, but I kept my head for all of that.

05:00:26.410 --> 05:00:30.470
First moving with all care, I gradually bailed out the coracle with my sea cap.

05:00:31.550 --> 05:00:37.390
Then, getting my eye once more above the gunnel, I set myself to study how it was she managed

05:00:37.390 --> 05:00:39.730
to slip so quietly through the rollers.

05:00:40.690 --> 05:00:46.130
I found each wave, instead of the big smooth glossy mountain it looks from the shore or

05:00:46.130 --> 05:00:52.350
from the vessel's deck, was for all the world like any range of hills on dry land, full

05:00:52.350 --> 05:00:54.850
of peaks and smooth places and valleys.

05:00:55.550 --> 05:01:00.710
The coracle, left to herself, turning from side to side, threaded, so to speak, her way

05:01:00.710 --> 05:01:05.250
through these lower parts and avoided the steep slopes and higher, toppling summits

05:01:05.250 --> 05:01:06.010
of the wave.

05:01:06.950 --> 05:01:12.590
Well now, thought I to myself, it is plain I must lie where I am and not disturb the

05:01:12.590 --> 05:01:17.130
balance, but it is plain also that I can put the paddle over the side and from time to

05:01:17.130 --> 05:01:21.030
time in smooth places give her a shove or two towards the land.

05:01:21.710 --> 05:01:23.890
No sooner thought upon than done.

05:01:24.550 --> 05:01:29.490
There I lay on my elbows in the most trying attitude and every now and again gave a weak

05:01:29.490 --> 05:01:32.450
stroke or two to turn her head towards shore.

05:01:33.510 --> 05:01:39.530
It was very tiring and slow work, yet I did visibly gain ground and as we neared the Cape

05:01:39.530 --> 05:01:46.210
of the Woods, though I saw I must infallibly miss that point, I had still made some hundred

05:01:46.210 --> 05:01:47.710
yards of isting.

05:01:48.230 --> 05:01:49.910
I was indeed close in.

05:01:50.430 --> 05:01:55.830
I could see the cool green tree tops swaying together in the breeze, and I felt sure I

05:01:55.830 --> 05:01:58.270
should make the next promontory without fail.

05:01:59.330 --> 05:02:03.430
It was high time, for I now began to be tortured with thirst.

05:02:04.110 --> 05:02:09.950
The glow of the sun from above, its thousand-fold reflections from the waves, the sea water

05:02:09.950 --> 05:02:15.470
that fell and dried upon me, caking my very lips with salt combined to make my throat

05:02:15.470 --> 05:02:17.690
burn and my brain ache.

05:02:18.650 --> 05:02:23.470
The sight of the trees so near at hand had almost made me sick with longing, but the

05:02:23.470 --> 05:02:28.370
current had soon carried me past the point, and as the next reach of sea opened out I

05:02:28.370 --> 05:02:31.810
beheld a sight that changed the nature of my thoughts.

05:02:32.770 --> 05:02:38.250
Right in front of me, not a half a mile away, I beheld the Hispaniola under sail.

05:02:38.990 --> 05:02:44.530
I made sure, of course, that I should be taken, but I was so distressed for want of water

05:02:44.530 --> 05:02:49.750
that I scarce knew whether to be glad or sorry at the thought, and long before I had come

05:02:49.750 --> 05:02:55.910
to a conclusion, surprise had taken entire possession of my mind, and I could do nothing

05:02:55.910 --> 05:02:57.950
but stare and wonder.

05:02:59.470 --> 05:03:05.130
The Hispaniola was under her mainsail, and two jibs, and the beautiful white canvas shone

05:03:05.130 --> 05:03:07.610
in the sun like snow or silver.

05:03:08.370 --> 05:03:13.310
When I first sighted her, all her sails were drawing, and she was laying a course about

05:03:13.310 --> 05:03:17.470
north-west, and I presumed the men on board were going around the island on their way

05:03:17.470 --> 05:03:18.730
back to the anchorage.

05:03:19.430 --> 05:03:24.030
Presently, she began to fetch more and more to the westward, so that I thought they had

05:03:24.030 --> 05:03:25.930
sighted me and were going about in chase.

05:03:26.910 --> 05:03:32.250
At last, however, she fell right into the wind's eye, was taken dead aback, and stood

05:03:32.250 --> 05:03:34.990
there while helpless with her sails shivering.

05:03:36.310 --> 05:03:42.550
Clumsy fellow, said I, they must still be as drunk as owls, and I thought how Captain

05:03:42.550 --> 05:03:44.390
Smollett would have sent them skipping.

05:03:45.390 --> 05:03:50.830
Meanwhile, the schooner gradually fell off, and filled again upon another tact, sailed

05:03:50.830 --> 05:03:56.070
swiftly for a minute or so, and brought up once more dead in the wind's eye.

05:03:56.950 --> 05:04:03.090
Again and again this was repeated, to and fro, up and down, north, south, east and west,

05:04:03.570 --> 05:04:09.330
the Hispaniola sailed by swoops and dashes, and at each repetition ended as she had begun

05:04:09.330 --> 05:04:11.210
with idly flapping canvas.

05:04:11.810 --> 05:04:17.990
It became plain to me that nobody was steering, and if so, where were the men?

05:04:18.730 --> 05:04:23.630
Either they were dead drunk, or had deserted her, I thought, and perhaps, if I could get

05:04:23.630 --> 05:04:26.430
on board, I might return the vessel to her captain.

05:04:27.470 --> 05:04:32.410
The current was bearing coracle and schooner, suffered at an equal rate.

05:04:33.150 --> 05:04:38.610
As for the latter's sailing, it was so wild and intermittent, and she hung each time so

05:04:38.610 --> 05:04:44.930
long in irons that she certainly gained nothing, if she did not even lose.

05:04:45.790 --> 05:04:50.150
If I only dared to sit up and paddle, I made sure that I could overhaul her.

05:04:50.590 --> 05:04:55.310
The scheme had an air of an adventure that inspired me, and the thought of the water-breaker

05:04:55.310 --> 05:04:59.010
inside the four companion doubled my growing courage.

05:05:00.010 --> 05:05:05.350
Up I got, was welcomed almost instantly by another cloud of spray, but this time stuck

05:05:05.350 --> 05:05:11.350
to my purpose, and met myself with all my strength and caution, to paddle after the

05:05:11.350 --> 05:05:12.810
unsteered Hispaniola.

05:05:13.710 --> 05:05:19.030
Once I shipped a sea so heavy that I had to stop and bail, with my heart fluttering like

05:05:19.030 --> 05:05:19.610
a bird.

05:05:20.030 --> 05:05:24.810
But gradually I got into the way of the thing, and guided my coracle among the waves, with

05:05:24.810 --> 05:05:29.430
only now and then a blow upon her bows and a dash of foam in my face.

05:05:29.810 --> 05:05:32.450
I was now gaining rapidly on the schooner.

05:05:32.450 --> 05:05:38.630
I could see the brass glisten on the tiller as it banged about, and still no soul appeared

05:05:38.630 --> 05:05:39.570
upon her decks.

05:05:40.230 --> 05:05:42.950
I could not choose but suppose she was deserted.

05:05:43.670 --> 05:05:48.490
If not, then the men were lying drunk below, where I might batten them down, perhaps, and

05:05:48.490 --> 05:05:50.030
do what I chose with the ship.

05:05:50.890 --> 05:05:55.630
For some time she had been doing the worst thing possible for me, standing still.

05:05:56.150 --> 05:05:59.890
She headed nearly due south, yawing, of course, all the time.

05:06:00.430 --> 05:06:05.390
Each time she fell off, her sails partly filled, and these brought her in a moment right to

05:06:05.390 --> 05:06:06.110
the wind again.

05:06:06.970 --> 05:06:11.190
I have said this was the worst possible thing for me, for helpless as she looked in this

05:06:11.190 --> 05:06:16.690
situation with the canvas cracking like cannons and the blocks tundling and banging on the

05:06:16.690 --> 05:06:21.950
deck, she still continued to run away from me, not only with the speed of the current,

05:06:22.510 --> 05:06:26.010
but by the whole amount of her leeway, which was naturally great.

05:06:26.690 --> 05:06:28.750
But now, at last, I had my chance.

05:06:29.190 --> 05:06:35.230
The breeze fell for some seconds, very low, and the current gradually turning her, the

05:06:35.230 --> 05:06:40.930
Hispaniola revolved slowly round her center and at last presented me her stern, with the

05:06:40.930 --> 05:06:46.330
cabin window still gaping open and the lamp over the table still burning on into the day.

05:06:47.130 --> 05:06:49.410
The mainsail hung drooped like a banner.

05:06:49.910 --> 05:06:51.950
She was stock still but for the current.

05:06:52.910 --> 05:06:58.110
For the last little while I had even lost, but now, redoubling my efforts, I began once

05:06:58.110 --> 05:06:59.710
more to overhaul the chase.

05:07:00.670 --> 05:07:02.390
I was not a hundred yards from her.

05:07:03.610 --> 05:07:08.890
When the wind came up again in the clap, she filled on the port tack and was off again,

05:07:09.090 --> 05:07:10.690
stooping and skimming like a swallow.

05:07:11.530 --> 05:07:15.150
My first impulse was one of despair, but my second was towards joy.

05:07:15.630 --> 05:07:21.110
She came round till she was broadside on to me, round still till she had covered a half

05:07:21.110 --> 05:07:25.390
and then two thirds and then three quarters of the distance that separated us.

05:07:25.390 --> 05:07:29.030
I could see the waves boiling white under her forefoot.

05:07:29.530 --> 05:07:33.150
Immensely tall, she looked to me from my low station in the coracle.

05:07:34.250 --> 05:07:37.350
And then, of a sudden, I began to comprehend.

05:07:38.290 --> 05:07:42.270
I had scarce time to think, scarce time to act and save myself.

05:07:42.850 --> 05:07:46.770
I was on the summit of one swell when the schooner came stooping over the next.

05:07:47.210 --> 05:07:48.930
The bowsprint was over my head.

05:07:49.250 --> 05:07:52.790
I sprang to my feet and leaped, stamping the coracle under water.

05:07:53.090 --> 05:07:57.810
With one hand I caught the jib boom while my foot was lodged between the stay and the

05:07:57.810 --> 05:07:58.110
brace.

05:07:58.690 --> 05:08:04.290
And as I still clung there panting, a dull blow told me that the schooner had charged

05:08:04.290 --> 05:08:07.030
down upon and struck the coracle.

05:08:07.590 --> 05:08:11.010
And I was left without retreat on the Hispaniola.

05:08:35.730 --> 05:08:37.710
CHAPTER XXV.

05:08:38.350 --> 05:08:40.630
I STRIKE THE JOLLY ROGER.

05:08:42.050 --> 05:08:48.830
I had scarce gained a position on the bowsprit, when the flying jib flapped and filled upon

05:08:48.830 --> 05:08:51.690
the other tack, with a report like a gun.

05:08:52.370 --> 05:08:57.950
The schooner trembled to her keel under the reverse, but next moment, the other sails

05:08:57.950 --> 05:09:01.610
still drawing, the jib flapped back again and hung idle.

05:09:02.730 --> 05:09:08.570
This had nearly tossed me off into the sea, and now I lost no time, crawled back along

05:09:08.570 --> 05:09:11.970
the bowsprit, and tumbled head foremost on the deck.

05:09:13.070 --> 05:09:18.270
I was on the lee side of the forecastle, and the mainsail, which was still drawing,

05:09:18.890 --> 05:09:22.070
concealed from me a certain portion of the afterdeck.

05:09:22.290 --> 05:09:23.990
Not a soul was to be seen.

05:09:24.610 --> 05:09:31.050
The planks, which had not been swabbed since the mutiny, bore the print of many feet, and

05:09:31.050 --> 05:09:36.990
an empty bottle, broken by the neck, tumbled to and fro like a live thing in the scuppers.

05:09:38.870 --> 05:09:42.450
Suddenly the Hispaniola came right into the wind.

05:09:43.070 --> 05:09:50.450
The jibs behind me cracked aloud, the rudder slammed too, the whole ship gave a sickening

05:09:50.450 --> 05:09:57.470
heave and shudder, and at the same moment the main boom swung inboard, the sheet groaning

05:09:57.470 --> 05:10:00.970
the blocks, and showed me the lee afterdeck.

05:10:01.990 --> 05:10:08.430
There were the two watchmen, sure enough, red cap on his back, as stiff as a hand-spike,

05:10:08.670 --> 05:10:13.090
with his arms stretched out like those of a crucifix and his teeth showing through his

05:10:13.090 --> 05:10:26.950
open lips, Israel hands propped against the bulwarks, his chin on his chest, his hands

05:10:28.210 --> 05:10:35.410
For a while the ship kept bucking and sidling, like a vicious horse, the sails filling, now

05:10:35.410 --> 05:10:42.510
on one tack, now on another, and the boom swinging to and fro, till the mast roamed

05:10:42.510 --> 05:10:43.790
aloud under the strain.

05:10:45.150 --> 05:10:51.730
Now and again, too, there would come a cloud of light sprays over the bulwark, and a heavy

05:10:51.730 --> 05:10:54.290
of the ship's bows against the swell.

05:10:55.030 --> 05:11:01.030
So much heavier weather was made of it by this great-rigged ship than by my home-made

05:11:01.030 --> 05:11:04.490
lopsided coracle, now gone to the bottom of the sea.

05:11:06.150 --> 05:11:14.130
At every jump of the schooner red cap slipped to and fro, but what was ghastly to behold,

05:11:14.130 --> 05:11:23.530
Neither his attitude nor his fixed-teeth-disclosing grin was anyway disturbed by this rough usage.

05:11:24.830 --> 05:11:31.790
At every jump, too, hands appeared still more to sink into himself and settle down upon

05:11:31.790 --> 05:11:38.990
the deck, his feet sliding ever the farther out, and the whole body canting towards the

05:11:38.990 --> 05:11:45.270
so that his face became, little by little, hid from me, and at last I could see nothing

05:11:45.270 --> 05:11:49.430
beyond his ear and the frayed ringlet of one whisker.

05:11:50.310 --> 05:11:56.630
At the same time I observed, around both of them, splashes of dark blood upon the planks,

05:11:57.070 --> 05:12:01.030
and began to feel sure that they had killed each other in their drunken wrath.

05:12:02.450 --> 05:12:08.590
While I was thus looking and wondering in a calm moment, when the ship was still, Israel

05:12:08.590 --> 05:12:15.730
hands turned partly round, and with a low moan writhed himself back to the position

05:12:15.730 --> 05:12:17.290
in which I had seen him first.

05:12:18.190 --> 05:12:25.630
The moan, which told of pain and deadly weakness, and the way in which his jaw hung open, went

05:12:25.630 --> 05:12:26.710
right to my heart.

05:12:27.190 --> 05:12:33.170
But when I remembered the talk I had overheard from the apple-barrel, all pity left me.

05:12:34.490 --> 05:12:37.750
I walked aft until I reached the main mast.

05:12:39.070 --> 05:12:43.250
"'Come aboard, Mr. Hands,' I said ironically.

05:12:44.030 --> 05:12:49.670
He rolled his eyes round heavily, but he was too far gone to express surprise.

05:12:50.670 --> 05:12:56.470
All he could do was to utter one word, "'Brandy!'

05:12:56.970 --> 05:13:03.030
It occurred to me there was no time to lose, and dodging the boom as it once more lurched

05:13:03.030 --> 05:13:08.590
across the deck, I slipped aft and down the companion stairs into the cabin.

05:13:09.710 --> 05:13:13.630
It was such a scene of confusion as you can hardly fancy.

05:13:14.690 --> 05:13:19.350
All the lock-fast places had been broken open in the quest of the chart.

05:13:20.290 --> 05:13:27.610
The floor was thick with mud where ruffians had sat down to drink or consult after wading

05:13:27.610 --> 05:13:29.410
in the marshes round their camp.

05:13:30.130 --> 05:13:37.870
The bulkheads, all painted in clear white and beaded round with gilt, bore a pattern

05:13:37.870 --> 05:13:39.310
of dirty hands.

05:13:40.070 --> 05:13:45.070
Dozens of empty bottles clinked together in corners to the rolling of the ship.

05:13:46.010 --> 05:13:50.970
One of the doctor's medical books lay open on the table, half of the leaves gutted out,

05:13:51.010 --> 05:13:53.190
I suppose, for pipe-lights.

05:13:53.930 --> 05:14:01.310
In the midst of all this the lamp still cast a smoky glow, obscure and brown as umber.

05:14:03.090 --> 05:14:04.650
I went into the cellar.

05:14:05.070 --> 05:14:10.550
All the barrels were gone, and of the bottles a most surprising number had been drunk out

05:14:10.550 --> 05:14:11.670
and thrown away.

05:14:12.450 --> 05:14:17.670
Certainly since the mutiny began not a man of them could ever have been sober.

05:14:19.010 --> 05:14:24.610
Foraging about I found a bottle with some brandy left for hands, and for myself I routed

05:14:24.610 --> 05:14:30.130
out some biscuit, some pickled fruits, a great bunch of raisins, and a piece of cheese.

05:14:30.930 --> 05:14:36.490
With these I came on deck, put down my own stock behind the rudder-head, and well out

05:14:36.490 --> 05:14:41.830
of the cockswain's reach, went forward to the water-breaker, and had a good deep drink

05:14:41.830 --> 05:14:48.030
of water, and then, and not till then, gave hands the brandy.

05:14:49.850 --> 05:14:53.550
He must have drunk a gill before he took the bottle from his mouth.

05:14:54.710 --> 05:14:59.210
I, said he, by thunder but I wanted some of that.

05:15:00.370 --> 05:15:03.510
I had sat down already in my own corner and begun to eat.

05:15:04.990 --> 05:15:07.170
Much hurt, I asked him.

05:15:07.920 --> 05:15:11.750
He grunted, or rather I might say he barked.

05:15:12.590 --> 05:15:17.450
If that doctor was aboard, he said, I'd be right enough on a couple of turns.

05:15:18.170 --> 05:15:23.930
But I don't have no manner of luck, you see, and that's what's the matter with me.

05:15:24.310 --> 05:15:27.950
As for that swab, he's good and dead he is.

05:15:28.330 --> 05:15:30.390
He added indicating the man with the red cap.

05:15:31.350 --> 05:15:33.210
He warn't no semen anyhow.

05:15:34.270 --> 05:15:36.790
And where might you have come from?

05:15:38.110 --> 05:15:44.110
Well, said I, I've come aboard to take possession of this ship, Mr. Hands, and you'll please

05:15:44.110 --> 05:15:46.310
regard me as your captain until further notice.

05:15:47.490 --> 05:15:50.050
He looked at me sourly enough, but said nothing.

05:15:50.870 --> 05:15:54.970
Some of the colour had come back into his cheeks, though he still looked very sick,

05:15:55.410 --> 05:15:59.170
and still continued to slip out and settle down as the ship banged about.

05:16:00.650 --> 05:16:02.210
By the by, I continued.

05:16:02.710 --> 05:16:07.990
I can't have these colours, Mr. Hands, and by your leave I'll strike them, better none

05:16:07.990 --> 05:16:08.710
than these.

05:16:10.390 --> 05:16:16.490
And again dodging the boom, I ran to the colour lines, handed down the cursed black flag,

05:16:17.130 --> 05:16:18.230
and chucked it overboard.

05:16:19.850 --> 05:16:25.270
God save the king, said I, waving my cap, and there's an end to Captain Silver.

05:16:26.410 --> 05:16:30.350
He watched me keenly and slyly, his chin all the while on his breast.

05:16:31.410 --> 05:16:40.550
I reckon, he said at last, I reckon, Captain Hawkins, you'll kind of want to get ashore

05:16:40.550 --> 05:16:41.250
now.

05:16:42.010 --> 05:16:43.350
Suppose we talks.

05:16:45.170 --> 05:16:52.850
Why, yes, says I, with all my heart, Mr. Hands, say on, and I went back to my meal with a

05:16:52.850 --> 05:16:53.450
good appetite.

05:16:54.670 --> 05:16:58.690
This man, he began, nodding feebly at the corpse.

05:16:59.690 --> 05:17:03.710
O'Brien were his name, a rank, irelander.

05:17:04.650 --> 05:17:10.270
This man, and me, got the canvas on her, meaning for to sail her back.

05:17:11.210 --> 05:17:19.550
Well, he's dead now, he is, as dead as bilge, and who's to sail this ship, I don't see.

05:17:20.130 --> 05:17:21.690
Without I gives you a hint.

05:17:22.490 --> 05:17:25.030
You ain't that man, as far as I can tell.

05:17:25.790 --> 05:17:33.970
Now, look here, you gives me food and drink and an old scarf, or anchorure, to tie my

05:17:33.970 --> 05:17:40.030
wound up, you do, and I'll tell you how to sail her, and that's about square all round,

05:17:40.090 --> 05:17:40.810
I take it.

05:17:42.310 --> 05:17:47.410
I'll tell you one thing, says I, I'm not going back to Captain Kidd's anchorage.

05:17:47.930 --> 05:17:51.490
I mean to get into North Inlet and beat her quietly there.

05:17:52.350 --> 05:17:55.150
To be sure you did, he cried.

05:17:56.670 --> 05:18:01.690
Why, I ain't such an infernal lubber after all, I can see, can't I?

05:18:02.690 --> 05:18:09.330
I've tried my fling, I have, and I've lost, and it's you has the wind of me, North Inlet.

05:18:09.930 --> 05:18:12.190
Why, I haven't no choice, not I.

05:18:12.570 --> 05:18:17.070
I'd help you sail her up to Execution Dock by thunder, so I would.

05:18:18.670 --> 05:18:22.730
Well, as it seemed to me, there was some sense in this.

05:18:23.110 --> 05:18:24.890
We struck our bargain on the spot.

05:18:25.530 --> 05:18:30.770
In three minutes I had the Hispaniola sailing easily before the wind along the coast of

05:18:30.770 --> 05:18:36.710
Treasure Island, with good hopes of turning the northern point air noon and beating down

05:18:36.710 --> 05:18:42.790
again as far as North Inlet before high water, when we might beach her safely and wait till

05:18:42.790 --> 05:18:45.210
the subsiding tide permitted us to land.

05:18:46.610 --> 05:18:52.650
Then I lashed the tiller and went below to my own chest, where I got a soft silk handkerchief

05:18:52.650 --> 05:18:54.630
of my mother's.

05:18:54.750 --> 05:19:00.910
With this and with my aid hands bound up the great bleeding stab he had received in the

05:19:00.910 --> 05:19:07.310
thigh, and after he had eaten a little and had a swallow or two more of the brandy he

05:19:07.310 --> 05:19:13.570
began to pick up visibly, sat straighter up, spoke louder and clearer, and looked in every

05:19:13.570 --> 05:19:14.750
way another man.

05:19:16.670 --> 05:19:18.950
The breeze served us admirably.

05:19:19.130 --> 05:19:25.190
We skimmed before it like a bird, the coast of the island flashing by and the view changing

05:19:25.190 --> 05:19:25.830
every minute.

05:19:26.810 --> 05:19:33.130
Soon we were past the highlands and bowling beside low, sandy country, sparsely dotted

05:19:33.130 --> 05:19:34.770
with dwarf pines.

05:19:35.870 --> 05:19:41.290
And soon we were beyond that again and had turned the corner of the rocky hill that ends

05:19:41.290 --> 05:19:42.670
the island on the north.

05:19:44.430 --> 05:19:50.130
I was greatly elated with my new command and pleased with the bright sunshiny weather and

05:19:50.130 --> 05:19:51.890
these different prospects of the coast.

05:19:53.050 --> 05:19:59.350
I had now plenty of water and good things to eat, and my conscience, which had smitten

05:19:59.350 --> 05:20:04.490
me hard for my desertion, was quieted by the great conquest I had made.

05:20:04.490 --> 05:20:10.930
I should, I think, have had nothing left me to desire but for the eyes of the cockswain

05:20:10.930 --> 05:20:16.370
as they followed me derisively about the deck and the odd smile that appeared continually

05:20:16.370 --> 05:20:17.470
on his face.

05:20:18.310 --> 05:20:26.910
It was a smile that had in it something both of pain and weakness, a haggard old man's

05:20:26.910 --> 05:20:27.250
smile.

05:20:27.730 --> 05:20:36.910
But there was, besides that, a grain of derision, a shadow of treachery in his expression as

05:20:36.910 --> 05:20:43.010
he craftily watched and watched and watched me at my work.

05:20:47.730 --> 05:20:49.690
CHAPTER 26

05:20:50.570 --> 05:20:52.910
ISRAEL HANDS

05:20:52.910 --> 05:20:57.470
The wind, serving us to a desire, now hauled into the west.

05:20:57.710 --> 05:21:03.210
We could run so much the easier from the northeast corner of the island to the mouth of the north

05:21:03.210 --> 05:21:03.550
inlet.

05:21:04.710 --> 05:21:10.450
Only, as we had no power to anchor and dared not beecher till the tide had flowed a good

05:21:10.450 --> 05:21:13.150
deal farther, time hung on our hands.

05:21:14.050 --> 05:21:16.670
The cockswain told me how to lay the ship too.

05:21:17.410 --> 05:21:21.970
After a good many trials I succeeded, and we both sat in silence over another meal.

05:21:23.030 --> 05:21:27.710
"'Gap'n!' said he at length, with that same uncomfortable smile.

05:21:29.170 --> 05:21:31.690
"'Here's my old shipmate, O'Brien.

05:21:32.530 --> 05:21:34.790
Suppose you was to heave him overboard.

05:21:35.090 --> 05:21:42.050
I ain't particular as a rule, and I don't take no blame for settling his hash, but I

05:21:42.050 --> 05:21:45.170
don't reckon him ornamental now, do you?'

05:21:45.170 --> 05:21:50.770
"'I'm not strong enough, and I don't like the job, and there he lies for me,' said I.

05:21:52.250 --> 05:21:58.650
"'This here's an unlucky ship, this Hispaniola, Jim,' he went on blinking.

05:21:59.710 --> 05:22:06.930
"'There's a power of men been killed in this Hispaniola, a sight a poor seaman dead and

05:22:06.930 --> 05:22:09.250
gone since you and me took ship to Bristol.

05:22:10.150 --> 05:22:13.590
I never seen such dirty luck, not I.

05:22:14.430 --> 05:22:17.270
"'There was this here, O'Brien, now.

05:22:18.010 --> 05:22:19.570
He's dead, ain't he?

05:22:20.070 --> 05:22:27.050
Well, now, I'm no scholar, and your lattice can read and figure, and to put it straight,

05:22:27.910 --> 05:22:34.970
do you take it as dead man is dead for good, or do he come alive again?'

05:22:35.810 --> 05:22:38.810
"'You can kill the body, Mr. Hands, but not the spirit.

05:22:39.050 --> 05:22:41.550
You must know that already,' I replied.

05:22:41.550 --> 05:22:45.530
"'O'Brien there is in another world and may be watching us.'

05:22:45.530 --> 05:22:47.570
"'Ah,' says he.

05:22:47.850 --> 05:22:49.670
"'Well, that's unfortunate.

05:22:50.730 --> 05:22:54.430
Appears as if killing parties was a waste of time.

05:22:55.290 --> 05:22:56.630
"'How, some ever.

05:22:57.270 --> 05:23:00.770
Spirits don't reckon for much by what I've seen.

05:23:01.210 --> 05:23:03.390
I'll chance it with the spirits, Jim.

05:23:04.490 --> 05:23:11.510
"'And now you've spoke up free, and I'll take it kind if you'd step down into that there

05:23:11.510 --> 05:23:13.270
cabin and get me a—'

05:23:13.550 --> 05:23:16.310
"'Well, ah, shiver me timbers.

05:23:17.170 --> 05:23:19.090
I can't hit the naimont.

05:23:19.690 --> 05:23:23.070
Well, you get me a bottle of wine, Jim.

05:23:23.670 --> 05:23:28.310
This here brandy's too strong for my head.'

05:23:28.310 --> 05:23:35.570
Now the cockswain's hesitation seemed to be unnatural, and as for the notion of his preferring

05:23:35.570 --> 05:23:38.770
wine to brandy, I entirely disbelieved it.

05:23:39.350 --> 05:23:41.130
The whole story was a pretext.

05:23:41.730 --> 05:23:43.250
He wanted me to leave the deck.

05:23:43.830 --> 05:23:44.930
So much was plain.

05:23:45.670 --> 05:23:48.950
But with what purpose I could in no way imagine.

05:23:49.590 --> 05:23:51.150
His eyes never met mine.

05:23:51.610 --> 05:23:57.690
They kept wandering to and fro, up and down, now with a look to the sky, now with a flitting

05:23:57.690 --> 05:23:59.510
glance upon the dead O'Brien.

05:24:00.470 --> 05:24:06.110
All the time he kept smiling and putting his tongue out in the most guilty, embarrassed

05:24:06.110 --> 05:24:11.110
manner, so that a child could have told that he was bent on some deception.

05:24:12.190 --> 05:24:18.230
I was prompt with my answer, however, for I saw where my advantage lay, and that with

05:24:18.230 --> 05:24:23.170
a fellow so densely stupid I could easily conceal my suspicions to the end.

05:24:24.430 --> 05:24:26.530
"'Some wine,' I said.

05:24:26.810 --> 05:24:27.870
"'Far better.

05:24:28.070 --> 05:24:30.830
Will you have white or red?'

05:24:31.790 --> 05:24:37.930
"'Well, I reckon it's about the blessed same to me e-shipmate,' he replied.

05:24:38.450 --> 05:24:40.790
"'So it's strong, and plenty of it.

05:24:40.790 --> 05:24:43.230
What's the odds?'

05:24:43.230 --> 05:24:45.190
"'All right,' I answered.

05:24:45.930 --> 05:24:51.170
"'I'll bring you port, Mr. Hans, but I'll have to dig for it.'

05:24:51.170 --> 05:24:53.770
With that I scuttled down the companion.

05:24:54.550 --> 05:25:00.850
With all the noise I could, slipped off my shoes, ran quietly along the sparred gallery,

05:25:01.530 --> 05:25:06.070
mounted the forecastle ladder, and popped my head out of the fore companion.

05:25:06.810 --> 05:25:12.050
I knew he would not expect to see me there, yet I took every precaution possible, and

05:25:12.050 --> 05:25:15.350
certainly the worst of my suspicions proved too true.

05:25:16.110 --> 05:25:21.550
He had risen from his position to his hands and knees, and though his leg obviously hurt

05:25:21.550 --> 05:25:27.650
him pretty sharply when he moved, for I could hear him stifle a groan, yet it was at a good

05:25:27.650 --> 05:25:30.750
rattling rate that he trailed himself across the deck.

05:25:31.430 --> 05:25:37.430
In half a minute he had reached the port's scuppers and picked, out of a coil of rope,

05:25:37.770 --> 05:25:44.090
a long knife, or rather a short dirk, discoloured to the hilt with blood.

05:25:44.090 --> 05:25:50.690
He looked upon it for a moment, thrusting forth his under-jaw, tried the point upon

05:25:50.690 --> 05:25:56.490
his hand, and then, hastily concealing it in the bosom of his jacket, trundled back

05:25:56.490 --> 05:25:59.350
again into his old place against the bulwark.

05:26:00.710 --> 05:26:02.610
This was all that I required to know.

05:26:03.470 --> 05:26:04.750
Israel could move about.

05:26:05.590 --> 05:26:11.090
He was now armed, and if he had been at so much trouble to get rid of me, it was plain

05:26:11.090 --> 05:26:12.550
that I was meant to be the victim.

05:26:13.350 --> 05:26:18.530
What he would do afterwards, whether he would try to crawl right across the island from

05:26:18.530 --> 05:26:23.590
north inlet to the camp among the swamps, or whether he would fire long Tom, trusting

05:26:23.590 --> 05:26:28.110
that his own comrades might come first to help him, was of course more than I could

05:26:28.110 --> 05:26:28.570
say.

05:26:30.170 --> 05:26:32.890
Yet I felt sure that I could trust him in one point.

05:26:33.750 --> 05:26:38.810
Since, in that our interests jumped together, and that was in the disposition of the schooner,

05:26:38.810 --> 05:26:44.210
we both desired to have her stranded safe enough, in a sheltered place, and so that

05:26:44.210 --> 05:26:48.970
when the time came she could be got off again with as little labour and danger as might

05:26:48.970 --> 05:26:49.590
be.

05:26:50.730 --> 05:26:55.450
And until that was done I considered that my life would certainly be spared.

05:26:57.550 --> 05:27:02.750
While I was thus turning the business over in my mind, I had not been idle with my body.

05:27:02.750 --> 05:27:10.230
I had stolen back to the cabin, slipped once more into my shoes, and laid my hand at random

05:27:10.230 --> 05:27:16.250
on a bottle of wine, and now, with this for an excuse, I made my reappearance on the deck.

05:27:18.130 --> 05:27:24.530
Hands lay as I had left him, all fallen together in a bundle, and with his eyelids lowered

05:27:24.530 --> 05:27:26.970
as though he were too weak to bear the light.

05:27:26.970 --> 05:27:32.690
He looked up, however, at my coming, knocked the neck off the bottle like a man who had

05:27:32.690 --> 05:27:39.550
done the same thing often, and took a good swig, with his unfortunate toast of here's

05:27:39.550 --> 05:27:39.870
luck.

05:27:41.030 --> 05:27:46.630
Then he lay quiet for a little, and then, pulling out a stick of tobacco, begged me

05:27:46.630 --> 05:27:48.010
to cut him a quid.

05:27:48.830 --> 05:27:57.110
Cut me a chunk of that, says he, for I haven't no knife, and hardly strength enough, so be

05:27:57.110 --> 05:27:57.970
as I had.

05:27:59.050 --> 05:28:03.930
Ah, Jim, Jim, I reckon I've missed stays.

05:28:04.910 --> 05:28:13.010
Cut me a quid, as I'll likely be the last lad, for I'm for my long home, and no mistake."

05:28:14.810 --> 05:28:22.290
Well, said I, I'll cut you some tobacco, but if I was you and thought myself so badly,

05:28:22.830 --> 05:28:25.750
I would go to my prayers like a Christian man.

05:28:27.310 --> 05:28:30.990
Why, said he, now you tell me why.

05:28:32.130 --> 05:28:36.610
Why, I cried, you are asking me just now about the dead.

05:28:37.350 --> 05:28:38.770
You've broken your trust.

05:28:39.310 --> 05:28:42.090
You've lived in sin and lies and blood.

05:28:42.090 --> 05:28:48.090
There's a man you killed lying at your feet this moment, and you ask me why?

05:28:49.050 --> 05:28:52.770
For God's mercy, Mr. Hands, that's why.

05:28:54.070 --> 05:29:00.090
I spoke with a little heat, thinking of the bloody dirk he had hidden in his pocket and

05:29:00.090 --> 05:29:03.430
designed in his ill thoughts to end me with.

05:29:04.150 --> 05:29:10.150
He, for his part, took a great draught of the wine, and spoke with the most unusual

05:29:10.150 --> 05:29:10.810
solemnity.

05:29:12.590 --> 05:29:22.010
For thirty years, he said, I've sailed the seas, and seen good and bad, better and worse,

05:29:23.010 --> 05:29:29.450
fair weather and foul, provisions running out, knives going, and what not.

05:29:30.750 --> 05:29:36.970
Well, now I tell you, I never seen good come a goodness yet.

05:29:37.630 --> 05:29:40.490
Him as strikes first is my fancy.

05:29:41.490 --> 05:29:44.810
Dead men don't bite, that's my views.

05:29:45.770 --> 05:29:47.230
Amen, so be it.

05:29:47.750 --> 05:29:51.510
And now you look here, he added, suddenly changing his tone.

05:29:52.390 --> 05:29:54.850
We've had about enough of this foolery.

05:29:55.630 --> 05:29:57.550
The tide's made good enough by now.

05:29:58.410 --> 05:30:04.290
You just take my orders, Captain Hawkins, and we'll sail slap in and be done with it.

05:30:04.910 --> 05:30:09.930
All told, we had scarce two miles to run, but the navigation was delicate.

05:30:10.450 --> 05:30:16.390
The entrance to this northern anchorage was not only narrow and shoal, but lay east and

05:30:16.390 --> 05:30:20.690
west, so that the schooner must be nicely handled to be got in.

05:30:21.590 --> 05:30:27.090
I think I was a good prompt subaltern, and I am very sure that Hans was an excellent

05:30:27.090 --> 05:30:34.030
pilot, for we went about and about and dodged in, shaving the banks with a certainty and

05:30:34.030 --> 05:30:36.530
neatness that were a pleasure to behold.

05:30:38.290 --> 05:30:42.690
Scarcely had we passed the heads before the land closed around us.

05:30:43.090 --> 05:30:47.890
The shores of North Inlet were as thickly wooded as those of the southern anchorage,

05:30:48.150 --> 05:30:54.070
but the space was longer and narrower and more like, what in truth it was, the estuary

05:30:54.070 --> 05:30:54.850
of a river.

05:30:55.650 --> 05:31:01.850
Right before us, at the southern end, we saw the wreck of a ship and the last stages of

05:31:01.850 --> 05:31:02.610
dilapidation.

05:31:02.610 --> 05:31:09.310
It had been a great vessel of three masts, but had lain so long exposed to the injuries

05:31:09.310 --> 05:31:15.410
of the weather that it was hung about with great webs of dripping seaweed, and on the

05:31:15.410 --> 05:31:20.510
deck of it shore bushes had taken root and now flourished thick with flowers.

05:31:21.710 --> 05:31:25.990
It was a sad sight, but it showed us that the anchorage was calm.

05:31:26.870 --> 05:31:35.870
Now, said Hans, look there, there's a pet bit for to beach a ship in, fine flat sand,

05:31:36.190 --> 05:31:43.170
never a cat's paw, trees all around of it, and flowers a-blowin' like a guarding on that

05:31:43.170 --> 05:31:43.890
old ship.

05:31:45.130 --> 05:31:49.330
And once beached, I inquired, how shall we get her off again?

05:31:50.250 --> 05:31:52.190
Why, so, he replied.

05:31:53.150 --> 05:31:59.670
You take a line ashore, there on the other side, at low water, take a turn about one

05:31:59.670 --> 05:32:06.710
of them big pines, bring it back, take a turn around the cap-stand, and lie too for the

05:32:06.710 --> 05:32:07.110
tide.

05:32:07.770 --> 05:32:14.150
Come high water, all hands take a pull upon the line, and off she comes, as sweet as nature.

05:32:15.050 --> 05:32:17.570
And now, boy, you stand by.

05:32:17.570 --> 05:32:26.730
We're near the bit now, she's too much way on her, starboard a little, so steady, starboard,

05:32:27.270 --> 05:32:31.550
larboard a little, steady, steady.

05:32:32.530 --> 05:32:39.190
So he issued his commands, which I breathlessly obeyed, till all of a sudden he cried, Now,

05:32:39.190 --> 05:32:45.690
my hearty, luff! and I put the helm hard up, and the Hispaniola swung round rapidly and

05:32:45.690 --> 05:32:48.170
stem on for the low wooded shore.

05:32:49.070 --> 05:32:53.770
The excitement of these last maneuvers had somewhat interfered with the watch I had kept

05:32:53.770 --> 05:32:56.770
hitherto, sharply enough upon the coxswain.

05:32:57.390 --> 05:33:02.310
Even then I was still so much interested, waiting for the ship to touch, that I had

05:33:02.310 --> 05:33:07.790
quite forgot the peril that hung over my head, and stood craning over the starboard bulwarks,

05:33:08.410 --> 05:33:11.510
and watching the ripples spreading wide before the bows.

05:33:12.750 --> 05:33:18.470
I might have fallen without a struggle for my life, had not a sudden disquietude seized

05:33:18.470 --> 05:33:20.430
upon me and made me turn my head.

05:33:21.290 --> 05:33:26.850
Perhaps I had heard a creak, or seen his shadow moving with the tail of my eye.

05:33:27.410 --> 05:33:30.590
Perhaps it was an instinct, like a cat's.

05:33:30.930 --> 05:33:37.610
But sure enough, when I looked round, there was hands, already half way towards me, with

05:33:37.610 --> 05:33:39.090
the dirk in his right hand.

05:33:40.250 --> 05:33:46.190
We must both have cried out aloud when our eyes met, but while mine was the shrill cry

05:33:46.190 --> 05:33:51.090
of terror, his was a roar of fury like a charging bully's.

05:33:52.610 --> 05:33:58.590
At the same instant he threw himself forward, and I leapt sideways towards the bows.

05:33:59.630 --> 05:34:05.190
As I did so, I let go of the tiller, which sprang sharp to leeward, and I think this

05:34:05.190 --> 05:34:10.070
saved my life, for it struck hands across the chest and stopped him for a moment dead.

05:34:11.090 --> 05:34:16.870
Before he could recover I was safe out of the corner where he had me trapped, with all

05:34:16.870 --> 05:34:18.030
the deck to dodge about.

05:34:19.010 --> 05:34:24.510
Just forward of the main mast I stopped, drew a pistol from my pocket, took a cool aim,

05:34:25.010 --> 05:34:29.870
though he had already turned and was once more coming directly after me, and drew the

05:34:29.870 --> 05:34:30.170
trigger.

05:34:30.990 --> 05:34:35.590
The hammer fell, but there followed neither flash nor sound.

05:34:36.150 --> 05:34:38.570
The priming was useless with sea water.

05:34:39.030 --> 05:34:40.850
I cursed myself for my neglect.

05:34:41.690 --> 05:34:46.570
Why had not I long before reprimed and reloaded my only weapons?

05:34:47.650 --> 05:34:52.350
Then I should not have been as now, a mere fleeing sheep before this butcher.

05:34:53.610 --> 05:34:57.550
Wounded as he was, it was wonderful how fast he could move.

05:34:57.550 --> 05:35:05.030
His grizzled hair tumbling over his face, and his face itself as red as a red ensign

05:35:05.030 --> 05:35:07.070
with his haste and fury.

05:35:08.030 --> 05:35:13.770
I had no time to try my other pistol, nor indeed much inclination, for I was sure it

05:35:13.770 --> 05:35:14.610
would be useless.

05:35:15.590 --> 05:35:21.730
One thing I saw plainly, I must not simply retreat before him, or he would speedily hold

05:35:21.730 --> 05:35:23.170
me boxed into the bows.

05:35:23.170 --> 05:35:30.970
As a moment since he had so nearly boxed me in the stern, once so caught, and nine or

05:35:30.970 --> 05:35:36.590
ten inches of the blood-stained dirk would be my last experience on this side of eternity.

05:35:37.710 --> 05:35:45.750
I placed my palms against the main mast, which was of a goodish bigness, and waited, each

05:35:45.750 --> 05:35:47.530
nerve upon the stretch.

05:35:48.390 --> 05:35:55.030
Seeing that I meant to dodge, he also paused, and a moment or two passed in feints on his

05:35:55.030 --> 05:35:57.250
part, and corresponding movements upon mine.

05:35:57.950 --> 05:36:03.410
It was such a game as I had often played at home about the rocks of Blackhill Cove, but

05:36:03.410 --> 05:36:08.210
never before, you may be sure, with such a wildly beating heart as now.

05:36:09.130 --> 05:36:14.490
Still, as I say, it was a boy's game, and I thought I could hold my own at it against

05:36:14.490 --> 05:36:16.570
an elderly seaman with a wounded thigh.

05:36:17.310 --> 05:36:22.790
Indeed my courage had begun to rise so high that I allowed myself a few darting thoughts

05:36:22.790 --> 05:36:28.330
on what would be the end of the affair, and while I saw certainly that I could spin it

05:36:28.330 --> 05:36:33.110
out for long, I saw no hope of any ultimate escape.

05:36:34.310 --> 05:36:42.010
Well, while things stood thus, suddenly the Hispaniola struck, staggered, ground for an

05:36:42.010 --> 05:36:47.750
instant in the sand, and then, swift as a blow, canted over to the port side till the

05:36:47.750 --> 05:36:54.410
deck stood at an angle of forty-five degrees, and about a punchin' of water splashed into

05:36:54.410 --> 05:36:57.970
the scupper holes and lay in a pool between the deck and bulwark.

05:36:59.310 --> 05:37:04.450
We were both of us capsized in a second, and both of us rolled almost together into the

05:37:04.450 --> 05:37:04.970
scuppers.

05:37:05.650 --> 05:37:11.150
The dead red cap with his arms still spread out, tumbling stiffly after us.

05:37:12.130 --> 05:37:18.070
So near were we, indeed, that my head came against the cockswain's foot with a crack

05:37:18.070 --> 05:37:19.470
that made my teeth rattle.

05:37:20.370 --> 05:37:25.850
Low and all, I was the first to foot again, for hands had got involved with the dead body.

05:37:26.730 --> 05:37:30.470
The sudden canting of the ship had made the deck no place for running on.

05:37:30.470 --> 05:37:37.490
I had to find some new way of escape, and that upon the instant, for my foe was almost

05:37:37.490 --> 05:37:38.650
touching me.

05:37:39.050 --> 05:37:45.590
Quick as thought I sprang into the mizzen shrouds, rattled up hand over hand, and did

05:37:45.590 --> 05:37:48.910
not draw a breath till I was seated on the cross-trees.

05:37:49.750 --> 05:37:51.750
I had been saved by being prompt.

05:37:52.590 --> 05:37:58.430
The dirk had struck not half a foot below me as I pursued my upward flight, and there

05:37:58.430 --> 05:38:05.630
stood Israel hands, with his mouth open and his face upturned to mine, a perfect statue

05:38:05.630 --> 05:38:07.810
of surprise and disappointment.

05:38:08.810 --> 05:38:13.610
Now that I had a moment to myself I lost no time in changing the priming of my pistol,

05:38:14.030 --> 05:38:19.510
and then, having one ready for service, and to make assurance, doubly sure, I proceeded

05:38:19.510 --> 05:38:23.250
to draw the load of the other and recharge it afresh from the beginning.

05:38:24.270 --> 05:38:27.090
My new employment struck hands all of a heap.

05:38:27.090 --> 05:38:34.410
He began to see the dice going against him, and after an obvious hesitation he also hauled

05:38:34.410 --> 05:38:41.850
himself heavily into the shrouds, and with the dirk in his teeth began slowly and painfully

05:38:41.850 --> 05:38:42.450
to mount.

05:38:43.590 --> 05:38:50.230
It cost him no end of time and groans to haul his wounded leg behind him, and I had quietly

05:38:50.230 --> 05:38:54.090
finished my arrangements before he was much more than a third of the way up.

05:38:54.750 --> 05:38:58.930
Then, with a pistol in either hand, I addressed him.

05:38:59.670 --> 05:39:05.090
"'One more step, Mr. Hands,' said I, and I'll blow your brains out.

05:39:05.990 --> 05:39:10.130
"'Dead men don't bite, you know,' I added with a chuckle.

05:39:11.310 --> 05:39:12.850
He stopped instantly.

05:39:13.270 --> 05:39:18.590
I could see by the working of his face that he was trying to think, and the process was

05:39:18.590 --> 05:39:22.510
so slow and laborious that in my newfound security I laughed aloud.

05:39:23.310 --> 05:39:29.290
At last, with a swallow or two, he spoke, his face still wearing the same expression

05:39:29.290 --> 05:39:30.930
of extreme perplexity.

05:39:31.530 --> 05:39:37.310
In order to speak he had to take the dagger from his mouth, but in all else he remained

05:39:37.310 --> 05:39:38.170
unmoved.

05:39:39.190 --> 05:39:46.570
"'Jim,' says he, "'I reckon we're fouled, you and me, and will have to sign articles.

05:39:47.480 --> 05:39:50.290
I'd have had you but for that there lurch.

05:39:50.810 --> 05:39:58.370
But I don't have no luck, not I, and I reckon I'll have to strike, which comes hard, you

05:39:58.370 --> 05:40:04.150
see, for a master mariner to a ship's yunker like you, Jim.'

05:40:04.150 --> 05:40:11.270
I was drinking in his words and smiling away, as conceited as a cock upon a wall, when all

05:40:11.270 --> 05:40:14.610
in a breath back went his right hand over his shoulder.

05:40:15.310 --> 05:40:17.650
Something sang like an arrow through the air.

05:40:17.930 --> 05:40:24.150
I felt a blow and then a sharp pang, and there I was, pinned by the shoulder to the mast.

05:40:25.050 --> 05:40:30.750
In the horrid pain and surprise of the moment, I scarce can say it was by my own volition,

05:40:30.990 --> 05:40:33.670
and I am sure it was without a conscious aim.

05:40:34.450 --> 05:40:38.470
Both my pistols went off, and both escaped out of my hands.

05:40:38.470 --> 05:40:40.910
They did not fall alone.

05:40:41.330 --> 05:40:49.470
With a choked cry, the cockswain loosed his grip upon the shrouds and plunged headfirst

05:40:49.470 --> 05:40:50.590
into the water.

05:41:12.870 --> 05:41:14.890
PIECES OF EIGHT

05:41:15.870 --> 05:41:21.090
Owing to the count of the vessel, the masts hung far out over the water, and from my perch

05:41:21.090 --> 05:41:25.530
on the cross-trees I had nothing below me but the surface of the bay. Hans, who was

05:41:25.530 --> 05:41:30.390
not so far up, was in consequence nearer to the ship, and fell between me and the bulwarks.

05:41:31.030 --> 05:41:36.250
He rose once to the surface in a lather of foam and blood, and then sank again for good.

05:41:38.290 --> 05:41:42.630
As the water settled, I could see him lying huddled together on the clean, bright sand

05:41:42.630 --> 05:41:48.430
in the shadow of the vessel's sides. A fish or two whipped past his body. Sometimes by

05:41:48.430 --> 05:41:52.430
the quivering of the water he appeared to move a little, as if he were trying to rise.

05:41:54.250 --> 05:41:59.310
But he was dead enough for all that, being both shot and drowned, and was food for fish

05:41:59.310 --> 05:42:02.070
in the very place where he had designed my slaughter.

05:42:03.930 --> 05:42:09.830
I was no sooner certain of this than I began to feel sick, faint, and terrified. The hot

05:42:09.830 --> 05:42:14.210
blood was running over my back and chest. The dirk where it had pinned my shoulder to

05:42:14.210 --> 05:42:20.250
like a hot iron. Yet it was not so much these real sufferings that distressed me. For these

05:42:20.250 --> 05:42:25.230
it seemed to me I could bear without a murmur. It was the horror I had upon my mind of falling

05:42:25.230 --> 05:42:29.670
from the cross-trees into that still green water beside the body of the coxswain.

05:42:31.210 --> 05:42:36.410
I clung with both hands until my nails ached, and I shut my eyes as if to cover up the peril.

05:42:37.250 --> 05:42:42.410
Gradually my mind came back again, my pulses quieted down to a more natural time, and I

05:42:42.410 --> 05:42:44.290
was once again in possession of myself.

05:42:45.570 --> 05:42:50.270
It was my first thought to pluck forth the dirk, but either it stuck too hard or my nerve

05:42:50.270 --> 05:42:55.590
failed me, and I desisted with a violent shudder. Oddly enough that very shudder did the business.

05:42:56.030 --> 05:43:00.030
The knife, in fact, had come the nearest in the world to missing me altogether. It held

05:43:00.030 --> 05:43:05.590
me by a mere pinch of skin, and this the shudder tore away. The blood ran down the faster,

05:43:05.650 --> 05:43:10.170
to be sure, but I was my own master again, and only tacked to the mast by my coat and

05:43:11.530 --> 05:43:16.050
These last I broke through with a sudden jerk, and then regained the deck by the starboard

05:43:16.630 --> 05:43:20.970
shrouds, for nothing in the world would I have again ventured, shaken as I was, upon

05:43:20.970 --> 05:43:24.010
the overhanging port shrouds from which Israel had so lately fallen.

05:43:25.430 --> 05:43:30.570
I went below and did what I could for my wound. It pained me a good deal and still bled freely,

05:43:31.010 --> 05:43:35.210
but it was neither deep nor dangerous, nor did it greatly gall me when I used my arm.

05:43:35.870 --> 05:43:40.510
Then I looked around me, and as the ship was now, in a sense, my own, I began to think

05:43:40.510 --> 05:43:46.470
of clearing it from its last passenger, the dead man O'Brien. He had pitched, as I have

05:43:46.470 --> 05:43:52.070
said, against the bulwarks, where he lay like some horrible ungainly sort of puppet, life-size

05:43:52.070 --> 05:43:57.850
indeed, but how different from life's colour or life's comeliness. In that position I could

05:43:57.850 --> 05:44:02.350
easily have my way with him, and as the habit of tragical adventures had worn off almost

05:44:02.350 --> 05:44:06.450
all my terror for the dead, I took him by the waist as if he had been a sack of bran,

05:44:06.570 --> 05:44:11.730
and with one good heave tumbled him overboard. He went in with a sounding plunge, the red

05:44:11.730 --> 05:44:15.830
cap came off and remained floating on the surface, and as soon as the splash subsided

05:44:15.830 --> 05:44:20.630
I could see him and Israel lying side by side, both wavering with the tremulous movement

05:44:20.630 --> 05:44:26.750
of the water. O'Brien, though still quite a young man, was very bold. There he lay with

05:44:26.750 --> 05:44:30.670
that bold head across the knees of the man who had killed him, and the quick fishes steering

05:44:30.670 --> 05:44:38.950
to and fro over both. I was now alone upon the ship. The tide had just turned. The sun

05:44:38.950 --> 05:44:42.830
was within so few degrees of setting that already the shadow of the pines upon the western

05:44:42.830 --> 05:44:48.510
shore began to reach right across the anchorage and fall in patterns on the deck. The evening

05:44:48.510 --> 05:44:52.550
breeze had sprung up, and though it was well warded off by the hill with the two peaks

05:44:52.550 --> 05:44:57.510
upon the east, the cordage had begun to sing a little softly to itself, and the idle sails

05:44:57.510 --> 05:45:05.070
a rattle to and fro. I began to see a danger to the ship. The jibs I speedily doused and

05:45:05.070 --> 05:45:09.890
brought tumbling to the deck, but the mainsail was a harder matter. Of course when the schooner

05:45:09.890 --> 05:45:14.270
canted over the boom had a swing outboard, and the cap of it and a foot or two of sail

05:45:14.270 --> 05:45:19.010
hung even under the water. I thought this made it still more dangerous, yet the strain

05:45:19.010 --> 05:45:24.370
was so heavy that I half feared to meddle. At last I got my knife and cut the halyards.

05:45:24.770 --> 05:45:29.070
The peak dropped instantly, a great belly of loose canvas floated broad upon the water,

05:45:29.470 --> 05:45:34.270
and since, pull as I liked, I could not budge the down-haul, that was the extent of what

05:45:34.270 --> 05:45:41.870
I could accomplish. For the rest, the Hispaniola must trust a luck like myself. By this time

05:45:41.870 --> 05:45:46.190
the whole anchorage had fallen into shadow, the last rays I remember falling through a

05:45:46.190 --> 05:45:50.790
glade of the wood and shining bright as jewels on the flowery mantle of the wreck. It began

05:45:50.790 --> 05:45:55.530
to be chill, the tide was rapidly fleeting sea-wood, the schooner settling more and

05:45:55.530 --> 05:46:01.090
more on her beam ends. I scrambled forward and looked over. It seemed shallow enough,

05:46:01.370 --> 05:46:06.270
and holding the cut-houser in both hands for last security, I let myself drop softly overboard.

05:46:07.110 --> 05:46:11.810
The water scarcely reached my waist, the sand was firm and covered with ripple marks, and

05:46:11.810 --> 05:46:16.690
I waded ashore in great spirits, leaving the Hispaniola on her side, with her mainsail

05:46:16.690 --> 05:46:21.770
trailing wide upon the surface of the bay. About the same time, the sun went fairly down

05:46:21.770 --> 05:46:27.050
and the breeze whistled low in the dusk among the tossing pines. At least and at last I

05:46:27.050 --> 05:46:32.350
was off the sea, nor had I returned thence empty-handed. There lay the schooner, clear

05:46:32.350 --> 05:46:36.790
at last from buccaneers and ready for our own men to board and get to sea again. I had

05:46:36.790 --> 05:46:40.270
nothing nearer my fancy than to get home to the stockade and boast of my achievements.

05:46:41.310 --> 05:46:45.630
Possibly I might be blamed a bit for my truantry, but the recapture of the Hispaniola was a

05:46:45.630 --> 05:46:50.310
wrenching answer, and I hoped that even Captain Smollett would confess I had not lost my time.

05:46:51.410 --> 05:46:55.590
So thinking, and in famous spirits, I began to set my face homeward for the blockhouse

05:46:55.590 --> 05:47:00.910
and my companions. I remembered that the most easterly of the rivers which drain into Captain

05:47:00.910 --> 05:47:05.070
Kidd's anchorage ran from the two-peaked hill upon my left, and I bent my course in

05:47:05.070 --> 05:47:09.830
that direction that I might pass the stream whilst it was small. The wood was pretty open,

05:47:10.050 --> 05:47:14.050
and keeping along the lower spurs, I had soon turned the corner of that hill, and was not

05:47:14.050 --> 05:47:19.330
long after waded to the mid-garve across the water-course. This brought me near to

05:47:19.330 --> 05:47:24.150
where I had encountered Ben Gunn, the maroon, and I walked more circumspectly, keeping an

05:47:24.150 --> 05:47:29.330
eye on every side. The dusk had come nigh-hand completely, and as I opened out the cleft

05:47:29.330 --> 05:47:34.450
between the two peaks, I became aware of a wavering glow against the sky, where, as I

05:47:34.450 --> 05:47:39.170
judged, the man of the island was cooking his supper before a roaring fire, and yet

05:47:39.170 --> 05:47:43.350
I wondered in my heart that he should show himself so careless, for if I could see this

05:47:43.350 --> 05:47:47.030
radiance, might it not reach the eyes of Silver himself, where he camped upon the shore

05:47:47.030 --> 05:47:48.010
among the marshes?

05:47:49.390 --> 05:47:53.790
Gradually the night fell blacker. It was all I could do to guide myself even roughly towards

05:47:53.790 --> 05:47:58.490
my destination. The double hill behind me and the spy-glass on my right hand loomed

05:47:58.490 --> 05:48:03.430
faint and fainter. The stars were few and pale, and in the low ground where I wandered,

05:48:03.590 --> 05:48:08.870
I kept tripping among bushes and rolling into sandy pits. Suddenly a kind of brightness

05:48:08.870 --> 05:48:14.370
fell about me. I looked up. A pale glimmer of moonbeams had alighted on the summit of

05:48:14.370 --> 05:48:18.990
the spy-glass, and soon after I saw something broad and silvery moving low down behind the

05:48:18.990 --> 05:48:24.990
trees, and knew that the moon had risen. With this to help me, I passed rapidly over what

05:48:24.990 --> 05:48:29.670
remained to me of my journey, and sometimes walking, sometimes running, impatiently drew

05:48:29.670 --> 05:48:35.390
near to the stockade. Yet as I began to thread the grove that lies before it, I was not so

05:48:35.390 --> 05:48:39.630
thoughtless but that I slacked my pace and went a trifle warily. It would have been a

05:48:39.630 --> 05:48:42.850
poor end of my adventures to get shot down by my own party and mistake.

05:48:44.530 --> 05:48:48.990
The moon was climbing higher and higher. Its light began to fall here and there in masses

05:48:48.990 --> 05:48:53.090
through the more open districts of the wood, and right in front of me a glow of a different

05:48:53.090 --> 05:48:58.010
colour appeared among the trees. It was red and hot, and now and again it was a little

05:48:58.010 --> 05:49:01.330
darkened, as it were the embers of a bonfire smouldering.

05:49:02.850 --> 05:49:06.230
For the life of me, I could not think what it might be.

05:49:07.850 --> 05:49:12.690
At last I came right down upon the borders of the clearing. The western end was already

05:49:12.690 --> 05:49:17.970
steeped in moonshine. The rest, and the block-house itself, still lay in a black shadow checkered

05:49:17.970 --> 05:49:22.850
with long silvery streaks of light. On the other side of the house an immense fire had

05:49:22.850 --> 05:49:27.750
burned itself into clear embers and shed a steady red reverberation contrasted strongly

05:49:27.750 --> 05:49:33.010
with the mellow paleness of the moon. There was not a soul stirring, nor a sound beside

05:49:33.010 --> 05:49:34.070
the noises of the breeze.

05:49:35.910 --> 05:49:41.550
I stopped, with much wonder in my heart, and perhaps a little terror also. It had not been

05:49:41.550 --> 05:49:46.630
our way to build great fires. We were, indeed by the captain's orders, somewhat niggardly

05:49:46.630 --> 05:49:50.390
of firewood, and I began to fear that something had gone wrong while I was absent.

05:49:51.550 --> 05:49:56.210
I stole round by the eastern end, keeping close in shadow, and at a convenient place

05:49:56.210 --> 05:49:58.810
where the darkness was thickest, crossed the palisade.

05:50:00.550 --> 05:50:05.090
To make assurance to Shura, I got upon my knees and hands and crawled without a sound

05:50:05.090 --> 05:50:10.170
towards the corner of the house. As I drew nearer, my heart was suddenly and greatly

05:50:10.170 --> 05:50:14.630
lightened. It is not a pleasant noise in itself, and I have often complained of it at other

05:50:14.630 --> 05:50:19.270
times, but just then it was like music to hear my friends snoring together so loud and

05:50:19.270 --> 05:50:24.870
peaceful in their sleep. The sea-cry of the watch, that beautiful all's well, never fell

05:50:24.870 --> 05:50:26.550
more reassuringly on my ear.

05:50:28.790 --> 05:50:33.230
In the meantime, there was no doubt of one thing. They had kept an infamous bad watch.

05:50:33.750 --> 05:50:37.210
If it had been Silver and his lads that were now creeping in on them, not a soul would

05:50:37.210 --> 05:50:41.530
have seen daybreak. That was what it was, thought I, to have had the captain wounded,

05:50:41.970 --> 05:50:46.110
and again I blamed myself sharply for leaving them in that danger with so few to mount guard.

05:50:48.910 --> 05:50:54.550
By this time I had got to the door and stood up. All was dark within, so that I could distinguish

05:50:54.550 --> 05:50:59.750
nothing by the eye. As for sounds, there was the steady drone of the snorers and a small

05:50:59.750 --> 05:51:04.110
occasional noise, a flickering or pecking that I could in no way account for.

05:51:05.910 --> 05:51:10.970
With my arms before me, I walked steadily in. I should lie down in my own place, I thought

05:51:10.970 --> 05:51:14.430
with a silent chuckle, and enjoy their faces when they found me in the morning.

05:51:16.130 --> 05:51:21.710
My foot struck something yielding. It was a sleeper's leg, and he turned and groaned

05:51:21.710 --> 05:51:28.310
without awaking. And then all of a sudden a shrill voice broke forth out of the darkness.

05:51:28.830 --> 05:51:33.450
—Pieces of eight! Pieces of eight! Pieces of eight! Pieces of eight! Pieces of eight!

05:51:33.890 --> 05:51:37.290
And so forth, without pause or change, like the clacking of a tiny mill.

05:51:38.070 --> 05:51:42.970
Silver's green parrot, Captain Flint. It was she whom I had heard pecking at a piece of

05:51:42.970 --> 05:51:47.530
bark. It was she keeping better watch than any human being, who thus announced my arrival

05:51:47.530 --> 05:51:53.170
with her wearisome refrain. I had no time left to me to recover. At the sharp clipping

05:51:53.170 --> 05:51:57.470
tone of the parrot, the sleepers awoke and sprang up, and with a mighty oath the voice

05:51:57.470 --> 05:52:03.850
of Silver cried, Who goes? I turned to run, struck violently against one person, recoiled

05:52:03.850 --> 05:52:08.190
and ran full into the arms of a second, who for his part closed upon and held me tight.

05:52:08.890 --> 05:52:11.970
—Bring a torch, Dick! said Silver when my capture was thus assured.

05:52:11.970 --> 05:52:17.270
And one of the men left the log-house, and presently returned with a lighted brand.

05:52:35.270 --> 05:52:39.410
Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson

05:52:39.410 --> 05:52:42.350
Part 6. Captain Silver

05:52:42.350 --> 05:52:45.710
Chapter 28. In the Enemy's Camp

05:52:48.110 --> 05:52:55.450
The red glare of the torch, lighting up the interior of the blockhouse, showed me the worst of my apprehensions realized.

05:52:56.310 --> 05:53:07.630
The pirates were in possession of the house and stores, there was the cask of cognac, there were the pork and bread, as before, and what tenfold increased my horror, not a sign of any prisoner.

05:53:08.530 --> 05:53:15.370
I could only judge that all had perished, and my heart smote me sorely that I had not been there to perish with them.

05:53:17.010 --> 05:53:27.490
There were six of the buccaneers all told, not another man was left alive. Five of them were on their feet, flushed and swollen, suddenly called out of the first sleep of drunkenness.

05:53:27.490 --> 05:53:37.530
The sixth had only risen upon his elbows, he was deadly pale and the bloodstained bandage around his head told that he had recently been wounded and still more recently dressed.

05:53:38.910 --> 05:53:44.990
I remembered the man who had been shot and had run back among the woods in the great attack and doubted not that this was he.

05:53:46.450 --> 05:53:55.310
The parrot sat, preening her plumage on Long John's shoulder. He himself, I thought, looked somewhat paler and more stern than I was used to.

05:53:55.310 --> 05:54:05.230
He still wore the fine broadcloth suit in which he had fulfilled his mission, but it was bitterly the worse for wear, daubed with clay and torn with the sharp briars of the wood.

05:54:06.470 --> 05:54:13.690
So, said he, here's Jim Hawkins, shiver my timbers, dropped in like a, welcome, I take that friendly.

05:54:15.250 --> 05:54:19.110
And thereupon he sat down across the brandy cask and began to fill a pipe.

05:54:20.190 --> 05:54:30.950
Give me the loan of the link, Dick, said he, and then, when he had a good light, that'll do, lad, he added, stick the glim in the wood-heap, and you gentlemen bring yourselves too.

05:54:31.370 --> 05:54:35.050
You needn't stand up for Mr. Hawkins, he'll excuse you, you may later that.

05:54:35.670 --> 05:54:41.190
And so, Jim, stopping the tobacco, here you were, and quite a pleasant surprise for poor old John.

05:54:41.870 --> 05:54:46.950
I see you were smart when I first set eyes on you, but this here gets clean away from me, it do.

05:54:48.330 --> 05:54:51.930
To this, as may be well supposed, I made no answer.

05:54:52.670 --> 05:54:56.870
They had set me with my back against the wall, and I stood there looking silver in the face,

05:54:57.170 --> 05:55:02.150
pluckly enough, I hope, to all outward appearance, but with black despair in my heart.

05:55:03.490 --> 05:55:07.230
Silver took a whiff or two of his pipe with great composure, and then ran on again.

05:55:08.130 --> 05:55:13.370
Now you see, Jim, so be as you are here, says he, I'll give you a piece of my mind.

05:55:13.830 --> 05:55:19.110
I've always liked you, I have for a lad of spirit, and the picture of my own self when I was young and handsome.

05:55:19.690 --> 05:55:25.710
I always want you to jine and take your share, and die a gentleman, and now, my cock, you've got to.

05:55:26.350 --> 05:55:30.310
Captain Smollett's a fine seaman, I'll own up to any day, but stiff on discipline.

05:55:30.990 --> 05:55:33.390
Duty is duty, says he, and right he is.

05:55:33.930 --> 05:55:35.330
Just you keep clear of the captain.

05:55:35.870 --> 05:55:39.470
The doctor himself has gone dead again, you, ungrateful scamp, was what he said,

05:55:39.570 --> 05:55:42.030
and the short and the long of the whole story is about here.

05:55:42.030 --> 05:55:45.010
You can't go back to your own lot, for they won't have you,

05:55:45.170 --> 05:55:49.070
and without you start a third ship's company all by yourself, which might be lonely,

05:55:49.530 --> 05:55:51.110
you'll have to jine with Captain Silver.

05:55:53.050 --> 05:55:56.030
So far so good, my friends then were still alive,

05:55:56.410 --> 05:55:58.750
and though I partly believed the truth of Silver's statement,

05:55:58.930 --> 05:56:01.430
that the cabin party were incensed at me for my desertion,

05:56:01.810 --> 05:56:04.250
I was more relieved than distressed by what I heard.

05:56:05.430 --> 05:56:08.810
I don't say nothing as to your being in our hands, continued Silver,

05:56:08.810 --> 05:56:11.310
though you are, and you may lay to it.

05:56:11.390 --> 05:56:14.710
I'm all for argument, I never seen good come out a-threatening.

05:56:14.970 --> 05:56:17.310
If you like the service, well, you'll jine.

05:56:17.510 --> 05:56:20.110
If you don't, Jim, why, you're free to answer no.

05:56:20.310 --> 05:56:23.270
Free and welcome, shipmate, and a fairer can be said by mortal seaman,

05:56:23.510 --> 05:56:24.450
shiver my sides.

05:56:26.930 --> 05:56:30.330
Am I to answer then? I asked with a very tremulous voice.

05:56:30.950 --> 05:56:35.090
Through all this sneering talk I made to feel the threat of death that overhung me,

05:56:35.090 --> 05:56:38.350
and my cheeks burned and my heart beat painfully in my breast.

05:56:39.190 --> 05:56:41.870
Lad, said Silver, there's no one oppressing of you.

05:56:42.110 --> 05:56:44.610
Take your bearings, none of us won't hurry you, mate.

05:56:45.110 --> 05:56:47.530
Time goes so pleasant in your company, you see.

05:56:48.630 --> 05:56:51.770
Well, says I, growing a bit bolder, if I'm to choose,

05:56:52.070 --> 05:56:53.890
I declare I have a right to know what's what,

05:56:54.190 --> 05:56:56.310
and why you're here, and where my friends are.

05:56:57.430 --> 05:57:00.230
What's what? repeated one of the buccaneers in a deep growl.

05:57:00.690 --> 05:57:02.810
Ah, he'd be a lucky one has known that.

05:57:04.730 --> 05:57:08.050
You'll perhaps batten down your hatches till you're spoke to, my friend,

05:57:08.330 --> 05:57:10.630
cried Silver, trusulently to this speaker.

05:57:11.470 --> 05:57:14.110
And then, in his first gracious tones, he replied to me.

05:57:14.570 --> 05:57:17.210
Yesterday morning, Mr. Hawkins, said he.

05:57:17.950 --> 05:57:21.650
In the dog-watch, down came Dr. Livesey with a flag of truce.

05:57:22.050 --> 05:57:24.830
Says he, Captain Silver, you're sold out, ship's gone.

05:57:25.710 --> 05:57:29.710
Well, maybe we'd been taken a glass and a song to help it round, I won't say no.

05:57:30.110 --> 05:57:31.630
Least ways none of us had looked out.

05:57:31.630 --> 05:57:34.490
We looked out, and by thunder the old ship was gone.

05:57:35.050 --> 05:57:37.170
I never seen a pack of fools look fishier,

05:57:37.190 --> 05:57:40.110
and you may lay to that if I tells you that I looked the fishiest.

05:57:41.810 --> 05:57:43.570
Well, says the doctor, let's bargain.

05:57:44.210 --> 05:57:47.790
We bargained, him and I, and here we are, stores, brandy, blockhouse,

05:57:48.030 --> 05:57:49.990
the firewood you was thoughtful enough to cut,

05:57:50.350 --> 05:57:55.750
and, in a manner of speaking, the whole boat, from Cross Trees to Kelson.

05:57:56.330 --> 05:57:59.430
As for them, they've tramped. I don't know to where's they are.

05:58:00.150 --> 05:58:02.130
He drew again quietly at his pipe.

05:58:03.170 --> 05:58:06.030
Unless you should take it into that head of yours, he went on,

05:58:06.290 --> 05:58:10.050
that you was included in the treaty, here's the last word that was said.

05:58:10.510 --> 05:58:12.930
How many of you are there, says I, to leave?

05:58:13.670 --> 05:58:15.970
Four, says he, four and one of us wounded.

05:58:16.630 --> 05:58:20.010
As for that boy, I don't know where he is, confound him, says he,

05:58:20.110 --> 05:58:23.170
nor I don't much care, we're about sick of him.

05:58:23.790 --> 05:58:24.950
These were his words.

05:58:26.110 --> 05:58:27.430
Is that all, I asked?

05:58:28.110 --> 05:58:31.090
Well, that's all that you're to hear, my son, returned Silver.

05:58:32.230 --> 05:58:33.570
And now I am to choose?

05:58:34.250 --> 05:58:37.590
And now you are to choose, and you may lay to that, said Silver.

05:58:38.910 --> 05:58:44.210
Well, said I, I am not such a fool, but I know pretty well what I have to look for.

05:58:44.670 --> 05:58:46.850
Let the worst come to the worstest, little I care.

05:58:47.250 --> 05:58:49.870
I've seen too many dyes since I fell in with you.

05:58:50.450 --> 05:58:54.570
But there's a thing or two I have to tell you, I said, and by this time I was quite excited.

05:58:54.570 --> 05:58:57.930
And the first is this, here you are in a bad way.

05:58:58.030 --> 05:59:01.910
Ship lost, treasure lost, men lost, your whole business gone to wreck,

05:59:02.210 --> 05:59:04.290
and if you want to know who did it, it was I.

05:59:04.770 --> 05:59:07.250
I was in the apple barrel the night we sighted land,

05:59:07.270 --> 05:59:10.270
and I heard you, John, and you, Dick Johnson and Hans,

05:59:10.590 --> 05:59:11.990
who is now at the bottom of the sea,

05:59:12.370 --> 05:59:14.930
and told every word you said before the hour was out.

05:59:15.310 --> 05:59:17.750
And as for the schooner, it was I who cut her cable,

05:59:17.790 --> 05:59:20.570
and it was I that killed the men that you had aboard of her,

05:59:20.570 --> 05:59:24.370
and it was I who brought her where you'll never see her more, not one of you.

05:59:24.810 --> 05:59:26.150
The laugh's on my side.

05:59:26.410 --> 05:59:28.410
I've had the top of this business from the first.

05:59:28.750 --> 05:59:30.970
I no more fear you than I fear a fly.

05:59:31.370 --> 05:59:33.390
Kill me if you please, or spare me.

05:59:33.650 --> 05:59:35.350
But one thing I'll say and no more,

05:59:35.770 --> 05:59:38.430
if you spare me, bygones are bygones.

05:59:38.830 --> 05:59:42.230
And when you fellows are in court for piracy, I'll save you all I can.

05:59:42.690 --> 05:59:43.810
It's for you to choose.

05:59:44.390 --> 05:59:46.190
Kill another and do yourselves no good,

05:59:46.590 --> 05:59:49.770
or spare me, and keep a witness to save you from the gallows.

05:59:51.550 --> 05:59:54.450
I stopped, for I will tell you I was out of breath,

05:59:54.690 --> 05:59:56.550
and to my wonder not a man of them moved,

05:59:56.750 --> 05:59:59.390
but all sat staring at me like as many sheep,

06:00:00.030 --> 06:00:02.510
and while they were still staring I broke out again.

06:00:03.370 --> 06:00:06.830
And now, Mr. Silver, I said, I believe you're the best man here,

06:00:07.030 --> 06:00:08.290
and if things go to the worst,

06:00:08.650 --> 06:00:11.610
I'll take it kind of you to let the doctor know the way I took it.

06:00:13.170 --> 06:00:16.390
I'll bear it in mind, said Silver with an accent so curious

06:00:16.390 --> 06:00:18.030
that I could not, for the life of me,

06:00:18.410 --> 06:00:20.370
decide whether he were laughing at my request,

06:00:20.770 --> 06:00:22.970
or had been favourably affected by my courage.

06:00:24.050 --> 06:00:28.470
I'll put one to that, cried the old mahogany-faced seaman, Morgan, by name,

06:00:28.890 --> 06:00:32.050
whom I had seen in Long John's public house upon the keys of Bristol.

06:00:32.610 --> 06:00:34.110
It was him that know'd Black Dog.

06:00:34.930 --> 06:00:36.810
Well, and see here, added the seacook,

06:00:37.110 --> 06:00:39.090
I'll put another again to that by thunder,

06:00:39.090 --> 06:00:42.070
for it was this same boy that faked the chart from Billy Bones.

06:00:42.470 --> 06:00:44.810
First and last we've split him on John Hawkins.

06:00:45.710 --> 06:00:47.750
Then here goes, said Morgan with an oath,

06:00:48.130 --> 06:00:51.030
and he sprang up, drawing his knife as if he had been twenty.

06:00:51.870 --> 06:00:53.670
Avars there, cried Silver.

06:00:54.030 --> 06:00:55.610
Who are you, Tom Morgan?

06:00:56.210 --> 06:00:59.210
Maybe you thought you was captain here, perhaps, by the powers,

06:00:59.250 --> 06:01:00.370
but I'll teach you better.

06:01:00.950 --> 06:01:03.810
Cross me and you'll go where many a good man's gone before you,

06:01:03.890 --> 06:01:05.750
first and last these thirty years back,

06:01:05.750 --> 06:01:09.110
some to the yard-arms shiver my timbers and some by the board,

06:01:09.410 --> 06:01:10.950
and all to feed the fishes.

06:01:11.490 --> 06:01:13.650
There's never a man looked me between the eyes

06:01:13.650 --> 06:01:16.750
and seen a good day afterwards, Tom Morgan, you may later that.

06:01:18.330 --> 06:01:21.250
Morgan paused, but a hoarse murmur rose from the others.

06:01:22.050 --> 06:01:23.690
Tom's right, said one.

06:01:24.490 --> 06:01:26.870
I stood hazing long enough from one, added another.

06:01:27.130 --> 06:01:29.810
I'll be hanged if I'll be hazed by you, John Silver.

06:01:31.010 --> 06:01:34.550
Did any of you gentlemen want to have it out with me?

06:01:34.550 --> 06:01:38.030
Roared Silver, bending far forward from his position on the keg,

06:01:38.090 --> 06:01:40.210
with his pipe still glowing in his right hand.

06:01:40.550 --> 06:01:43.470
Put a name on what you're at. You ain't dumb, I reckon.

06:01:44.030 --> 06:01:45.710
Him that wants shall get it.

06:01:46.010 --> 06:01:47.570
Have I lived this many years?

06:01:47.690 --> 06:01:49.450
And a sum of a rum punch and cock,

06:01:49.590 --> 06:01:51.990
his hat a thwart my house at the latter end of it.

06:01:52.510 --> 06:01:55.770
You know the way, you're all gentlemen of fortune by your account.

06:01:56.350 --> 06:01:59.170
While I'm ready, take a cutlass him that dares,

06:01:59.210 --> 06:02:00.910
and I'll see the colour of his inside,

06:02:00.910 --> 06:02:03.490
crutch an awl before that pipe's empty.

06:02:05.670 --> 06:02:06.870
Not a man stirred.

06:02:07.990 --> 06:02:09.330
Not a man answered.

06:02:10.470 --> 06:02:12.150
That's your sort, is it?

06:02:12.330 --> 06:02:14.490
he added, returning his pipe to his mouth.

06:02:15.470 --> 06:02:17.850
Well, you're a gay lot to look at anyway.

06:02:18.450 --> 06:02:20.410
Not much worth to fight, yaint.

06:02:20.990 --> 06:02:23.230
Perhaps you can understand King George's English.

06:02:23.810 --> 06:02:25.750
I'm captain here by lection.

06:02:26.250 --> 06:02:29.870
I'm captain here because I'm the best man by a long sea mile.

06:02:29.870 --> 06:02:33.150
You won't fight as gentlemen of fortune should.

06:02:33.450 --> 06:02:36.370
Then by thunder you'll obey, and you may lay to it.

06:02:36.810 --> 06:02:38.250
I like that boy now.

06:02:38.650 --> 06:02:40.470
I never seen a better boy than that.

06:02:40.810 --> 06:02:43.670
He's more a man than any pair of rats are you in this here house.

06:02:43.970 --> 06:02:45.290
And what I say is this.

06:02:46.030 --> 06:02:48.330
Let me see him that'll lay a hand on him.

06:02:48.610 --> 06:02:50.930
That's what I say, and you may lay to it.

06:02:52.270 --> 06:02:54.370
There was a long pause after this.

06:02:54.650 --> 06:02:56.450
I stood straight up against the wall,

06:02:56.550 --> 06:02:58.390
my heart still going like a sledgehammer,

06:02:58.390 --> 06:03:01.770
but with a ray of hope now shining in my bosom.

06:03:02.010 --> 06:03:03.510
Silver leant back against the wall,

06:03:03.710 --> 06:03:06.410
his arms crossed, his pipe in the corner of his mouth,

06:03:06.850 --> 06:03:08.750
as calm as though he had been in church.

06:03:09.330 --> 06:03:11.350
Yet his eye kept wandering furtively,

06:03:11.750 --> 06:03:13.830
and he kept the tail of it on his unruly followers.

06:03:14.790 --> 06:03:17.430
They, on their part, drew gradually together

06:03:17.430 --> 06:03:19.110
towards the far end of the blockhouse,

06:03:19.630 --> 06:03:21.130
and the low hiss of their whispering

06:03:21.130 --> 06:03:23.690
sounded in my ear continuously like a stream.

06:03:24.630 --> 06:03:26.450
One after another they would look up,

06:03:26.450 --> 06:03:28.330
and the red light of the torch would fall

06:03:28.330 --> 06:03:30.110
for a second on their nervous faces.

06:03:30.730 --> 06:03:32.230
But it was not towards me.

06:03:32.790 --> 06:03:35.310
It was towards Silver that they turned their eyes.

06:03:37.090 --> 06:03:38.850
You seem to have a lot to say,

06:03:39.170 --> 06:03:41.330
remarked Silver, spitting far into the air.

06:03:41.930 --> 06:03:44.070
Pipe up and let me hear it or lay to.

06:03:45.490 --> 06:03:47.930
Ask your pardon, sir, returned one of the men.

06:03:48.410 --> 06:03:50.130
You're pretty free with some of the rules.

06:03:50.250 --> 06:03:52.330
Maybe you'll kindly keep an eye upon the rest.

06:03:52.910 --> 06:03:54.510
This crew's dissatisfied.

06:03:54.510 --> 06:03:57.530
This crew don't valley-bullying like a marlin spike.

06:03:58.030 --> 06:04:00.130
This crew has its rights like other crews.

06:04:00.550 --> 06:04:01.750
I'll make so free as that,

06:04:01.770 --> 06:04:04.230
and by your own rules I take it we can talk together.

06:04:04.910 --> 06:04:06.810
I ask your pardon, sir, acknowledging you

06:04:06.810 --> 06:04:08.270
for to be captain at the moment.

06:04:08.830 --> 06:04:11.910
But I claim my right and steps outside for a council.

06:04:14.210 --> 06:04:15.850
And with an elaborate sea salute,

06:04:16.150 --> 06:04:20.090
this fellow, a long, ill-looking yellow-eyed man of five and thirty,

06:04:20.090 --> 06:04:23.630
stepped coolly towards the door and disappeared out of the house.

06:04:24.590 --> 06:04:26.670
One after another the rest followed his example,

06:04:26.810 --> 06:04:28.190
each making a salute as he passed,

06:04:28.610 --> 06:04:29.950
each adding some apology.

06:04:30.850 --> 06:04:32.690
According to the rules, said one,

06:04:33.130 --> 06:04:34.810
foxtal council, said Morgan.

06:04:35.910 --> 06:04:37.430
And so with one remark or another,

06:04:37.910 --> 06:04:41.310
all marched out and left Silver and me alone with a torch.

06:04:43.630 --> 06:04:45.550
The sea cook instantly removed his pipe.

06:04:47.230 --> 06:04:49.130
Now look you here, Jim Hawkins,

06:04:49.130 --> 06:04:52.710
he said with a steady whisper that was no more than audible.

06:04:53.570 --> 06:04:55.270
You're within half a plank of death,

06:04:55.290 --> 06:04:57.350
and what's alongside worse, of torture.

06:04:57.910 --> 06:04:59.290
They're gonna throw me off.

06:04:59.810 --> 06:05:02.370
But you, Mark, I stand by you through thick and thin.

06:05:02.810 --> 06:05:05.370
I didn't mean to, no, not till you spoke up.

06:05:05.910 --> 06:05:08.030
I was about desperate to lose that much blunt

06:05:08.030 --> 06:05:09.810
and be hanged into the bargain.

06:05:10.530 --> 06:05:12.090
But I see you as the right sort.

06:05:12.670 --> 06:05:14.650
I says to myself, you stand by Hawkins,

06:05:14.890 --> 06:05:16.630
John, and Hawkins will stand by you.

06:05:16.950 --> 06:05:18.150
You're his last card,

06:05:18.150 --> 06:05:20.430
and by the living thunder, John, he's yours.

06:05:21.030 --> 06:05:22.350
Back to back says I.

06:05:23.010 --> 06:05:25.130
You save your witness, and he'll save your neck.

06:05:26.290 --> 06:05:28.730
I began dimly to understand.

06:05:29.730 --> 06:05:31.850
You mean all's lost, I asked.

06:05:32.450 --> 06:05:34.470
Aye, by gum I do, he answered.

06:05:35.110 --> 06:05:37.670
Ship gone, neck gone, that's the size of it.

06:05:37.950 --> 06:05:39.730
Once I looked into that bay, Jim Hawkins,

06:05:39.810 --> 06:05:40.870
and seen no schooner.

06:05:41.370 --> 06:05:43.070
Well, I'm tough, but I gave out.

06:05:43.510 --> 06:05:44.950
As for that lot and their council,

06:05:45.150 --> 06:05:47.390
mark me, they're outright fools and cowards.

06:05:47.390 --> 06:05:49.310
I'll save your life,

06:05:49.410 --> 06:05:51.470
if so be as I can, from them.

06:05:51.990 --> 06:05:53.810
But see here, Jim, tit for tat,

06:05:54.270 --> 06:05:55.850
you save Long John from swinging.

06:05:57.530 --> 06:05:58.870
I was bewildered.

06:05:59.290 --> 06:06:01.090
It seemed a thing so hopeless he was asking,

06:06:01.270 --> 06:06:03.750
he, the old buccaneer, the ringleader threw out.

06:06:04.450 --> 06:06:06.850
What I can do, that I'll do, I said.

06:06:07.530 --> 06:06:09.290
It's a bargain, cried Long John.

06:06:09.870 --> 06:06:11.550
You speak up, plucky, and by thunder,

06:06:11.850 --> 06:06:12.710
I've a chance.

06:06:14.450 --> 06:06:15.910
He hobbled to the torch,

06:06:15.910 --> 06:06:17.970
where it stood propped among the firewood,

06:06:18.550 --> 06:06:20.250
and took a fresh light to his pipe.

06:06:21.530 --> 06:06:23.630
Understand me, Jim, he said, returning.

06:06:24.070 --> 06:06:25.670
I've a head on my shoulders, I have.

06:06:25.850 --> 06:06:27.510
I'm on Squire's side now.

06:06:27.870 --> 06:06:29.990
I know that you've got that ship safe somewheres.

06:06:30.830 --> 06:06:33.250
How you done it, I don't know, but safe it is.

06:06:33.650 --> 06:06:35.890
I guess Hans and O'Brien turned soft.

06:06:36.290 --> 06:06:38.470
I never much believed in neither of them.

06:06:39.450 --> 06:06:40.570
Now you mark me.

06:06:40.690 --> 06:06:43.010
I ask no questions, nor I won't let others.

06:06:43.310 --> 06:06:45.030
I know when a game's up, I do.

06:06:45.030 --> 06:06:47.350
And I know a lad that's staunch.

06:06:47.570 --> 06:06:48.590
Ah, you that's young.

06:06:48.670 --> 06:06:51.230
You and me might have done the power of good together.

06:06:53.030 --> 06:06:56.210
He drew some cognac from the cask into a tin canikin.

06:06:56.890 --> 06:06:58.670
Will you taste, mess-mate, he asked.

06:06:58.950 --> 06:07:03.150
And when I had refused, well, I'll take a drain myself, Jim, said he.

06:07:03.670 --> 06:07:05.770
I need a corker, that's the trouble on land.

06:07:06.670 --> 06:07:09.830
And talking of trouble, why did that doctor give me the chart, Jim?

06:07:11.310 --> 06:07:13.230
My face expressed a wonder so unaffected

06:07:13.230 --> 06:07:16.110
that he saw the needlessness of further questions.

06:07:16.850 --> 06:07:19.430
Ah, well, he did, though, said he.

06:07:19.690 --> 06:07:21.250
And there's something under that, no doubt,

06:07:21.390 --> 06:07:24.410
something surely under that, Jim, bad or good.

06:07:25.670 --> 06:07:28.030
And he took another swallow of the brandy,

06:07:28.230 --> 06:07:31.950
shaking his great fair head like a man who looks forward to the worst.

06:07:43.430 --> 06:07:43.490
Thank you.

06:07:58.330 --> 06:08:05.090
Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson. Chapter 29. The Black Spot Again.

06:08:06.810 --> 06:08:11.730
The Council of Buccaneers had lasted some time when one of them re-entered the house,

06:08:11.730 --> 06:08:16.210
and with a repetition of the same salute which had in my eyes an

06:08:16.210 --> 06:08:19.770
ironical air, begged for a moment's loan of the torch.

06:08:20.990 --> 06:08:26.490
Silver briefly agreed, and this emissary retired again, leaving us together in the dark.

06:08:27.670 --> 06:08:33.550
There's a breeze coming, Jim, said Silver, who had by this time adopted quite a friendly

06:08:33.550 --> 06:08:38.550
and familiar tone. I turned to the loophole nearest me and looked out.

06:08:38.550 --> 06:08:44.870
The embers of the great fire had so far burned themselves out and now glowed so low and duskily

06:08:44.870 --> 06:08:48.930
that I understood why these conspirators desired a torch.

06:08:50.030 --> 06:08:56.370
About halfway down the slope to the stockade they were collected in a group. One held the light,

06:08:56.890 --> 06:09:03.270
another was on his knees in their midst, and I saw the blade of an open knife shine in his hand

06:09:03.270 --> 06:09:06.510
with varying colors in the moon and torchlight.

06:09:07.550 --> 06:09:12.010
The rest were all somewhat stooping as though watching the maneuvers of this last.

06:09:13.090 --> 06:09:17.170
I could just make out that he had a book as well as a knife in his hand,

06:09:17.630 --> 06:09:22.310
and was still wondering how anything so incongruous had come in their possession

06:09:22.310 --> 06:09:28.630
when the kneeling figure rose once more to his feet and the whole party began to move together

06:09:28.630 --> 06:09:29.770
towards the house.

06:09:30.650 --> 06:09:37.050
Here they come, said I, and I returned to my former position, for it seemed beneath my dignity

06:09:37.050 --> 06:09:39.390
that they should find me watching them.

06:09:40.230 --> 06:09:46.770
Well, let them come, lad, let them come, said Silver cheerfully. I've still a shot in my locker.

06:09:48.110 --> 06:09:53.690
The door opened and the five men standing huddled together just inside pushed one of

06:09:53.690 --> 06:10:00.370
their number forward. In any other circumstances it would have been comical to see his slow advance,

06:10:00.850 --> 06:10:06.490
hesitating as he set down each foot, but holding his closed right hand in front of him.

06:10:07.170 --> 06:10:14.410
Step up, lad, cried Silver. I won't eat you. Hand it over, lover. I know the rules I do.

06:10:14.550 --> 06:10:16.370
I won't hurt your deputation.

06:10:18.350 --> 06:10:23.830
Thus encouraged, the buccaneer stepped forward more briskly, and having passed something to Silver

06:10:23.830 --> 06:10:28.730
from hand to hand, slipped yet more smartly back again to his companions.

06:10:29.990 --> 06:10:32.170
The seacook looked at what had been given him.

06:10:32.730 --> 06:10:40.070
The black spot, I thought so, he observed. Where might ye have got the paper? Why,

06:10:40.070 --> 06:10:47.390
look here now. This ain't lucky. You've gone and cut this out of a Bible. What fools cut a Bible.

06:10:48.550 --> 06:10:54.830
Ah, there, said Morgan, there. What did I say? No good'll come of that, I said.

06:10:56.190 --> 06:10:59.270
Well, you've about fixed it now among you,

06:11:00.050 --> 06:11:05.950
continued Silver. You'll all swing now, I reckon. What soft-headed lubber had a Bible?

06:11:06.730 --> 06:11:13.250
It was Dick, said one. Dick was it? Then Dick can get to prayers, said Silver.

06:11:14.310 --> 06:11:17.630
He's seen his slice of luck as Dick, and you may lay to that.

06:11:18.810 --> 06:11:21.970
But here the long man with the yellow eyes struck in.

06:11:22.510 --> 06:11:28.870
Belay that talk, Silver, he said. This crew has tipped you the black spot in full counsel,

06:11:29.230 --> 06:11:35.250
as in duty bound. Just you turn it over, as in duty bound, and see what's wrote there.

06:11:35.250 --> 06:11:42.210
Then you can talk. Thank ye, George, replied the sea cook. You've always was brisk for business,

06:11:42.250 --> 06:11:47.850
and has the rules at heart, George, as I'm pleased to see. Well, what is it, anyway?

06:11:49.810 --> 06:11:57.030
Ah, deposed. That's it, is it? Very pretty wrote, to be sure. Like print, I swear.

06:11:57.710 --> 06:12:03.350
Your hand aright, George? Why, you was getting quite a leadin' man in this here crew.

06:12:03.350 --> 06:12:09.710
You'll be captain next, I shouldn't wonder. Just oblige me with that torch again, will you?

06:12:09.730 --> 06:12:18.850
This pipe don't draw. Come now, said George, you don't fool this crew no more. You're a funny man

06:12:18.850 --> 06:12:24.670
by your account, but you're over now, and you'll maybe step down off that barrel and help vote.

06:12:25.790 --> 06:12:32.870
I thought you said you knowed the rules, returned Silver contemptuously. Least ways if you don't,

06:12:32.870 --> 06:12:39.490
I do, and I wait here, and I'm still your captain, mind, till you outs with your grievances,

06:12:39.490 --> 06:12:46.510
and I reply, in the meantime, your black spot ain't worth a biscuit. After that, we'll see.

06:12:47.550 --> 06:12:55.950
Oh, replied George, you don't be under no kind of apprehension. We're all square we are. First,

06:12:55.970 --> 06:13:02.770
you've made a hash of this cruise. You'll be a bold man to say no to that. Second, you let

06:13:02.770 --> 06:13:08.970
the enemy out of this here trap for nothin'. Why did they want out? I don't know, but it's

06:13:08.970 --> 06:13:16.290
pretty plain they wanted it. Third, you wouldn't let us go with them upon the march. Oh, we see

06:13:16.290 --> 06:13:23.050
through you, John Silver. You want to play booty, that's what's wrong with you. And then, fourth,

06:13:23.630 --> 06:13:29.210
there's this here boy. Is that all? asked Silver quietly.

06:13:29.990 --> 06:13:36.150
Enough, two, retorted George. We'll all swing and sundry for your bungling.

06:13:37.790 --> 06:13:42.370
Well, now, look here. I'll answer these far pints one after another, I'll answer them.

06:13:42.870 --> 06:13:49.130
I made a hash of this cruise, did I? Well, now, you all know what I wanted, and you all know if

06:13:49.130 --> 06:13:54.350
that had been done that we'd have been aboard the Hispagnola this night as ever was, every man of

06:13:54.350 --> 06:13:59.830
us alive and fit and full of good plum duff, and the treasure in the hold of her by thunder.

06:14:00.990 --> 06:14:07.910
Well, who crossed me? Who forced my hand as was the lawful captain? Who tipped me the black spot

06:14:07.910 --> 06:14:14.330
the day we landed and began this dance? Ah, it's a fine dance, I'm with you there, and looks mighty

06:14:14.330 --> 06:14:21.550
like a hornpipe in a rope's end at Execution Dock, my London town it does. But who done it? Why,

06:14:21.550 --> 06:14:28.090
it was Anderson and Hans and you, George Mary, and you're the last aboveboard of that same

06:14:28.090 --> 06:14:34.170
meddling crew, and you have the Davy Jones insolence to have up and stand for captain over me,

06:14:34.490 --> 06:14:41.030
you that sank the lot of us? By the powers, but this tops the stiffest yarn to nothing.

06:14:42.770 --> 06:14:48.630
Silver paused, and I could see by the faces of George and his late comrades that these words had

06:14:48.630 --> 06:14:55.410
been said in vain. That's for number one, cried the accused, wiping the sweat from his brow,

06:14:55.750 --> 06:15:00.970
for he had been talking with the vehemence that shook the house. Why, I give you my word,

06:15:00.990 --> 06:15:07.070
I'm sick to speak to you. You've neither sense nor memory, and I leave it to fancy where your

06:15:07.070 --> 06:15:14.040
mother's was that let you come to see. See, gentlemen of fortune, I reckon Taylor's is your

06:15:14.040 --> 06:15:22.900
aid. Go on, John, said Morgan, speak up to the others. Ah, the others, returned John.

06:15:23.920 --> 06:15:29.860
They're a nice lot, ain't they? You say this cruise is bungled? Ah, by gum, if you could

06:15:29.860 --> 06:15:36.080
understand how bad it's bungled, you would see. We're that near the gibbet that my neck's stiff

06:15:36.080 --> 06:15:42.200
with thinking on it. You've seen them, maybe, hanged in chains, birds about them, seamen

06:15:42.200 --> 06:15:47.860
pointing them out as they go down with the tide. Who's that, says one? That, why, that's John

06:15:47.860 --> 06:15:54.180
Silver. I knowed him well, said another. And you can hear the chains a-jangle as you go about and

06:15:54.180 --> 06:15:59.800
reach for the other buoy. Now, that's about where we are, every mother's son of us, thanks to him

06:15:59.800 --> 06:16:06.960
and Hans and Anderson and other ruination fools of you. And if you want to know about number four,

06:16:06.960 --> 06:16:13.820
and that boy, why, shiver me timbers, isn't he a hostage? Are we going to waste a hostage?

06:16:14.220 --> 06:16:21.740
No, not us. He might be our last chance and I wouldn't wonder. Kill that boy, not me, mates.

06:16:22.540 --> 06:16:29.060
And number three, ah, well, there's a deal to say to number three. Maybe you don't count it

06:16:29.060 --> 06:16:35.660
nothing to have a real college doctor to see you every day, you, John, with your head broke, or you,

06:16:35.660 --> 06:16:41.900
George, Mary, that had the og shakes about you not six hours ago, and has your eyes the color of

06:16:41.900 --> 06:16:47.900
lemon peel to this same moment of the clock. And maybe, perhaps, you didn't know there was a consort

06:16:47.900 --> 06:16:54.760
coming either. But there is, and not so long till then, and we'll see who'll be glad to have a

06:16:54.760 --> 06:17:02.200
hostage when it comes to that. And as for number two, and why I made a bargain, well, you came

06:17:02.200 --> 06:17:09.860
crawling on your knees to me to make it. On your knees you came. You was downhearted and you'd have

06:17:09.860 --> 06:17:17.280
starved, too, if I hadn't. But that's a trifle. You look there, that's why. And he cast down upon

06:17:17.280 --> 06:17:23.740
the floor a paper that I instantly recognized, none other than the chart on yellow paper with

06:17:23.740 --> 06:17:28.880
the three red crosses that I had found in the oilcloth at the bottom of the captain's chest.

06:17:29.440 --> 06:17:32.900
Why the doctor had given it to him was more than I could fancy.

06:17:33.840 --> 06:17:39.500
But if it were inexplicable to me, the appearance of the chart was incredible to the surviving

06:17:39.500 --> 06:17:46.280
mutineers. They leaped upon it like cats upon a mouse. It went from hand to hand, one tearing

06:17:46.280 --> 06:17:51.280
it from another. And by the oaths and the cries and the childish laughter with which they

06:17:51.280 --> 06:17:56.320
accompanied their examination, you would have thought not only were they fingering the very gold,

06:17:56.320 --> 06:18:03.660
but were at sea with it besides in safety. Yes, said one, that's flint, sure enough.

06:18:03.920 --> 06:18:08.640
J.F. and a score below with the clove hitched to it. So he done ever.

06:18:10.240 --> 06:18:16.160
Mighty pretty, said George, but how are we to get away with it and us no ship?

06:18:17.420 --> 06:18:21.920
Silver suddenly sprang up and supporting himself with a hand against the wall.

06:18:22.480 --> 06:18:28.060
Now I give you warning, George, he cried. One more word of your sauce and I'll call you down

06:18:28.060 --> 06:18:34.260
and fight you. How? Why, how do I know? You would ought to tell me that. You and the rest

06:18:34.260 --> 06:18:40.460
that lost me my schooner with your interference burn you. But not in you you can't. You ain't got

06:18:40.460 --> 06:18:46.500
the invention of a cockroach. But civil you can speak and shall, George Mary, you may lay to that.

06:18:47.260 --> 06:18:50.020
Now that's fair enough, said the old man Morgan.

06:18:51.420 --> 06:18:58.080
Fair, I reckon so, said the sea cook. You lost the ship, I found the treasure. Who's the better man

06:18:58.080 --> 06:19:04.720
at that? And now I resign by thunder. Elect whom you please to be your captain now. I'm done with

06:19:04.720 --> 06:19:13.360
it. Silver, they cried. Barbecue forever. Barbecue for captain. So that's the tune as it cried the

06:19:14.160 --> 06:19:19.800
George, I reckon you'll have to wait another turn friend and lucky for you as I'm not a revengeful

06:19:19.800 --> 06:19:28.420
man, but that never was my way. And now shipmates, this black spot, taint much good now, is it?

06:19:28.840 --> 06:19:33.380
Dick's crossed his luck and spoiled his Bible and that's about all.

06:19:34.580 --> 06:19:43.340
It'll do to kiss the book on still, won't it? growled Dick, who was evidently uneasy at the

06:19:43.340 --> 06:19:50.260
Bible with a bit cut out, returned Silver derisively. Not it. It won't buy no more in a

06:19:50.260 --> 06:19:58.180
ballot book. Don't it though? cried Dick with a sort of joy. Well, I reckon that's worth having too.

06:19:59.860 --> 06:20:04.420
Here Jim, here's a curiosity for you, said Silver and he tossed me the paper.

06:20:05.500 --> 06:20:11.560
It was around the size of a crown piece. One side was blank for it had been the last leaf.

06:20:11.560 --> 06:20:17.800
The other contained a verse or two of Revelation. These words among the rest which struck sharply

06:20:17.800 --> 06:20:26.020
home upon my mind. Without are dogs and murderers. The printed side had been blackened with wood ash

06:20:26.020 --> 06:20:31.540
which already began to come off and soil my fingers. On the blank side had been written

06:20:31.540 --> 06:20:38.600
with the same material the one word deposed. I had that curiosity beside me at this moment,

06:20:38.600 --> 06:20:44.960
but not a trace of writing now remains beyond a single scratch such as a man might make with

06:20:44.960 --> 06:20:51.900
his thumbnail. That was the end of the night's business. Soon after with a drink all round we

06:20:51.900 --> 06:20:57.740
lay down to sleep and the outside of Silver's vengeance was to put George Mary up for sentinel

06:20:57.740 --> 06:21:04.720
and threaten him with death if he should prove unfaithful. It was long ere I could close an eye

06:21:04.720 --> 06:21:10.220
and heaven knows I had matter enough for thought in the man whom I had slain that afternoon

06:21:10.220 --> 06:21:17.260
in my most perilous position and above all in the remarkable game that I saw Silver now engaged upon

06:21:17.260 --> 06:21:23.260
keeping the mutineers together with one hand and grasping with the other after every means

06:21:23.260 --> 06:21:30.900
possible and impossible to make his peace and save his miserable life. He himself slept peacefully

06:21:30.900 --> 06:21:38.240
and snored aloud yet my heart was sore for him, wicked as he was, to think on the dark perils

06:21:38.240 --> 06:21:44.320
that environed and the shameful gibbet that awaited him.

06:22:03.940 --> 06:22:04.540
I

06:22:05.960 --> 06:22:10.880
was wakened—indeed, we were all wakened, for I could see even the sentinel shake himself

06:22:10.880 --> 06:22:16.180
together from where he had fallen against the door-post, by a clear, hearty voice hailing

06:22:16.180 --> 06:22:17.860
us from the margin of the wood.

06:22:19.200 --> 06:22:21.180
"'Blockhouse ahoy!' it cried.

06:22:21.500 --> 06:22:23.620
"'Here's the doctor!'

06:22:23.620 --> 06:22:25.320
And the doctor it was.

06:22:25.800 --> 06:22:30.840
Although I was glad to hear the sound, yet my gladness was not without admixture.

06:22:31.380 --> 06:22:37.220
I remembered with confusion my insubordinate and stealthy conduct, and when I saw where

06:22:37.220 --> 06:22:42.960
it had brought me, among what companions and surrounded by what dangers, I felt ashamed

06:22:42.960 --> 06:22:44.300
to look him in the face.

06:22:45.340 --> 06:22:50.720
He must have risen in the dark, for the day had hardly come, and when I ran to a loophole

06:22:50.720 --> 06:22:56.740
and looked out, I saw him standing, like Silver once before, up to the mid-leg in creeping

06:22:56.740 --> 06:22:57.220
vapor.

06:22:58.620 --> 06:22:59.700
"'You, doctor!

06:22:59.820 --> 06:23:04.980
Top of the mornin' to you, sir!' cried Silver, broad awake and beaming with good

06:23:04.980 --> 06:23:06.000
nature in a moment.

06:23:06.520 --> 06:23:11.040
"'Bright and early, to be sure, and it's the early bird, as the saying goes, that gets

06:23:11.040 --> 06:23:11.800
the rations.

06:23:12.320 --> 06:23:16.800
George, shake up your timber, son, and help Dr. Livesey over the ship's side.

06:23:17.200 --> 06:23:21.960
All a' doin' well, your patients, was all merry and well.'

06:23:21.960 --> 06:23:27.780
So he padded on, standing on the hilltop with his crutch under his elbow, and one hand upon

06:23:27.780 --> 06:23:32.380
the side of the log-house, quite the old John in voice, manner, and expression.

06:23:33.660 --> 06:23:37.560
"'We've quite a surprise for you too, sir,' he continued.

06:23:37.880 --> 06:23:39.980
"'We've a little stranger here.

06:23:40.620 --> 06:23:45.420
A new boarder and lodger, sir, and lookin' fit and taut as a fiddle.

06:23:45.700 --> 06:23:49.320
Slept like a super-cargo he did, right alongside a John.

06:23:49.920 --> 06:23:52.040
Stem to stem we was all night.'

06:23:53.240 --> 06:23:59.180
Dr. Livesey was by this time across the stockade and pretty near the cook, and I could hear

06:23:59.180 --> 06:24:02.820
the alteration in his voice as he said, "'Not Jim.

06:24:03.620 --> 06:24:06.960
The very same Jim as ever was,' said Silver.

06:24:08.120 --> 06:24:13.420
The doctor stopped outright, although he did not speak, and it was some seconds before

06:24:13.420 --> 06:24:14.960
he seemed able to move on.

06:24:15.920 --> 06:24:22.040
"'Well, well,' he said at last, "'duty first and pleasure afterwards, as you might have

06:24:22.040 --> 06:24:23.160
said yourself, Silver.

06:24:23.600 --> 06:24:26.860
Let us overhaul these patients of yours.'

06:24:26.860 --> 06:24:32.860
A moment afterwards he had entered the block-house, and with one grim nod to me proceeded with

06:24:32.860 --> 06:24:34.200
his work among the sick.

06:24:35.200 --> 06:24:39.980
He seemed under no apprehension, though he must have known that his life among these

06:24:39.980 --> 06:24:45.860
treacherous demons depended on a hair, and he rattled on to his patients as if he were

06:24:45.860 --> 06:24:49.840
paying an ordinary professional visit in a quiet English family.

06:24:50.820 --> 06:24:56.140
His manner, I suppose, reacted on the men, for they all behaved to him as if nothing

06:24:56.140 --> 06:25:01.020
had occurred, as if he were still ship's doctor, and they were still faithful hands

06:25:01.020 --> 06:25:01.940
before the mast.

06:25:03.140 --> 06:25:07.660
"'You're doing well, my friend,' he said to the fellow with the bandaged head,

06:25:07.980 --> 06:25:11.180
"'and if ever any person has a close shave, it was you.

06:25:11.580 --> 06:25:13.770
Your head must have been hard as iron.'

06:25:14.640 --> 06:25:16.280
"'Well, George, how goes it?

06:25:16.280 --> 06:25:17.920
You're a pretty color, certainly.

06:25:18.520 --> 06:25:20.620
Why, your liver man is upside down.

06:25:20.660 --> 06:25:21.840
Did you take that medicine?

06:25:22.420 --> 06:25:24.680
Did he take that medicine, then?'

06:25:24.680 --> 06:25:28.780
"'Aye, aye, sir, he took it, sure enough,' returned Morgan.

06:25:29.760 --> 06:25:34.920
"'Because, you see, since I am mutineer's doctor, or prison doctor, as I prefer to call

06:25:34.920 --> 06:25:41.280
it,' said Dr. Livesey, in his pleasantest way, I make it a point of honor not to lose

06:25:41.280 --> 06:25:45.760
a man for King George, God bless him, and the gallows.'

06:25:45.760 --> 06:25:50.200
The rogues looked at each other, but swallowed the home thrust in silence.

06:25:51.140 --> 06:25:54.040
"'Dick don't feel well, sir,' said one.

06:25:54.400 --> 06:25:56.240
"'Don't he?' replied the doctor.

06:25:56.280 --> 06:25:59.440
"'Well, step up here, Dick, and let me see your tongue.'

06:26:00.220 --> 06:26:02.660
"'No, I should be surprised if he did.

06:26:02.920 --> 06:26:05.760
The man's tongue is fit to frighten the French.

06:26:06.300 --> 06:26:07.560
Another fever.'

06:26:08.220 --> 06:26:12.140
"'Ah, there,' said Morgan, that come to spiling Bibles.

06:26:13.060 --> 06:26:19.600
That comes, as you call it, of being arrant asses,' retorted the doctor, and not having

06:26:19.600 --> 06:26:25.240
sense enough to know honest air from poison, and the dry land from a vile, pestiferous

06:26:25.240 --> 06:26:25.940
slew.

06:26:26.740 --> 06:26:32.100
I think it most probable, though of course it's only an opinion, that you'll all have

06:26:32.100 --> 06:26:35.600
the deuce to pay before you get that malaria out of your system.

06:26:36.840 --> 06:26:38.340
Camp in a bog, would you?

06:26:39.100 --> 06:26:40.900
Silver, I'm surprised at you.

06:26:41.120 --> 06:26:45.960
You're less of a fool than many, take you all around, but you don't appear to me to

06:26:45.960 --> 06:26:48.410
notion of the rules of health.'

06:26:49.640 --> 06:26:54.360
"'Well,' he added, after he had dosed them round, and they had taken his prescriptions

06:26:54.360 --> 06:27:00.440
with really laughable humility, more like charity schoolchildren than blood-guilty mutineers

06:27:00.440 --> 06:27:03.180
and pirates, "'well, that's done for today.

06:27:03.840 --> 06:27:07.500
And now I should wish to have a talk with that boy, please.'

06:27:08.050 --> 06:27:10.880
And he nodded his head in my direction carelessly.

06:27:12.120 --> 06:27:18.260
George Mary was at the door, spitting and spluttering over some bad-tasted medicine,

06:27:19.000 --> 06:27:23.680
but at the first word of the doctor's proposal he swung round with a deep flush and cried,

06:27:24.520 --> 06:27:26.500
"'No!' and swore.

06:27:27.320 --> 06:27:29.620
Silver struck the barrel with his open hand.

06:27:30.920 --> 06:27:35.500
"'Silence!' he roared, and looked about him positively like a lion.

06:27:36.400 --> 06:27:38.660
"'Doctor,' he went on in his usual tones.

06:27:38.660 --> 06:27:43.180
I was a-thinkin' of that, knowin' as how you had a fancy for the boy.

06:27:44.020 --> 06:27:49.300
We're all humbly grateful for your kindness, and as you see, puts faith in you, and takes

06:27:49.300 --> 06:27:51.420
the drugs down like that much grog.

06:27:52.340 --> 06:27:55.080
And I take it I've found your way as'll suit all.

06:27:55.740 --> 06:28:00.800
Hawkins, will you give me your word of honor as a young gentleman, for a young gentleman

06:28:00.800 --> 06:28:06.880
you are, although poor-born, your word of honor not to slip your cable?'

06:28:06.880 --> 06:28:09.060
I readily gave the pledge required.

06:28:09.800 --> 06:28:15.340
"'Then, Doctor,' said Silver, you just step outside of that stockade, and once you're

06:28:15.340 --> 06:28:20.440
there I'll bring the boy down on the inside, and I reckon you can yarn through the spars.

06:28:21.160 --> 06:28:27.280
Good day to you, sir, and all of our duties to the Squire and Captain Smollett.'

06:28:27.280 --> 06:28:33.040
The explosion of disapproval, which nothing but Silver's black looks had restrained, broke

06:28:33.040 --> 06:28:35.620
out immediately the doctor had left the house.

06:28:36.420 --> 06:28:42.240
Silver was roundly accused of playing double, of trying to make a separate piece for himself,

06:28:42.860 --> 06:28:48.860
of sacrificing the interests of his accomplices and victims, and, in one word, of the identical

06:28:48.860 --> 06:28:50.820
exact thing that he was doing.

06:28:51.820 --> 06:28:57.200
It seemed to me so obvious in this case that I could not imagine how he was to turn their

06:28:57.200 --> 06:29:02.680
anger, but he was twice the man the rest were, and his last night's victory had given him

06:29:02.680 --> 06:29:04.840
a huge preponderance on their minds.

06:29:05.680 --> 06:29:10.580
He called them all the fools and doachs you can imagine, said it was necessary that I

06:29:10.580 --> 06:29:15.940
should talk to the doctor, fluttered the charts in their very faces, asked them if they could

06:29:15.940 --> 06:29:20.140
afford to break the treaty that very day they were bound to treasure hunting.

06:29:21.080 --> 06:29:26.580
"'No, by thunder,' he cried, "'it's us must break the treaty when the time comes.

06:29:26.960 --> 06:29:32.580
Until then I'll gammon that doctor if I have to aisle his boots with brandy.'

06:29:32.580 --> 06:29:37.660
And then he bade them to get the fire lit, and stalked out upon his crutch with his hand

06:29:37.660 --> 06:29:43.960
on my shoulder, leaving them in a disarray, and silenced by his volubility rather than

06:29:43.960 --> 06:29:44.540
convinced.

06:29:45.880 --> 06:29:51.840
"'Slow, lad, slow,' he said, they might round upon us in a twinkle of an eye if we was seen

06:29:51.840 --> 06:29:53.680
to hurry.'

06:29:53.680 --> 06:29:59.060
Very deliberately, then, did we advance across the sand to where the doctor awaited us on

06:29:59.060 --> 06:30:04.460
the other side of the stockade, and as soon as we were within easy speaking distance Silver

06:30:04.460 --> 06:30:04.900
stopped.

06:30:06.180 --> 06:30:11.460
"'You'll make a note of this here also, doctor,' he said, "'and the boy'll tell you how I saved

06:30:11.460 --> 06:30:15.720
his life, and were deposed for it too, and you may lay to that.

06:30:16.340 --> 06:30:22.580
Doctor, when a man steering as near the wind as me, paying chuck farthing with the last

06:30:22.580 --> 06:30:27.240
breath in his body, like, you wouldn't think it too much, mayhap, to give him one last

06:30:27.240 --> 06:30:27.940
good word.

06:30:28.780 --> 06:30:34.160
You'll please bear in mind that it's not my life only now, it's that boy's into the bargain,

06:30:34.680 --> 06:30:39.640
and you'll speak me fair, doctor, and give me a bit of hope to go on for the sake of

06:30:41.040 --> 06:30:41.560
mercy.'

06:30:41.560 --> 06:30:47.180
Silver was a changed man once he was out there and had his back to his friends in the blockhouse.

06:30:47.920 --> 06:30:54.020
His cheeks seemed to have fallen in, his voice trembled, never was a soul more dead in earnest.

06:30:55.120 --> 06:30:59.080
"'Why, John, you're not afraid?' asked Dr. Livesey.

06:30:59.740 --> 06:31:05.200
"'Doctor, I'm no coward, no, not I, not so much,' and he snapped his fingers.

06:31:05.560 --> 06:31:11.420
"'If I was, I wouldn't say it, but I'll own up fairly, I've the shakes upon me for the

06:31:11.420 --> 06:31:11.820
gallows.

06:31:12.120 --> 06:31:17.160
You're a good man and a true, I've never seen a better man, and you'll not forget what

06:31:17.160 --> 06:31:21.060
I done good, not any more than you'll forget the bad I know.

06:31:21.680 --> 06:31:26.740
And I step aside, see here, and leave you and Jim alone, and you'll put that down for

06:31:26.740 --> 06:31:30.260
me too, for it's a long stretch is that.'

06:31:30.260 --> 06:31:35.300
So saying, he stepped back a little way until he was out of earshot, and there sat down

06:31:35.300 --> 06:31:41.060
upon a tree stump and began to whistle, spinning round now and again upon his seat so as to

06:31:41.060 --> 06:31:47.040
command a sight sometimes of me and the doctor, and sometimes of his unruly ruffians as they

06:31:47.040 --> 06:31:52.920
went to and fro in the sand between the fire, which they were busily rekindling, and to

06:31:52.920 --> 06:31:56.740
the house from which they brought forth pork and bread to make the breakfast.

06:31:57.960 --> 06:32:01.500
"'So Jim,' said the doctor sadly, "'here you are.

06:32:02.300 --> 06:32:05.160
As you have brewed, so shall you drink, my boy.

06:32:05.620 --> 06:32:10.560
Heaven knows I cannot find it in my heart to blame you, but this much I will say, be

06:32:10.560 --> 06:32:11.820
it kind or unkind.

06:32:12.320 --> 06:32:17.720
When Captain Smollett was well, you dared not have gone off, and when he was ill and

06:32:17.720 --> 06:32:21.020
couldn't help it by George, it was downright cowardly.

06:32:22.320 --> 06:32:24.900
I will own that I here began to weep.

06:32:25.680 --> 06:32:28.640
"'Doctor,' I said, "'you might spare me.

06:32:28.840 --> 06:32:30.880
I have blamed myself enough.

06:32:31.340 --> 06:32:36.360
My life's forfeit anyway, and I should have been dead by now if Silver hadn't stood for

06:32:36.360 --> 06:32:36.940
me.

06:32:36.940 --> 06:32:42.180
And Doctor, believe this, I can die, and I dare say I deserve it.

06:32:42.460 --> 06:32:44.140
But what I fear is torture.

06:32:45.080 --> 06:32:51.580
If they come to torture me, Jim,' the doctor interrupted, and his voice was quite changed,

06:32:52.000 --> 06:32:53.640
"'Jim, I can't have this.

06:32:53.880 --> 06:32:56.240
Whip over, and we'll run for it.'

06:32:56.240 --> 06:33:00.060
"'Doctor,' said I, "'I passed my word.

06:33:00.560 --> 06:33:04.800
I know, I know,' he cried, "'we can't help that, Jim, now.

06:33:05.340 --> 06:33:07.100
I'll take it on my shoulders.

06:33:07.500 --> 06:33:11.580
Holas bolas, blame and shame, my boy, but stay here, I cannot let you.

06:33:11.680 --> 06:33:12.000
Jump!

06:33:12.280 --> 06:33:15.240
One jump and you're out, and we'll run for it like antelopes.'

06:33:16.340 --> 06:33:21.620
"'No,' I replied, "'you know right well you wouldn't do the same yourself.

06:33:22.220 --> 06:33:25.980
Neither you nor Squire nor Captain, and no more will I.

06:33:26.660 --> 06:33:30.120
Silver trusted me, I passed my word, and back I go.

06:33:30.840 --> 06:33:33.380
But Doctor, you did not let me finish.

06:33:33.380 --> 06:33:39.960
If they come to torture me, I might let slip a word of where the ship is, for I got the ship,

06:33:40.120 --> 06:33:46.160
part by luck and part by risking, and she lies in north inlet, on the southern beach,

06:33:46.640 --> 06:33:48.340
and just below high water.

06:33:49.120 --> 06:33:51.660
At half tide she must be high and dry.'

06:33:53.160 --> 06:33:55.700
"'The ship!' exclaimed the doctor.

06:33:56.760 --> 06:34:01.060
Rapidly I described to him my adventures, and he heard me out in silence.

06:34:02.280 --> 06:34:05.860
"'There is a kind of fate in this,' he observed when I had done.

06:34:06.240 --> 06:34:09.360
"'Every step, it's you that saved our lives.

06:34:09.580 --> 06:34:13.600
And do you suppose by any chance that we are going to let you lose yours?

06:34:14.240 --> 06:34:16.480
That would be a poor return, my boy.

06:34:17.040 --> 06:34:18.360
You found out the plot.

06:34:18.860 --> 06:34:20.180
You found Ben Gunn.

06:34:20.220 --> 06:34:24.100
The best deed that ever you did, or will do, though you lived till ninety.'

06:34:24.840 --> 06:34:29.760
"'Oh, by Jupiter, and talking of Ben Gunn, why this is the mischief in person.'

06:34:29.760 --> 06:34:30.860
"'Silver!' he cried.

06:34:31.000 --> 06:34:36.160
"'Silver! I'll give you a piece of advice,' he continued as the cook drew nearer again.

06:34:36.780 --> 06:34:39.440
"'Don't you be in any great hurry after that treasure.'

06:34:40.480 --> 06:34:44.620
"'Why, sir, I do my possible, which that ain't,' said Silver.

06:34:44.820 --> 06:34:49.620
"'I can only, asking your pardon, save my life and the boys by seeking for that treasure,

06:34:49.860 --> 06:34:51.200
and you may lay to that.'

06:34:52.400 --> 06:34:54.500
"'Well, Silver,' replied the doctor,

06:34:54.500 --> 06:34:56.780
"'if that is so, I'll go one step further.

06:34:57.400 --> 06:34:59.860
Look out for squalls when you find it.'

06:35:01.200 --> 06:35:02.440
"'Sir,' said Silver,

06:35:02.500 --> 06:35:06.420
"'as between man and man, that's too much and too little.

06:35:07.120 --> 06:35:12.320
What you're after, why you left the blockhouse, why you given me that hair chart,

06:35:12.340 --> 06:35:13.940
I don't know now, do I?

06:35:14.160 --> 06:35:18.000
And yet I done your bidding with my eyes shut and never a word of hope.

06:35:18.480 --> 06:35:20.380
But no, this here's too much.

06:35:20.920 --> 06:35:25.640
If you won't tell me what you mean plain out, just say so, and I'll leave the helm.'

06:35:27.120 --> 06:35:29.000
"'No,' said the doctor musingly,

06:35:29.120 --> 06:35:31.040
"'I've got no right to say more.

06:35:31.080 --> 06:35:35.300
It's not my secret, you see, Silver, or I give you my word, I tell it to you.

06:35:35.940 --> 06:35:39.780
But I'll go as far with you as I dare go, and a step beyond,

06:35:40.200 --> 06:35:43.340
for I'll have my wigs sorted by the captain or I'm mistaken.

06:35:44.060 --> 06:35:46.540
And first I'll give you a bit of hope, Silver.

06:35:46.680 --> 06:35:48.960
If we both get alive out of this wolf trap,

06:35:49.260 --> 06:35:51.900
I'll do my best to save you short of perjury.'

06:35:53.420 --> 06:35:55.000
Silver's face was radiant.

06:35:55.000 --> 06:36:00.320
"'You couldn't say more, I'm sure, sir, not if you was my mother,' he cried.

06:36:01.460 --> 06:36:04.460
"'Well, that's my first concession,' added the doctor.

06:36:04.880 --> 06:36:06.980
"'My second is a piece of advice.

06:36:07.500 --> 06:36:12.240
Keep the boy close beside you, and when you need help, hello.

06:36:12.960 --> 06:36:17.900
I'm off to seek it for you, and that itself should show you if I speak at random.

06:36:18.660 --> 06:36:20.020
Goodbye, Jim.'

06:36:20.020 --> 06:36:23.480
And Dr. Livesey shook hands with me through the stockade,

06:36:23.480 --> 06:36:27.560
knotted to Silver, and set off at a brisk pace into the wood.

06:36:43.460 --> 06:36:45.100
This is Jean O'Sullivan.

06:36:45.660 --> 06:36:49.280
The book is Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson.

06:36:49.520 --> 06:36:50.920
This is Chapter 31.

06:36:51.500 --> 06:36:52.520
The Treasure Hunt.

06:36:52.980 --> 06:36:53.980
Flint's Pointer

06:36:55.160 --> 06:36:58.120
Jim, said Silver, when we were alone,

06:36:58.480 --> 06:37:02.300
If I saved your life, you saved mine, and I'll not forget it.

06:37:02.880 --> 06:37:05.440
I seen the doctor waving you to run for it,

06:37:05.600 --> 06:37:07.500
With the tail of my eye I did,

06:37:07.660 --> 06:37:10.560
And I seen you say, No plane is hearing.

06:37:11.120 --> 06:37:12.740
Jim, that's one to you.

06:37:13.260 --> 06:37:17.720
This is the first glint of hope I had since the attack failed,

06:37:17.900 --> 06:37:19.420
And I owe it to you.

06:37:19.660 --> 06:37:23.140
And now, Jim, we're to go in for this here treasure hunting

06:37:23.140 --> 06:37:26.520
With sealed orders, too, and I don't like it,

06:37:26.600 --> 06:37:31.860
And you and me must stick close, back to back-like,

06:37:32.100 --> 06:37:35.060
And we'll save our next spite of fate and fortune.

06:37:36.280 --> 06:37:39.780
Just then a man hails from the fire that breakfast was ready,

06:37:40.000 --> 06:37:44.560
And we were soon seated here and there about the sand over biscuit and fried junk.

06:37:45.040 --> 06:37:47.240
They had lit a fire to roast an ox,

06:37:47.480 --> 06:37:51.200
And it was now grown so hot that they could only approach it from the windward,

06:37:51.200 --> 06:37:53.940
And even there, not without precaution.

06:37:54.440 --> 06:37:56.160
In the same wasteful spirit,

06:37:56.600 --> 06:38:00.320
They had cooked, I suppose, three times more than we could eat,

06:38:00.640 --> 06:38:05.180
And one of them, with an empty laugh, threw what was left into the fire,

06:38:05.460 --> 06:38:08.900
Which blazed and roared again over this unusual fuel.

06:38:09.520 --> 06:38:13.880
I never in my life saw men so careless of the morrow.

06:38:14.220 --> 06:38:18.220
Hand to mouth is the only word that can describe their way of doing,

06:38:18.220 --> 06:38:21.660
And what with wasted food and sleeping sentries,

06:38:21.780 --> 06:38:24.780
Though they were bold enough for a brush and be done with it,

06:38:25.100 --> 06:38:29.900
I could see their entire unfitness for anything like a prolonged campaign.

06:38:31.020 --> 06:38:35.020
Even Silver, eating away with Captain Flint upon his shoulder,

06:38:35.380 --> 06:38:37.580
Had not a word of blame for their recklessness,

06:38:37.880 --> 06:38:39.800
And this the more surprised me,

06:38:39.960 --> 06:38:43.960
For I thought he had never shown himself so cunning as he did then.

06:38:44.720 --> 06:38:46.900
Aye, mates, said he,

06:38:47.020 --> 06:38:51.600
It's lucky you have barbeque to think for you with this herehead.

06:38:52.280 --> 06:38:54.780
I got what I wanted, I did, sure enough.

06:38:54.960 --> 06:38:58.240
They have the ship. Where they have it, I don't know yet,

06:38:58.300 --> 06:39:02.300
But once we hit the treasure, we'll have to jump about and find out.

06:39:02.560 --> 06:39:07.600
And then, mates, us that has the boats, I reckon, has the upper hand.

06:39:08.280 --> 06:39:12.180
Thus he kept running on with his mouth full of the hot bacon,

06:39:12.180 --> 06:39:14.600
Thus he restored their hope and confidence,

06:39:15.020 --> 06:39:18.880
And, I more than suspect, repaired his own at the same time.

06:39:19.760 --> 06:39:24.540
As for hostage, he continued, that's his last talk, I guess,

06:39:24.640 --> 06:39:28.800
With them that love so dear, I've got my piece of news,

06:39:28.840 --> 06:39:32.460
And thank you to him for that, but it's over and done.

06:39:33.300 --> 06:39:35.900
I'll take him in a line when we go treasure hunting,

06:39:36.480 --> 06:39:41.200
For we'll keep him like so much gold in case of accidents, you mark,

06:39:41.200 --> 06:39:45.880
And in the meantime, once we got the ship and treasure both,

06:39:46.340 --> 06:39:48.640
And off to sea like jolly companions,

06:39:49.540 --> 06:39:52.460
Why, then, we'll talk Mr. Hawkins over, we will,

06:39:52.820 --> 06:39:56.500
And we'll give him his share, to be sure, for all his kindness.

06:39:57.500 --> 06:40:01.100
It was no wonder the men were in good humour now.

06:40:01.400 --> 06:40:04.440
For my part, I was horribly cast down.

06:40:04.920 --> 06:40:08.740
Should the scheme he had now sketched prove feasible,

06:40:08.740 --> 06:40:13.880
Silver, already doubly a traitor, would not hesitate to adopt it.

06:40:14.400 --> 06:40:16.660
He had still a foot in either camp,

06:40:16.660 --> 06:40:20.860
And there was no doubt he would prefer wealth and freedom with the pirates

06:40:20.860 --> 06:40:23.020
To a bare escape from hanging,

06:40:23.300 --> 06:40:26.340
Which was the best he had to hope on our side.

06:40:27.120 --> 06:40:30.200
Nay, and even if things so fell out,

06:40:30.260 --> 06:40:33.520
That he was forced to keep his faith with Dr. Livesey,

06:40:33.520 --> 06:40:36.140
Even then, what danger lay before us!

06:40:36.140 --> 06:40:38.380
What a moment that would be

06:40:38.380 --> 06:40:41.480
When the suspicions of his followers turned to certainty,

06:40:41.880 --> 06:40:44.260
And he and I should have to fight for dear life,

06:40:44.560 --> 06:40:50.060
He a cripple and I a boy, against five strong and active seamen.

06:40:50.160 --> 06:40:52.420
Add to this double apprehension the mystery

06:40:52.420 --> 06:40:55.020
That still hung over the behaviour of my friends,

06:40:55.380 --> 06:40:57.540
Their unexplained desertion of the stockade,

06:40:57.900 --> 06:41:00.040
Their inexplicable session of the chart,

06:41:00.220 --> 06:41:04.600
Or, harder still to understand, the doctor's last warning to Silver.

06:41:04.600 --> 06:41:07.120
Look out the squalls when you find it,

06:41:07.360 --> 06:41:09.080
And you will readily believe

06:41:09.080 --> 06:41:11.940
How little taste I found in my breakfast,

06:41:12.380 --> 06:41:16.040
And with how uneasy a heart I set forth behind my captors

06:41:16.040 --> 06:41:17.560
On the quest for treasure.

06:41:18.560 --> 06:41:22.320
We made a curious figure, had anyone been there to see us,

06:41:22.680 --> 06:41:26.920
All in soiled sailor clothes and all but me armed to the teeth.

06:41:27.360 --> 06:41:29.420
Silver had two guns slung about him,

06:41:29.580 --> 06:41:31.260
One before and one behind,

06:41:31.580 --> 06:41:33.500
Besides the great cutlass at his waist,

06:41:33.500 --> 06:41:36.480
And a pistol in each pocket of his square-tailed coat.

06:41:36.980 --> 06:41:38.880
To complete this strange appearance,

06:41:39.280 --> 06:41:41.640
Captain Flint sat perched upon his shoulder,

06:41:42.420 --> 06:41:45.260
And gabbling odds and ends of purposeless sea-talk.

06:41:45.880 --> 06:41:47.820
I had a line about my waist,

06:41:47.880 --> 06:41:50.300
And followed obediently after the sea-cook,

06:41:50.660 --> 06:41:52.420
Who held the loose end of the rope,

06:41:52.680 --> 06:41:55.980
Now in his free hand, now between his powerful teeth.

06:41:56.260 --> 06:41:59.500
For all the world I was led like a dancing bear.

06:41:59.800 --> 06:42:01.660
The other men were variously berthened,

06:42:01.660 --> 06:42:03.840
Some carrying picks and shovels,

06:42:03.840 --> 06:42:06.560
For that had been the very first necessary

06:42:06.560 --> 06:42:08.900
They brought ashore from the Hispaniola,

06:42:09.200 --> 06:42:13.120
Others laden with pork, bread, and brandy for the midday meal.

06:42:13.540 --> 06:42:16.540
All the stores, I observed, came from our stock,

06:42:16.780 --> 06:42:20.620
And I could see the truth of Silver's words the night before.

06:42:21.200 --> 06:42:23.320
Had he not struck a bargain with the doctor,

06:42:23.620 --> 06:42:26.080
He and his mutineers, deserted by the ship,

06:42:26.500 --> 06:42:29.080
Must have been driven to subsist on clear water

06:42:29.080 --> 06:42:30.680
In the proceeds of their hunting.

06:42:30.680 --> 06:42:33.600
Water would have been little to their taste,

06:42:33.880 --> 06:42:36.360
A sailor is not usually a good shot,

06:42:36.480 --> 06:42:39.380
And besides all that, when they were so short of eatables,

06:42:39.740 --> 06:42:42.660
It was not likely they would be very flush of powder.

06:42:43.320 --> 06:42:45.940
Well, thus equipped, we all set out,

06:42:46.080 --> 06:42:47.700
Even the fellow with the broken head,

06:42:48.040 --> 06:42:50.060
Who certainly should have kept in shadow,

06:42:50.360 --> 06:42:53.180
And straggled, one after another, to the beach,

06:42:53.480 --> 06:42:55.140
Where the two gigs awaited us.

06:42:55.480 --> 06:42:58.560
Even these bore trace of the drunken folly of the pirates,

06:42:58.560 --> 06:43:00.240
One in a broken thwart,

06:43:00.520 --> 06:43:02.960
And both in their muddy and unbailed condition,

06:43:03.500 --> 06:43:06.380
Both were to be carried along with us for the sake of safety,

06:43:06.660 --> 06:43:09.220
And so, with our numbers divided between them,

06:43:09.460 --> 06:43:11.940
We set forth upon the bosom of the anchorage.

06:43:12.820 --> 06:43:16.200
As we pulled over, there was some discussion on the chart.

06:43:16.540 --> 06:43:21.240
The Red Cross was, of course, far too large to be a guide,

06:43:21.540 --> 06:43:24.360
And the terms of the note on the back, as you will hear,

06:43:24.920 --> 06:43:26.740
Admittedly of some ambiguity.

06:43:26.740 --> 06:43:30.120
They ran, the reader may remember, thus,

06:43:31.080 --> 06:43:39.060
Tall tree, spy-glass shoulder, bearing a point to the N of N-N-E,

06:43:39.440 --> 06:43:45.380
Skeleton island, E-S-E, and by E, ten feet.

06:43:46.940 --> 06:43:49.380
A tall tree was thus the principal mark.

06:43:49.420 --> 06:43:53.200
Now, right before us, the anchorage was bounded by a plateau

06:43:53.200 --> 06:43:56.880
From two to three hundred feet high, adjoining on the north

06:43:56.880 --> 06:43:59.760
The sloping southern shoulder of the spy-glass,

06:44:00.220 --> 06:44:02.760
And rising again toward the south to the rough,

06:44:02.920 --> 06:44:05.280
Cliffy eminence called Mizenmast hill.

06:44:05.660 --> 06:44:08.960
The top of the plateau was dotted thickly with pine trees

06:44:08.960 --> 06:44:09.940
Of varying height.

06:44:10.360 --> 06:44:13.500
Every here and there, one of a different species,

06:44:13.800 --> 06:44:16.760
Rose forty or fifty feet clear above its neighbors,

06:44:17.060 --> 06:44:20.020
And which of these was the particular tall tree

06:44:20.020 --> 06:44:23.200
Of Captain Flint, could only be decided on the spot

06:44:23.200 --> 06:44:24.980
And by readings of the compass.

06:44:25.220 --> 06:44:29.000
Yet, although that was the case, every man on board the boats

06:44:29.000 --> 06:44:32.420
Had picked a favorite of his own, ere we were half way over,

06:44:32.720 --> 06:44:35.560
Long John alone, shrugging his shoulders and bidding them

06:44:35.560 --> 06:44:37.160
Wait till they were there.

06:44:37.940 --> 06:44:42.380
We pulled easily by Silver's directions, not to weary the hands

06:44:42.380 --> 06:44:46.540
Primiturally, and after quite a long passage, landed at the mouth

06:44:46.540 --> 06:44:49.920
Of the second river, that which runs down a woody cleft

06:44:49.920 --> 06:44:50.920
Of the spy-glass.

06:44:51.420 --> 06:44:55.320
Thence, bending to our left, we began to ascend the slope

06:44:55.320 --> 06:44:56.680
Towards the plateau.

06:44:57.280 --> 06:45:01.280
At the first outset, heavy, miry ground and a matted,

06:45:01.460 --> 06:45:03.860
Marish vegetation greatly delayed our progress,

06:45:04.160 --> 06:45:07.320
But by little and little the hill began to steepen

06:45:07.320 --> 06:45:11.080
And become stony underfoot, and the wood to change its character

06:45:11.080 --> 06:45:13.100
And to grow in a more open order.

06:45:13.380 --> 06:45:17.080
It was, indeed, a most pleasant portion of the island

06:45:17.080 --> 06:45:18.320
That we were now approaching.

06:45:18.320 --> 06:45:22.080
A heavy-scented broom and many flowering shrubs

06:45:22.080 --> 06:45:24.280
Had almost taken the place of grass.

06:45:24.720 --> 06:45:28.340
Thickets of green nutmeg trees were dotted here and there

06:45:28.340 --> 06:45:31.600
With the red columns and the broad shadow of the pines,

06:45:31.620 --> 06:45:35.360
And the first mingled their spice with the aroma of the others.

06:45:35.780 --> 06:45:39.800
The air, besides, was fresh and stirring, and this,

06:45:40.000 --> 06:45:43.420
Under the sheer sunbeams, was a wonderful refreshment

06:45:43.420 --> 06:45:44.440
To our senses.

06:45:45.060 --> 06:45:47.800
The party spread itself abroad, in a fan-shape,

06:45:47.800 --> 06:45:49.680
Shouting and leaping to and fro.

06:45:50.000 --> 06:45:52.280
About the centre and a good way behind the rest,

06:45:52.640 --> 06:45:55.420
Silver and I followed, I tethered by my rope,

06:45:55.640 --> 06:45:58.800
He ploughing with deep pants among the sliding gravel.

06:45:59.300 --> 06:46:02.520
From time to time, indeed, I had to lend him a hand,

06:46:02.780 --> 06:46:05.940
Or he must have missed his footing and fallen backward down the hill.

06:46:06.720 --> 06:46:09.280
We had thus proceeded for about half a mile

06:46:09.280 --> 06:46:11.380
And were approaching the brow of the plateau

06:46:11.380 --> 06:46:14.180
When the man upon the farthest left began to cry aloud,

06:46:14.260 --> 06:46:15.100
As if in terror.

06:46:15.520 --> 06:46:17.080
Shout after shout came from him,

06:46:17.080 --> 06:46:19.420
And the others began to run in his direction.

06:46:19.740 --> 06:46:22.280
He can't have found the treasure, said old Morgan,

06:46:22.420 --> 06:46:25.420
Hurrying past us from the right, for that's clean atop.

06:46:25.660 --> 06:46:28.120
Indeed, we found when we also reached the spot

06:46:28.120 --> 06:46:29.640
It was something very different.

06:46:30.100 --> 06:46:34.020
At the foot of a pretty big pine and involved in a green creeper,

06:46:34.080 --> 06:46:37.380
Which had even partly lifted some of the smaller bones,

06:46:37.680 --> 06:46:41.700
A human skeleton lay, with a few shreds of clothing on the ground.

06:46:42.260 --> 06:46:45.740
I believe a chill struck for a moment to every heart.

06:46:47.080 --> 06:46:51.500
He was a seaman, said George Mary, who, bolder than the rest,

06:46:51.580 --> 06:46:54.700
Had gone up close and was examining the rags of clothing.

06:46:55.520 --> 06:46:58.380
Least ways, this is good sea-cloth.

06:46:59.120 --> 06:47:01.360
Aye, aye, said Silver, like enough.

06:47:02.020 --> 06:47:04.040
You wouldn't look to find a bishop here, I reckon.

06:47:04.580 --> 06:47:09.000
But what sort of a way is that for bones to lie?

06:47:09.640 --> 06:47:10.680
Taint in nature!

06:47:11.600 --> 06:47:15.480
Indeed, on a second glance, it seemed impossible to fancy

06:47:15.480 --> 06:47:17.600
That the body was in a natural position.

06:47:18.140 --> 06:47:21.500
But for some disarray, the work perhaps of the birds

06:47:21.500 --> 06:47:24.760
That had fed upon him, or of the slow-growing creeper

06:47:24.760 --> 06:47:27.060
That had gradually enveloped his remains,

06:47:27.600 --> 06:47:31.640
The man lay perfectly straight, his feet pointing in one direction,

06:47:32.020 --> 06:47:34.940
His hands raised above his head like a diver's,

06:47:35.060 --> 06:47:36.980
Pointing directly in the opposite.

06:47:37.380 --> 06:47:41.340
I've taken a notion into my old numb skull, observed Silver.

06:47:41.340 --> 06:47:42.720
Here's the compass.

06:47:43.260 --> 06:47:46.160
There's the tip-top point of Skeleton Island

06:47:46.160 --> 06:47:47.520
Sticking out like a tooth.

06:47:48.180 --> 06:47:51.520
Just take a bearing, will you, along the line of them bones.

06:47:52.240 --> 06:47:53.280
It was done.

06:47:53.540 --> 06:47:56.600
The body pointed straight in the direction of the island,

06:47:56.740 --> 06:48:02.540
And the compass read duly, E, S, E, and by E.

06:48:03.100 --> 06:48:04.900
I thought so, cried the cook.

06:48:05.260 --> 06:48:06.480
This here is a pointer.

06:48:06.740 --> 06:48:10.640
Right up there is our line for the Pole Star and the Jolly Dollars,

06:48:10.640 --> 06:48:14.080
But by thunder if it don't make me cold inside to think of Flint.

06:48:14.520 --> 06:48:17.600
This was one of his jokes, and no mistake.

06:48:18.000 --> 06:48:19.840
Him and these six was alone here.

06:48:19.860 --> 06:48:21.440
He killed them every man.

06:48:21.680 --> 06:48:25.040
And this one he hauled here and laid down by compass.

06:48:25.220 --> 06:48:26.400
Shiver me, Timbers.

06:48:26.900 --> 06:48:29.460
They're long bones and the hair's been yellow.

06:48:30.320 --> 06:48:32.500
Ay, that would be Allardus.

06:48:33.840 --> 06:48:35.980
You mind Allardus, Tom Morgan?

06:48:37.040 --> 06:48:39.120
Ay, ay, returned Morgan.

06:48:39.120 --> 06:48:40.520
I mind him.

06:48:40.820 --> 06:48:42.360
He owed me money, he did.

06:48:42.780 --> 06:48:44.800
And took my knife ashore with him.

06:48:45.600 --> 06:48:47.360
Speaking of knives, said another,

06:48:47.580 --> 06:48:49.260
Why don't we find his lying around?

06:48:49.760 --> 06:48:51.840
Flint weren't the man to pick a seaman's pocket,

06:48:52.080 --> 06:48:54.440
And the birds, I guess, would leave it be.

06:48:55.360 --> 06:48:58.520
By the powers that's true, cried Silver.

06:48:59.080 --> 06:49:02.560
There ain't a thing left here, said Mary,

06:49:02.620 --> 06:49:04.920
Still feeling around among the bones.

06:49:05.280 --> 06:49:08.100
Not a copper doot or a becky box.

06:49:08.100 --> 06:49:11.160
It don't look natural to me.

06:49:11.560 --> 06:49:13.820
No, by gum it don't, agreed Silver.

06:49:13.920 --> 06:49:18.000
Not natural, nor not nice, says you.

06:49:18.000 --> 06:49:19.780
Great guns, mess mates.

06:49:20.320 --> 06:49:23.920
But if Flint was living, this would be a hot spot for you and me.

06:49:24.520 --> 06:49:26.740
Six they were, and six are we,

06:49:26.860 --> 06:49:29.360
And bones is what they are now.

06:49:30.240 --> 06:49:33.840
I saw him dead with these here dead lights, said Morgan.

06:49:34.380 --> 06:49:35.400
Billy took me in.

06:49:35.400 --> 06:49:39.200
There he laid with penny pieces on his eyes.

06:49:39.360 --> 06:49:42.040
Did I? Sure enough, he's dead and gone below,

06:49:42.240 --> 06:49:43.740
Said the fellow with the bandage.

06:49:44.160 --> 06:49:47.580
But if ever a spirit walked, it would be Flint's.

06:49:47.720 --> 06:49:50.980
Dear heart, but he died bad, did Flint.

06:49:52.000 --> 06:49:54.020
I, that he did, observed another.

06:49:54.460 --> 06:49:57.380
Now he raged, and now he hollered for the rum,

06:49:57.640 --> 06:49:59.020
And now he sang.

06:49:59.720 --> 06:50:02.600
Fifteen men were his only songmates,

06:50:02.600 --> 06:50:07.020
And I tell you true, I never rightly liked to hear it since.

06:50:07.440 --> 06:50:10.340
It was main hot, and the windy was open,

06:50:10.500 --> 06:50:14.440
And I hear that old song coming out as clear as clear,

06:50:14.640 --> 06:50:16.900
And the death-hall on the man already.

06:50:17.340 --> 06:50:20.320
Come, come, said Silver, stow this talk.

06:50:20.640 --> 06:50:22.680
He's dead, and he don't walk.

06:50:23.000 --> 06:50:25.660
That I know least ways he won't walk by day.

06:50:26.420 --> 06:50:28.240
And you may lay to that.

06:50:29.020 --> 06:50:30.340
Care killed a cat.

06:50:30.340 --> 06:50:32.240
Fetch a head for the doubloons.

06:50:33.040 --> 06:50:36.100
We started certainly, but in spite of the hot sun

06:50:36.100 --> 06:50:39.200
And the staring daylight, the pirates no longer

06:50:39.200 --> 06:50:41.580
Ran separate and shouting through the wood,

06:50:42.000 --> 06:50:45.380
But kept side by side and spoke with bated breath.

06:50:45.900 --> 06:50:49.980
The terror of the dead buccaneer had fallen on their spirits.

06:51:00.340 --> 06:51:01.160
Thanks for watching.

06:51:16.360 --> 06:51:18.020
This is Jean O'Sullivan.

06:51:18.700 --> 06:51:22.020
The book is Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson.

06:51:22.640 --> 06:51:27.460
This is Chapter 32, The Treasure Hunt, The Voice Among the Trees.

06:51:27.460 --> 06:51:32.900
Partly from the damping influence of this alarm, partly to rest silver in the sick folk,

06:51:33.320 --> 06:51:38.800
the whole party sat down as soon as they had gained the brow of the ascent. The plateau being

06:51:38.800 --> 06:51:44.640
somewhat tilted towards the west, this spot on which we had paused commanded a wide prospect on

06:51:44.640 --> 06:51:50.880
either hand. Before us, over the treetops, we beheld the cape of the woods, fringed with surf.

06:51:50.880 --> 06:51:57.980
Behind, we looked not only down upon the anchorage and skeleton island, but saw, clear across the

06:51:57.980 --> 06:52:04.380
spit and the eastern lowlands, a great field of open sea upon the east. Sheer above us rose the

06:52:04.380 --> 06:52:10.960
spyglass, here dotted with single pines, there black with precipices. There was no sound but

06:52:10.960 --> 06:52:17.320
that of the distant breakers mounting from all round, and the chirp of countless insects in the

06:52:17.320 --> 06:52:24.500
bush. Not a man, not a sail upon the sea. The very largeness of the view increased the sense of

06:52:24.500 --> 06:52:29.480
solitude. Silver, as he sat, took certain bearings with his compass.

06:52:30.580 --> 06:52:40.540
There are three tall trees, said he, about in the right line from skeleton island. Spyglass shoulder,

06:52:40.540 --> 06:52:48.340
I take it, means that lower point there. It's child's play to find the stuff now. I have half

06:52:48.340 --> 06:52:56.460
a mind to dine first. I don't feel sharp, growled Morgan, thinking a flint I think it were has done

06:52:56.460 --> 06:53:03.100
me. Ah, well, my son, if you praise your stars, he's dead, said Silver. You were an ugly devil,

06:53:03.620 --> 06:53:09.620
cried a third pirate with a shudder. That blew in the face, too. That was how the rum took him,

06:53:09.620 --> 06:53:16.140
added Mary. Blue. Well, I reckon he was blue. That's a true word. Ever since they had found

06:53:16.140 --> 06:53:21.540
the skeleton and got upon this train of thought, they had spoken lower and lower, and they almost

06:53:21.540 --> 06:53:26.880
had got to whispering by now, so that the sound of their talk hardly interrupted the silence of the

06:53:26.880 --> 06:53:33.620
wood. All of the sudden, out of the middle of the trees in front of us, a thin, high, trembling voice

06:53:33.620 --> 06:53:46.300
struck up the well-known air and words. I never have seen men more dreadfully affected than the

06:53:46.300 --> 06:53:51.160
pirates. The color went from their six faces like enchantment. Some leaped to their feet,

06:53:51.340 --> 06:53:57.460
some clawed hold of others. Morgan groveled on the ground. It's flint bike, cried Mary.

06:53:57.960 --> 06:54:02.300
The song had stopped as suddenly as it began. Broken off, you would have said, in the middle

06:54:02.300 --> 06:54:08.280
of a note, as though someone had laid his hand upon the singer's mouth. Coming through the clear,

06:54:08.440 --> 06:54:13.760
sunny atmosphere among the green treetops, I thought it had sounded airily and sweetly,

06:54:13.860 --> 06:54:19.660
and the effect on my companions was the stranger. Come, said Silver, struggling with his ashen lips

06:54:19.660 --> 06:54:28.000
to get the word out. This won't do. Stand by to go about. This is a rum start, and I can't name the

06:54:28.000 --> 06:54:35.160
but it's someone skylarking, someone that's flesh and blood, and you may lay to that.

06:54:35.620 --> 06:54:40.460
His courage had come back as he spoke, and some of the color to his face along with it.

06:54:40.940 --> 06:54:45.300
Already the others had begun to lend an ear to this encouragement and were coming a little to

06:54:45.300 --> 06:54:51.380
themselves when the same voice broke out again, not this time singing, but in a faint, distant

06:54:51.380 --> 06:54:55.300
that echoed yet fainter among the clefts of the spyglass.

06:54:56.300 --> 06:55:01.420
Darby McGraw, it wailed, for that is the word that best describes the sound.

06:55:01.560 --> 06:55:07.840
Darby McGraw, Darby McGraw. Again and again, and then rising a little higher,

06:55:08.120 --> 06:55:12.580
and with an oath that I leave out. Fetch after the rum, Darby.

06:55:13.680 --> 06:55:19.440
The buccaneers remained rooted to the ground, their eyes starting from their heads. Long after

06:55:19.440 --> 06:55:25.480
voice had died away, they still stared in silence, dreadfully before them.

06:55:25.880 --> 06:55:28.600
That fixes it, gasped one. Let's go.

06:55:29.320 --> 06:55:35.320
They were his last words, moaned Morgan. His last words above board.

06:55:36.240 --> 06:55:41.100
Dick had his Bible out and was praying volubly. He had been well brought up,

06:55:41.200 --> 06:55:44.360
had Dick, before he came to see and fell among bad companions.

06:55:44.960 --> 06:55:49.520
Still, Silver was unconquered. I could hear his teeth rattle in his head,

06:55:49.960 --> 06:55:51.440
but he had not yet surrendered.

06:55:53.100 --> 06:55:57.100
Nobody in this here island ever heard of Darby, he muttered.

06:55:57.460 --> 06:55:59.820
Not one, but us that's here.

06:56:00.420 --> 06:56:03.500
And then, making a great effort, shipmates, he cried.

06:56:04.080 --> 06:56:07.980
I'm here to get that stuff and I'll not be beat by man or devil.

06:56:08.360 --> 06:56:12.280
I never was a fear to flint in his life and by the powers I'll face him dead.

06:56:12.280 --> 06:56:16.200
There's seven hundred thousand pound, not a quarter mile from here.

06:56:16.540 --> 06:56:20.620
When did ever a gentleman of fortune show his stern to that much dollars

06:56:20.620 --> 06:56:24.440
for a boozy old seaman with a blue mug and him dead too?

06:56:25.080 --> 06:56:28.180
But there was no sign of reawakening courage in his followers,

06:56:28.640 --> 06:56:32.300
rather indeed of growing terror at the irreverence of his words.

06:56:33.740 --> 06:56:37.300
Belay there, John, said Mary. Don't you cross a spirit?

06:56:38.180 --> 06:56:40.940
And the rest were all too terrified to reply.

06:56:40.940 --> 06:56:45.180
They would have run away severally had they dared, but fear kept them together

06:56:45.180 --> 06:56:48.980
and kept them close by John as if his daring helped them.

06:56:49.180 --> 06:56:52.440
He, on his part, had pretty well fought his weakness down.

06:56:53.520 --> 06:56:59.320
Spirit? Well, maybe, he said, but there's one thing not clear to me.

06:56:59.780 --> 06:57:05.320
There was an echo. Now no man ever seen a spirit with a shadow.

06:57:05.700 --> 06:57:07.600
Well, then what's he doing with an echo to him?

06:57:07.600 --> 06:57:11.320
I should like to know. That ain't in nature, surely.

06:57:12.520 --> 06:57:16.820
This argument seemed weak enough to me, but you can never tell what will affect the

06:57:16.820 --> 06:57:20.860
superstitious. And to my wonder, George Mary was greatly relieved.

06:57:21.720 --> 06:57:26.200
Well, that's so, he said. You have a head upon your shoulders, John, and no mistake.

06:57:26.600 --> 06:57:31.500
Bouch, shipmates. This here crew is on a wrong tack, I do believe, and come to think of it.

06:57:31.500 --> 06:57:38.180
It was like Flint's voice, I grant you, but not just so clear away like it after all.

06:57:38.460 --> 06:57:43.700
It was like her somebody else's voice now. It was like her by the powers.

06:57:44.160 --> 06:57:46.280
Ben Gunn, roared Silver.

06:57:47.520 --> 06:57:52.100
Aye, and so it were, cried Morgan, springing on his knees.

06:57:52.520 --> 06:57:54.070
Ben Gunn, it were.

06:57:55.020 --> 06:57:58.720
It don't make much odds do it now, asked Dick.

06:57:58.720 --> 06:58:02.280
Ben Gunn's not here in the body any more than Flint.

06:58:03.200 --> 06:58:06.160
But the older hands greeted this remark with scorn.

06:58:07.000 --> 06:58:11.940
Why, nobody minds Ben Gunn, cried Mary. Dead or alive, nobody minds him.

06:58:12.880 --> 06:58:18.040
It was extraordinary how their spirits had returned and how the natural color had revived

06:58:18.040 --> 06:58:22.280
in their faces. Soon they were chatting together, with intervals of listening,

06:58:22.320 --> 06:58:26.860
and not long after, hearing no further sound, they shouldered the tools and set forth again,

06:58:26.860 --> 06:58:31.940
Mary walking first with Silver's compass to keep them on the right line with Skeleton Island.

06:58:32.440 --> 06:58:39.040
He had said the truth, dead or alive, nobody minded Ben Gunn. Dick alone still held his Bible

06:58:39.040 --> 06:58:43.860
and looked around him as he went, with fearful glances, but he found no sympathy,

06:58:44.300 --> 06:58:46.920
and Silver even joked him on his precautions.

06:58:49.040 --> 06:58:56.040
I told you, said he, I told you he had spoiled your Bible. If it ain't no good to swear by,

06:58:56.040 --> 06:59:01.220
what do you suppose a spirit would give for it? Not that! And he snapped his big fingers,

06:59:01.560 --> 06:59:07.440
halting a moment on his crutch. But Dick was not to be comforted. Indeed, it was soon plain to me

06:59:07.440 --> 06:59:12.680
that the lad was falling sick, hastened by heat, exhaustion, and the shock of his alarm,

06:59:13.000 --> 06:59:17.380
the fever predicted by Dr. Livesey was evidently growing swiftly higher.

06:59:18.140 --> 06:59:24.400
It was fine, open, walking here upon the summit. Our way lay a little downhill, for,

06:59:24.400 --> 06:59:30.760
as I have said, the plateau tilted toward the west. The pines, great and small, grew wide apart,

06:59:31.020 --> 06:59:36.580
and even between the clumps of nutmeg and azalea, wide open spaces baked in the hot sunshine.

06:59:37.100 --> 06:59:42.740
Striking as we did, pretty near northwest across the island, we drew, on the one hand,

06:59:42.800 --> 06:59:48.280
ever nearer under the shoulders of the spyglass, and on the other, looked ever wider over that

06:59:48.280 --> 06:59:54.080
western bay where I had once tossed and trembled in the oracle. The first of the tall trees was

06:59:54.080 --> 06:59:59.800
reached, and by the bearings proved the wrong one, so with the second. The third rose nearly

06:59:59.800 --> 07:00:05.700
two hundred feet into the air above a clump of underwood, a giant of a vegetable with a red

07:00:05.700 --> 07:00:10.960
column as big as a cottage, and a wide shadow around in which a company could have maneuvered.

07:00:11.020 --> 07:00:17.220
It was conspicuous far to see both on the east and west, and might have been entered as a sailing

07:00:17.220 --> 07:00:22.360
mark upon the chart. But it was not its size that now impressed my companions. It was the

07:00:22.360 --> 07:00:27.800
knowledge that seven hundred thousand pounds in gold lay somewhere buried below its spreading

07:00:27.800 --> 07:00:33.440
shadow. The thought of the money as they drew nearer swallowed up their previous terrors,

07:00:33.760 --> 07:00:40.160
their eyes burned in their heads, their feet grew speedier and lighter, their whole soul was found

07:00:40.160 --> 07:00:46.440
up in that fortune, that whole lifetime of extravagance and pleasure that lay waiting there

07:00:46.440 --> 07:00:52.960
for each of them. Silver hobbled, grunting on his crutch, his nostrils stood out and quivered. He

07:00:52.960 --> 07:00:58.140
cursed like a madman when the flies settled on his hot and shiny countenance. He plucked furiously at

07:00:58.140 --> 07:01:03.220
the line that held me to him, and from time to time turned his eyes upon me with a deadly look.

07:01:03.860 --> 07:01:10.200
Certainly he took no pains to hide his thoughts, and certainly I read them like print. In the

07:01:10.200 --> 07:01:15.640
immediate nearness of the gold all else had been forgotten. His promise and the doctor's warning

07:01:15.640 --> 07:01:20.600
were both things of the past, and I could not doubt that he hoped to seize upon the treasure,

07:01:21.100 --> 07:01:26.600
find and board the Hispaniola under cover of night, cut every honest throat about that island,

07:01:26.700 --> 07:01:33.600
and sail away as he had first intended, laden with crimes and riches. Shaken as I was with

07:01:33.600 --> 07:01:38.040
these alarms, it was hard for me to keep up with the rapid pace of the treasure hunters.

07:01:38.580 --> 07:01:43.680
Now and again I stumbled, and it was then that Silver plucked so roughly at the rope and launched

07:01:43.680 --> 07:01:48.860
at me his murderous glances. Dick, who had dropped behind us and now brought up the rear,

07:01:48.960 --> 07:01:55.040
was babbling to himself, both prayers and curses as his fever kept rising. This also added to my

07:01:55.040 --> 07:02:00.520
wretchedness, and to crown it all I was haunted by the thought of the tragedy that had once been

07:02:00.520 --> 07:02:06.620
acted on that plateau, when that ungodly buccaneer with the blue face, he who died at Savannah,

07:02:06.800 --> 07:02:13.240
singing and shouting for a drink, had there, with his own hand, cut down his six accomplices.

07:02:13.240 --> 07:02:19.820
This grove that was now so peaceful must then have rung with cries, I thought, and even with

07:02:19.820 --> 07:02:26.240
the thought I could believe I heard it ringing still. We were now at the margin of the thicket.

07:02:27.520 --> 07:02:32.380
Huzzah mates, all together! shouted Mary, and the foremost broke into a run, and suddenly,

07:02:32.520 --> 07:02:39.000
not ten yards further, we beheld them stop. A low cry arose. Silver doubled his pace,

07:02:39.000 --> 07:02:44.480
digging away with the foot of his crutch like one possessed, and next moment he and I had come also

07:02:44.480 --> 07:02:52.260
to a dead halt. Before us was a great excavation, not very recent, for the sides had fallen in and

07:02:52.260 --> 07:02:58.540
grass had sprouted on the bottom. In this were the shaft of a pick broken in two and the boards of

07:02:58.540 --> 07:03:05.100
several packing cases strewn around. On one of these boards I saw, branded with a hot iron,

07:03:05.100 --> 07:03:12.320
the name Walrus, the name of Flint's ship. All was clear to probation.

07:03:13.020 --> 07:03:19.660
The cash had been found and rifled. The seven hundred thousand pounds were gone.

07:03:40.560 --> 07:03:43.740
There never was such an overturn in this world.

07:03:44.400 --> 07:03:47.460
Each of these six men was as though he had been struck.

07:03:48.100 --> 07:03:51.640
But with silver, the blow passed him almost instantly.

07:03:52.520 --> 07:03:56.600
Every thought of his soul had been set full stretch like a racer on that money.

07:03:57.280 --> 07:04:03.120
Well, he was brought up in a single second, dead, and he kept his head, found his temper,

07:04:03.580 --> 07:04:07.560
and changed his plan before the others had had time to realize the disappointment.

07:04:08.720 --> 07:04:12.460
Jim, he whispered, take that and stand by for trouble.

07:04:13.660 --> 07:04:16.000
And he passed me a double-barreled pistol.

07:04:17.020 --> 07:04:22.440
At the same time he began quietly moving northward, and in a few steps had put the

07:04:22.440 --> 07:04:27.700
hollow between us two and the other five. Then he looked at me and nodded as much to say,

07:04:28.140 --> 07:04:34.300
here is a narrow corner as indeed I thought it was. His looks were not quite friendly,

07:04:34.320 --> 07:04:39.400
and I was so revolted at these constant changes that I could not forbear whispering,

07:04:39.940 --> 07:04:42.320
so you've changed sides again.

07:04:43.320 --> 07:04:49.240
There was no time left for him to answer in. The buccaneers with oaths and cries began to

07:04:49.240 --> 07:04:54.860
leap one after the other into the pit and to dig with their fingers, throwing the boards aside

07:04:54.860 --> 07:05:00.940
as they did so. Morgan found a piece of gold. He held it up with a perfect spout of oaths.

07:05:01.560 --> 07:05:06.600
It was a two-guinea piece, and it went from hand to hand among them for a quarter of a minute.

07:05:07.380 --> 07:05:13.560
Two guineas roared Mary, shaking in at Silver. That's your seven hundred thousand pounds, is it?

07:05:14.020 --> 07:05:18.320
You're the man for bargains, ain't you? You're him that never bungled nothing,

07:05:18.520 --> 07:05:24.520
you wooded-headed lubber. Dig away, boys, said Silver with the coolest insolence.

07:05:24.960 --> 07:05:31.240
You'll find some pig nuts, and I shouldn't wonder. Pig nuts, repeated Mary in a scream.

07:05:31.240 --> 07:05:36.240
Mates, do you hear that? I tell you now that man there knew it all along.

07:05:36.460 --> 07:05:39.200
Look in the face of him, and you'll see it wrote there.

07:05:40.100 --> 07:05:46.380
Ah, Mary, remarked Silver, standing for captain again. You're a pushing lad, to be sure.

07:05:47.400 --> 07:05:53.060
But this time everyone was entirely in Mary's favour. They began to scramble out of the

07:05:53.060 --> 07:06:00.200
excavation, darting furious glances behind them. One thing I observed, which looked well for us,

07:06:00.200 --> 07:06:07.160
they all got out upon the opposite side from Silver. Well, there we stood, two on one side,

07:06:07.240 --> 07:06:13.180
five on the other, the pit between us, and nobody screwed up high enough to offer the first blow.

07:06:14.080 --> 07:06:20.720
Silver never moved. He watched them, very upright on his crutch, and looked as cool as ever I saw

07:06:20.720 --> 07:06:27.680
him. He was brave, and no mistake. At last Mary seemed to think a speech might help matters.

07:06:28.460 --> 07:06:34.900
Mates, he said, there's two of them alone there. One, the old cripple that brought us all here,

07:06:35.040 --> 07:06:39.820
and blundered us down to this. The other's that cub that I meant to have the heart of.

07:06:39.900 --> 07:06:46.200
Now, Mates, he was just raising his arm and his voice, and plainly meant to lead the charge.

07:06:46.880 --> 07:06:53.120
But just then, crack, crack, crack, three musket shots flashed out of the thicket.

07:06:53.660 --> 07:07:00.100
Mary tumbled head foremost into the excavation. The man with the bandage spun round like a

07:07:00.100 --> 07:07:05.600
teetotem, and fell all his length upon his side where he lay dead, but still twitching,

07:07:05.980 --> 07:07:09.180
and the other three turned and ran for it with all their might.

07:07:11.060 --> 07:07:16.320
Before you could wink, Long John had fired two barrels of a pistol into the struggling Mary,

07:07:16.320 --> 07:07:20.100
and as the man rolled up his eyes at him in the last agony,

07:07:21.080 --> 07:07:28.400
George, said he, I reckon I settled you. At that same moment, the doctor,

07:07:28.740 --> 07:07:34.740
Gray, and Ben Gunn joined us with smoking muskets from among the nutmeg trees.

07:07:35.880 --> 07:07:40.900
Forward, cried the doctor, double quick, my lads, we must head them off the boats.

07:07:41.680 --> 07:07:46.960
And we set off at a greater pace, sometimes plunging through the bushes to the chest.

07:07:48.100 --> 07:07:53.360
I tell you, but Silver was anxious to keep up with us. The work that man went through,

07:07:53.680 --> 07:07:57.520
leaping on his crutch until the muscles of his chest were fit to burst,

07:07:58.020 --> 07:08:04.600
was work no sound man ever equaled, and so thinks the doctor. As it was, he was already

07:08:04.600 --> 07:08:09.580
thirty yards behind us, and on the verge of strangling when we reached the brow of the slope.

07:08:10.760 --> 07:08:18.760
Doctor, he hailed, see there, no hurry. Sure enough, there was no hurry. In a more open

07:08:18.760 --> 07:08:23.760
part of the plateau, we could see the three survivors still running in the same direction

07:08:23.760 --> 07:08:29.640
as they had started, right for the mizzenmast hill. We were already between them and the boats,

07:08:30.100 --> 07:08:36.400
and so we sat, four of us, down to breathe, while Long John, mopping his face, came slowly up with

07:08:36.400 --> 07:08:44.020
us. Thank ye kindly, doctor, says he. You came in at about the nick, I guess, for me and Hawkins.

07:08:45.000 --> 07:08:49.340
And so it's you, Ben Gunn, he added. Well, you're a nice one, to be sure.

07:08:50.120 --> 07:08:56.000
I'm Ben Gunn, I am, replied the maroon, wriggling like an eel in his embarrassment.

07:08:56.780 --> 07:09:03.140
And, he added, after a long pause, how do, Mr. Silver? Pretty well, I think ye, says you.

07:09:03.920 --> 07:09:08.780
Ben, Ben, murmured Silver, to think as you've done me.

07:09:10.180 --> 07:09:16.840
The doctors sent back Gray for one of the pickaxes deserted in their flight by the mutineers, and then

07:09:16.840 --> 07:09:22.260
as we proceeded leisurely downhill to where the boats were lying, related in a few words what had

07:09:22.260 --> 07:09:28.760
taken place. It was a story that profoundly interested Silver, and Ben Gunn, the half-idiot

07:09:28.760 --> 07:09:35.620
of the maroon, was the hero from beginning to end. Ben, in his long, lonely wanderings about

07:09:35.620 --> 07:09:41.660
the island, had found the skeleton. It was he that had rifled it. He had found the treasure.

07:09:41.840 --> 07:09:48.920
He had dug it up. It was the haft of his pickaxe that lay broken in the excavation. He had carried

07:09:48.920 --> 07:09:55.440
it on his back in many weary journeys, from the foot of the tall pine to a cave he had on the

07:09:55.440 --> 07:10:00.760
two-pointed hill at the northeast angle of the island, and there it had lain stored in safety

07:10:00.760 --> 07:10:08.240
since two months before the arrival of the hispanola. When the doctor had wormed this secret from him on

07:10:08.240 --> 07:10:14.600
the afternoon of the attack, and when next morning he saw the anchorage deserted, he had gone to

07:10:14.600 --> 07:10:21.180
Silver, given him the chart, which was now useless, given him the stores, for Ben Gunn's cave was well

07:10:21.180 --> 07:10:27.100
supplied with goatsmeat salted by himself, given anything and everything to get a chance of moving

07:10:27.100 --> 07:10:33.320
in safety from the stockade to the two-pointed hill, there to be clear of malaria and keep a

07:10:33.320 --> 07:10:40.540
guard upon the money. As for you, Jim, he said, it went against my heart, but I did what I thought

07:10:40.540 --> 07:10:46.380
best for those who had stood by their duty, and if you were not one of these, whose fault was it?

07:10:47.600 --> 07:10:53.100
That morning, finding that I was to be involved in the horrid disappointment he had prepared for

07:10:53.100 --> 07:10:59.080
the mutineers, he had run all the way to the cave, and leaving the squire to guard the captain,

07:10:59.260 --> 07:11:05.040
had taken Gray and the maroon, and started making the diagonal across the island to be at hand beside

07:11:05.040 --> 07:11:12.040
the pine. Soon, however, he saw that our party had the start of him, and Ben Gunn, being fleet of foot,

07:11:12.040 --> 07:11:18.800
had been dispatched in front to do his best alone. Then it had occurred to him to work upon the

07:11:18.800 --> 07:11:24.540
superstitions of his former shipmates, and he was so far successful that Gray and the doctors had

07:11:24.540 --> 07:11:28.600
come up and were already ambushed before the arrival of the treasure hunters.

07:11:29.960 --> 07:11:37.280
Ah, said Silver, it were fortunate for me that I had Hawkins here. You would have let old John

07:11:37.280 --> 07:11:44.200
be cut to bits and never given it a thought, doctor. Not a thought, replied Dr. Livesey cheerily.

07:11:45.640 --> 07:11:50.780
And by this time we had reached the gigs. The doctor with his pickaxe demolished one of them,

07:11:51.120 --> 07:11:55.720
and then we all got aboard the other and set out to go round by sea for North Inlet.

07:11:57.440 --> 07:12:03.600
This was a run of eight or nine miles. Silver, though he was almost killed already with fatigue,

07:12:03.600 --> 07:12:09.960
was set to an oar, like the rest of us, and we were soon skimming swiftly over a smooth sea.

07:12:11.080 --> 07:12:15.320
Soon we passed out of the straits and doubled the southeast corner of the island,

07:12:15.580 --> 07:12:18.520
round which four days ago we had towed the Hispaniola.

07:12:19.700 --> 07:12:24.680
As we passed the two-pointed hill we could see the black mouth of Ben Gunn's cave,

07:12:24.860 --> 07:12:30.820
and a figure standing by it, leaning on a musket. It was the squire, and we waved a

07:12:30.820 --> 07:12:36.240
handkerchief and gave him three cheers, in which the voice of silver joined as heartily as any.

07:12:38.000 --> 07:12:41.100
Three miles farther, just inside the mouth of North Inlet,

07:12:41.800 --> 07:12:48.080
what should we meet but the Hispaniola cruising by herself? The last flood had lifted her,

07:12:48.200 --> 07:12:52.420
and had there been much wind or a strong tide current as in the southern anchorage,

07:12:52.780 --> 07:12:56.840
we should never have found her more, or found her stranded beyond help.

07:12:57.480 --> 07:13:00.960
As it was, there was little amiss beyond the wreck of the mainsail.

07:13:01.920 --> 07:13:06.680
Another anchor was got ready and dropped in a fathom and a half of water. We all pulled

07:13:06.680 --> 07:13:12.480
round again to Rum Cove, the nearest point for Ben Gunn's treasure house, and then Gray,

07:13:12.780 --> 07:13:18.200
single-handed, returned with the gig to the Hispaniola where he was to pass the night on guard.

07:13:19.660 --> 07:13:23.120
A gentle slope ran up from the beach to the entrance of the cave.

07:13:23.120 --> 07:13:28.000
At the top, the squire met us. To me, he was cordial and kind,

07:13:28.120 --> 07:13:31.860
saying nothing of my escapade either in the way of blame or praise.

07:13:32.640 --> 07:13:35.530
At Silver's polite salute, he somewhat flushed.

07:13:37.200 --> 07:13:44.320
John Silver, he said, you are a prodigious villain, an imposter, a monstrous imposter, sir.

07:13:44.860 --> 07:13:51.940
I am told I am not to prosecute you. Well, then I will not. But the dead men, sir,

07:13:51.940 --> 07:13:58.540
hang about your neck like millstones. Thank you kindly, sir, replied Long John,

07:13:58.740 --> 07:14:06.360
again saluting. I dare you to thank me, cried the squire. It is a gross dereliction of my duty.

07:14:06.620 --> 07:14:10.800
Stand back. And thereupon we all entered the cave.

07:14:11.760 --> 07:14:17.220
It was a large, airy place with a little spring and a pool of clear water overhung with ferns.

07:14:17.860 --> 07:14:22.480
The floor was sand. Before a big fire lay Captain Smollett,

07:14:22.680 --> 07:14:29.320
and in a far corner only duskily flickered over by the blaze, I beheld great heaps of coin and

07:14:29.320 --> 07:14:35.920
quadrilaterals built of bars of gold. That was Flint's treasure that we had come so far to seek,

07:14:36.220 --> 07:14:40.760
and then it cost already the lives of seventeen men from the Hispaniola.

07:14:41.360 --> 07:14:45.320
How many it had cost in the amassing, what blood and sorrow,

07:14:45.320 --> 07:14:50.860
what good ships scuttled on the deep, what brave men walking the plank blindfold,

07:14:51.420 --> 07:14:58.060
what shot of cannon, what shame and lies and cruelty, perhaps no man alive could tell.

07:14:58.740 --> 07:15:04.600
Yet there were still three upon that island, Silver and Old Morgan and Ben Gunn,

07:15:04.960 --> 07:15:10.400
who had each taken his share in these crimes, as each had hoped in vain to share in the reward.

07:15:11.700 --> 07:15:16.880
"'Come in, Jim,' said the Captain. "'You're a good boy in your line, Jim,

07:15:16.980 --> 07:15:22.840
but I don't think you and me'll go to sea again. You're too much of the born favorite for me.'

07:15:23.600 --> 07:15:26.820
"'Is that you, John Silver? What brings you here, man?'

07:15:27.560 --> 07:15:30.800
"'Come back to my duty, sir,' returned Silver.

07:15:31.980 --> 07:15:35.420
"'Ah,' said the Captain, and that was all he said.

07:15:36.500 --> 07:15:42.580
"'What a supper I had of it that night, with all my friends around me, and what a meal it was,

07:15:42.720 --> 07:15:48.800
with Ben Gunn's salted goat and some delicacies and a bottle of old wine from the Hispaniola.

07:15:49.420 --> 07:15:56.040
Never, I am sure, were people gayer or happier. And there was Silver, sitting back almost out

07:15:56.040 --> 07:16:00.980
of the firelight, but eating heartily, prompt to spring forward when anything was wanted,

07:16:00.980 --> 07:16:09.100
even joining quietly in our laughter, the same bland, polite, obsequious seaman of the voyage out."

07:16:28.000 --> 07:16:28.520
The

07:16:29.180 --> 07:16:34.680
next morning we fell early to work for the transportation of this great mass of gold

07:16:34.680 --> 07:16:40.740
near a mile by land to the beach, and thence three miles by boat to the Hispaniola, was

07:16:40.740 --> 07:16:46.180
a considerable task for so small a number of workmen. The three fellows still abroad

07:16:46.180 --> 07:16:51.220
upon the island did not greatly trouble us. A single sentry on the shoulder of the hill

07:16:51.220 --> 07:16:57.060
was sufficient to insure us against any sudden onslaught, and we thought, besides, they had

07:16:57.060 --> 07:17:03.820
had more than enough of fighting. Therefore the work was pushed on briskly. Gray and Ben

07:17:03.820 --> 07:17:09.140
Gunn came and went with the boat, while the rest, during their absences, piled treasures

07:17:09.140 --> 07:17:15.080
on the beach. Two of the bars, slung in a rope-sand, made a good load for a grown man,

07:17:15.280 --> 07:17:21.180
one that he was glad to walk slowly with. For my part, as I was not much use at carrying,

07:17:21.340 --> 07:17:27.800
I was kept busy all day in the cave, packing the minted money into bread-bags. It was a

07:17:27.800 --> 07:17:33.640
strange collection, like Billy Bone's hoard for the diversity of the coinage, but so much

07:17:33.640 --> 07:17:38.000
larger and so much more varied that I think I never had more pleasure than in sorting

07:17:38.000 --> 07:17:45.740
them. English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, Georges and Luises, doubloons and double guineas,

07:17:46.140 --> 07:17:50.960
and Morderes and sequins, the pictures of all the kings of Europe for the last hundred

07:17:50.960 --> 07:17:57.480
years, strange oriental pieces stamped with what looked like wisps of string or bits of

07:17:57.480 --> 07:18:03.480
spider's web, round pieces, square pieces, and pieces bored through the middle, as if

07:18:03.480 --> 07:18:09.780
neck. Nearly every variety of money in the world must, I think, have found a place in

07:18:09.780 --> 07:18:15.320
that collection, and for number I am sure they were like autumn leaves, so that my back

07:18:15.320 --> 07:18:22.160
ached with stooping and my fingers with sorting them out. Day after day this work went on.

07:18:22.420 --> 07:18:26.760
By every evening a fortune had been stowed aboard, but there was another fortune waiting

07:18:26.760 --> 07:18:31.760
for the morrow, and all this time we heard nothing of the three surviving mutineers.

07:18:32.780 --> 07:18:37.820
At last, I think it was on the third night, the doctor and I were strolling on the shoulder

07:18:37.820 --> 07:18:43.160
of the hill where it overlooks the lowlands of the isle, when from out of the thick darkness

07:18:43.160 --> 07:18:50.420
below, the wind brought us a noise between shrieking and singing. It was only a snatch

07:18:50.420 --> 07:18:53.540
that reached our ears, followed by the former silence.

07:18:54.700 --> 07:18:58.600
Heaven forgive them, said the doctor, tis the mutineers.

07:19:00.340 --> 07:19:04.620
All drunk, sir, struck in the voice of silver from behind us.

07:19:05.440 --> 07:19:11.080
Silver, I should say, was allowed his entire liberty, and in spite of daily rebuffs, seemed

07:19:11.080 --> 07:19:17.440
to regard himself once more as quite a privileged and friendly dependent. Indeed it was remarkable

07:19:17.440 --> 07:19:23.120
how well he bore these slights, and with what unwearying politeness he kept on trying to

07:19:23.120 --> 07:19:29.180
ingratiate himself with all. Yet I think none treated him better than a dog unless

07:19:29.180 --> 07:19:35.600
it was Ben Gunn, who was still terribly afraid of his old quartermaster, or myself, who had

07:19:35.600 --> 07:19:40.480
really something to thank him for. Although for that matter, I suppose, I had reason to

07:19:40.480 --> 07:19:46.020
think even worse of him than anyone else, for I had seen him meditating a fresh treachery

07:19:46.020 --> 07:19:51.180
upon the plateau. Accordingly, it was pretty gruffly that the doctor answered him.

07:19:51.180 --> 07:19:54.100
Drunk or raving, said he.

07:19:54.680 --> 07:20:00.200
Right you were, sir, replied Silver, and precious little odds which to you and me.

07:20:01.480 --> 07:20:07.180
I suppose you would hardly ask me to call you a humane man, returned the doctor with

07:20:07.180 --> 07:20:13.900
a sneer, and so my feelings may surprise you, Master Silver. But if I were sure they were

07:20:13.900 --> 07:20:19.720
raving, as I am mortally certain one at least of them is down with fever, I should leave

07:20:19.720 --> 07:20:25.520
this camp, and at whatever risk to my own carcass take them the assistance of my skill.

07:20:26.800 --> 07:20:33.100
Ask your pardon, sir, you would be very wrong, quote Silver. You would lose your precious

07:20:33.100 --> 07:20:39.060
life and you may lay to that. I am on your side now, hand in glove, and I shouldn't wish

07:20:39.060 --> 07:20:45.580
for to see the party weakened, let alone yourself, seeing as I know what I owes you. But these

07:20:45.580 --> 07:20:51.100
men down there, they couldn't keep their word, no, not supposing they wished to, and what's

07:20:51.100 --> 07:20:53.300
more, they couldn't believe as you could.

07:20:54.360 --> 07:20:58.880
No, said the doctor, you're the man to keep their word, we know that.

07:21:00.220 --> 07:21:05.680
Well, that was about the last news we had of the three pirates. Only once we heard a

07:21:05.680 --> 07:21:11.700
gunshot a great way off, and supposed them to be hunting. A council was held and it was

07:21:11.700 --> 07:21:17.440
decided that we must desert them on the island, to the huge glee, I must say, of Ben Gunn

07:21:17.440 --> 07:21:23.640
and with the strong approval of Gray. We left a good stock of powder and shot, the bulk

07:21:23.640 --> 07:21:29.420
of the salt-coat, a few medicines and some other necessaries, tools, clothing, a spare

07:21:29.420 --> 07:21:35.480
sail, a fathom or two of rope, and by the particular desire of the doctor, a handsome

07:21:35.480 --> 07:21:42.400
president of tobacco. That was about our last doing on the island. Before that, we

07:21:42.400 --> 07:21:46.340
had got the treasure stowed and had shipped enough water and the remainder of the goat

07:21:46.340 --> 07:21:52.200
meat in case of any distress. And at last, one fine morning, we weighed anchor, which

07:21:52.200 --> 07:21:57.380
was about all that we could manage, and stood out of North Inlet, the same colors flying

07:21:57.380 --> 07:22:03.340
that the captain had flown and fought under at the palisade. The three fellows must have

07:22:03.340 --> 07:22:07.940
been watching us closer than we thought for, as we soon had proved, for coming through

07:22:07.940 --> 07:22:13.680
the narrows, we had to lie very near the southern point, and there we saw all three of them,

07:22:14.040 --> 07:22:20.440
kneeling together on a spit of sand with their arms raised in supplication. It went to all

07:22:20.440 --> 07:22:25.400
our hearts, I think, to leave them in that wretched state, but we could not risk another

07:22:25.400 --> 07:22:30.740
mutiny, and to take them home for the gibbet would have been a cruel sort of kindness.

07:22:31.620 --> 07:22:36.580
The doctor hailed them and told them of the stores we had left, and where they were to

07:22:36.580 --> 07:22:42.280
find them, but they continued to call us by name and appeal to us, for God's sake, to

07:22:42.280 --> 07:22:49.420
be merciful and not leave them to die in such a place. At last, seeing the ship still bore

07:22:49.420 --> 07:22:54.800
on her course, and was now swiftly drawing out of earshot, one of them, I know not which

07:22:54.800 --> 07:23:00.760
it was, leaped to his feet with a hoarse cry, whipped his musket to his shoulder, and sent

07:23:00.760 --> 07:23:07.520
a shot whistling over Silver's head and through the mainsail. After that we kept under cover

07:23:07.520 --> 07:23:12.320
of the bulwarks, and when next I looked out they had disappeared from the spit, and the

07:23:12.320 --> 07:23:17.880
spit itself had almost melted out of sight in the growing distance. That was at least

07:23:17.880 --> 07:23:24.780
the end of that. And before noon, to my inexpressible joy, the highest rock of Treasure Island had

07:23:24.780 --> 07:23:31.280
sunk into the blue round of sea. We were so short of men that everyone on board had

07:23:31.280 --> 07:23:36.420
to bear a hand, only the captain lying on a mattress in the stern and giving his orders,

07:23:36.900 --> 07:23:42.060
for though greatly recovered he was still in want of quiet. We laid her head for the

07:23:42.060 --> 07:23:47.340
nearest port in Spanish America, for we could not risk the voyage home without fresh hands,

07:23:47.700 --> 07:23:53.280
and as it was, what with the baffling winds and a couple of fresh gales, we were all worn

07:23:53.280 --> 07:24:00.300
out before we reached it. It was just at sundown when we cast anchor in a most beautiful landlocked

07:24:00.300 --> 07:24:05.720
gulf, and were immediately surrounded by shore boats full of Negroes and Mexican Indians

07:24:05.720 --> 07:24:12.180
and half-bloods selling fruits and vegetables and offering to dive for bits of money. The

07:24:12.180 --> 07:24:17.640
sight of so many good-humored faces, especially the blacks, the taste of the tropical fruits,

07:24:17.640 --> 07:24:23.320
and above all the lights that began to shine in the town made a most charming contrast

07:24:23.320 --> 07:24:29.040
to our dark and bloody sojourn on the island, and the doctor and the squire, taking me along

07:24:29.040 --> 07:24:34.840
with him, went ashore to pass the early part of the night. Here they met the captain of

07:24:34.840 --> 07:24:40.340
an Englishman of war, fell in talk with him, went on board his ship, and in short had so

07:24:40.340 --> 07:24:45.040
agreeable a time that day was breaking when we came alongside the Hispaniola.

07:24:46.260 --> 07:24:51.360
Ben Gunn was on the deck alone, and as soon as we came on board he began, with wonderful

07:24:51.360 --> 07:24:59.640
contortions, to make us a confession. Silver was gone. The maroon had connived at his escape

07:24:59.640 --> 07:25:05.500
in a shore boat some hours ago, and he now assured us that he had only done so to preserve

07:25:05.500 --> 07:25:10.540
their lives, which would certainly have been forfeit if that man with the one leg that

07:25:10.540 --> 07:25:18.080
stayed aboard. But this was not all. The sea cook had not gone empty-handed. He had cut

07:25:18.080 --> 07:25:23.500
through a bulkhead unobserved and had removed one of the sacks of coin, worth perhaps three

07:25:23.500 --> 07:25:29.980
or four hundred guineas, to help him on his further wanderings. I think we were all pleased

07:25:29.980 --> 07:25:31.740
to be so cheaply quit of him.

07:25:33.000 --> 07:25:37.940
Well, to make a long story short, we got a few hands on board, made a good cruise home,

07:25:37.940 --> 07:25:43.020
when the Hispaniola reached Bristol just as Mr. Blandly was beginning to think of fitting

07:25:43.020 --> 07:25:49.480
out her consort. Five men, only of those who had sailed, returned with her. Drink, and

07:25:49.480 --> 07:25:54.420
the devil has done for the rest, with a vengeance, although to be sure, we were not quite in

07:25:54.420 --> 07:26:00.780
so bad a case as that other ship they sang about. With one man of her crew alive, what

07:26:00.780 --> 07:26:07.360
put to sea with seventy-five. All of us had an ample share of the treasure and used it

07:26:07.360 --> 07:26:13.320
wisely or foolishly, according to our natures. Captain Smollett is now retired from the sea.

07:26:14.540 --> 07:26:20.180
Gray not only saved his money, but being suddenly smit with the desire to rise, also studied

07:26:20.180 --> 07:26:26.000
his profession, and he is now mate and part owner of a fine, full-rigged ship, married

07:26:26.000 --> 07:26:32.840
besides, and the father of a family. As for Ben Gunn, he got a thousand pounds, which

07:26:32.840 --> 07:26:38.800
he spent or lost in three weeks, or, to be more exact, in nineteen days, for he was back

07:26:38.800 --> 07:26:44.760
begging on the twentieth. Then he was given a lodge to keep, exactly as he had feared

07:26:44.760 --> 07:26:50.020
upon the island. But he still lives, a great favorite, though something of a butt, with

07:26:50.020 --> 07:26:56.660
the country boys, and a notable singer in church on Sundays and Saints' days. Of silver

07:26:56.660 --> 07:27:02.780
we have heard no more. That formidable seafaring man with one leg has at last gone clean out

07:27:02.780 --> 07:27:08.660
of my life, and I dare say he met his old Negress, and perhaps still lives in comfort

07:27:08.660 --> 07:27:14.720
with her and Captain Flint. It is to be hoped so, I suppose, for his chance of comfort in

07:27:14.720 --> 07:27:22.000
another world are very small. The bar silver and the arms still lie, for all that I know,

07:27:22.000 --> 07:27:28.060
where Flint buried them, and certainly they shall lie there for me. Oxen and wane ropes

07:27:28.060 --> 07:27:33.500
would not bring me back again to that accursed island, and the worst dreams that ever I have

07:27:33.500 --> 07:27:39.280
